U||CHAPTER I
U||JONATHAN HARKER’S JOURNAL
U||   (Kept in shorthand.)
U||   3 May. Bistritz.—Left Munich at 8:35 P. M., on 1st May, arriving at
U||   Vienna early next morning; should have arrived at 6:46, but train was
U||   an hour late. Buda-Pesth seems a wonderful place, from the glimpse
U||   which I got of it from the train and the little I could walk through
U||   the streets. I feared to go very far from the station, as we had
U||   arrived late and would start as near the correct time as possible. The
U||   impression I had was that we were leaving the West and entering the
U||   East; the most western of splendid bridges over the Danube, which is
U||   here of noble width and depth, took us among the traditions of Turkish
U||   rule.
U||   We left in pretty good time, and came after nightfall to Klausenburgh.
U||   Here I stopped for the night at the Hotel Royale. I had for dinner, or
U||   rather supper, a chicken done up some way with red pepper, which was
U||   very good but thirsty. (Mem., get recipe for Mina.) I asked the waiter,
U||   and he said it was called “paprika hendl,” and that, as it was a
U||   national dish, I should be able to get it anywhere along the
U||   Carpathians. I found my smattering of German very useful here; indeed,
U||   I don’t know how I should be able to get on without it.
U||   Having had some time at my disposal when in London, I had visited the
U||   British Museum, and made search among the books and maps in the library
U||   regarding Transylvania; it had struck me that some foreknowledge of the
U||   country could hardly fail to have some importance in dealing with a
U||   nobleman of that country. I find that the district he named is in the
U||   extreme east of the country, just on the borders of three states,
U||   Transylvania, Moldavia and Bukovina, in the midst of the Carpathian
U||   mountains; one of the wildest and least known portions of Europe. I was
U||   not able to light on any map or work giving the exact locality of the
U||   Castle Dracula, as there are no maps of this country as yet to compare
U||   with our own Ordnance Survey maps; but I found that Bistritz, the post
U||   town named by Count Dracula, is a fairly well-known place. I shall
U||   enter here some of my notes, as they may refresh my memory when I talk
U||   over my travels with Mina.
U||   In the population of Transylvania there are four distinct
U||   nationalities: Saxons in the South, and mixed with them the Wallachs,
U||   who are the descendants of the Dacians; Magyars in the West, and
U||   Szekelys in the East and North. I am going among the latter, who claim
U||   to be descended from Attila and the Huns. This may be so, for when the
U||   Magyars conquered the country in the eleventh century they found the
U||   Huns settled in it. I read that every known superstition in the world
U||   is gathered into the horseshoe of the Carpathians, as if it were the
U||   centre of some sort of imaginative whirlpool; if so my stay may be very
U||   interesting. (Mem., I must ask the Count all about them.)
U||   I did not sleep well, though my bed was comfortable enough, for I had
U||   all sorts of queer dreams. There was a dog howling all night under my
U||   window, which may have had something to do with it; or it may have been
U||   the paprika, for I had to drink up all the water in my carafe, and was
U||   still thirsty. Towards morning I slept and was wakened by the
U||   continuous knocking at my door, so I guess I must have been sleeping
U||   soundly then. I had for breakfast more paprika, and a sort of porridge
U||   of maize flour which they said was “mamaliga,” and egg-plant stuffed
U||   with forcemeat, a very excellent dish, which they call “impletata.”
U||   (Mem., get recipe for this also.) I had to hurry breakfast, for the
U||   train started a little before eight, or rather it ought to have done
U||   so, for after rushing to the station at 7:30 I had to sit in the
U||   carriage for more than an hour before we began to move. It seems to me
U||   that the further east you go the more unpunctual are the trains. What
U||   ought they to be in China?
U||   All day long we seemed to dawdle through a country which was full of
U||   beauty of every kind. Sometimes we saw little towns or castles on the
U||   top of steep hills such as we see in old missals; sometimes we ran by
U||   rivers and streams which seemed from the wide stony margin on each side
U||   of them to be subject to great floods. It takes a lot of water, and
U||   running strong, to sweep the outside edge of a river clear. At every
U||   station there were groups of people, sometimes crowds, and in all sorts
U||   of attire. Some of them were just like the peasants at home or those I
U||   saw coming through France and Germany, with short jackets and round
U||   hats and home-made trousers; but others were very picturesque. The
U||   women looked pretty, except when you got near them, but they were very
U||   clumsy about the waist. They had all full white sleeves of some kind or
U||   other, and most of them had big belts with a lot of strips of something
U||   fluttering from them like the dresses in a ballet, but of course there
U||   were petticoats under them. The strangest figures we saw were the
U||   Slovaks, who were more barbarian than the rest, with their big cow-boy
U||   hats, great baggy dirty-white trousers, white linen shirts, and
U||   enormous heavy leather belts, nearly a foot wide, all studded over with
U||   brass nails. They wore high boots, with their trousers tucked into
U||   them, and had long black hair and heavy black moustaches. They are very
U||   picturesque, but do not look prepossessing. On the stage they would be
U||   set down at once as some old Oriental band of brigands. They are,
U||   however, I am told, very harmless and rather wanting in natural
U||   self-assertion.
U||   It was on the dark side of twilight when we got to Bistritz, which is a
U||   very interesting old place. Being practically on the frontier—for the
U||   Borgo Pass leads from it into Bukovina—it has had a very stormy
U||   existence, and it certainly shows marks of it. Fifty years ago a series
U||   of great fires took place, which made terrible havoc on five separate
U||   occasions. At the very beginning of the seventeenth century it
U||   underwent a siege of three weeks and lost 13,000 people, the casualties
U||   of war proper being assisted by famine and disease.
U||   Count Dracula had directed me to go to the Golden Krone Hotel, which I
U||   found, to my great delight, to be thoroughly old-fashioned, for of
U||   course I wanted to see all I could of the ways of the country. I was
U||   evidently expected, for when I got near the door I faced a
U||   cheery-looking elderly woman in the usual peasant dress—white
U||   undergarment with long double apron, front, and back, of coloured stuff
U||   fitting almost too tight for modesty. When I came close she bowed and
U||   said, “The Herr Englishman?” “Yes,” I said, “Jonathan Harker.” She
U||   smiled, and gave some message to an elderly man in white shirt-sleeves,
U||   who had followed her to the door. He went, but immediately returned
U||   with a letter:—
U||   “My Friend.—Welcome to the Carpathians. I am anxiously expecting you.
U||   Sleep well to-night. At three to-morrow the diligence will start for
U||   Bukovina; a place on it is kept for you. At the Borgo Pass my carriage
U||   will await you and will bring you to me. I trust that your journey from
U||   London has been a happy one, and that you will enjoy your stay in my
U||   beautiful land.
U||   “Your friend,
U||   “Dracula.”
U||   4 May.—I found that my landlord had got a letter from the Count,
U||   directing him to secure the best place on the coach for me; but on
U||   making inquiries as to details he seemed somewhat reticent, and
U||   pretended that he could not understand my German. This could not be
U||   true, because up to then he had understood it perfectly; at least, he
U||   answered my questions exactly as if he did. He and his wife, the old
U||   lady who had received me, looked at each other in a frightened sort of
U||   way. He mumbled out that the money had been sent in a letter, and that
U||   was all he knew. When I asked him if he knew Count Dracula, and could
U||   tell me anything of his castle, both he and his wife crossed
U||   themselves, and, saying that they knew nothing at all, simply refused
U||   to speak further. It was so near the time of starting that I had no
U||   time to ask any one else, for it was all very mysterious and not by any
U||   means comforting.
U||   Just before I was leaving, the old lady came up to my room and said in
U||   a very hysterical way:
U||   “Must you go? Oh! young Herr, must you go?” She was in such an excited
U||   state that she seemed to have lost her grip of what German she knew,
U||   and mixed it all up with some other language which I did not know at
U||   all. I was just able to follow her by asking many questions. When I
U||   told her that I must go at once, and that I was engaged on important
U||   business, she asked again:
U||   “Do you know what day it is?” I answered that it was the fourth of May.
U||   She shook her head as she said again:
U||   “Oh, yes! I know that! I know that, but do you know what day it is?” On
U||   my saying that I did not understand, she went on:
U||   “It is the eve of St. George’s Day. Do you not know that to-night, when
U||   the clock strikes midnight, all the evil things in the world will have
U||   full sway? Do you know where you are going, and what you are going to?”
U||   She was in such evident distress that I tried to comfort her, but
U||   without effect. Finally she went down on her knees and implored me not
U||   to go; at least to wait a day or two before starting. It was all very
U||   ridiculous but I did not feel comfortable. However, there was business
U||   to be done, and I could allow nothing to interfere with it. I therefore
U||   tried to raise her up, and said, as gravely as I could, that I thanked
U||   her, but my duty was imperative, and that I must go. She then rose and
U||   dried her eyes, and taking a crucifix from her neck offered it to me. I
U||   did not know what to do, for, as an English Churchman, I have been
U||   taught to regard such things as in some measure idolatrous, and yet it
U||   seemed so ungracious to refuse an old lady meaning so well and in such
U||   a state of mind. She saw, I suppose, the doubt in my face, for she put
U||   the rosary round my neck, and said, “For your mother’s sake,” and went
U||   out of the room. I am writing up this part of the diary whilst I am
U||   waiting for the coach, which is, of course, late; and the crucifix is
U||   still round my neck. Whether it is the old lady’s fear, or the many
U||   ghostly traditions of this place, or the crucifix itself, I do not
U||   know, but I am not feeling nearly as easy in my mind as usual. If this
U||   book should ever reach Mina before I do, let it bring my good-bye. Here
U||   comes the coach!
U||   5 May. The Castle.—The grey of the morning has passed, and the sun is
U||   high over the distant horizon, which seems jagged, whether with trees
U||   or hills I know not, for it is so far off that big things and little
U||   are mixed. I am not sleepy, and, as I am not to be called till I awake,
U||   naturally I write till sleep comes. There are many odd things to put
U||   down, and, lest who reads them may fancy that I dined too well before I
U||   left Bistritz, let me put down my dinner exactly. I dined on what they
U||   called “robber steak”—bits of bacon, onion, and beef, seasoned with red
U||   pepper, and strung on sticks and roasted over the fire, in the simple
U||   style of the London cat’s meat! The wine was Golden Mediasch, which
U||   produces a queer sting on the tongue, which is, however, not
U||   disagreeable. I had only a couple of glasses of this, and nothing else.
U||   When I got on the coach the driver had not taken his seat, and I saw
U||   him talking with the landlady. They were evidently talking of me, for
U||   every now and then they looked at me, and some of the people who were
U||   sitting on the bench outside the door—which they call by a name meaning
U||   “word-bearer”—came and listened, and then looked at me, most of them
U||   pityingly. I could hear a lot of words often repeated, queer words, for
U||   there were many nationalities in the crowd; so I quietly got my
U||   polyglot dictionary from my bag and looked them out. I must say they
U||   were not cheering to me, for amongst them were “Ordog”—Satan,
U||   “pokol”—hell, “stregoica”—witch, “vrolok” and “vlkoslak”—both of which
U||   mean the same thing, one being Slovak and the other Servian for
U||   something that is either were-wolf or vampire. (Mem., I must ask the
U||   Count about these superstitions)
U||   When we started, the crowd round the inn door, which had by this time
U||   swelled to a considerable size, all made the sign of the cross and
U||   pointed two fingers towards me. With some difficulty I got a
U||   fellow-passenger to tell me what they meant; he would not answer at
U||   first, but on learning that I was English, he explained that it was a
U||   charm or guard against the evil eye. This was not very pleasant for me,
U||   just starting for an unknown place to meet an unknown man; but every
U||   one seemed so kind-hearted, and so sorrowful, and so sympathetic that I
U||   could not but be touched. I shall never forget the last glimpse which I
U||   had of the inn-yard and its crowd of picturesque figures, all crossing
U||   themselves, as they stood round the wide archway, with its background
U||   of rich foliage of oleander and orange trees in green tubs clustered in
U||   the centre of the yard. Then our driver, whose wide linen drawers
U||   covered the whole front of the box-seat—“gotza” they call them—cracked
U||   his big whip over his four small horses, which ran abreast, and we set
U||   off on our journey.
U||   I soon lost sight and recollection of ghostly fears in the beauty of
U||   the scene as we drove along, although had I known the language, or
U||   rather languages, which my fellow-passengers were speaking, I might not
U||   have been able to throw them off so easily. Before us lay a green
U||   sloping land full of forests and woods, with here and there steep
U||   hills, crowned with clumps of trees or with farmhouses, the blank gable
U||   end to the road. There was everywhere a bewildering mass of fruit
U||   blossom—apple, plum, pear, cherry; and as we drove by I could see the
U||   green grass under the trees spangled with the fallen petals. In and out
U||   amongst these green hills of what they call here the “Mittel Land” ran
U||   the road, losing itself as it swept round the grassy curve, or was shut
U||   out by the straggling ends of pine woods, which here and there ran down
U||   the hillsides like tongues of flame. The road was rugged, but still we
U||   seemed to fly over it with a feverish haste. I could not understand
U||   then what the haste meant, but the driver was evidently bent on losing
U||   no time in reaching Borgo Prund. I was told that this road is in
U||   summertime excellent, but that it had not yet been put in order after
U||   the winter snows. In this respect it is different from the general run
U||   of roads in the Carpathians, for it is an old tradition that they are
U||   not to be kept in too good order. Of old the Hospadars would not repair
U||   them, lest the Turk should think that they were preparing to bring in
U||   foreign troops, and so hasten the war which was always really at
U||   loading point.
U||   Beyond the green swelling hills of the Mittel Land rose mighty slopes
U||   of forest up to the lofty steeps of the Carpathians themselves. Right
U||   and left of us they towered, with the afternoon sun falling full upon
U||   them and bringing out all the glorious colours of this beautiful range,
U||   deep blue and purple in the shadows of the peaks, green and brown where
U||   grass and rock mingled, and an endless perspective of jagged rock and
U||   pointed crags, till these were themselves lost in the distance, where
U||   the snowy peaks rose grandly. Here and there seemed mighty rifts in the
U||   mountains, through which, as the sun began to sink, we saw now and
U||   again the white gleam of falling water. One of my companions touched my
U||   arm as we swept round the base of a hill and opened up the lofty,
U||   snow-covered peak of a mountain, which seemed, as we wound on our
U||   serpentine way, to be right before us:—
U||   “Look! Isten szek!”—“God’s seat!”—and he crossed himself reverently.
U||   As we wound on our endless way, and the sun sank lower and lower behind
U||   us, the shadows of the evening began to creep round us. This was
U||   emphasised by the fact that the snowy mountain-top still held the
U||   sunset, and seemed to glow out with a delicate cool pink. Here and
U||   there we passed Cszeks and Slovaks, all in picturesque attire, but I
U||   noticed that goitre was painfully prevalent. By the roadside were many
U||   crosses, and as we swept by, my companions all crossed themselves. Here
U||   and there was a peasant man or woman kneeling before a shrine, who did
U||   not even turn round as we approached, but seemed in the self-surrender
U||   of devotion to have neither eyes nor ears for the outer world. There
U||   were many things new to me: for instance, hay-ricks in the trees, and
U||   here and there very beautiful masses of weeping birch, their white
U||   stems shining like silver through the delicate green of the leaves. Now
U||   and again we passed a leiter-wagon—the ordinary peasant’s cart—with its
U||   long, snake-like vertebra, calculated to suit the inequalities of the
U||   road. On this were sure to be seated quite a group of home-coming
U||   peasants, the Cszeks with their white, and the Slovaks with their
U||   coloured, sheepskins, the latter carrying lance-fashion their long
U||   staves, with axe at end. As the evening fell it began to get very cold,
U||   and the growing twilight seemed to merge into one dark mistiness the
U||   gloom of the trees, oak, beech, and pine, though in the valleys which
U||   ran deep between the spurs of the hills, as we ascended through the
U||   Pass, the dark firs stood out here and there against the background of
U||   late-lying snow. Sometimes, as the road was cut through the pine woods
U||   that seemed in the darkness to be closing down upon us, great masses of
U||   greyness, which here and there bestrewed the trees, produced a
U||   peculiarly weird and solemn effect, which carried on the thoughts and
U||   grim fancies engendered earlier in the evening, when the falling sunset
U||   threw into strange relief the ghost-like clouds which amongst the
U||   Carpathians seem to wind ceaselessly through the valleys. Sometimes the
U||   hills were so steep that, despite our driver’s haste, the horses could
U||   only go slowly. I wished to get down and walk up them, as we do at
U||   home, but the driver would not hear of it. “No, no,” he said; “you must
U||   not walk here; the dogs are too fierce”; and then he added, with what
U||   he evidently meant for grim pleasantry—for he looked round to catch the
U||   approving smile of the rest—“and you may have enough of such matters
U||   before you go to sleep.” The only stop he would make was a moment’s
U||   pause to light his lamps.
U||   When it grew dark there seemed to be some excitement amongst the
U||   passengers, and they kept speaking to him, one after the other, as
U||   though urging him to further speed. He lashed the horses unmercifully
U||   with his long whip, and with wild cries of encouragement urged them on
U||   to further exertions. Then through the darkness I could see a sort of
U||   patch of grey light ahead of us, as though there were a cleft in the
U||   hills. The excitement of the passengers grew greater; the crazy coach
U||   rocked on its great leather springs, and swayed like a boat tossed on a
U||   stormy sea. I had to hold on. The road grew more level, and we appeared
U||   to fly along. Then the mountains seemed to come nearer to us on each
U||   side and to frown down upon us; we were entering on the Borgo Pass. One
U||   by one several of the passengers offered me gifts, which they pressed
U||   upon me with an earnestness which would take no denial; these were
U||   certainly of an odd and varied kind, but each was given in simple good
U||   faith, with a kindly word, and a blessing, and that strange mixture of
U||   fear-meaning movements which I had seen outside the hotel at
U||   Bistritz—the sign of the cross and the guard against the evil eye.
U||   Then, as we flew along, the driver leaned forward, and on each side the
U||   passengers, craning over the edge of the coach, peered eagerly into the
U||   darkness. It was evident that something very exciting was either
U||   happening or expected, but though I asked each passenger, no one would
U||   give me the slightest explanation. This state of excitement kept on for
U||   some little time; and at last we saw before us the Pass opening out on
U||   the eastern side. There were dark, rolling clouds overhead, and in the
U||   air the heavy, oppressive sense of thunder. It seemed as though the
U||   mountain range had separated two atmospheres, and that now we had got
U||   into the thunderous one. I was now myself looking out for the
U||   conveyance which was to take me to the Count. Each moment I expected to
U||   see the glare of lamps through the blackness; but all was dark. The
U||   only light was the flickering rays of our own lamps, in which the steam
U||   from our hard-driven horses rose in a white cloud. We could see now the
U||   sandy road lying white before us, but there was on it no sign of a
U||   vehicle. The passengers drew back with a sigh of gladness, which seemed
U||   to mock my own disappointment. I was already thinking what I had best
U||   do, when the driver, looking at his watch, said to the others something
U||   which I could hardly hear, it was spoken so quietly and in so low a
U||   tone; I thought it was “An hour less than the time.” Then turning to
U||   me, he said in German worse than my own:—
U||   “There is no carriage here. The Herr is not expected after all. He will
U||   now come on to Bukovina, and return to-morrow or the next day; better
U||   the next day.” Whilst he was speaking the horses began to neigh and
U||   snort and plunge wildly, so that the driver had to hold them up. Then,
U||   amongst a chorus of screams from the peasants and a universal crossing
U||   of themselves, a calèche, with four horses, drove up behind us,
U||   overtook us, and drew up beside the coach. I could see from the flash
U||   of our lamps, as the rays fell on them, that the horses were coal-black
U||   and splendid animals. They were driven by a tall man, with a long brown
U||   beard and a great black hat, which seemed to hide his face from us. I
U||   could only see the gleam of a pair of very bright eyes, which seemed
U||   red in the lamplight, as he turned to us. He said to the driver:—
U||   “You are early to-night, my friend.” The man stammered in reply:—
U||   “The English Herr was in a hurry,” to which the stranger replied:—
U||   “That is why, I suppose, you wished him to go on to Bukovina. You
U||   cannot deceive me, my friend; I know too much, and my horses are
U||   swift.” As he spoke he smiled, and the lamplight fell on a hard-looking
U||   mouth, with very red lips and sharp-looking teeth, as white as ivory.
U||   One of my companions whispered to another the line from Burger’s
U||   “Lenore”:—
U||   “Denn die Todten reiten schnell”—
U||   (“For the dead travel fast.”)
U||   The strange driver evidently heard the words, for he looked up with a
U||   gleaming smile. The passenger turned his face away, at the same time
U||   putting out his two fingers and crossing himself. “Give me the Herr’s
U||   luggage,” said the driver; and with exceeding alacrity my bags were
U||   handed out and put in the calèche. Then I descended from the side of
U||   the coach, as the calèche was close alongside, the driver helping me
U||   with a hand which caught my arm in a grip of steel; his strength must
U||   have been prodigious. Without a word he shook his reins, the horses
U||   turned, and we swept into the darkness of the Pass. As I looked back I
U||   saw the steam from the horses of the coach by the light of the lamps,
U||   and projected against it the figures of my late companions crossing
U||   themselves. Then the driver cracked his whip and called to his horses,
U||   and off they swept on their way to Bukovina. As they sank into the
U||   darkness I felt a strange chill, and a lonely feeling came over me; but
U||   a cloak was thrown over my shoulders, and a rug across my knees, and
U||   the driver said in excellent German:—
U||   “The night is chill, mein Herr, and my master the Count bade me take
U||   all care of you. There is a flask of slivovitz (the plum brandy of the
U||   country) underneath the seat, if you should require it.” I did not take
U||   any, but it was a comfort to know it was there all the same. I felt a
U||   little strangely, and not a little frightened. I think had there been
U||   any alternative I should have taken it, instead of prosecuting that
U||   unknown night journey. The carriage went at a hard pace straight along,
U||   then we made a complete turn and went along another straight road. It
U||   seemed to me that we were simply going over and over the same ground
U||   again; and so I took note of some salient point, and found that this
U||   was so. I would have liked to have asked the driver what this all
U||   meant, but I really feared to do so, for I thought that, placed as I
U||   was, any protest would have had no effect in case there had been an
U||   intention to delay. By-and-by, however, as I was curious to know how
U||   time was passing, I struck a match, and by its flame looked at my
U||   watch; it was within a few minutes of midnight. This gave me a sort of
U||   shock, for I suppose the general superstition about midnight was
U||   increased by my recent experiences. I waited with a sick feeling of
U||   suspense.
U||   Then a dog began to howl somewhere in a farmhouse far down the road—a
U||   long, agonised wailing, as if from fear. The sound was taken up by
U||   another dog, and then another and another, till, borne on the wind
U||   which now sighed softly through the Pass, a wild howling began, which
U||   seemed to come from all over the country, as far as the imagination
U||   could grasp it through the gloom of the night. At the first howl the
U||   horses began to strain and rear, but the driver spoke to them
U||   soothingly, and they quieted down, but shivered and sweated as though
U||   after a runaway from sudden fright. Then, far off in the distance, from
U||   the mountains on each side of us began a louder and a sharper
U||   howling—that of wolves—which affected both the horses and myself in the
U||   same way—for I was minded to jump from the calèche and run, whilst they
U||   reared again and plunged madly, so that the driver had to use all his
U||   great strength to keep them from bolting. In a few minutes, however, my
U||   own ears got accustomed to the sound, and the horses so far became
U||   quiet that the driver was able to descend and to stand before them. He
U||   petted and soothed them, and whispered something in their ears, as I
U||   have heard of horse-tamers doing, and with extraordinary effect, for
U||   under his caresses they became quite manageable again, though they
U||   still trembled. The driver again took his seat, and shaking his reins,
U||   started off at a great pace. This time, after going to the far side of
U||   the Pass, he suddenly turned down a narrow roadway which ran sharply to
U||   the right.
U||   Soon we were hemmed in with trees, which in places arched right over
U||   the roadway till we passed as through a tunnel; and again great
U||   frowning rocks guarded us boldly on either side. Though we were in
U||   shelter, we could hear the rising wind, for it moaned and whistled
U||   through the rocks, and the branches of the trees crashed together as we
U||   swept along. It grew colder and colder still, and fine, powdery snow
U||   began to fall, so that soon we and all around us were covered with a
U||   white blanket. The keen wind still carried the howling of the dogs,
U||   though this grew fainter as we went on our way. The baying of the
U||   wolves sounded nearer and nearer, as though they were closing round on
U||   us from every side. I grew dreadfully afraid, and the horses shared my
U||   fear. The driver, however, was not in the least disturbed; he kept
U||   turning his head to left and right, but I could not see anything
U||   through the darkness.
U||   Suddenly, away on our left, I saw a faint flickering blue flame. The
U||   driver saw it at the same moment; he at once checked the horses, and,
U||   jumping to the ground, disappeared into the darkness. I did not know
U||   what to do, the less as the howling of the wolves grew closer; but
U||   while I wondered the driver suddenly appeared again, and without a word
U||   took his seat, and we resumed our journey. I think I must have fallen
U||   asleep and kept dreaming of the incident, for it seemed to be repeated
U||   endlessly, and now looking back, it is like a sort of awful nightmare.
U||   Once the flame appeared so near the road, that even in the darkness
U||   around us I could watch the driver’s motions. He went rapidly to where
U||   the blue flame arose—it must have been very faint, for it did not seem
U||   to illumine the place around it at all—and gathering a few stones,
U||   formed them into some device. Once there appeared a strange optical
U||   effect: when he stood between me and the flame he did not obstruct it,
U||   for I could see its ghostly flicker all the same. This startled me, but
U||   as the effect was only momentary, I took it that my eyes deceived me
U||   straining through the darkness. Then for a time there were no blue
U||   flames, and we sped onwards through the gloom, with the howling of the
U||   wolves around us, as though they were following in a moving circle.
U||   At last there came a time when the driver went further afield than he
U||   had yet gone, and during his absence, the horses began to tremble worse
U||   than ever and to snort and scream with fright. I could not see any
U||   cause for it, for the howling of the wolves had ceased altogether; but
U||   just then the moon, sailing through the black clouds, appeared behind
U||   the jagged crest of a beetling, pine-clad rock, and by its light I saw
U||   around us a ring of wolves, with white teeth and lolling red tongues,
U||   with long, sinewy limbs and shaggy hair. They were a hundred times more
U||   terrible in the grim silence which held them than even when they
U||   howled. For myself, I felt a sort of paralysis of fear. It is only when
U||   a man feels himself face to face with such horrors that he can
U||   understand their true import.
U||   All at once the wolves began to howl as though the moonlight had had
U||   some peculiar effect on them. The horses jumped about and reared, and
U||   looked helplessly round with eyes that rolled in a way painful to see;
U||   but the living ring of terror encompassed them on every side; and they
U||   had perforce to remain within it. I called to the coachman to come, for
U||   it seemed to me that our only chance was to try to break out through
U||   the ring and to aid his approach. I shouted and beat the side of the
U||   calèche, hoping by the noise to scare the wolves from that side, so as
U||   to give him a chance of reaching the trap. How he came there, I know
U||   not, but I heard his voice raised in a tone of imperious command, and
U||   looking towards the sound, saw him stand in the roadway. As he swept
U||   his long arms, as though brushing aside some impalpable obstacle, the
U||   wolves fell back and back further still. Just then a heavy cloud passed
U||   across the face of the moon, so that we were again in darkness.
U||   When I could see again the driver was climbing into the calèche, and
U||   the wolves had disappeared. This was all so strange and uncanny that a
U||   dreadful fear came upon me, and I was afraid to speak or move. The time
U||   seemed interminable as we swept on our way, now in almost complete
U||   darkness, for the rolling clouds obscured the moon. We kept on
U||   ascending, with occasional periods of quick descent, but in the main
U||   always ascending. Suddenly, I became conscious of the fact that the
U||   driver was in the act of pulling up the horses in the courtyard of a
U||   vast ruined castle, from whose tall black windows came no ray of light,
U||   and whose broken battlements showed a jagged line against the moonlit
U||   sky.
U||CHAPTER II
U||JONATHAN HARKER’S JOURNAL—continued
U||   5 May.—I must have been asleep, for certainly if I had been fully awake
U||   I must have noticed the approach of such a remarkable place. In the
U||   gloom the courtyard looked of considerable size, and as several dark
U||   ways led from it under great round arches, it perhaps seemed bigger
U||   than it really is. I have not yet been able to see it by daylight.
U||   When the calèche stopped, the driver jumped down and held out his hand
U||   to assist me to alight. Again I could not but notice his prodigious
U||   strength. His hand actually seemed like a steel vice that could have
U||   crushed mine if he had chosen. Then he took out my traps, and placed
U||   them on the ground beside me as I stood close to a great door, old and
U||   studded with large iron nails, and set in a projecting doorway of
U||   massive stone. I could see even in the dim light that the stone was
U||   massively carved, but that the carving had been much worn by time and
U||   weather. As I stood, the driver jumped again into his seat and shook
U||   the reins; the horses started forward, and trap and all disappeared
U||   down one of the dark openings.
U||   I stood in silence where I was, for I did not know what to do. Of bell
U||   or knocker there was no sign; through these frowning walls and dark
U||   window openings it was not likely that my voice could penetrate. The
U||   time I waited seemed endless, and I felt doubts and fears crowding upon
U||   me. What sort of place had I come to, and among what kind of people?
U||   What sort of grim adventure was it on which I had embarked? Was this a
U||   customary incident in the life of a solicitor’s clerk sent out to
U||   explain the purchase of a London estate to a foreigner? Solicitor’s
U||   clerk! Mina would not like that. Solicitor—for just before leaving
U||   London I got word that my examination was successful; and I am now a
U||   full-blown solicitor! I began to rub my eyes and pinch myself to see if
U||   I were awake. It all seemed like a horrible nightmare to me, and I
U||   expected that I should suddenly awake, and find myself at home, with
U||   the dawn struggling in through the windows, as I had now and again felt
U||   in the morning after a day of overwork. But my flesh answered the
U||   pinching test, and my eyes were not to be deceived. I was indeed awake
U||   and among the Carpathians. All I could do now was to be patient, and to
U||   wait the coming of the morning.
U||   Just as I had come to this conclusion I heard a heavy step approaching
U||   behind the great door, and saw through the chinks the gleam of a coming
U||   light. Then there was the sound of rattling chains and the clanking of
U||   massive bolts drawn back. A key was turned with the loud grating noise
U||   of long disuse, and the great door swung back.
U||   Within, stood a tall old man, clean shaven save for a long white
U||   moustache, and clad in black from head to foot, without a single speck
U||   of colour about him anywhere. He held in his hand an antique silver
U||   lamp, in which the flame burned without chimney or globe of any kind,
U||   throwing long quivering shadows as it flickered in the draught of the
U||   open door. The old man motioned me in with his right hand with a
U||   courtly gesture, saying in excellent English, but with a strange
U||   intonation:—
U||   “Welcome to my house! Enter freely and of your own will!” He made no
U||   motion of stepping to meet me, but stood like a statue, as though his
U||   gesture of welcome had fixed him into stone. The instant, however, that
U||   I had stepped over the threshold, he moved impulsively forward, and
U||   holding out his hand grasped mine with a strength which made me wince,
U||   an effect which was not lessened by the fact that it seemed as cold as
U||   ice—more like the hand of a dead than a living man. Again he said:—
U||   “Welcome to my house. Come freely. Go safely; and leave something of
U||   the happiness you bring!” The strength of the handshake was so much
U||   akin to that which I had noticed in the driver, whose face I had not
U||   seen, that for a moment I doubted if it were not the same person to
U||   whom I was speaking; so to make sure, I said interrogatively:—
U||   “Count Dracula?” He bowed in a courtly way as he replied:—
U||   “I am Dracula; and I bid you welcome, Mr. Harker, to my house. Come in;
U||   the night air is chill, and you must need to eat and rest.” As he was
U||   speaking, he put the lamp on a bracket on the wall, and stepping out,
U||   took my luggage; he had carried it in before I could forestall him. I
U||   protested but he insisted:—
U||   “Nay, sir, you are my guest. It is late, and my people are not
U||   available. Let me see to your comfort myself.” He insisted on carrying
U||   my traps along the passage, and then up a great winding stair, and
U||   along another great passage, on whose stone floor our steps rang
U||   heavily. At the end of this he threw open a heavy door, and I rejoiced
U||   to see within a well-lit room in which a table was spread for supper,
U||   and on whose mighty hearth a great fire of logs, freshly replenished,
U||   flamed and flared.
U||   The Count halted, putting down my bags, closed the door, and crossing
U||   the room, opened another door, which led into a small octagonal room
U||   lit by a single lamp, and seemingly without a window of any sort.
U||   Passing through this, he opened another door, and motioned me to enter.
U||   It was a welcome sight; for here was a great bedroom well lighted and
U||   warmed with another log fire,—also added to but lately, for the top
U||   logs were fresh—which sent a hollow roar up the wide chimney. The Count
U||   himself left my luggage inside and withdrew, saying, before he closed
U||   the door:—
U||   “You will need, after your journey, to refresh yourself by making your
U||   toilet. I trust you will find all you wish. When you are ready, come
U||   into the other room, where you will find your supper prepared.”
U||   The light and warmth and the Count’s courteous welcome seemed to have
U||   dissipated all my doubts and fears. Having then reached my normal
U||   state, I discovered that I was half famished with hunger; so making a
U||   hasty toilet, I went into the other room.
U||   I found supper already laid out. My host, who stood on one side of the
U||   great fireplace, leaning against the stonework, made a graceful wave of
U||   his hand to the table, and said:—
U||   “I pray you, be seated and sup how you please. You will, I trust,
U||   excuse me that I do not join you; but I have dined already, and I do
U||   not sup.”
U||   I handed to him the sealed letter which Mr. Hawkins had entrusted to
U||   me. He opened it and read it gravely; then, with a charming smile, he
U||   handed it to me to read. One passage of it, at least, gave me a thrill
U||   of pleasure.
U||   “I must regret that an attack of gout, from which malady I am a
U||   constant sufferer, forbids absolutely any travelling on my part for
U||   some time to come; but I am happy to say I can send a sufficient
U||   substitute, one in whom I have every possible confidence. He is a young
U||   man, full of energy and talent in his own way, and of a very faithful
U||   disposition. He is discreet and silent, and has grown into manhood in
U||   my service. He shall be ready to attend on you when you will during his
U||   stay, and shall take your instructions in all matters.”
U||   The Count himself came forward and took off the cover of a dish, and I
U||   fell to at once on an excellent roast chicken. This, with some cheese
U||   and a salad and a bottle of old Tokay, of which I had two glasses, was
U||   my supper. During the time I was eating it the Count asked me many
U||   questions as to my journey, and I told him by degrees all I had
U||   experienced.
U||   By this time I had finished my supper, and by my host’s desire had
U||   drawn up a chair by the fire and begun to smoke a cigar which he
U||   offered me, at the same time excusing himself that he did not smoke. I
U||   had now an opportunity of observing him, and found him of a very marked
U||   physiognomy.
U||   His face was a strong—a very strong—aquiline, with high bridge of the
U||   thin nose and peculiarly arched nostrils; with lofty domed forehead,
U||   and hair growing scantily round the temples but profusely elsewhere.
U||   His eyebrows were very massive, almost meeting over the nose, and with
U||   bushy hair that seemed to curl in its own profusion. The mouth, so far
U||   as I could see it under the heavy moustache, was fixed and rather
U||   cruel-looking, with peculiarly sharp white teeth; these protruded over
U||   the lips, whose remarkable ruddiness showed astonishing vitality in a
U||   man of his years. For the rest, his ears were pale, and at the tops
U||   extremely pointed; the chin was broad and strong, and the cheeks firm
U||   though thin. The general effect was one of extraordinary pallor.
U||   Hitherto I had noticed the backs of his hands as they lay on his knees
U||   in the firelight, and they had seemed rather white and fine; but seeing
U||   them now close to me, I could not but notice that they were rather
U||   coarse—broad, with squat fingers. Strange to say, there were hairs in
U||   the centre of the palm. The nails were long and fine, and cut to a
U||   sharp point. As the Count leaned over me and his hands touched me, I
U||   could not repress a shudder. It may have been that his breath was rank,
U||   but a horrible feeling of nausea came over me, which, do what I would,
U||   I could not conceal. The Count, evidently noticing it, drew back; and
U||   with a grim sort of smile, which showed more than he had yet done his
U||   protuberant teeth, sat himself down again on his own side of the
U||   fireplace. We were both silent for a while; and as I looked towards the
U||   window I saw the first dim streak of the coming dawn. There seemed a
U||   strange stillness over everything; but as I listened I heard as if from
U||   down below in the valley the howling of many wolves. The Count’s eyes
U||   gleamed, and he said:—
U||   “Listen to them—the children of the night. What music they make!”
U||   Seeing, I suppose, some expression in my face strange to him, he
U||   added:—
U||   “Ah, sir, you dwellers in the city cannot enter into the feelings of
U||   the hunter.” Then he rose and said:—
U||   “But you must be tired. Your bedroom is all ready, and to-morrow you
U||   shall sleep as late as you will. I have to be away till the afternoon;
U||   so sleep well and dream well!” With a courteous bow, he opened for me
U||   himself the door to the octagonal room, and I entered my bedroom....
U||   I am all in a sea of wonders. I doubt; I fear; I think strange things,
U||   which I dare not confess to my own soul. God keep me, if only for the
U||   sake of those dear to me!
U||   7 May.—It is again early morning, but I have rested and enjoyed the
U||   last twenty-four hours. I slept till late in the day, and awoke of my
U||   own accord. When I had dressed myself I went into the room where we had
U||   supped, and found a cold breakfast laid out, with coffee kept hot by
U||   the pot being placed on the hearth. There was a card on the table, on
U||   which was written:—
U||   “I have to be absent for a while. Do not wait for me.—D.” I set to and
U||   enjoyed a hearty meal. When I had done, I looked for a bell, so that I
U||   might let the servants know I had finished; but I could not find one.
U||   There are certainly odd deficiencies in the house, considering the
U||   extraordinary evidences of wealth which are round me. The table service
U||   is of gold, and so beautifully wrought that it must be of immense
U||   value. The curtains and upholstery of the chairs and sofas and the
U||   hangings of my bed are of the costliest and most beautiful fabrics, and
U||   must have been of fabulous value when they were made, for they are
U||   centuries old, though in excellent order. I saw something like them in
U||   Hampton Court, but there they were worn and frayed and moth-eaten. But
U||   still in none of the rooms is there a mirror. There is not even a
U||   toilet glass on my table, and I had to get the little shaving glass
U||   from my bag before I could either shave or brush my hair. I have not
U||   yet seen a servant anywhere, or heard a sound near the castle except
U||   the howling of wolves. Some time after I had finished my meal—I do not
U||   know whether to call it breakfast or dinner, for it was between five
U||   and six o’clock when I had it—I looked about for something to read, for
U||   I did not like to go about the castle until I had asked the Count’s
U||   permission. There was absolutely nothing in the room, book, newspaper,
U||   or even writing materials; so I opened another door in the room and
U||   found a sort of library. The door opposite mine I tried, but found it
U||   locked.
U||   In the library I found, to my great delight, a vast number of English
U||   books, whole shelves full of them, and bound volumes of magazines and
U||   newspapers. A table in the centre was littered with English magazines
U||   and newspapers, though none of them were of very recent date. The books
U||   were of the most varied kind—history, geography, politics, political
U||   economy, botany, geology, law—all relating to England and English life
U||   and customs and manners. There were even such books of reference as the
U||   London Directory, the “Red” and “Blue” books, Whitaker’s Almanac, the
U||   Army and Navy Lists, and—it somehow gladdened my heart to see it—the
U||   Law List.
U||   Whilst I was looking at the books, the door opened, and the Count
U||   entered. He saluted me in a hearty way, and hoped that I had had a good
U||   night’s rest. Then he went on:—
U||   “I am glad you found your way in here, for I am sure there is much that
U||   will interest you. These companions”—and he laid his hand on some of
U||   the books—“have been good friends to me, and for some years past, ever
U||   since I had the idea of going to London, have given me many, many hours
U||   of pleasure. Through them I have come to know your great England; and
U||   to know her is to love her. I long to go through the crowded streets of
U||   your mighty London, to be in the midst of the whirl and rush of
U||   humanity, to share its life, its change, its death, and all that makes
U||   it what it is. But alas! as yet I only know your tongue through books.
U||   To you, my friend, I look that I know it to speak.”
U||   “But, Count,” I said, “you know and speak English thoroughly!” He bowed
U||   gravely.
U||   “I thank you, my friend, for your all too-flattering estimate, but yet
U||   I fear that I am but a little way on the road I would travel. True, I
U||   know the grammar and the words, but yet I know not how to speak them.”
U||   “Indeed,” I said, “you speak excellently.”
U||   “Not so,” he answered. “Well, I know that, did I move and speak in your
U||   London, none there are who would not know me for a stranger. That is
U||   not enough for me. Here I am noble; I am boyar; the common people know
U||   me, and I am master. But a stranger in a strange land, he is no one;
U||   men know him not—and to know not is to care not for. I am content if I
U||   am like the rest, so that no man stops if he see me, or pause in his
U||   speaking if he hear my words, ‘Ha, ha! a stranger!’ I have been so long
U||   master that I would be master still—or at least that none other should
U||   be master of me. You come to me not alone as agent of my friend Peter
U||   Hawkins, of Exeter, to tell me all about my new estate in London. You
U||   shall, I trust, rest here with me awhile, so that by our talking I may
U||   learn the English intonation; and I would that you tell me when I make
U||   error, even of the smallest, in my speaking. I am sorry that I had to
U||   be away so long to-day; but you will, I know, forgive one who has so
U||   many important affairs in hand.”
U||   Of course I said all I could about being willing, and asked if I might
U||   come into that room when I chose. He answered: “Yes, certainly,” and
U||   added:—
U||   “You may go anywhere you wish in the castle, except where the doors are
U||   locked, where of course you will not wish to go. There is reason that
U||   all things are as they are, and did you see with my eyes and know with
U||   my knowledge, you would perhaps better understand.” I said I was sure
U||   of this, and then he went on:—
U||   “We are in Transylvania; and Transylvania is not England. Our ways are
U||   not your ways, and there shall be to you many strange things. Nay, from
U||   what you have told me of your experiences already, you know something
U||   of what strange things there may be.”
U||   This led to much conversation; and as it was evident that he wanted to
U||   talk, if only for talking’s sake, I asked him many questions regarding
U||   things that had already happened to me or come within my notice.
U||   Sometimes he sheered off the subject, or turned the conversation by
U||   pretending not to understand; but generally he answered all I asked
U||   most frankly. Then as time went on, and I had got somewhat bolder, I
U||   asked him of some of the strange things of the preceding night, as, for
U||   instance, why the coachman went to the places where he had seen the
U||   blue flames. He then explained to me that it was commonly believed that
U||   on a certain night of the year—last night, in fact, when all evil
U||   spirits are supposed to have unchecked sway—a blue flame is seen over
U||   any place where treasure has been concealed. “That treasure has been
U||   hidden,” he went on, “in the region through which you came last night,
U||   there can be but little doubt; for it was the ground fought over for
U||   centuries by the Wallachian, the Saxon, and the Turk. Why, there is
U||   hardly a foot of soil in all this region that has not been enriched by
U||   the blood of men, patriots or invaders. In old days there were stirring
U||   times, when the Austrian and the Hungarian came up in hordes, and the
U||   patriots went out to meet them—men and women, the aged and the children
U||   too—and waited their coming on the rocks above the passes, that they
U||   might sweep destruction on them with their artificial avalanches. When
U||   the invader was triumphant he found but little, for whatever there was
U||   had been sheltered in the friendly soil.”
U||   “But how,” said I, “can it have remained so long undiscovered, when
U||   there is a sure index to it if men will but take the trouble to look?”
U||   The Count smiled, and as his lips ran back over his gums, the long,
U||   sharp, canine teeth showed out strangely; he answered:—
U||   “Because your peasant is at heart a coward and a fool! Those flames
U||   only appear on one night; and on that night no man of this land will,
U||   if he can help it, stir without his doors. And, dear sir, even if he
U||   did he would not know what to do. Why, even the peasant that you tell
U||   me of who marked the place of the flame would not know where to look in
U||   daylight even for his own work. Even you would not, I dare be sworn, be
U||   able to find these places again?”
U||   “There you are right,” I said. “I know no more than the dead where even
U||   to look for them.” Then we drifted into other matters.
U||   “Come,” he said at last, “tell me of London and of the house which you
U||   have procured for me.” With an apology for my remissness, I went into
U||   my own room to get the papers from my bag. Whilst I was placing them in
U||   order I heard a rattling of china and silver in the next room, and as I
U||   passed through, noticed that the table had been cleared and the lamp
U||   lit, for it was by this time deep into the dark. The lamps were also
U||   lit in the study or library, and I found the Count lying on the sofa,
U||   reading, of all things in the world, an English Bradshaw’s Guide. When
U||   I came in he cleared the books and papers from the table; and with him
U||   I went into plans and deeds and figures of all sorts. He was interested
U||   in everything, and asked me a myriad questions about the place and its
U||   surroundings. He clearly had studied beforehand all he could get on the
U||   subject of the neighbourhood, for he evidently at the end knew very
U||   much more than I did. When I remarked this, he answered:—
U||   “Well, but, my friend, is it not needful that I should? When I go there
U||   I shall be all alone, and my friend Harker Jonathan—nay, pardon me, I
U||   fall into my country’s habit of putting your patronymic first—my friend
U||   Jonathan Harker will not be by my side to correct and aid me. He will
U||   be in Exeter, miles away, probably working at papers of the law with my
U||   other friend, Peter Hawkins. So!”
U||   We went thoroughly into the business of the purchase of the estate at
U||   Purfleet. When I had told him the facts and got his signature to the
U||   necessary papers, and had written a letter with them ready to post to
U||   Mr. Hawkins, he began to ask me how I had come across so suitable a
U||   place. I read to him the notes which I had made at the time, and which
U||   I inscribe here:—
U||   “At Purfleet, on a by-road, I came across just such a place as seemed
U||   to be required, and where was displayed a dilapidated notice that the
U||   place was for sale. It is surrounded by a high wall, of ancient
U||   structure, built of heavy stones, and has not been repaired for a large
U||   number of years. The closed gates are of heavy old oak and iron, all
U||   eaten with rust.
U||   “The estate is called Carfax, no doubt a corruption of the old Quatre
U||   Face, as the house is four-sided, agreeing with the cardinal points of
U||   the compass. It contains in all some twenty acres, quite surrounded by
U||   the solid stone wall above mentioned. There are many trees on it, which
U||   make it in places gloomy, and there is a deep, dark-looking pond or
U||   small lake, evidently fed by some springs, as the water is clear and
U||   flows away in a fair-sized stream. The house is very large and of all
U||   periods back, I should say, to mediæval times, for one part is of stone
U||   immensely thick, with only a few windows high up and heavily barred
U||   with iron. It looks like part of a keep, and is close to an old chapel
U||   or church. I could not enter it, as I had not the key of the door
U||   leading to it from the house, but I have taken with my kodak views of
U||   it from various points. The house has been added to, but in a very
U||   straggling way, and I can only guess at the amount of ground it covers,
U||   which must be very great. There are but few houses close at hand, one
U||   being a very large house only recently added to and formed into a
U||   private lunatic asylum. It is not, however, visible from the grounds.”
U||   When I had finished, he said:—
U||   “I am glad that it is old and big. I myself am of an old family, and to
U||   live in a new house would kill me. A house cannot be made habitable in
U||   a day; and, after all, how few days go to make up a century. I rejoice
U||   also that there is a chapel of old times. We Transylvanian nobles love
U||   not to think that our bones may lie amongst the common dead. I seek not
U||   gaiety nor mirth, not the bright voluptuousness of much sunshine and
U||   sparkling waters which please the young and gay. I am no longer young;
U||   and my heart, through weary years of mourning over the dead, is not
U||   attuned to mirth. Moreover, the walls of my castle are broken; the
U||   shadows are many, and the wind breathes cold through the broken
U||   battlements and casements. I love the shade and the shadow, and would
U||   be alone with my thoughts when I may.” Somehow his words and his look
U||   did not seem to accord, or else it was that his cast of face made his
U||   smile look malignant and saturnine.
U||   Presently, with an excuse, he left me, asking me to put all my papers
U||   together. He was some little time away, and I began to look at some of
U||   the books around me. One was an atlas, which I found opened naturally
U||   at England, as if that map had been much used. On looking at it I found
U||   in certain places little rings marked, and on examining these I noticed
U||   that one was near London on the east side, manifestly where his new
U||   estate was situated; the other two were Exeter, and Whitby on the
U||   Yorkshire coast.
U||   It was the better part of an hour when the Count returned. “Aha!” he
U||   said; “still at your books? Good! But you must not work always. Come; I
U||   am informed that your supper is ready.” He took my arm, and we went
U||   into the next room, where I found an excellent supper ready on the
U||   table. The Count again excused himself, as he had dined out on his
U||   being away from home. But he sat as on the previous night, and chatted
U||   whilst I ate. After supper I smoked, as on the last evening, and the
U||   Count stayed with me, chatting and asking questions on every
U||   conceivable subject, hour after hour. I felt that it was getting very
U||   late indeed, but I did not say anything, for I felt under obligation to
U||   meet my host’s wishes in every way. I was not sleepy, as the long sleep
U||   yesterday had fortified me; but I could not help experiencing that
U||   chill which comes over one at the coming of the dawn, which is like, in
U||   its way, the turn of the tide. They say that people who are near death
U||   die generally at the change to the dawn or at the turn of the tide; any
U||   one who has when tired, and tied as it were to his post, experienced
U||   this change in the atmosphere can well believe it. All at once we heard
U||   the crow of a cock coming up with preternatural shrillness through the
U||   clear morning air; Count Dracula, jumping to his feet, said:—
U||   “Why, there is the morning again! How remiss I am to let you stay up so
U||   long. You must make your conversation regarding my dear new country of
U||   England less interesting, so that I may not forget how time flies by
U||   us,” and, with a courtly bow, he quickly left me.
U||   I went into my own room and drew the curtains, but there was little to
U||   notice; my window opened into the courtyard, all I could see was the
U||   warm grey of quickening sky. So I pulled the curtains again, and have
U||   written of this day.
U||   8 May.—I began to fear as I wrote in this book that I was getting too
U||   diffuse; but now I am glad that I went into detail from the first, for
U||   there is something so strange about this place and all in it that I
U||   cannot but feel uneasy. I wish I were safe out of it, or that I had
U||   never come. It may be that this strange night-existence is telling on
U||   me; but would that that were all! If there were any one to talk to I
U||   could bear it, but there is no one. I have only the Count to speak
U||   with, and he!—I fear I am myself the only living soul within the place.
U||   Let me be prosaic so far as facts can be; it will help me to bear up,
U||   and imagination must not run riot with me. If it does I am lost. Let me
U||   say at once how I stand—or seem to.
U||   I only slept a few hours when I went to bed, and feeling that I could
U||   not sleep any more, got up. I had hung my shaving glass by the window,
U||   and was just beginning to shave. Suddenly I felt a hand on my shoulder,
U||   and heard the Count’s voice saying to me, “Good-morning.” I started,
U||   for it amazed me that I had not seen him, since the reflection of the
U||   glass covered the whole room behind me. In starting I had cut myself
U||   slightly, but did not notice it at the moment. Having answered the
U||   Count’s salutation, I turned to the glass again to see how I had been
U||   mistaken. This time there could be no error, for the man was close to
U||   me, and I could see him over my shoulder. But there was no reflection
U||   of him in the mirror! The whole room behind me was displayed; but there
U||   was no sign of a man in it, except myself. This was startling, and,
U||   coming on the top of so many strange things, was beginning to increase
U||   that vague feeling of uneasiness which I always have when the Count is
U||   near; but at the instant I saw that the cut had bled a little, and the
U||   blood was trickling over my chin. I laid down the razor, turning as I
U||   did so half round to look for some sticking plaster. When the Count saw
U||   my face, his eyes blazed with a sort of demoniac fury, and he suddenly
U||   made a grab at my throat. I drew away, and his hand touched the string
U||   of beads which held the crucifix. It made an instant change in him, for
U||   the fury passed so quickly that I could hardly believe that it was ever
U||   there.
U||   “Take care,” he said, “take care how you cut yourself. It is more
U||   dangerous than you think in this country.” Then seizing the shaving
U||   glass, he went on: “And this is the wretched thing that has done the
U||   mischief. It is a foul bauble of man’s vanity. Away with it!” and
U||   opening the heavy window with one wrench of his terrible hand, he flung
U||   out the glass, which was shattered into a thousand pieces on the stones
U||   of the courtyard far below. Then he withdrew without a word. It is very
U||   annoying, for I do not see how I am to shave, unless in my watch-case
U||   or the bottom of the shaving-pot, which is fortunately of metal.
U||   When I went into the dining-room, breakfast was prepared; but I could
U||   not find the Count anywhere. So I breakfasted alone. It is strange that
U||   as yet I have not seen the Count eat or drink. He must be a very
U||   peculiar man! After breakfast I did a little exploring in the castle. I
U||   went out on the stairs, and found a room looking towards the South. The
U||   view was magnificent, and from where I stood there was every
U||   opportunity of seeing it. The castle is on the very edge of a terrible
U||   precipice. A stone falling from the window would fall a thousand feet
U||   without touching anything! As far as the eye can reach is a sea of
U||   green tree tops, with occasionally a deep rift where there is a chasm.
U||   Here and there are silver threads where the rivers wind in deep gorges
U||   through the forests.
U||   But I am not in heart to describe beauty, for when I had seen the view
U||   I explored further; doors, doors, doors everywhere, and all locked and
U||   bolted. In no place save from the windows in the castle walls is there
U||   an available exit.
U||   The castle is a veritable prison, and I am a prisoner!
U||CHAPTER III
U||JONATHAN HARKER’S JOURNAL—continued
U||   WHEN I found that I was a prisoner a sort of wild feeling came over me.
U||   I rushed up and down the stairs, trying every door and peering out of
U||   every window I could find; but after a little the conviction of my
U||   helplessness overpowered all other feelings. When I look back after a
U||   few hours I think I must have been mad for the time, for I behaved much
U||   as a rat does in a trap. When, however, the conviction had come to me
U||   that I was helpless I sat down quietly—as quietly as I have ever done
U||   anything in my life—and began to think over what was best to be done. I
U||   am thinking still, and as yet have come to no definite conclusion. Of
U||   one thing only am I certain; that it is no use making my ideas known to
U||   the Count. He knows well that I am imprisoned; and as he has done it
U||   himself, and has doubtless his own motives for it, he would only
U||   deceive me if I trusted him fully with the facts. So far as I can see,
U||   my only plan will be to keep my knowledge and my fears to myself, and
U||   my eyes open. I am, I know, either being deceived, like a baby, by my
U||   own fears, or else I am in desperate straits; and if the latter be so,
U||   I need, and shall need, all my brains to get through.
U||   I had hardly come to this conclusion when I heard the great door below
U||   shut, and knew that the Count had returned. He did not come at once
U||   into the library, so I went cautiously to my own room and found him
U||   making the bed. This was odd, but only confirmed what I had all along
U||   thought—that there were no servants in the house. When later I saw him
U||   through the chink of the hinges of the door laying the table in the
U||   dining-room, I was assured of it; for if he does himself all these
U||   menial offices, surely it is proof that there is no one else to do
U||   them. This gave me a fright, for if there is no one else in the castle,
U||   it must have been the Count himself who was the driver of the coach
U||   that brought me here. This is a terrible thought; for if so, what does
U||   it mean that he could control the wolves, as he did, by only holding up
U||   his hand in silence. How was it that all the people at Bistritz and on
U||   the coach had some terrible fear for me? What meant the giving of the
U||   crucifix, of the garlic, of the wild rose, of the mountain ash? Bless
U||   that good, good woman who hung the crucifix round my neck! for it is a
U||   comfort and a strength to me whenever I touch it. It is odd that a
U||   thing which I have been taught to regard with disfavour and as
U||   idolatrous should in a time of loneliness and trouble be of help. Is it
U||   that there is something in the essence of the thing itself, or that it
U||   is a medium, a tangible help, in conveying memories of sympathy and
U||   comfort? Some time, if it may be, I must examine this matter and try to
U||   make up my mind about it. In the meantime I must find out all I can
U||   about Count Dracula, as it may help me to understand. To-night he may
U||   talk of himself, if I turn the conversation that way. I must be very
U||   careful, however, not to awake his suspicion.
U||   Midnight.—I have had a long talk with the Count. I asked him a few
U||   questions on Transylvania history, and he warmed up to the subject
U||   wonderfully. In his speaking of things and people, and especially of
U||   battles, he spoke as if he had been present at them all. This he
U||   afterwards explained by saying that to a boyar the pride of his house
U||   and name is his own pride, that their glory is his glory, that their
U||   fate is his fate. Whenever he spoke of his house he always said “we,”
U||   and spoke almost in the plural, like a king speaking. I wish I could
U||   put down all he said exactly as he said it, for to me it was most
U||   fascinating. It seemed to have in it a whole history of the country. He
U||   grew excited as he spoke, and walked about the room pulling his great
U||   white moustache and grasping anything on which he laid his hands as
U||   though he would crush it by main strength. One thing he said which I
U||   shall put down as nearly as I can; for it tells in its way the story of
U||   his race:—
U||   “We Szekelys have a right to be proud, for in our veins flows the blood
U||   of many brave races who fought as the lion fights, for lordship. Here,
U||   in the whirlpool of European races, the Ugric tribe bore down from
U||   Iceland the fighting spirit which Thor and Wodin gave them, which their
U||   Berserkers displayed to such fell intent on the seaboards of Europe,
U||   ay, and of Asia and Africa too, till the peoples thought that the
U||   were-wolves themselves had come. Here, too, when they came, they found
U||   the Huns, whose warlike fury had swept the earth like a living flame,
U||   till the dying peoples held that in their veins ran the blood of those
U||   old witches, who, expelled from Scythia had mated with the devils in
U||   the desert. Fools, fools! What devil or what witch was ever so great as
U||   Attila, whose blood is in these veins?” He held up his arms. “Is it a
U||   wonder that we were a conquering race; that we were proud; that when
U||   the Magyar, the Lombard, the Avar, the Bulgar, or the Turk poured his
U||   thousands on our frontiers, we drove them back? Is it strange that when
U||   Arpad and his legions swept through the Hungarian fatherland he found
U||   us here when he reached the frontier; that the Honfoglalas was
U||   completed there? And when the Hungarian flood swept eastward, the
U||   Szekelys were claimed as kindred by the victorious Magyars, and to us
U||   for centuries was trusted the guarding of the frontier of Turkey-land;
U||   ay, and more than that, endless duty of the frontier guard, for, as the
U||   Turks say, ‘water sleeps, and enemy is sleepless.’ Who more gladly than
U||   we throughout the Four Nations received the ‘bloody sword,’ or at its
U||   warlike call flocked quicker to the standard of the King? When was
U||   redeemed that great shame of my nation, the shame of Cassova, when the
U||   flags of the Wallach and the Magyar went down beneath the Crescent? Who
U||   was it but one of my own race who as Voivode crossed the Danube and
U||   beat the Turk on his own ground? This was a Dracula indeed! Woe was it
U||   that his own unworthy brother, when he had fallen, sold his people to
U||   the Turk and brought the shame of slavery on them! Was it not this
U||   Dracula, indeed, who inspired that other of his race who in a later age
U||   again and again brought his forces over the great river into
U||   Turkey-land; who, when he was beaten back, came again, and again, and
U||   again, though he had to come alone from the bloody field where his
U||   troops were being slaughtered, since he knew that he alone could
U||   ultimately triumph! They said that he thought only of himself. Bah!
U||   what good are peasants without a leader? Where ends the war without a
U||   brain and heart to conduct it? Again, when, after the battle of Mohács,
U||   we threw off the Hungarian yoke, we of the Dracula blood were amongst
U||   their leaders, for our spirit would not brook that we were not free.
U||   Ah, young sir, the Szekelys—and the Dracula as their heart’s blood,
U||   their brains, and their swords—can boast a record that mushroom growths
U||   like the Hapsburgs and the Romanoffs can never reach. The warlike days
U||   are over. Blood is too precious a thing in these days of dishonourable
U||   peace; and the glories of the great races are as a tale that is told.”
U||   It was by this time close on morning, and we went to bed. (Mem., this
U||   diary seems horribly like the beginning of the “Arabian Nights,” for
U||   everything has to break off at cockcrow—or like the ghost of Hamlet’s
U||   father.)
U||   12 May.—Let me begin with facts—bare, meagre facts, verified by books
U||   and figures, and of which there can be no doubt. I must not confuse
U||   them with experiences which will have to rest on my own observation, or
U||   my memory of them. Last evening when the Count came from his room he
U||   began by asking me questions on legal matters and on the doing of
U||   certain kinds of business. I had spent the day wearily over books, and,
U||   simply to keep my mind occupied, went over some of the matters I had
U||   been examining at Lincoln’s Inn. There was a certain method in the
U||   Count’s inquiries, so I shall try to put them down in sequence; the
U||   knowledge may somehow or some time be useful to me.
U||   First, he asked if a man in England might have two solicitors or more.
U||   I told him he might have a dozen if he wished, but that it would not be
U||   wise to have more than one solicitor engaged in one transaction, as
U||   only one could act at a time, and that to change would be certain to
U||   militate against his interest. He seemed thoroughly to understand, and
U||   went on to ask if there would be any practical difficulty in having one
U||   man to attend, say, to banking, and another to look after shipping, in
U||   case local help were needed in a place far from the home of the banking
U||   solicitor. I asked him to explain more fully, so that I might not by
U||   any chance mislead him, so he said:—
U||   “I shall illustrate. Your friend and mine, Mr. Peter Hawkins, from
U||   under the shadow of your beautiful cathedral at Exeter, which is far
U||   from London, buys for me through your good self my place at London.
U||   Good! Now here let me say frankly, lest you should think it strange
U||   that I have sought the services of one so far off from London instead
U||   of some one resident there, that my motive was that no local interest
U||   might be served save my wish only; and as one of London residence
U||   might, perhaps, have some purpose of himself or friend to serve, I went
U||   thus afield to seek my agent, whose labours should be only to my
U||   interest. Now, suppose I, who have much of affairs, wish to ship goods,
U||   say, to Newcastle, or Durham, or Harwich, or Dover, might it not be
U||   that it could with more ease be done by consigning to one in these
U||   ports?” I answered that certainly it would be most easy, but that we
U||   solicitors had a system of agency one for the other, so that local work
U||   could be done locally on instruction from any solicitor, so that the
U||   client, simply placing himself in the hands of one man, could have his
U||   wishes carried out by him without further trouble.
U||   “But,” said he, “I could be at liberty to direct myself. Is it not so?”
U||   “Of course,” I replied; and “such is often done by men of business, who
U||   do not like the whole of their affairs to be known by any one person.”
U||   “Good!” he said, and then went on to ask about the means of making
U||   consignments and the forms to be gone through, and of all sorts of
U||   difficulties which might arise, but by forethought could be guarded
U||   against. I explained all these things to him to the best of my ability,
U||   and he certainly left me under the impression that he would have made a
U||   wonderful solicitor, for there was nothing that he did not think of or
U||   foresee. For a man who was never in the country, and who did not
U||   evidently do much in the way of business, his knowledge and acumen were
U||   wonderful. When he had satisfied himself on these points of which he
U||   had spoken, and I had verified all as well as I could by the books
U||   available, he suddenly stood up and said:—
U||   “Have you written since your first letter to our friend Mr. Peter
U||   Hawkins, or to any other?” It was with some bitterness in my heart that
U||   I answered that I had not, that as yet I had not seen any opportunity
U||   of sending letters to anybody.
U||   “Then write now, my young friend,” he said, laying a heavy hand on my
U||   shoulder: “write to our friend and to any other; and say, if it will
U||   please you, that you shall stay with me until a month from now.”
U||   “Do you wish me to stay so long?” I asked, for my heart grew cold at
U||   the thought.
U||   “I desire it much; nay, I will take no refusal. When your master,
U||   employer, what you will, engaged that someone should come on his
U||   behalf, it was understood that my needs only were to be consulted. I
U||   have not stinted. Is it not so?”
U||   What could I do but bow acceptance? It was Mr. Hawkins’s interest, not
U||   mine, and I had to think of him, not myself; and besides, while Count
U||   Dracula was speaking, there was that in his eyes and in his bearing
U||   which made me remember that I was a prisoner, and that if I wished it I
U||   could have no choice. The Count saw his victory in my bow, and his
U||   mastery in the trouble of my face, for he began at once to use them,
U||   but in his own smooth, resistless way:—
U||   “I pray you, my good young friend, that you will not discourse of
U||   things other than business in your letters. It will doubtless please
U||   your friends to know that you are well, and that you look forward to
U||   getting home to them. Is it not so?” As he spoke he handed me three
U||   sheets of note-paper and three envelopes. They were all of the thinnest
U||   foreign post, and looking at them, then at him, and noticing his quiet
U||   smile, with the sharp, canine teeth lying over the red underlip, I
U||   understood as well as if he had spoken that I should be careful what I
U||   wrote, for he would be able to read it. So I determined to write only
U||   formal notes now, but to write fully to Mr. Hawkins in secret, and also
U||   to Mina, for to her I could write in shorthand, which would puzzle the
U||   Count, if he did see it. When I had written my two letters I sat quiet,
U||   reading a book whilst the Count wrote several notes, referring as he
U||   wrote them to some books on his table. Then he took up my two and
U||   placed them with his own, and put by his writing materials, after
U||   which, the instant the door had closed behind him, I leaned over and
U||   looked at the letters, which were face down on the table. I felt no
U||   compunction in doing so, for under the circumstances I felt that I
U||   should protect myself in every way I could.
U||   One of the letters was directed to Samuel F. Billington, No. 7, The
U||   Crescent, Whitby, another to Herr Leutner, Varna; the third was to
U||   Coutts & Co., London, and the fourth to Herren Klopstock & Billreuth,
U||   bankers, Buda-Pesth. The second and fourth were unsealed. I was just
U||   about to look at them when I saw the door-handle move. I sank back in
U||   my seat, having just had time to replace the letters as they had been
U||   and to resume my book before the Count, holding still another letter in
U||   his hand, entered the room. He took up the letters on the table and
U||   stamped them carefully, and then turning to me, said:—
U||   “I trust you will forgive me, but I have much work to do in private
U||   this evening. You will, I hope, find all things as you wish.” At the
U||   door he turned, and after a moment’s pause said:—
U||   “Let me advise you, my dear young friend—nay, let me warn you with all
U||   seriousness, that should you leave these rooms you will not by any
U||   chance go to sleep in any other part of the castle. It is old, and has
U||   many memories, and there are bad dreams for those who sleep unwisely.
U||   Be warned! Should sleep now or ever overcome you, or be like to do,
U||   then haste to your own chamber or to these rooms, for your rest will
U||   then be safe. But if you be not careful in this respect, then”—He
U||   finished his speech in a gruesome way, for he motioned with his hands
U||   as if he were washing them. I quite understood; my only doubt was as to
U||   whether any dream could be more terrible than the unnatural, horrible
U||   net of gloom and mystery which seemed closing around me.
U||   Later.—I endorse the last words written, but this time there is no
U||   doubt in question. I shall not fear to sleep in any place where he is
U||   not. I have placed the crucifix over the head of my bed—I imagine that
U||   my rest is thus freer from dreams; and there it shall remain.
U||   When he left me I went to my room. After a little while, not hearing
U||   any sound, I came out and went up the stone stair to where I could look
U||   out towards the South. There was some sense of freedom in the vast
U||   expanse, inaccessible though it was to me, as compared with the narrow
U||   darkness of the courtyard. Looking out on this, I felt that I was
U||   indeed in prison, and I seemed to want a breath of fresh air, though it
U||   were of the night. I am beginning to feel this nocturnal existence tell
U||   on me. It is destroying my nerve. I start at my own shadow, and am full
U||   of all sorts of horrible imaginings. God knows that there is ground for
U||   my terrible fear in this accursed place! I looked out over the
U||   beautiful expanse, bathed in soft yellow moonlight till it was almost
U||   as light as day. In the soft light the distant hills became melted, and
U||   the shadows in the valleys and gorges of velvety blackness. The mere
U||   beauty seemed to cheer me; there was peace and comfort in every breath
U||   I drew. As I leaned from the window my eye was caught by something
U||   moving a storey below me, and somewhat to my left, where I imagined,
U||   from the order of the rooms, that the windows of the Count’s own room
U||   would look out. The window at which I stood was tall and deep,
U||   stone-mullioned, and though weatherworn, was still complete; but it was
U||   evidently many a day since the case had been there. I drew back behind
U||   the stonework, and looked carefully out.
U||   What I saw was the Count’s head coming out from the window. I did not
U||   see the face, but I knew the man by the neck and the movement of his
U||   back and arms. In any case I could not mistake the hands which I had
U||   had so many opportunities of studying. I was at first interested and
U||   somewhat amused, for it is wonderful how small a matter will interest
U||   and amuse a man when he is a prisoner. But my very feelings changed to
U||   repulsion and terror when I saw the whole man slowly emerge from the
U||   window and begin to crawl down the castle wall over that dreadful
U||   abyss, face down with his cloak spreading out around him like great
U||   wings. At first I could not believe my eyes. I thought it was some
U||   trick of the moonlight, some weird effect of shadow; but I kept
U||   looking, and it could be no delusion. I saw the fingers and toes grasp
U||   the corners of the stones, worn clear of the mortar by the stress of
U||   years, and by thus using every projection and inequality move downwards
U||   with considerable speed, just as a lizard moves along a wall.
U||   What manner of man is this, or what manner of creature is it in the
U||   semblance of man? I feel the dread of this horrible place overpowering
U||   me; I am in fear—in awful fear—and there is no escape for me; I am
U||   encompassed about with terrors that I dare not think of....
U||   15 May.—Once more have I seen the Count go out in his lizard fashion.
U||   He moved downwards in a sidelong way, some hundred feet down, and a
U||   good deal to the left. He vanished into some hole or window. When his
U||   head had disappeared, I leaned out to try and see more, but without
U||   avail—the distance was too great to allow a proper angle of sight. I
U||   knew he had left the castle now, and thought to use the opportunity to
U||   explore more than I had dared to do as yet. I went back to the room,
U||   and taking a lamp, tried all the doors. They were all locked, as I had
U||   expected, and the locks were comparatively new; but I went down the
U||   stone stairs to the hall where I had entered originally. I found I
U||   could pull back the bolts easily enough and unhook the great chains;
U||   but the door was locked, and the key was gone! That key must be in the
U||   Count’s room; I must watch should his door be unlocked, so that I may
U||   get it and escape. I went on to make a thorough examination of the
U||   various stairs and passages, and to try the doors that opened from
U||   them. One or two small rooms near the hall were open, but there was
U||   nothing to see in them except old furniture, dusty with age and
U||   moth-eaten. At last, however, I found one door at the top of the
U||   stairway which, though it seemed to be locked, gave a little under
U||   pressure. I tried it harder, and found that it was not really locked,
U||   but that the resistance came from the fact that the hinges had fallen
U||   somewhat, and the heavy door rested on the floor. Here was an
U||   opportunity which I might not have again, so I exerted myself, and with
U||   many efforts forced it back so that I could enter. I was now in a wing
U||   of the castle further to the right than the rooms I knew and a storey
U||   lower down. From the windows I could see that the suite of rooms lay
U||   along to the south of the castle, the windows of the end room looking
U||   out both west and south. On the latter side, as well as to the former,
U||   there was a great precipice. The castle was built on the corner of a
U||   great rock, so that on three sides it was quite impregnable, and great
U||   windows were placed here where sling, or bow, or culverin could not
U||   reach, and consequently light and comfort, impossible to a position
U||   which had to be guarded, were secured. To the west was a great valley,
U||   and then, rising far away, great jagged mountain fastnesses, rising
U||   peak on peak, the sheer rock studded with mountain ash and thorn, whose
U||   roots clung in cracks and crevices and crannies of the stone. This was
U||   evidently the portion of the castle occupied by the ladies in bygone
U||   days, for the furniture had more air of comfort than any I had seen.
U||   The windows were curtainless, and the yellow moonlight, flooding in
U||   through the diamond panes, enabled one to see even colours, whilst it
U||   softened the wealth of dust which lay over all and disguised in some
U||   measure the ravages of time and the moth. My lamp seemed to be of
U||   little effect in the brilliant moonlight, but I was glad to have it
U||   with me, for there was a dread loneliness in the place which chilled my
U||   heart and made my nerves tremble. Still, it was better than living
U||   alone in the rooms which I had come to hate from the presence of the
U||   Count, and after trying a little to school my nerves, I found a soft
U||   quietude come over me. Here I am, sitting at a little oak table where
U||   in old times possibly some fair lady sat to pen, with much thought and
U||   many blushes, her ill-spelt love-letter, and writing in my diary in
U||   shorthand all that has happened since I closed it last. It is
U||   nineteenth century up-to-date with a vengeance. And yet, unless my
U||   senses deceive me, the old centuries had, and have, powers of their own
U||   which mere “modernity” cannot kill.
U||   Later: the Morning of 16 May.—God preserve my sanity, for to this I am
U||   reduced. Safety and the assurance of safety are things of the past.
U||   Whilst I live on here there is but one thing to hope for, that I may
U||   not go mad, if, indeed, I be not mad already. If I be sane, then surely
U||   it is maddening to think that of all the foul things that lurk in this
U||   hateful place the Count is the least dreadful to me; that to him alone
U||   I can look for safety, even though this be only whilst I can serve his
U||   purpose. Great God! merciful God! Let me be calm, for out of that way
U||   lies madness indeed. I begin to get new lights on certain things which
U||   have puzzled me. Up to now I never quite knew what Shakespeare meant
U||   when he made Hamlet say:—
U||   “My tablets! quick, my tablets!
U||   ’Tis meet that I put it down,” etc.,
U||   for now, feeling as though my own brain were unhinged or as if the
U||   shock had come which must end in its undoing, I turn to my diary for
U||   repose. The habit of entering accurately must help to soothe me.
U||   The Count’s mysterious warning frightened me at the time; it frightens
U||   me more now when I think of it, for in future he has a fearful hold
U||   upon me. I shall fear to doubt what he may say!
U||   When I had written in my diary and had fortunately replaced the book
U||   and pen in my pocket I felt sleepy. The Count’s warning came into my
U||   mind, but I took a pleasure in disobeying it. The sense of sleep was
U||   upon me, and with it the obstinacy which sleep brings as outrider. The
U||   soft moonlight soothed, and the wide expanse without gave a sense of
U||   freedom which refreshed me. I determined not to return to-night to the
U||   gloom-haunted rooms, but to sleep here, where, of old, ladies had sat
U||   and sung and lived sweet lives whilst their gentle breasts were sad for
U||   their menfolk away in the midst of remorseless wars. I drew a great
U||   couch out of its place near the corner, so that as I lay, I could look
U||   at the lovely view to east and south, and unthinking of and uncaring
U||   for the dust, composed myself for sleep. I suppose I must have fallen
U||   asleep; I hope so, but I fear, for all that followed was startlingly
U||   real—so real that now sitting here in the broad, full sunlight of the
U||   morning, I cannot in the least believe that it was all sleep.
U||   I was not alone. The room was the same, unchanged in any way since I
U||   came into it; I could see along the floor, in the brilliant moonlight,
U||   my own footsteps marked where I had disturbed the long accumulation of
U||   dust. In the moonlight opposite me were three young women, ladies by
U||   their dress and manner. I thought at the time that I must be dreaming
U||   when I saw them, for, though the moonlight was behind them, they threw
U||   no shadow on the floor. They came close to me, and looked at me for
U||   some time, and then whispered together. Two were dark, and had high
U||   aquiline noses, like the Count, and great dark, piercing eyes that
U||   seemed to be almost red when contrasted with the pale yellow moon. The
U||   other was fair, as fair as can be, with great wavy masses of golden
U||   hair and eyes like pale sapphires. I seemed somehow to know her face,
U||   and to know it in connection with some dreamy fear, but I could not
U||   recollect at the moment how or where. All three had brilliant white
U||   teeth that shone like pearls against the ruby of their voluptuous lips.
U||   There was something about them that made me uneasy, some longing and at
U||   the same time some deadly fear. I felt in my heart a wicked, burning
U||   desire that they would kiss me with those red lips. It is not good to
U||   note this down, lest some day it should meet Mina’s eyes and cause her
U||   pain; but it is the truth. They whispered together, and then they all
U||   three laughed—such a silvery, musical laugh, but as hard as though the
U||   sound never could have come through the softness of human lips. It was
U||   like the intolerable, tingling sweetness of water-glasses when played
U||   on by a cunning hand. The fair girl shook her head coquettishly, and
U||   the other two urged her on. One said:—
U||   “Go on! You are first, and we shall follow; yours is the right to
U||   begin.” The other added:—
U||   “He is young and strong; there are kisses for us all.” I lay quiet,
U||   looking out under my eyelashes in an agony of delightful anticipation.
U||   The fair girl advanced and bent over me till I could feel the movement
U||   of her breath upon me. Sweet it was in one sense, honey-sweet, and sent
U||   the same tingling through the nerves as her voice, but with a bitter
U||   underlying the sweet, a bitter offensiveness, as one smells in blood.
U||   I was afraid to raise my eyelids, but looked out and saw perfectly
U||   under the lashes. The girl went on her knees, and bent over me, simply
U||   gloating. There was a deliberate voluptuousness which was both
U||   thrilling and repulsive, and as she arched her neck she actually licked
U||   her lips like an animal, till I could see in the moonlight the moisture
U||   shining on the scarlet lips and on the red tongue as it lapped the
U||   white sharp teeth. Lower and lower went her head as the lips went below
U||   the range of my mouth and chin and seemed about to fasten on my throat.
U||   Then she paused, and I could hear the churning sound of her tongue as
U||   it licked her teeth and lips, and could feel the hot breath on my neck.
U||   Then the skin of my throat began to tingle as one’s flesh does when the
U||   hand that is to tickle it approaches nearer—nearer. I could feel the
U||   soft, shivering touch of the lips on the super-sensitive skin of my
U||   throat, and the hard dents of two sharp teeth, just touching and
U||   pausing there. I closed my eyes in a languorous ecstasy and
U||   waited—waited with beating heart.
U||   But at that instant, another sensation swept through me as quick as
U||   lightning. I was conscious of the presence of the Count, and of his
U||   being as if lapped in a storm of fury. As my eyes opened involuntarily
U||   I saw his strong hand grasp the slender neck of the fair woman and with
U||   giant’s power draw it back, the blue eyes transformed with fury, the
U||   white teeth champing with rage, and the fair cheeks blazing red with
U||   passion. But the Count! Never did I imagine such wrath and fury, even
U||   to the demons of the pit. His eyes were positively blazing. The red
U||   light in them was lurid, as if the flames of hell-fire blazed behind
U||   them. His face was deathly pale, and the lines of it were hard like
U||   drawn wires; the thick eyebrows that met over the nose now seemed like
U||   a heaving bar of white-hot metal. With a fierce sweep of his arm, he
U||   hurled the woman from him, and then motioned to the others, as though
U||   he were beating them back; it was the same imperious gesture that I had
U||   seen used to the wolves. In a voice which, though low and almost in a
U||   whisper seemed to cut through the air and then ring round the room he
U||   said:—
U||   “How dare you touch him, any of you? How dare you cast eyes on him when
U||   I had forbidden it? Back, I tell you all! This man belongs to me!
U||   Beware how you meddle with him, or you’ll have to deal with me.” The
U||   fair girl, with a laugh of ribald coquetry, turned to answer him:—
U||   “You yourself never loved; you never love!” On this the other women
U||   joined, and such a mirthless, hard, soulless laughter rang through the
U||   room that it almost made me faint to hear; it seemed like the pleasure
U||   of fiends. Then the Count turned, after looking at my face attentively,
U||   and said in a soft whisper:—
U||   “Yes, I too can love; you yourselves can tell it from the past. Is it
U||   not so? Well, now I promise you that when I am done with him you shall
U||   kiss him at your will. Now go! go! I must awaken him, for there is work
U||   to be done.”
U||   “Are we to have nothing to-night?” said one of them, with a low laugh,
U||   as she pointed to the bag which he had thrown upon the floor, and which
U||   moved as though there were some living thing within it. For answer he
U||   nodded his head. One of the women jumped forward and opened it. If my
U||   ears did not deceive me there was a gasp and a low wail, as of a
U||   half-smothered child. The women closed round, whilst I was aghast with
U||   horror; but as I looked they disappeared, and with them the dreadful
U||   bag. There was no door near them, and they could not have passed me
U||   without my noticing. They simply seemed to fade into the rays of the
U||   moonlight and pass out through the window, for I could see outside the
U||   dim, shadowy forms for a moment before they entirely faded away.
U||   Then the horror overcame me, and I sank down unconscious.
U||CHAPTER IV
U||JONATHAN HARKER’S JOURNAL—continued
U||   I AWOKE in my own bed. If it be that I had not dreamt, the Count must
U||   have carried me here. I tried to satisfy myself on the subject, but
U||   could not arrive at any unquestionable result. To be sure, there were
U||   certain small evidences, such as that my clothes were folded and laid
U||   by in a manner which was not my habit. My watch was still unwound, and
U||   I am rigorously accustomed to wind it the last thing before going to
U||   bed, and many such details. But these things are no proof, for they may
U||   have been evidences that my mind was not as usual, and, from some cause
U||   or another, I had certainly been much upset. I must watch for proof. Of
U||   one thing I am glad: if it was that the Count carried me here and
U||   undressed me, he must have been hurried in his task, for my pockets are
U||   intact. I am sure this diary would have been a mystery to him which he
U||   would not have brooked. He would have taken or destroyed it. As I look
U||   round this room, although it has been to me so full of fear, it is now
U||   a sort of sanctuary, for nothing can be more dreadful than those awful
U||   women, who were—who are—waiting to suck my blood.
U||   18 May.—I have been down to look at that room again in daylight, for I
U||   must know the truth. When I got to the doorway at the top of the stairs
U||   I found it closed. It had been so forcibly driven against the jamb that
U||   part of the woodwork was splintered. I could see that the bolt of the
U||   lock had not been shot, but the door is fastened from the inside. I
U||   fear it was no dream, and must act on this surmise.
U||   19 May.—I am surely in the toils. Last night the Count asked me in the
U||   suavest tones to write three letters, one saying that my work here was
U||   nearly done, and that I should start for home within a few days,
U||   another that I was starting on the next morning from the time of the
U||   letter, and the third that I had left the castle and arrived at
U||   Bistritz. I would fain have rebelled, but felt that in the present
U||   state of things it would be madness to quarrel openly with the Count
U||   whilst I am so absolutely in his power; and to refuse would be to
U||   excite his suspicion and to arouse his anger. He knows that I know too
U||   much, and that I must not live, lest I be dangerous to him; my only
U||   chance is to prolong my opportunities. Something may occur which will
U||   give me a chance to escape. I saw in his eyes something of that
U||   gathering wrath which was manifest when he hurled that fair woman from
U||   him. He explained to me that posts were few and uncertain, and that my
U||   writing now would ensure ease of mind to my friends; and he assured me
U||   with so much impressiveness that he would countermand the later
U||   letters, which would be held over at Bistritz until due time in case
U||   chance would admit of my prolonging my stay, that to oppose him would
U||   have been to create new suspicion. I therefore pretended to fall in
U||   with his views, and asked him what dates I should put on the letters.
U||   He calculated a minute, and then said:—
U||   “The first should be June 12, the second June 19, and the third June
U||   29.”
U||   I know now the span of my life. God help me!
U||   28 May.—There is a chance of escape, or at any rate of being able to
U||   send word home. A band of Szgany have come to the castle, and are
U||   encamped in the courtyard. These Szgany are gipsies; I have notes of
U||   them in my book. They are peculiar to this part of the world, though
U||   allied to the ordinary gipsies all the world over. There are thousands
U||   of them in Hungary and Transylvania, who are almost outside all law.
U||   They attach themselves as a rule to some great noble or boyar, and call
U||   themselves by his name. They are fearless and without religion, save
U||   superstition, and they talk only their own varieties of the Romany
U||   tongue.
U||   I shall write some letters home, and shall try to get them to have them
U||   posted. I have already spoken them through my window to begin
U||   acquaintanceship. They took their hats off and made obeisance and many
U||   signs, which, however, I could not understand any more than I could
U||   their spoken language....
U||   I have written the letters. Mina’s is in shorthand, and I simply ask
U||   Mr. Hawkins to communicate with her. To her I have explained my
U||   situation, but without the horrors which I may only surmise. It would
U||   shock and frighten her to death were I to expose my heart to her.
U||   Should the letters not carry, then the Count shall not yet know my
U||   secret or the extent of my knowledge....
U||   I have given the letters; I threw them through the bars of my window
U||   with a gold piece, and made what signs I could to have them posted. The
U||   man who took them pressed them to his heart and bowed, and then put
U||   them in his cap. I could do no more. I stole back to the study, and
U||   began to read. As the Count did not come in, I have written here....
U||   The Count has come. He sat down beside me, and said in his smoothest
U||   voice as he opened two letters:—
U||   “The Szgany has given me these, of which, though I know not whence they
U||   come, I shall, of course, take care. See!”—he must have looked at
U||   it—“one is from you, and to my friend Peter Hawkins; the other”—here he
U||   caught sight of the strange symbols as he opened the envelope, and the
U||   dark look came into his face, and his eyes blazed wickedly—“the other
U||   is a vile thing, an outrage upon friendship and hospitality! It is not
U||   signed. Well! so it cannot matter to us.” And he calmly held letter and
U||   envelope in the flame of the lamp till they were consumed. Then he went
U||   on:—
U||   “The letter to Hawkins—that I shall, of course, send on, since it is
U||   yours. Your letters are sacred to me. Your pardon, my friend, that
U||   unknowingly I did break the seal. Will you not cover it again?” He held
U||   out the letter to me, and with a courteous bow handed me a clean
U||   envelope. I could only redirect it and hand it to him in silence. When
U||   he went out of the room I could hear the key turn softly. A minute
U||   later I went over and tried it, and the door was locked.
U||   When, an hour or two after, the Count came quietly into the room, his
U||   coming awakened me, for I had gone to sleep on the sofa. He was very
U||   courteous and very cheery in his manner, and seeing that I had been
U||   sleeping, he said:—
U||   “So, my friend, you are tired? Get to bed. There is the surest rest. I
U||   may not have the pleasure to talk to-night, since there are many
U||   labours to me; but you will sleep, I pray.” I passed to my room and
U||   went to bed, and, strange to say, slept without dreaming. Despair has
U||   its own calms.
U||   31 May.—This morning when I woke I thought I would provide myself with
U||   some paper and envelopes from my bag and keep them in my pocket, so
U||   that I might write in case I should get an opportunity, but again a
U||   surprise, again a shock!
U||   Every scrap of paper was gone, and with it all my notes, my memoranda,
U||   relating to railways and travel, my letter of credit, in fact all that
U||   might be useful to me were I once outside the castle. I sat and
U||   pondered awhile, and then some thought occurred to me, and I made
U||   search of my portmanteau and in the wardrobe where I had placed my
U||   clothes.
U||   The suit in which I had travelled was gone, and also my overcoat and
U||   rug; I could find no trace of them anywhere. This looked like some new
U||   scheme of villainy....
U||   17 June.—This morning, as I was sitting on the edge of my bed
U||   cudgelling my brains, I heard without a cracking of whips and pounding
U||   and scraping of horses’ feet up the rocky path beyond the courtyard.
U||   With joy I hurried to the window, and saw drive into the yard two great
U||   leiter-wagons, each drawn by eight sturdy horses, and at the head of
U||   each pair a Slovak, with his wide hat, great nail-studded belt, dirty
U||   sheepskin, and high boots. They had also their long staves in hand. I
U||   ran to the door, intending to descend and try and join them through the
U||   main hall, as I thought that way might be opened for them. Again a
U||   shock: my door was fastened on the outside.
U||   Then I ran to the window and cried to them. They looked up at me
U||   stupidly and pointed, but just then the “hetman” of the Szgany came
U||   out, and seeing them pointing to my window, said something, at which
U||   they laughed. Henceforth no effort of mine, no piteous cry or agonised
U||   entreaty, would make them even look at me. They resolutely turned away.
U||   The leiter-wagons contained great, square boxes, with handles of thick
U||   rope; these were evidently empty by the ease with which the Slovaks
U||   handled them, and by their resonance as they were roughly moved. When
U||   they were all unloaded and packed in a great heap in one corner of the
U||   yard, the Slovaks were given some money by the Szgany, and spitting on
U||   it for luck, lazily went each to his horse’s head. Shortly afterwards,
U||   I heard the cracking of their whips die away in the distance.
U||   24 June, before morning.—Last night the Count left me early, and locked
U||   himself into his own room. As soon as I dared I ran up the winding
U||   stair, and looked out of the window, which opened south. I thought I
U||   would watch for the Count, for there is something going on. The Szgany
U||   are quartered somewhere in the castle and are doing work of some kind.
U||   I know it, for now and then I hear a far-away muffled sound as of
U||   mattock and spade, and, whatever it is, it must be the end of some
U||   ruthless villainy.
U||   I had been at the window somewhat less than half an hour, when I saw
U||   something coming out of the Count’s window. I drew back and watched
U||   carefully, and saw the whole man emerge. It was a new shock to me to
U||   find that he had on the suit of clothes which I had worn whilst
U||   travelling here, and slung over his shoulder the terrible bag which I
U||   had seen the women take away. There could be no doubt as to his quest,
U||   and in my garb, too! This, then, is his new scheme of evil: that he
U||   will allow others to see me, as they think, so that he may both leave
U||   evidence that I have been seen in the towns or villages posting my own
U||   letters, and that any wickedness which he may do shall by the local
U||   people be attributed to me.
U||   It makes me rage to think that this can go on, and whilst I am shut up
U||   here, a veritable prisoner, but without that protection of the law
U||   which is even a criminal’s right and consolation.
U||   I thought I would watch for the Count’s return, and for a long time sat
U||   doggedly at the window. Then I began to notice that there were some
U||   quaint little specks floating in the rays of the moonlight. They were
U||   like the tiniest grains of dust, and they whirled round and gathered in
U||   clusters in a nebulous sort of way. I watched them with a sense of
U||   soothing, and a sort of calm stole over me. I leaned back in the
U||   embrasure in a more comfortable position, so that I could enjoy more
U||   fully the aërial gambolling.
U||   Something made me start up, a low, piteous howling of dogs somewhere
U||   far below in the valley, which was hidden from my sight. Louder it
U||   seemed to ring in my ears, and the floating motes of dust to take new
U||   shapes to the sound as they danced in the moonlight. I felt myself
U||   struggling to awake to some call of my instincts; nay, my very soul was
U||   struggling, and my half-remembered sensibilities were striving to
U||   answer the call. I was becoming hypnotised! Quicker and quicker danced
U||   the dust; the moonbeams seemed to quiver as they went by me into the
U||   mass of gloom beyond. More and more they gathered till they seemed to
U||   take dim phantom shapes. And then I started, broad awake and in full
U||   possession of my senses, and ran screaming from the place. The phantom
U||   shapes, which were becoming gradually materialised from the moonbeams,
U||   were those of the three ghostly women to whom I was doomed. I fled, and
U||   felt somewhat safer in my own room, where there was no moonlight and
U||   where the lamp was burning brightly.
U||   When a couple of hours had passed I heard something stirring in the
U||   Count’s room, something like a sharp wail quickly suppressed; and then
U||   there was silence, deep, awful silence, which chilled me. With a
U||   beating heart, I tried the door; but I was locked in my prison, and
U||   could do nothing. I sat down and simply cried.
U||   As I sat I heard a sound in the courtyard without—the agonised cry of a
U||   woman. I rushed to the window, and throwing it up, peered out between
U||   the bars. There, indeed, was a woman with dishevelled hair, holding her
U||   hands over her heart as one distressed with running. She was leaning
U||   against a corner of the gateway. When she saw my face at the window she
U||   threw herself forward, and shouted in a voice laden with menace:—
U||   “Monster, give me my child!”
U||   She threw herself on her knees, and raising up her hands, cried the
U||   same words in tones which wrung my heart. Then she tore her hair and
U||   beat her breast, and abandoned herself to all the violences of
U||   extravagant emotion. Finally, she threw herself forward, and, though I
U||   could not see her, I could hear the beating of her naked hands against
U||   the door.
U||   Somewhere high overhead, probably on the tower, I heard the voice of
U||   the Count calling in his harsh, metallic whisper. His call seemed to be
U||   answered from far and wide by the howling of wolves. Before many
U||   minutes had passed a pack of them poured, like a pent-up dam when
U||   liberated, through the wide entrance into the courtyard.
U||   There was no cry from the woman, and the howling of the wolves was but
U||   short. Before long they streamed away singly, licking their lips.
U||   I could not pity her, for I knew now what had become of her child, and
U||   she was better dead.
U||   What shall I do? what can I do? How can I escape from this dreadful
U||   thing of night and gloom and fear?
U||   25 June, morning.—No man knows till he has suffered from the night how
U||   sweet and how dear to his heart and eye the morning can be. When the
U||   sun grew so high this morning that it struck the top of the great
U||   gateway opposite my window, the high spot which it touched seemed to me
U||   as if the dove from the ark had lighted there. My fear fell from me as
U||   if it had been a vaporous garment which dissolved in the warmth. I must
U||   take action of some sort whilst the courage of the day is upon me. Last
U||   night one of my post-dated letters went to post, the first of that
U||   fatal series which is to blot out the very traces of my existence from
U||   the earth.
U||   Let me not think of it. Action!
U||   It has always been at night-time that I have been molested or
U||   threatened, or in some way in danger or in fear. I have not yet seen
U||   the Count in the daylight. Can it be that he sleeps when others wake,
U||   that he may be awake whilst they sleep? If I could only get into his
U||   room! But there is no possible way. The door is always locked, no way
U||   for me.
U||   Yes, there is a way, if one dares to take it. Where his body has gone
U||   why may not another body go? I have seen him myself crawl from his
U||   window. Why should not I imitate him, and go in by his window? The
U||   chances are desperate, but my need is more desperate still. I shall
U||   risk it. At the worst it can only be death; and a man’s death is not a
U||   calf’s, and the dreaded Hereafter may still be open to me. God help me
U||   in my task! Good-bye, Mina, if I fail; good-bye, my faithful friend and
U||   second father; good-bye, all, and last of all Mina!
U||   Same day, later.—I have made the effort, and God, helping me, have come
U||   safely back to this room. I must put down every detail in order. I went
U||   whilst my courage was fresh straight to the window on the south side,
U||   and at once got outside on the narrow ledge of stone which runs around
U||   the building on this side. The stones are big and roughly cut, and the
U||   mortar has by process of time been washed away between them. I took off
U||   my boots, and ventured out on the desperate way. I looked down once, so
U||   as to make sure that a sudden glimpse of the awful depth would not
U||   overcome me, but after that kept my eyes away from it. I knew pretty
U||   well the direction and distance of the Count’s window, and made for it
U||   as well as I could, having regard to the opportunities available. I did
U||   not feel dizzy—I suppose I was too excited—and the time seemed
U||   ridiculously short till I found myself standing on the window-sill and
U||   trying to raise up the sash. I was filled with agitation, however, when
U||   I bent down and slid feet foremost in through the window. Then I looked
U||   around for the Count, but, with surprise and gladness, made a
U||   discovery. The room was empty! It was barely furnished with odd things,
U||   which seemed to have never been used; the furniture was something the
U||   same style as that in the south rooms, and was covered with dust. I
U||   looked for the key, but it was not in the lock, and I could not find it
U||   anywhere. The only thing I found was a great heap of gold in one
U||   corner—gold of all kinds, Roman, and British, and Austrian, and
U||   Hungarian, and Greek and Turkish money, covered with a film of dust, as
U||   though it had lain long in the ground. None of it that I noticed was
U||   less than three hundred years old. There were also chains and
U||   ornaments, some jewelled, but all of them old and stained.
U||   At one corner of the room was a heavy door. I tried it, for, since I
U||   could not find the key of the room or the key of the outer door, which
U||   was the main object of my search, I must make further examination, or
U||   all my efforts would be in vain. It was open, and led through a stone
U||   passage to a circular stairway, which went steeply down. I descended,
U||   minding carefully where I went, for the stairs were dark, being only
U||   lit by loopholes in the heavy masonry. At the bottom there was a dark,
U||   tunnel-like passage, through which came a deathly, sickly odour, the
U||   odour of old earth newly turned. As I went through the passage the
U||   smell grew closer and heavier. At last I pulled open a heavy door which
U||   stood ajar, and found myself in an old, ruined chapel, which had
U||   evidently been used as a graveyard. The roof was broken, and in two
U||   places were steps leading to vaults, but the ground had recently been
U||   dug over, and the earth placed in great wooden boxes, manifestly those
U||   which had been brought by the Slovaks. There was nobody about, and I
U||   made search for any further outlet, but there was none. Then I went
U||   over every inch of the ground, so as not to lose a chance. I went down
U||   even into the vaults, where the dim light struggled, although to do so
U||   was a dread to my very soul. Into two of these I went, but saw nothing
U||   except fragments of old coffins and piles of dust; in the third,
U||   however, I made a discovery.
U||   There, in one of the great boxes, of which there were fifty in all, on
U||   a pile of newly dug earth, lay the Count! He was either dead or asleep,
U||   I could not say which—for the eyes were open and stony, but without the
U||   glassiness of death—and the cheeks had the warmth of life through all
U||   their pallor; the lips were as red as ever. But there was no sign of
U||   movement, no pulse, no breath, no beating of the heart. I bent over
U||   him, and tried to find any sign of life, but in vain. He could not have
U||   lain there long, for the earthy smell would have passed away in a few
U||   hours. By the side of the box was its cover, pierced with holes here
U||   and there. I thought he might have the keys on him, but when I went to
U||   search I saw the dead eyes, and in them, dead though they were, such a
U||   look of hate, though unconscious of me or my presence, that I fled from
U||   the place, and leaving the Count’s room by the window, crawled again up
U||   the castle wall. Regaining my room, I threw myself panting upon the bed
U||   and tried to think....
U||   29 June.—To-day is the date of my last letter, and the Count has taken
U||   steps to prove that it was genuine, for again I saw him leave the
U||   castle by the same window, and in my clothes. As he went down the wall,
U||   lizard fashion, I wished I had a gun or some lethal weapon, that I
U||   might destroy him; but I fear that no weapon wrought alone by man’s
U||   hand would have any effect on him. I dared not wait to see him return,
U||   for I feared to see those weird sisters. I came back to the library,
U||   and read there till I fell asleep.
U||   I was awakened by the Count, who looked at me as grimly as a man can
U||   look as he said:—
U||   “To-morrow, my friend, we must part. You return to your beautiful
U||   England, I to some work which may have such an end that we may never
U||   meet. Your letter home has been despatched; to-morrow I shall not be
U||   here, but all shall be ready for your journey. In the morning come the
U||   Szgany, who have some labours of their own here, and also come some
U||   Slovaks. When they have gone, my carriage shall come for you, and shall
U||   bear you to the Borgo Pass to meet the diligence from Bukovina to
U||   Bistritz. But I am in hopes that I shall see more of you at Castle
U||   Dracula.” I suspected him, and determined to test his sincerity.
U||   Sincerity! It seems like a profanation of the word to write it in
U||   connection with such a monster, so asked him point-blank:—
U||   “Why may I not go to-night?”
U||   “Because, dear sir, my coachman and horses are away on a mission.”
U||   “But I would walk with pleasure. I want to get away at once.” He
U||   smiled, such a soft, smooth, diabolical smile that I knew there was
U||   some trick behind his smoothness. He said:—
U||   “And your baggage?”
U||   “I do not care about it. I can send for it some other time.”
U||   The Count stood up, and said, with a sweet courtesy which made me rub
U||   my eyes, it seemed so real:—
U||   “You English have a saying which is close to my heart, for its spirit
U||   is that which rules our boyars: ‘Welcome the coming; speed the parting
U||   guest.’ Come with me, my dear young friend. Not an hour shall you wait
U||   in my house against your will, though sad am I at your going, and that
U||   you so suddenly desire it. Come!” With a stately gravity, he, with the
U||   lamp, preceded me down the stairs and along the hall. Suddenly he
U||   stopped.
U||   “Hark!”
U||   Close at hand came the howling of many wolves. It was almost as if the
U||   sound sprang up at the rising of his hand, just as the music of a great
U||   orchestra seems to leap under the bâton of the conductor. After a pause
U||   of a moment, he proceeded, in his stately way, to the door, drew back
U||   the ponderous bolts, unhooked the heavy chains, and began to draw it
U||   open.
U||   To my intense astonishment I saw that it was unlocked. Suspiciously, I
U||   looked all round, but could see no key of any kind.
U||   As the door began to open, the howling of the wolves without grew
U||   louder and angrier; their red jaws, with champing teeth, and their
U||   blunt-clawed feet as they leaped, came in through the opening door. I
U||   knew then that to struggle at the moment against the Count was useless.
U||   With such allies as these at his command, I could do nothing. But still
U||   the door continued slowly to open, and only the Count’s body stood in
U||   the gap. Suddenly it struck me that this might be the moment and means
U||   of my doom; I was to be given to the wolves, and at my own instigation.
U||   There was a diabolical wickedness in the idea great enough for the
U||   Count, and as a last chance I cried out:—
U||   “Shut the door; I shall wait till morning!” and covered my face with my
U||   hands to hide my tears of bitter disappointment. With one sweep of his
U||   powerful arm, the Count threw the door shut, and the great bolts
U||   clanged and echoed through the hall as they shot back into their
U||   places.
U||   In silence we returned to the library, and after a minute or two I went
U||   to my own room. The last I saw of Count Dracula was his kissing his
U||   hand to me; with a red light of triumph in his eyes, and with a smile
U||   that Judas in hell might be proud of.
U||   When I was in my room and about to lie down, I thought I heard a
U||   whispering at my door. I went to it softly and listened. Unless my ears
U||   deceived me, I heard the voice of the Count:—
U||   “Back, back, to your own place! Your time is not yet come. Wait! Have
U||   patience! To-night is mine. To-morrow night is yours!” There was a low,
U||   sweet ripple of laughter, and in a rage I threw open the door, and saw
U||   without the three terrible women licking their lips. As I appeared they
U||   all joined in a horrible laugh, and ran away.
U||   I came back to my room and threw myself on my knees. It is then so near
U||   the end? To-morrow! to-morrow! Lord, help me, and those to whom I am
U||   dear!
U||   30 June, morning.—These may be the last words I ever write in this
U||   diary. I slept till just before the dawn, and when I woke threw myself
U||   on my knees, for I determined that if Death came he should find me
U||   ready.
U||   At last I felt that subtle change in the air, and knew that the morning
U||   had come. Then came the welcome cock-crow, and I felt that I was safe.
U||   With a glad heart, I opened my door and ran down to the hall. I had
U||   seen that the door was unlocked, and now escape was before me. With
U||   hands that trembled with eagerness, I unhooked the chains and drew back
U||   the massive bolts.
U||   But the door would not move. Despair seized me. I pulled, and pulled,
U||   at the door, and shook it till, massive as it was, it rattled in its
U||   casement. I could see the bolt shot. It had been locked after I left
U||   the Count.
U||   Then a wild desire took me to obtain that key at any risk, and I
U||   determined then and there to scale the wall again and gain the Count’s
U||   room. He might kill me, but death now seemed the happier choice of
U||   evils. Without a pause I rushed up to the east window, and scrambled
U||   down the wall, as before, into the Count’s room. It was empty, but that
U||   was as I expected. I could not see a key anywhere, but the heap of gold
U||   remained. I went through the door in the corner and down the winding
U||   stair and along the dark passage to the old chapel. I knew now well
U||   enough where to find the monster I sought.
U||   The great box was in the same place, close against the wall, but the
U||   lid was laid on it, not fastened down, but with the nails ready in
U||   their places to be hammered home. I knew I must reach the body for the
U||   key, so I raised the lid, and laid it back against the wall; and then I
U||   saw something which filled my very soul with horror. There lay the
U||   Count, but looking as if his youth had been half renewed, for the white
U||   hair and moustache were changed to dark iron-grey; the cheeks were
U||   fuller, and the white skin seemed ruby-red underneath; the mouth was
U||   redder than ever, for on the lips were gouts of fresh blood, which
U||   trickled from the corners of the mouth and ran over the chin and neck.
U||   Even the deep, burning eyes seemed set amongst swollen flesh, for the
U||   lids and pouches underneath were bloated. It seemed as if the whole
U||   awful creature were simply gorged with blood. He lay like a filthy
U||   leech, exhausted with his repletion. I shuddered as I bent over to
U||   touch him, and every sense in me revolted at the contact; but I had to
U||   search, or I was lost. The coming night might see my own body a banquet
U||   in a similar way to those horrid three. I felt all over the body, but
U||   no sign could I find of the key. Then I stopped and looked at the
U||   Count. There was a mocking smile on the bloated face which seemed to
U||   drive me mad. This was the being I was helping to transfer to London,
U||   where, perhaps, for centuries to come he might, amongst its teeming
U||   millions, satiate his lust for blood, and create a new and
U||   ever-widening circle of semi-demons to batten on the helpless. The very
U||   thought drove me mad. A terrible desire came upon me to rid the world
U||   of such a monster. There was no lethal weapon at hand, but I seized a
U||   shovel which the workmen had been using to fill the cases, and lifting
U||   it high, struck, with the edge downward, at the hateful face. But as I
U||   did so the head turned, and the eyes fell full upon me, with all their
U||   blaze of basilisk horror. The sight seemed to paralyse me, and the
U||   shovel turned in my hand and glanced from the face, merely making a
U||   deep gash above the forehead. The shovel fell from my hand across the
U||   box, and as I pulled it away the flange of the blade caught the edge of
U||   the lid which fell over again, and hid the horrid thing from my sight.
U||   The last glimpse I had was of the bloated face, blood-stained and fixed
U||   with a grin of malice which would have held its own in the nethermost
U||   hell.
U||   I thought and thought what should be my next move, but my brain seemed
U||   on fire, and I waited with a despairing feeling growing over me. As I
U||   waited I heard in the distance a gipsy song sung by merry voices coming
U||   closer, and through their song the rolling of heavy wheels and the
U||   cracking of whips; the Szgany and the Slovaks of whom the Count had
U||   spoken were coming. With a last look around and at the box which
U||   contained the vile body, I ran from the place and gained the Count’s
U||   room, determined to rush out at the moment the door should be opened.
U||   With strained ears, I listened, and heard downstairs the grinding of
U||   the key in the great lock and the falling back of the heavy door. There
U||   must have been some other means of entry, or some one had a key for one
U||   of the locked doors. Then there came the sound of many feet tramping
U||   and dying away in some passage which sent up a clanging echo. I turned
U||   to run down again towards the vault, where I might find the new
U||   entrance; but at the moment there seemed to come a violent puff of
U||   wind, and the door to the winding stair blew to with a shock that set
U||   the dust from the lintels flying. When I ran to push it open, I found
U||   that it was hopelessly fast. I was again a prisoner, and the net of
U||   doom was closing round me more closely.
U||   As I write there is in the passage below a sound of many tramping feet
U||   and the crash of weights being set down heavily, doubtless the boxes,
U||   with their freight of earth. There is a sound of hammering; it is the
U||   box being nailed down. Now I can hear the heavy feet tramping again
U||   along the hall, with many other idle feet coming behind them.
U||   The door is shut, and the chains rattle; there is a grinding of the key
U||   in the lock; I can hear the key withdraw: then another door opens and
U||   shuts; I hear the creaking of lock and bolt.
U||   Hark! in the courtyard and down the rocky way the roll of heavy wheels,
U||   the crack of whips, and the chorus of the Szgany as they pass into the
U||   distance.
U||   I am alone in the castle with those awful women. Faugh! Mina is a
U||   woman, and there is nought in common. They are devils of the Pit!
U||   I shall not remain alone with them; I shall try to scale the castle
U||   wall farther than I have yet attempted. I shall take some of the gold
U||   with me, lest I want it later. I may find a way from this dreadful
U||   place.
U||   And then away for home! away to the quickest and nearest train! away
U||   from this cursed spot, from this cursed land, where the devil and his
U||   children still walk with earthly feet!
U||   At least God’s mercy is better than that of these monsters, and the
U||   precipice is steep and high. At its foot a man may sleep—as a man.
U||   Good-bye, all! Mina!
U||CHAPTER V
U||   Letter from Miss Mina Murray to Miss Lucy Westenra.
U||   “9 May.
U||   “My dearest Lucy,—
U||   “Forgive my long delay in writing, but I have been simply overwhelmed
U||   with work. The life of an assistant schoolmistress is sometimes trying.
U||   I am longing to be with you, and by the sea, where we can talk together
U||   freely and build our castles in the air. I have been working very hard
U||   lately, because I want to keep up with Jonathan’s studies, and I have
U||   been practising shorthand very assiduously. When we are married I shall
U||   be able to be useful to Jonathan, and if I can stenograph well enough I
U||   can take down what he wants to say in this way and write it out for him
U||   on the typewriter, at which also I am practising very hard. He and I
U||   sometimes write letters in shorthand, and he is keeping a stenographic
U||   journal of his travels abroad. When I am with you I shall keep a diary
U||   in the same way. I don’t mean one of those
U||   two-pages-to-the-week-with-Sunday-squeezed-in-a-corner diaries, but a
U||   sort of journal which I can write in whenever I feel inclined. I do not
U||   suppose there will be much of interest to other people; but it is not
U||   intended for them. I may show it to Jonathan some day if there is in it
U||   anything worth sharing, but it is really an exercise book. I shall try
U||   to do what I see lady journalists do: interviewing and writing
U||   descriptions and trying to remember conversations. I am told that, with
U||   a little practice, one can remember all that goes on or that one hears
U||   said during a day. However, we shall see. I will tell you of my little
U||   plans when we meet. I have just had a few hurried lines from Jonathan
U||   from Transylvania. He is well, and will be returning in about a week. I
U||   am longing to hear all his news. It must be so nice to see strange
U||   countries. I wonder if we—I mean Jonathan and I—shall ever see them
U||   together. There is the ten o’clock bell ringing. Good-bye.
U||   “Your loving
U||   “Mina.
U||   “Tell me all the news when you write. You have not told me anything for
U||   a long time. I hear rumours, and especially of a tall, handsome,
U||   curly-haired man???”
U||   Letter, Lucy Westenra to Mina Murray.
U||   “17, Chatham Street,
U||   “Wednesday.
U||   “My dearest Mina,—
U||   “I must say you tax me very unfairly with being a bad correspondent. I
U||   wrote to you twice since we parted, and your last letter was only your
U||   second. Besides, I have nothing to tell you. There is really nothing to
U||   interest you. Town is very pleasant just now, and we go a good deal to
U||   picture-galleries and for walks and rides in the park. As to the tall,
U||   curly-haired man, I suppose it was the one who was with me at the last
U||   Pop. Some one has evidently been telling tales. That was Mr. Holmwood.
U||   He often comes to see us, and he and mamma get on very well together;
U||   they have so many things to talk about in common. We met some time ago
U||   a man that would just do for you, if you were not already engaged to
U||   Jonathan. He is an excellent parti, being handsome, well off, and of
U||   good birth. He is a doctor and really clever. Just fancy! He is only
U||   nine-and-twenty, and he has an immense lunatic asylum all under his own
U||   care. Mr. Holmwood introduced him to me, and he called here to see us,
U||   and often comes now. I think he is one of the most resolute men I ever
U||   saw, and yet the most calm. He seems absolutely imperturbable. I can
U||   fancy what a wonderful power he must have over his patients. He has a
U||   curious habit of looking one straight in the face, as if trying to read
U||   one’s thoughts. He tries this on very much with me, but I flatter
U||   myself he has got a tough nut to crack. I know that from my glass. Do
U||   you ever try to read your own face? I do, and I can tell you it is not
U||   a bad study, and gives you more trouble than you can well fancy if you
U||   have never tried it. He says that I afford him a curious psychological
U||   study, and I humbly think I do. I do not, as you know, take sufficient
U||   interest in dress to be able to describe the new fashions. Dress is a
U||   bore. That is slang again, but never mind; Arthur says that every day.
U||   There, it is all out. Mina, we have told all our secrets to each other
U||   since we were children; we have slept together and eaten together, and
U||   laughed and cried together; and now, though I have spoken, I would like
U||   to speak more. Oh, Mina, couldn’t you guess? I love him. I am blushing
U||   as I write, for although I think he loves me, he has not told me so in
U||   words. But oh, Mina, I love him; I love him; I love him! There, that
U||   does me good. I wish I were with you, dear, sitting by the fire
U||   undressing, as we used to sit; and I would try to tell you what I feel.
U||   I do not know how I am writing this even to you. I am afraid to stop,
U||   or I should tear up the letter, and I don’t want to stop, for I do so
U||   want to tell you all. Let me hear from you at once, and tell me all
U||   that you think about it. Mina, I must stop. Good-night. Bless me in
U||   your prayers; and, Mina, pray for my happiness.
U||   “LUCY.
U||   “P.S.—I need not tell you this is a secret. Good-night again.
U||   “L.”
U||   Letter, Lucy Westenra to Mina Murray.
U||   “24 May.
U||   “My dearest Mina,—
U||   “Thanks, and thanks, and thanks again for your sweet letter. It was so
U||   nice to be able to tell you and to have your sympathy.
U||   “My dear, it never rains but it pours. How true the old proverbs are.
U||   Here am I, who shall be twenty in September, and yet I never had a
U||   proposal till to-day, not a real proposal, and to-day I have had three.
U||   Just fancy! THREE proposals in one day! Isn’t it awful! I feel sorry,
U||   really and truly sorry, for two of the poor fellows. Oh, Mina, I am so
U||   happy that I don’t know what to do with myself. And three proposals!
U||   But, for goodness’ sake, don’t tell any of the girls, or they would be
U||   getting all sorts of extravagant ideas and imagining themselves injured
U||   and slighted if in their very first day at home they did not get six at
U||   least. Some girls are so vain! You and I, Mina dear, who are engaged
U||   and are going to settle down soon soberly into old married women, can
U||   despise vanity. Well, I must tell you about the three, but you must
U||   keep it a secret, dear, from every one, except, of course, Jonathan.
U||   You will tell him, because I would, if I were in your place, certainly
U||   tell Arthur. A woman ought to tell her husband everything—don’t you
U||   think so, dear?—and I must be fair. Men like women, certainly their
U||   wives, to be quite as fair as they are; and women, I am afraid, are not
U||   always quite as fair as they should be. Well, my dear, number One came
U||   just before lunch. I told you of him, Dr. John Seward, the
U||   lunatic-asylum man, with the strong jaw and the good forehead. He was
U||   very cool outwardly, but was nervous all the same. He had evidently
U||   been schooling himself as to all sorts of little things, and remembered
U||   them; but he almost managed to sit down on his silk hat, which men
U||   don’t generally do when they are cool, and then when he wanted to
U||   appear at ease he kept playing with a lancet in a way that made me
U||   nearly scream. He spoke to me, Mina, very straightforwardly. He told me
U||   how dear I was to him, though he had known me so little, and what his
U||   life would be with me to help and cheer him. He was going to tell me
U||   how unhappy he would be if I did not care for him, but when he saw me
U||   cry he said that he was a brute and would not add to my present
U||   trouble. Then he broke off and asked if I could love him in time; and
U||   when I shook my head his hands trembled, and then with some hesitation
U||   he asked me if I cared already for any one else. He put it very nicely,
U||   saying that he did not want to wring my confidence from me, but only to
U||   know, because if a woman’s heart was free a man might have hope. And
U||   then, Mina, I felt a sort of duty to tell him that there was some one.
U||   I only told him that much, and then he stood up, and he looked very
U||   strong and very grave as he took both my hands in his and said he hoped
U||   I would be happy, and that if I ever wanted a friend I must count him
U||   one of my best. Oh, Mina dear, I can’t help crying: and you must excuse
U||   this letter being all blotted. Being proposed to is all very nice and
U||   all that sort of thing, but it isn’t at all a happy thing when you have
U||   to see a poor fellow, whom you know loves you honestly, going away and
U||   looking all broken-hearted, and to know that, no matter what he may say
U||   at the moment, you are passing quite out of his life. My dear, I must
U||   stop here at present, I feel so miserable, though I am so happy.
U||   “Evening.
U||   “Arthur has just gone, and I feel in better spirits than when I left
U||   off, so I can go on telling you about the day. Well, my dear, number
U||   Two came after lunch. He is such a nice fellow, an American from Texas,
U||   and he looks so young and so fresh that it seems almost impossible that
U||   he has been to so many places and has had such adventures. I sympathise
U||   with poor Desdemona when she had such a dangerous stream poured in her
U||   ear, even by a black man. I suppose that we women are such cowards that
U||   we think a man will save us from fears, and we marry him. I know now
U||   what I would do if I were a man and wanted to make a girl love me. No,
U||   I don’t, for there was Mr. Morris telling us his stories, and Arthur
U||   never told any, and yet—— My dear, I am somewhat previous. Mr. Quincey
U||   P. Morris found me alone. It seems that a man always does find a girl
U||   alone. No, he doesn’t, for Arthur tried twice to make a chance, and I
U||   helping him all I could; I am not ashamed to say it now. I must tell
U||   you beforehand that Mr. Morris doesn’t always speak slang—that is to
U||   say, he never does so to strangers or before them, for he is really
U||   well educated and has exquisite manners—but he found out that it amused
U||   me to hear him talk American slang, and whenever I was present, and
U||   there was no one to be shocked, he said such funny things. I am afraid,
U||   my dear, he has to invent it all, for it fits exactly into whatever
U||   else he has to say. But this is a way slang has. I do not know myself
U||   if I shall ever speak slang; I do not know if Arthur likes it, as I
U||   have never heard him use any as yet. Well, Mr. Morris sat down beside
U||   me and looked as happy and jolly as he could, but I could see all the
U||   same that he was very nervous. He took my hand in his, and said ever so
U||   sweetly:—
U||   “‘Miss Lucy, I know I ain’t good enough to regulate the fixin’s of your
U||   little shoes, but I guess if you wait till you find a man that is you
U||   will go join them seven young women with the lamps when you quit. Won’t
U||   you just hitch up alongside of me and let us go down the long road
U||   together, driving in double harness?’
U||   “Well, he did look so good-humoured and so jolly that it didn’t seem
U||   half so hard to refuse him as it did poor Dr. Seward; so I said, as
U||   lightly as I could, that I did not know anything of hitching, and that
U||   I wasn’t broken to harness at all yet. Then he said that he had spoken
U||   in a light manner, and he hoped that if he had made a mistake in doing
U||   so on so grave, so momentous, an occasion for him, I would forgive him.
U||   He really did look serious when he was saying it, and I couldn’t help
U||   feeling a bit serious too—I know, Mina, you will think me a horrid
U||   flirt—though I couldn’t help feeling a sort of exultation that he was
U||   number two in one day. And then, my dear, before I could say a word he
U||   began pouring out a perfect torrent of love-making, laying his very
U||   heart and soul at my feet. He looked so earnest over it that I shall
U||   never again think that a man must be playful always, and never earnest,
U||   because he is merry at times. I suppose he saw something in my face
U||   which checked him, for he suddenly stopped, and said with a sort of
U||   manly fervour that I could have loved him for if I had been free:—
U||   “‘Lucy, you are an honest-hearted girl, I know. I should not be here
U||   speaking to you as I am now if I did not believe you clean grit, right
U||   through to the very depths of your soul. Tell me, like one good fellow
U||   to another, is there any one else that you care for? And if there is
U||   I’ll never trouble you a hair’s breadth again, but will be, if you will
U||   let me, a very faithful friend.’
U||   “My dear Mina, why are men so noble when we women are so little worthy
U||   of them? Here was I almost making fun of this great-hearted, true
U||   gentleman. I burst into tears—I am afraid, my dear, you will think this
U||   a very sloppy letter in more ways than one—and I really felt very
U||   badly. Why can’t they let a girl marry three men, or as many as want
U||   her, and save all this trouble? But this is heresy, and I must not say
U||   it. I am glad to say that, though I was crying, I was able to look into
U||   Mr. Morris’s brave eyes, and I told him out straight:—
U||   “‘Yes, there is some one I love, though he has not told me yet that he
U||   even loves me.’ I was right to speak to him so frankly, for quite a
U||   light came into his face, and he put out both his hands and took mine—I
U||   think I put them into his—and said in a hearty way:—
U||   “‘That’s my brave girl. It’s better worth being late for a chance of
U||   winning you than being in time for any other girl in the world. Don’t
U||   cry, my dear. If it’s for me, I’m a hard nut to crack; and I take it
U||   standing up. If that other fellow doesn’t know his happiness, well,
U||   he’d better look for it soon, or he’ll have to deal with me. Little
U||   girl, your honesty and pluck have made me a friend, and that’s rarer
U||   than a lover; it’s more unselfish anyhow. My dear, I’m going to have a
U||   pretty lonely walk between this and Kingdom Come. Won’t you give me one
U||   kiss? It’ll be something to keep off the darkness now and then. You
U||   can, you know, if you like, for that other good fellow—he must be a
U||   good fellow, my dear, and a fine fellow, or you could not love
U||   him—hasn’t spoken yet.’ That quite won me, Mina, for it was brave and
U||   sweet of him, and noble, too, to a rival—wasn’t it?—and he so sad; so I
U||   leant over and kissed him. He stood up with my two hands in his, and as
U||   he looked down into my face—I am afraid I was blushing very much—he
U||   said:—
U||   “‘Little girl, I hold your hand, and you’ve kissed me, and if these
U||   things don’t make us friends nothing ever will. Thank you for your
U||   sweet honesty to me, and good-bye.’ He wrung my hand, and taking up his
U||   hat, went straight out of the room without looking back, without a tear
U||   or a quiver or a pause; and I am crying like a baby. Oh, why must a man
U||   like that be made unhappy when there are lots of girls about who would
U||   worship the very ground he trod on? I know I would if I were free—only
U||   I don’t want to be free. My dear, this quite upset me, and I feel I
U||   cannot write of happiness just at once, after telling you of it; and I
U||   don’t wish to tell of the number three until it can be all happy.
U||   “Ever your loving
U||   “Lucy.
U||   “P.S.—Oh, about number Three—I needn’t tell you of number Three, need
U||   I? Besides, it was all so confused; it seemed only a moment from his
U||   coming into the room till both his arms were round me, and he was
U||   kissing me. I am very, very happy, and I don’t know what I have done to
U||   deserve it. I must only try in the future to show that I am not
U||   ungrateful to God for all His goodness to me in sending to me such a
U||   lover, such a husband, and such a friend.
U||   “Good-bye.”
