U||   25 May.—Ebb tide in appetite to-day. Cannot eat, cannot rest, so diary
U||   instead. Since my rebuff of yesterday I have a sort of empty feeling;
U||   nothing in the world seems of sufficient importance to be worth the
U||   doing.... As I knew that the only cure for this sort of thing was work,
U||   I went down amongst the patients. I picked out one who has afforded me
U||   a study of much interest. He is so quaint that I am determined to
U||   understand him as well as I can. To-day I seemed to get nearer than
U||   ever before to the heart of his mystery.
U||   I questioned him more fully than I had ever done, with a view to making
U||   myself master of the facts of his hallucination. In my manner of doing
U||   it there was, I now see, something of cruelty. I seemed to wish to keep
U||   him to the point of his madness—a thing which I avoid with the patients
U||   as I would the mouth of hell.
U||   (Mem., under what circumstances would I not avoid the pit of hell?)
U||   Omnia Romæ venalia sunt. Hell has its price! verb. sap. If there be
U||   anything behind this instinct it will be valuable to trace it
U||   afterwards accurately, so I had better commence to do so, therefore—
U||   R. M. Renfield, ætat 59.—Sanguine temperament; great physical strength;
U||   morbidly excitable; periods of gloom, ending in some fixed idea which I
U||   cannot make out. I presume that the sanguine temperament itself and the
U||   disturbing influence end in a mentally-accomplished finish; a possibly
U||   dangerous man, probably dangerous if unselfish. In selfish men caution
U||   is as secure an armour for their foes as for themselves. What I think
U||   of on this point is, when self is the fixed point the centripetal force
U||   is balanced with the centrifugal; when duty, a cause, etc., is the
U||   fixed point, the latter force is paramount, and only accident or a
U||   series of accidents can balance it.
