U||CHAPTER VI
U||MINA MURRAY’S JOURNAL
U||   24 July. Whitby.—Lucy met me at the station, looking sweeter and
U||   lovelier than ever, and we drove up to the house at the Crescent in
U||   which they have rooms. This is a lovely place. The little river, the
U||   Esk, runs through a deep valley, which broadens out as it comes near
U||   the harbour. A great viaduct runs across, with high piers, through
U||   which the view seems somehow further away than it really is. The valley
U||   is beautifully green, and it is so steep that when you are on the high
U||   land on either side you look right across it, unless you are near
U||   enough to see down. The houses of the old town—the side away from
U||   us—are all red-roofed, and seem piled up one over the other anyhow,
U||   like the pictures we see of Nuremberg. Right over the town is the ruin
U||   of Whitby Abbey, which was sacked by the Danes, and which is the scene
U||   of part of “Marmion,” where the girl was built up in the wall. It is a
U||   most noble ruin, of immense size, and full of beautiful and romantic
U||   bits; there is a legend that a white lady is seen in one of the
U||   windows. Between it and the town there is another church, the parish
U||   one, round which is a big graveyard, all full of tombstones. This is to
U||   my mind the nicest spot in Whitby, for it lies right over the town, and
U||   has a full view of the harbour and all up the bay to where the headland
U||   called Kettleness stretches out into the sea. It descends so steeply
U||   over the harbour that part of the bank has fallen away, and some of the
U||   graves have been destroyed. In one place part of the stonework of the
U||   graves stretches out over the sandy pathway far below. There are walks,
U||   with seats beside them, through the churchyard; and people go and sit
U||   there all day long looking at the beautiful view and enjoying the
U||   breeze. I shall come and sit here very often myself and work. Indeed, I
U||   am writing now, with my book on my knee, and listening to the talk of
U||   three old men who are sitting beside me. They seem to do nothing all
U||   day but sit up here and talk.
U||   The harbour lies below me, with, on the far side, one long granite wall
U||   stretching out into the sea, with a curve outwards at the end of it, in
U||   the middle of which is a lighthouse. A heavy sea-wall runs along
U||   outside of it. On the near side, the sea-wall makes an elbow crooked
U||   inversely, and its end too has a lighthouse. Between the two piers
U||   there is a narrow opening into the harbour, which then suddenly widens.
U||   It is nice at high water; but when the tide is out it shoals away to
U||   nothing, and there is merely the stream of the Esk, running between
U||   banks of sand, with rocks here and there. Outside the harbour on this
U||   side there rises for about half a mile a great reef, the sharp edge of
U||   which runs straight out from behind the south lighthouse. At the end of
U||   it is a buoy with a bell, which swings in bad weather, and sends in a
U||   mournful sound on the wind. They have a legend here that when a ship is
U||   lost bells are heard out at sea. I must ask the old man about this; he
U||   is coming this way....
U||   He is a funny old man. He must be awfully old, for his face is all
U||   gnarled and twisted like the bark of a tree. He tells me that he is
U||   nearly a hundred, and that he was a sailor in the Greenland fishing
U||   fleet when Waterloo was fought. He is, I am afraid, a very sceptical
U||   person, for when I asked him about the bells at sea and the White Lady
U||   at the abbey he said very brusquely:—
U||   “I wouldn’t fash masel’ about them, miss. Them things be all wore out.
U||   Mind, I don’t say that they never was, but I do say that they wasn’t in
U||   my time. They be all very well for comers and trippers, an’ the like,
U||   but not for a nice young lady like you. Them feet-folks from York and
U||   Leeds that be always eatin’ cured herrin’s an’ drinkin’ tea an’ lookin’
U||   out to buy cheap jet would creed aught. I wonder masel’ who’d be
U||   bothered tellin’ lies to them—even the newspapers, which is full of
U||   fool-talk.” I thought he would be a good person to learn interesting
U||   things from, so I asked him if he would mind telling me something about
U||   the whale-fishing in the old days. He was just settling himself to
U||   begin when the clock struck six, whereupon he laboured to get up, and
U||   said:—
U||   “I must gang ageeanwards home now, miss. My grand-daughter doesn’t like
U||   to be kept waitin’ when the tea is ready, for it takes me time to
U||   crammle aboon the grees, for there be a many of ’em; an’, miss, I lack
U||   belly-timber sairly by the clock.”
U||   He hobbled away, and I could see him hurrying, as well as he could,
U||   down the steps. The steps are a great feature on the place. They lead
U||   from the town up to the church, there are hundreds of them—I do not
U||   know how many—and they wind up in a delicate curve; the slope is so
U||   gentle that a horse could easily walk up and down them. I think they
U||   must originally have had something to do with the abbey. I shall go
U||   home too. Lucy went out visiting with her mother, and as they were only
U||   duty calls, I did not go. They will be home by this.
U||   1 August.—I came up here an hour ago with Lucy, and we had a most
U||   interesting talk with my old friend and the two others who always come
U||   and join him. He is evidently the Sir Oracle of them, and I should
U||   think must have been in his time a most dictatorial person. He will not
U||   admit anything, and downfaces everybody. If he can’t out-argue them he
U||   bullies them, and then takes their silence for agreement with his
U||   views. Lucy was looking sweetly pretty in her white lawn frock; she has
U||   got a beautiful colour since she has been here. I noticed that the old
U||   men did not lose any time in coming up and sitting near her when we sat
U||   down. She is so sweet with old people; I think they all fell in love
U||   with her on the spot. Even my old man succumbed and did not contradict
U||   her, but gave me double share instead. I got him on the subject of the
U||   legends, and he went off at once into a sort of sermon. I must try to
U||   remember it and put it down:—
U||   “It be all fool-talk, lock, stock, and barrel; that’s what it be, an’
U||   nowt else. These bans an’ wafts an’ boh-ghosts an’ barguests an’ bogles
U||   an’ all anent them is only fit to set bairns an’ dizzy women
U||   a-belderin’. They be nowt but air-blebs. They, an’ all grims an’ signs
U||   an’ warnin’s, be all invented by parsons an’ illsome beuk-bodies an’
U||   railway touters to skeer an’ scunner hafflin’s, an’ to get folks to do
U||   somethin’ that they don’t other incline to. It makes me ireful to think
U||   o’ them. Why, it’s them that, not content with printin’ lies on paper
U||   an’ preachin’ them out of pulpits, does want to be cuttin’ them on the
U||   tombstones. Look here all around you in what airt ye will; all them
U||   steans, holdin’ up their heads as well as they can out of their pride,
U||   is acant—simply tumblin’ down with the weight o’ the lies wrote on
U||   them, ‘Here lies the body’ or ‘Sacred to the memory’ wrote on all of
U||   them, an’ yet in nigh half of them there bean’t no bodies at all; an’
U||   the memories of them bean’t cared a pinch of snuff about, much less
U||   sacred. Lies all of them, nothin’ but lies of one kind or another! My
U||   gog, but it’ll be a quare scowderment at the Day of Judgment when they
U||   come tumblin’ up in their death-sarks, all jouped together an’ tryin’
U||   to drag their tombsteans with them to prove how good they was; some of
U||   them trimmlin’ and ditherin’, with their hands that dozzened an’ slippy
U||   from lyin’ in the sea that they can’t even keep their grup o’ them.”
U||   I could see from the old fellow’s self-satisfied air and the way in
U||   which he looked round for the approval of his cronies that he was
U||   “showing off,” so I put in a word to keep him going:—
U||   “Oh, Mr. Swales, you can’t be serious. Surely these tombstones are not
U||   all wrong?”
U||   “Yabblins! There may be a poorish few not wrong, savin’ where they make
U||   out the people too good; for there be folk that do think a balm-bowl be
U||   like the sea, if only it be their own. The whole thing be only lies.
U||   Now look you here; you come here a stranger, an’ you see this
U||   kirk-garth.” I nodded, for I thought it better to assent, though I did
U||   not quite understand his dialect. I knew it had something to do with
U||   the church. He went on: “And you consate that all these steans be aboon
U||   folk that be happed here, snod an’ snog?” I assented again. “Then that
U||   be just where the lie comes in. Why, there be scores of these lay-beds
U||   that be toom as old Dun’s ’bacca-box on Friday night.” He nudged one of
U||   his companions, and they all laughed. “And my gog! how could they be
U||   otherwise? Look at that one, the aftest abaft the bier-bank: read it!”
U||   I went over and read:—
U||   “Edward Spencelagh, master mariner, murdered by pirates off the coast
U||   of Andres, April, 1854, æt. 30.” When I came back Mr. Swales went on:—
U||   “Who brought him home, I wonder, to hap him here? Murdered off the
U||   coast of Andres! an’ you consated his body lay under! Why, I could name
U||   ye a dozen whose bones lie in the Greenland seas above”—he pointed
U||   northwards—“or where the currents may have drifted them. There be the
U||   steans around ye. Ye can, with your young eyes, read the small-print of
U||   the lies from here. This Braithwaite Lowrey—I knew his father, lost in
U||   the Lively off Greenland in ’20; or Andrew Woodhouse, drowned in the
U||   same seas in 1777; or John Paxton, drowned off Cape Farewell a year
U||   later; or old John Rawlings, whose grandfather sailed with me, drowned
U||   in the Gulf of Finland in ’50. Do ye think that all these men will have
U||   to make a rush to Whitby when the trumpet sounds? I have me antherums
U||   aboot it! I tell ye that when they got here they’d be jommlin’ an’
U||   jostlin’ one another that way that it ’ud be like a fight up on the ice
U||   in the old days, when we’d be at one another from daylight to dark, an’
U||   tryin’ to tie up our cuts by the light of the aurora borealis.” This
U||   was evidently local pleasantry, for the old man cackled over it, and
U||   his cronies joined in with gusto.
U||   “But,” I said, “surely you are not quite correct, for you start on the
U||   assumption that all the poor people, or their spirits, will have to
U||   take their tombstones with them on the Day of Judgment. Do you think
U||   that will be really necessary?”
U||   “Well, what else be they tombstones for? Answer me that, miss!”
U||   “To please their relatives, I suppose.”
U||   “To please their relatives, you suppose!” This he said with intense
U||   scorn. “How will it pleasure their relatives to know that lies is wrote
U||   over them, and that everybody in the place knows that they be lies?” He
U||   pointed to a stone at our feet which had been laid down as a slab, on
U||   which the seat was rested, close to the edge of the cliff. “Read the
U||   lies on that thruff-stean,” he said. The letters were upside down to me
U||   from where I sat, but Lucy was more opposite to them, so she leant over
U||   and read:—
U||   “Sacred to the memory of George Canon, who died, in the hope of a
U||   glorious resurrection, on July, 29, 1873, falling from the rocks at
U||   Kettleness. This tomb was erected by his sorrowing mother to her dearly
U||   beloved son. ‘He was the only son of his mother, and she was a widow.’
U||   Really, Mr. Swales, I don’t see anything very funny in that!” She spoke
U||   her comment very gravely and somewhat severely.
U||   “Ye don’t see aught funny! Ha! ha! But that’s because ye don’t gawm the
U||   sorrowin’ mother was a hell-cat that hated him because he was
U||   acrewk’d—a regular lamiter he was—an’ he hated her so that he committed
U||   suicide in order that she mightn’t get an insurance she put on his
U||   life. He blew nigh the top of his head off with an old musket that they
U||   had for scarin’ the crows with. ’Twarn’t for crows then, for it brought
U||   the clegs and the dowps to him. That’s the way he fell off the rocks.
U||   And, as to hopes of a glorious resurrection, I’ve often heard him say
U||   masel’ that he hoped he’d go to hell, for his mother was so pious that
U||   she’d be sure to go to heaven, an’ he didn’t want to addle where she
U||   was. Now isn’t that stean at any rate”—he hammered it with his stick as
U||   he spoke—“a pack of lies? and won’t it make Gabriel keckle when Geordie
U||   comes pantin’ up the grees with the tombstean balanced on his hump, and
U||   asks it to be took as evidence!”
U||   I did not know what to say, but Lucy turned the conversation as she
U||   said, rising up:—
U||   “Oh, why did you tell us of this? It is my favourite seat, and I cannot
U||   leave it; and now I find I must go on sitting over the grave of a
U||   suicide.”
U||   “That won’t harm ye, my pretty; an’ it may make poor Geordie gladsome
U||   to have so trim a lass sittin’ on his lap. That won’t hurt ye. Why,
U||   I’ve sat here off an’ on for nigh twenty years past, an’ it hasn’t done
U||   me no harm. Don’t ye fash about them as lies under ye, or that doesn’
U||   lie there either! It’ll be time for ye to be getting scart when ye see
U||   the tombsteans all run away with, and the place as bare as a
U||   stubble-field. There’s the clock, an’ I must gang. My service to ye,
U||   ladies!” And off he hobbled.
U||   Lucy and I sat awhile, and it was all so beautiful before us that we
U||   took hands as we sat; and she told me all over again about Arthur and
U||   their coming marriage. That made me just a little heart-sick, for I
U||   haven’t heard from Jonathan for a whole month.
U||   The same day. I came up here alone, for I am very sad. There was no
U||   letter for me. I hope there cannot be anything the matter with
U||   Jonathan. The clock has just struck nine. I see the lights scattered
U||   all over the town, sometimes in rows where the streets are, and
U||   sometimes singly; they run right up the Esk and die away in the curve
U||   of the valley. To my left the view is cut off by a black line of roof
U||   of the old house next the abbey. The sheep and lambs are bleating in
U||   the fields away behind me, and there is a clatter of a donkey’s hoofs
U||   up the paved road below. The band on the pier is playing a harsh waltz
U||   in good time, and further along the quay there is a Salvation Army
U||   meeting in a back street. Neither of the bands hears the other, but up
U||   here I hear and see them both. I wonder where Jonathan is and if he is
U||   thinking of me! I wish he were here.
U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   5 June.—The case of Renfield grows more interesting the more I get to
U||   understand the man. He has certain qualities very largely developed;
U||   selfishness, secrecy, and purpose. I wish I could get at what is the
U||   object of the latter. He seems to have some settled scheme of his own,
U||   but what it is I do not yet know. His redeeming quality is a love of
U||   animals, though, indeed, he has such curious turns in it that I
U||   sometimes imagine he is only abnormally cruel. His pets are of odd
U||   sorts. Just now his hobby is catching flies. He has at present such a
U||   quantity that I have had myself to expostulate. To my astonishment, he
U||   did not break out into a fury, as I expected, but took the matter in
U||   simple seriousness. He thought for a moment, and then said: “May I have
U||   three days? I shall clear them away.” Of course, I said that would do.
U||   I must watch him.
U||   18 June.—He has turned his mind now to spiders, and has got several
U||   very big fellows in a box. He keeps feeding them with his flies, and
U||   the number of the latter is becoming sensibly diminished, although he
U||   has used half his food in attracting more flies from outside to his
U||   room.
U||   1 July.—His spiders are now becoming as great a nuisance as his flies,
U||   and to-day I told him that he must get rid of them. He looked very sad
U||   at this, so I said that he must clear out some of them, at all events.
U||   He cheerfully acquiesced in this, and I gave him the same time as
U||   before for reduction. He disgusted me much while with him, for when a
U||   horrid blow-fly, bloated with some carrion food, buzzed into the room,
U||   he caught it, held it exultantly for a few moments between his finger
U||   and thumb, and, before I knew what he was going to do, put it in his
U||   mouth and ate it. I scolded him for it, but he argued quietly that it
U||   was very good and very wholesome; that it was life, strong life, and
U||   gave life to him. This gave me an idea, or the rudiment of one. I must
U||   watch how he gets rid of his spiders. He has evidently some deep
U||   problem in his mind, for he keeps a little note-book in which he is
U||   always jotting down something. Whole pages of it are filled with masses
U||   of figures, generally single numbers added up in batches, and then the
U||   totals added in batches again, as though he were “focussing” some
U||   account, as the auditors put it.
U||   8 July.—There is a method in his madness, and the rudimentary idea in
U||   my mind is growing. It will be a whole idea soon, and then, oh,
U||   unconscious cerebration! you will have to give the wall to your
U||   conscious brother. I kept away from my friend for a few days, so that I
U||   might notice if there were any change. Things remain as they were
U||   except that he has parted with some of his pets and got a new one. He
U||   has managed to get a sparrow, and has already partially tamed it. His
U||   means of taming is simple, for already the spiders have diminished.
U||   Those that do remain, however, are well fed, for he still brings in the
U||   flies by tempting them with his food.
U||   19 July.—We are progressing. My friend has now a whole colony of
U||   sparrows, and his flies and spiders are almost obliterated. When I came
U||   in he ran to me and said he wanted to ask me a great favour—a very,
U||   very great favour; and as he spoke he fawned on me like a dog. I asked
U||   him what it was, and he said, with a sort of rapture in his voice and
U||   bearing:—
U||   “A kitten, a nice little, sleek playful kitten, that I can play with,
U||   and teach, and feed—and feed—and feed!” I was not unprepared for this
U||   request, for I had noticed how his pets went on increasing in size and
U||   vivacity, but I did not care that his pretty family of tame sparrows
U||   should be wiped out in the same manner as the flies and the spiders; so
U||   I said I would see about it, and asked him if he would not rather have
U||   a cat than a kitten. His eagerness betrayed him as he answered:—
U||   “Oh, yes, I would like a cat! I only asked for a kitten lest you should
U||   refuse me a cat. No one would refuse me a kitten, would they?” I shook
U||   my head, and said that at present I feared it would not be possible,
U||   but that I would see about it. His face fell, and I could see a warning
U||   of danger in it, for there was a sudden fierce, sidelong look which
U||   meant killing. The man is an undeveloped homicidal maniac. I shall test
U||   him with his present craving and see how it will work out; then I shall
U||   know more.
U||   10 p. m.—I have visited him again and found him sitting in a corner
U||   brooding. When I came in he threw himself on his knees before me and
U||   implored me to let him have a cat; that his salvation depended upon it.
U||   I was firm, however, and told him that he could not have it, whereupon
U||   he went without a word, and sat down, gnawing his fingers, in the
U||   corner where I had found him. I shall see him in the morning early.
U||   20 July.—Visited Renfield very early, before the attendant went his
U||   rounds. Found him up and humming a tune. He was spreading out his
U||   sugar, which he had saved, in the window, and was manifestly beginning
U||   his fly-catching again; and beginning it cheerfully and with a good
U||   grace. I looked around for his birds, and not seeing them, asked him
U||   where they were. He replied, without turning round, that they had all
U||   flown away. There were a few feathers about the room and on his pillow
U||   a drop of blood. I said nothing, but went and told the keeper to report
U||   to me if there were anything odd about him during the day.
U||   11 a. m.—The attendant has just been to me to say that Renfield has
U||   been very sick and has disgorged a whole lot of feathers. “My belief
U||   is, doctor,” he said, “that he has eaten his birds, and that he just
U||   took and ate them raw!”
U||   11 p. m.—I gave Renfield a strong opiate to-night, enough to make even
U||   him sleep, and took away his pocket-book to look at it. The thought
U||   that has been buzzing about my brain lately is complete, and the theory
U||   proved. My homicidal maniac is of a peculiar kind. I shall have to
U||   invent a new classification for him, and call him a zoöphagous
U||   (life-eating) maniac; what he desires is to absorb as many lives as he
U||   can, and he has laid himself out to achieve it in a cumulative way. He
U||   gave many flies to one spider and many spiders to one bird, and then
U||   wanted a cat to eat the many birds. What would have been his later
U||   steps? It would almost be worth while to complete the experiment. It
U||   might be done if there were only a sufficient cause. Men sneered at
U||   vivisection, and yet look at its results to-day! Why not advance
U||   science in its most difficult and vital aspect—the knowledge of the
U||   brain? Had I even the secret of one such mind—did I hold the key to the
U||   fancy of even one lunatic—I might advance my own branch of science to a
U||   pitch compared with which Burdon-Sanderson’s physiology or Ferrier’s
U||   brain-knowledge would be as nothing. If only there were a sufficient
U||   cause! I must not think too much of this, or I may be tempted; a good
U||   cause might turn the scale with me, for may not I too be of an
U||   exceptional brain, congenitally?
U||   How well the man reasoned; lunatics always do within their own scope. I
U||   wonder at how many lives he values a man, or if at only one. He has
U||   closed the account most accurately, and to-day begun a new record. How
U||   many of us begin a new record with each day of our lives?
U||   To me it seems only yesterday that my whole life ended with my new
U||   hope, and that truly I began a new record. So it will be until the
U||   Great Recorder sums me up and closes my ledger account with a balance
U||   to profit or loss. Oh, Lucy, Lucy, I cannot be angry with you, nor can
U||   I be angry with my friend whose happiness is yours; but I must only
U||   wait on hopeless and work. Work! work!
U||   If I only could have as strong a cause as my poor mad friend there—a
U||   good, unselfish cause to make me work—that would be indeed happiness.
U||   Mina Murray’s Journal.
U||   26 July.—I am anxious, and it soothes me to express myself here; it is
U||   like whispering to one’s self and listening at the same time. And there
U||   is also something about the shorthand symbols that makes it different
U||   from writing. I am unhappy about Lucy and about Jonathan. I had not
U||   heard from Jonathan for some time, and was very concerned; but
U||   yesterday dear Mr. Hawkins, who is always so kind, sent me a letter
U||   from him. I had written asking him if he had heard, and he said the
U||   enclosed had just been received. It is only a line dated from Castle
U||   Dracula, and says that he is just starting for home. That is not like
U||   Jonathan; I do not understand it, and it makes me uneasy. Then, too,
U||   Lucy, although she is so well, has lately taken to her old habit of
U||   walking in her sleep. Her mother has spoken to me about it, and we have
U||   decided that I am to lock the door of our room every night. Mrs.
U||   Westenra has got an idea that sleep-walkers always go out on roofs of
U||   houses and along the edges of cliffs and then get suddenly wakened and
U||   fall over with a despairing cry that echoes all over the place. Poor
U||   dear, she is naturally anxious about Lucy, and she tells me that her
U||   husband, Lucy’s father, had the same habit; that he would get up in the
U||   night and dress himself and go out, if he were not stopped. Lucy is to
U||   be married in the autumn, and she is already planning out her dresses
U||   and how her house is to be arranged. I sympathise with her, for I do
U||   the same, only Jonathan and I will start in life in a very simple way,
U||   and shall have to try to make both ends meet. Mr. Holmwood—he is the
U||   Hon. Arthur Holmwood, only son of Lord Godalming—is coming up here very
U||   shortly—as soon as he can leave town, for his father is not very well,
U||   and I think dear Lucy is counting the moments till he comes. She wants
U||   to take him up to the seat on the churchyard cliff and show him the
U||   beauty of Whitby. I daresay it is the waiting which disturbs her; she
U||   will be all right when he arrives.
U||   27 July.—No news from Jonathan. I am getting quite uneasy about him,
U||   though why I should I do not know; but I do wish that he would write,
U||   if it were only a single line. Lucy walks more than ever, and each
U||   night I am awakened by her moving about the room. Fortunately, the
U||   weather is so hot that she cannot get cold; but still the anxiety and
U||   the perpetually being wakened is beginning to tell on me, and I am
U||   getting nervous and wakeful myself. Thank God, Lucy’s health keeps up.
U||   Mr. Holmwood has been suddenly called to Ring to see his father, who
U||   has been taken seriously ill. Lucy frets at the postponement of seeing
U||   him, but it does not touch her looks; she is a trifle stouter, and her
U||   cheeks are a lovely rose-pink. She has lost that anæmic look which she
U||   had. I pray it will all last.
U||   3 August.—Another week gone, and no news from Jonathan, not even to Mr.
U||   Hawkins, from whom I have heard. Oh, I do hope he is not ill. He surely
U||   would have written. I look at that last letter of his, but somehow it
U||   does not satisfy me. It does not read like him, and yet it is his
U||   writing. There is no mistake of that. Lucy has not walked much in her
U||   sleep the last week, but there is an odd concentration about her which
U||   I do not understand; even in her sleep she seems to be watching me. She
U||   tries the door, and finding it locked, goes about the room searching
U||   for the key.
U||   6 August.—Another three days, and no news. This suspense is getting
U||   dreadful. If I only knew where to write to or where to go to, I should
U||   feel easier; but no one has heard a word of Jonathan since that last
U||   letter. I must only pray to God for patience. Lucy is more excitable
U||   than ever, but is otherwise well. Last night was very threatening, and
U||   the fishermen say that we are in for a storm. I must try to watch it
U||   and learn the weather signs. To-day is a grey day, and the sun as I
U||   write is hidden in thick clouds, high over Kettleness. Everything is
U||   grey—except the green grass, which seems like emerald amongst it; grey
U||   earthy rock; grey clouds, tinged with the sunburst at the far edge,
U||   hang over the grey sea, into which the sand-points stretch like grey
U||   fingers. The sea is tumbling in over the shallows and the sandy flats
U||   with a roar, muffled in the sea-mists drifting inland. The horizon is
U||   lost in a grey mist. All is vastness; the clouds are piled up like
U||   giant rocks, and there is a “brool” over the sea that sounds like some
U||   presage of doom. Dark figures are on the beach here and there,
U||   sometimes half shrouded in the mist, and seem “men like trees walking.”
U||   The fishing-boats are racing for home, and rise and dip in the ground
U||   swell as they sweep into the harbour, bending to the scuppers. Here
U||   comes old Mr. Swales. He is making straight for me, and I can see, by
U||   the way he lifts his hat, that he wants to talk....
U||   I have been quite touched by the change in the poor old man. When he
U||   sat down beside me, he said in a very gentle way:—
U||   “I want to say something to you, miss.” I could see he was not at ease,
U||   so I took his poor old wrinkled hand in mine and asked him to speak
U||   fully; so he said, leaving his hand in mine:—
U||   “I’m afraid, my deary, that I must have shocked you by all the wicked
U||   things I’ve been sayin’ about the dead, and such like, for weeks past;
U||   but I didn’t mean them, and I want ye to remember that when I’m gone.
U||   We aud folks that be daffled, and with one foot abaft the krok-hooal,
U||   don’t altogether like to think of it, and we don’t want to feel scart
U||   of it; an’ that’s why I’ve took to makin’ light of it, so that I’d
U||   cheer up my own heart a bit. But, Lord love ye, miss, I ain’t afraid of
U||   dyin’, not a bit; only I don’t want to die if I can help it. My time
U||   must be nigh at hand now, for I be aud, and a hundred years is too much
U||   for any man to expect; and I’m so nigh it that the Aud Man is already
U||   whettin’ his scythe. Ye see, I can’t get out o’ the habit of caffin’
U||   about it all at once; the chafts will wag as they be used to. Some day
U||   soon the Angel of Death will sound his trumpet for me. But don’t ye
U||   dooal an’ greet, my deary!”—for he saw that I was crying—“if he should
U||   come this very night I’d not refuse to answer his call. For life be,
U||   after all, only a waitin’ for somethin’ else than what we’re doin’; and
U||   death be all that we can rightly depend on. But I’m content, for it’s
U||   comin’ to me, my deary, and comin’ quick. It may be comin’ while we be
U||   lookin’ and wonderin’. Maybe it’s in that wind out over the sea that’s
U||   bringin’ with it loss and wreck, and sore distress, and sad hearts.
U||   Look! look!” he cried suddenly. “There’s something in that wind and in
U||   the hoast beyont that sounds, and looks, and tastes, and smells like
U||   death. It’s in the air; I feel it comin’. Lord, make me answer cheerful
U||   when my call comes!” He held up his arms devoutly, and raised his hat.
U||   His mouth moved as though he were praying. After a few minutes’
U||   silence, he got up, shook hands with me, and blessed me, and said
U||   good-bye, and hobbled off. It all touched me, and upset me very much.
U||   I was glad when the coastguard came along, with his spy-glass under his
U||   arm. He stopped to talk with me, as he always does, but all the time
U||   kept looking at a strange ship.
U||   “I can’t make her out,” he said; “she’s a Russian, by the look of her;
U||   but she’s knocking about in the queerest way. She doesn’t know her mind
U||   a bit; she seems to see the storm coming, but can’t decide whether to
U||   run up north in the open, or to put in here. Look there again! She is
U||   steered mighty strangely, for she doesn’t mind the hand on the wheel;
U||   changes about with every puff of wind. We’ll hear more of her before
U||   this time to-morrow.”
