U||CUTTING FROM “THE DAILYGRAPH,” 8 AUGUST
U||   (Pasted in Mina Murray’s Journal.)
U||   From a Correspondent.
U||   Whitby.
U||   ONE of the greatest and suddenest storms on record has just been
U||   experienced here, with results both strange and unique. The weather had
U||   been somewhat sultry, but not to any degree uncommon in the month of
U||   August. Saturday evening was as fine as was ever known, and the great
U||   body of holiday-makers laid out yesterday for visits to Mulgrave Woods,
U||   Robin Hood’s Bay, Rig Mill, Runswick, Staithes, and the various trips
U||   in the neighbourhood of Whitby. The steamers Emma and Scarborough made
U||   trips up and down the coast, and there was an unusual amount of
U||   “tripping” both to and from Whitby. The day was unusually fine till the
U||   afternoon, when some of the gossips who frequent the East Cliff
U||   churchyard, and from that commanding eminence watch the wide sweep of
U||   sea visible to the north and east, called attention to a sudden show of
U||   “mares’-tails” high in the sky to the north-west. The wind was then
U||   blowing from the south-west in the mild degree which in barometrical
U||   language is ranked “No. 2: light breeze.” The coastguard on duty at
U||   once made report, and one old fisherman, who for more than half a
U||   century has kept watch on weather signs from the East Cliff, foretold
U||   in an emphatic manner the coming of a sudden storm. The approach of
U||   sunset was so very beautiful, so grand in its masses of
U||   splendidly-coloured clouds, that there was quite an assemblage on the
U||   walk along the cliff in the old churchyard to enjoy the beauty. Before
U||   the sun dipped below the black mass of Kettleness, standing boldly
U||   athwart the western sky, its downward way was marked by myriad clouds
U||   of every sunset-colour—flame, purple, pink, green, violet, and all the
U||   tints of gold; with here and there masses not large, but of seemingly
U||   absolute blackness, in all sorts of shapes, as well outlined as
U||   colossal silhouettes. The experience was not lost on the painters, and
U||   doubtless some of the sketches of the “Prelude to the Great Storm” will
U||   grace the R. A. and R. I. walls in May next. More than one captain made
U||   up his mind then and there that his “cobble” or his “mule,” as they
U||   term the different classes of boats, would remain in the harbour till
U||   the storm had passed. The wind fell away entirely during the evening,
U||   and at midnight there was a dead calm, a sultry heat, and that
U||   prevailing intensity which, on the approach of thunder, affects persons
U||   of a sensitive nature. There were but few lights in sight at sea, for
U||   even the coasting steamers, which usually “hug” the shore so closely,
U||   kept well to seaward, and but few fishing-boats were in sight. The only
U||   sail noticeable was a foreign schooner with all sails set, which was
U||   seemingly going westwards. The foolhardiness or ignorance of her
U||   officers was a prolific theme for comment whilst she remained in sight,
U||   and efforts were made to signal her to reduce sail in face of her
U||   danger. Before the night shut down she was seen with sails idly
U||   flapping as she gently rolled on the undulating swell of the sea,
U||   “As idle as a painted ship upon a painted ocean.”
U||   Shortly before ten o’clock the stillness of the air grew quite
U||   oppressive, and the silence was so marked that the bleating of a sheep
U||   inland or the barking of a dog in the town was distinctly heard, and
U||   the band on the pier, with its lively French air, was like a discord in
U||   the great harmony of nature’s silence. A little after midnight came a
U||   strange sound from over the sea, and high overhead the air began to
U||   carry a strange, faint, hollow booming.
U||   Then without warning the tempest broke. With a rapidity which, at the
U||   time, seemed incredible, and even afterwards is impossible to realize,
U||   the whole aspect of nature at once became convulsed. The waves rose in
U||   growing fury, each overtopping its fellow, till in a very few minutes
U||   the lately glassy sea was like a roaring and devouring monster.
U||   White-crested waves beat madly on the level sands and rushed up the
U||   shelving cliffs; others broke over the piers, and with their spume
U||   swept the lanthorns of the lighthouses which rise from the end of
U||   either pier of Whitby Harbour. The wind roared like thunder, and blew
U||   with such force that it was with difficulty that even strong men kept
U||   their feet, or clung with grim clasp to the iron stanchions. It was
U||   found necessary to clear the entire piers from the mass of onlookers,
U||   or else the fatalities of the night would have been increased manifold.
U||   To add to the difficulties and dangers of the time, masses of sea-fog
U||   came drifting inland—white, wet clouds, which swept by in ghostly
U||   fashion, so dank and damp and cold that it needed but little effort of
U||   imagination to think that the spirits of those lost at sea were
U||   touching their living brethren with the clammy hands of death, and many
U||   a one shuddered as the wreaths of sea-mist swept by. At times the mist
U||   cleared, and the sea for some distance could be seen in the glare of
U||   the lightning, which now came thick and fast, followed by such sudden
U||   peals of thunder that the whole sky overhead seemed trembling under the
U||   shock of the footsteps of the storm.
U||   Some of the scenes thus revealed were of immeasurable grandeur and of
U||   absorbing interest—the sea, running mountains high, threw skywards with
U||   each wave mighty masses of white foam, which the tempest seemed to
U||   snatch at and whirl away into space; here and there a fishing-boat,
U||   with a rag of sail, running madly for shelter before the blast; now and
U||   again the white wings of a storm-tossed sea-bird. On the summit of the
U||   East Cliff the new searchlight was ready for experiment, but had not
U||   yet been tried. The officers in charge of it got it into working order,
U||   and in the pauses of the inrushing mist swept with it the surface of
U||   the sea. Once or twice its service was most effective, as when a
U||   fishing-boat, with gunwale under water, rushed into the harbour, able,
U||   by the guidance of the sheltering light, to avoid the danger of dashing
U||   against the piers. As each boat achieved the safety of the port there
U||   was a shout of joy from the mass of people on shore, a shout which for
U||   a moment seemed to cleave the gale and was then swept away in its rush.
U||   Before long the searchlight discovered some distance away a schooner
U||   with all sails set, apparently the same vessel which had been noticed
U||   earlier in the evening. The wind had by this time backed to the east,
U||   and there was a shudder amongst the watchers on the cliff as they
U||   realized the terrible danger in which she now was. Between her and the
U||   port lay the great flat reef on which so many good ships have from time
U||   to time suffered, and, with the wind blowing from its present quarter,
U||   it would be quite impossible that she should fetch the entrance of the
U||   harbour. It was now nearly the hour of high tide, but the waves were so
U||   great that in their troughs the shallows of the shore were almost
U||   visible, and the schooner, with all sails set, was rushing with such
U||   speed that, in the words of one old salt, “she must fetch up somewhere,
U||   if it was only in hell.” Then came another rush of sea-fog, greater
U||   than any hitherto—a mass of dank mist, which seemed to close on all
U||   things like a grey pall, and left available to men only the organ of
U||   hearing, for the roar of the tempest, and the crash of the thunder, and
U||   the booming of the mighty billows came through the damp oblivion even
U||   louder than before. The rays of the searchlight were kept fixed on the
U||   harbour mouth across the East Pier, where the shock was expected, and
U||   men waited breathless. The wind suddenly shifted to the north-east, and
U||   the remnant of the sea-fog melted in the blast; and then, mirabile
U||   dictu, between the piers, leaping from wave to wave as it rushed at
U||   headlong speed, swept the strange schooner before the blast, with all
U||   sail set, and gained the safety of the harbour. The searchlight
U||   followed her, and a shudder ran through all who saw her, for lashed to
U||   the helm was a corpse, with drooping head, which swung horribly to and
U||   fro at each motion of the ship. No other form could be seen on deck at
U||   all. A great awe came on all as they realised that the ship, as if by a
U||   miracle, had found the harbour, unsteered save by the hand of a dead
U||   man! However, all took place more quickly than it takes to write these
U||   words. The schooner paused not, but rushing across the harbour, pitched
U||   herself on that accumulation of sand and gravel washed by many tides
U||   and many storms into the south-east corner of the pier jutting under
U||   the East Cliff, known locally as Tate Hill Pier.
U||   There was of course a considerable concussion as the vessel drove up on
U||   the sand heap. Every spar, rope, and stay was strained, and some of the
U||   “top-hammer” came crashing down. But, strangest of all, the very
U||   instant the shore was touched, an immense dog sprang up on deck from
U||   below, as if shot up by the concussion, and running forward, jumped
U||   from the bow on the sand. Making straight for the steep cliff, where
U||   the churchyard hangs over the laneway to the East Pier so steeply that
U||   some of the flat tombstones—“thruff-steans” or “through-stones,” as
U||   they call them in the Whitby vernacular—actually project over where the
U||   sustaining cliff has fallen away, it disappeared in the darkness, which
U||   seemed intensified just beyond the focus of the searchlight.
U||   It so happened that there was no one at the moment on Tate Hill Pier,
U||   as all those whose houses are in close proximity were either in bed or
U||   were out on the heights above. Thus the coastguard on duty on the
U||   eastern side of the harbour, who at once ran down to the little pier,
U||   was the first to climb on board. The men working the searchlight, after
U||   scouring the entrance of the harbour without seeing anything, then
U||   turned the light on the derelict and kept it there. The coastguard ran
U||   aft, and when he came beside the wheel, bent over to examine it, and
U||   recoiled at once as though under some sudden emotion. This seemed to
U||   pique general curiosity, and quite a number of people began to run. It
U||   is a good way round from the West Cliff by the Drawbridge to Tate Hill
U||   Pier, but your correspondent is a fairly good runner, and came well
U||   ahead of the crowd. When I arrived, however, I found already assembled
U||   on the pier a crowd, whom the coastguard and police refused to allow to
U||   come on board. By the courtesy of the chief boatman, I was, as your
U||   correspondent, permitted to climb on deck, and was one of a small group
U||   who saw the dead seaman whilst actually lashed to the wheel.
U||   It was no wonder that the coastguard was surprised, or even awed, for
U||   not often can such a sight have been seen. The man was simply fastened
U||   by his hands, tied one over the other, to a spoke of the wheel. Between
U||   the inner hand and the wood was a crucifix, the set of beads on which
U||   it was fastened being around both wrists and wheel, and all kept fast
U||   by the binding cords. The poor fellow may have been seated at one time,
U||   but the flapping and buffeting of the sails had worked through the
U||   rudder of the wheel and dragged him to and fro, so that the cords with
U||   which he was tied had cut the flesh to the bone. Accurate note was made
U||   of the state of things, and a doctor—Surgeon J. M. Caffyn, of 33, East
U||   Elliot Place—who came immediately after me, declared, after making
U||   examination, that the man must have been dead for quite two days. In
U||   his pocket was a bottle, carefully corked, empty save for a little roll
U||   of paper, which proved to be the addendum to the log. The coastguard
U||   said the man must have tied up his own hands, fastening the knots with
U||   his teeth. The fact that a coastguard was the first on board may save
U||   some complications, later on, in the Admiralty Court; for coastguards
U||   cannot claim the salvage which is the right of the first civilian
U||   entering on a derelict. Already, however, the legal tongues are
U||   wagging, and one young law student is loudly asserting that the rights
U||   of the owner are already completely sacrificed, his property being held
U||   in contravention of the statutes of mortmain, since the tiller, as
U||   emblemship, if not proof, of delegated possession, is held in a dead
U||   hand. It is needless to say that the dead steersman has been reverently
U||   removed from the place where he held his honourable watch and ward till
U||   death—a steadfastness as noble as that of the young Casabianca—and
U||   placed in the mortuary to await inquest.
U||   Already the sudden storm is passing, and its fierceness is abating;
U||   crowds are scattering homeward, and the sky is beginning to redden over
U||   the Yorkshire wolds. I shall send, in time for your next issue, further
U||   details of the derelict ship which found her way so miraculously into
U||   harbour in the storm.
U||   Whitby
U||   9 August.—The sequel to the strange arrival of the derelict in the
U||   storm last night is almost more startling than the thing itself. It
U||   turns out that the schooner is a Russian from Varna, and is called the
U||   Demeter. She is almost entirely in ballast of silver sand, with only a
U||   small amount of cargo—a number of great wooden boxes filled with mould.
U||   This cargo was consigned to a Whitby solicitor, Mr. S. F. Billington,
U||   of 7, The Crescent, who this morning went aboard and formally took
U||   possession of the goods consigned to him. The Russian consul, too,
U||   acting for the charter-party, took formal possession of the ship, and
U||   paid all harbour dues, etc. Nothing is talked about here to-day except
U||   the strange coincidence; the officials of the Board of Trade have been
U||   most exacting in seeing that every compliance has been made with
U||   existing regulations. As the matter is to be a “nine days’ wonder,”
U||   they are evidently determined that there shall be no cause of after
U||   complaint. A good deal of interest was abroad concerning the dog which
U||   landed when the ship struck, and more than a few of the members of the
U||   S. P. C. A., which is very strong in Whitby, have tried to befriend the
U||   animal. To the general disappointment, however, it was not to be found;
U||   it seems to have disappeared entirely from the town. It may be that it
U||   was frightened and made its way on to the moors, where it is still
U||   hiding in terror. There are some who look with dread on such a
U||   possibility, lest later on it should in itself become a danger, for it
U||   is evidently a fierce brute. Early this morning a large dog, a
U||   half-bred mastiff belonging to a coal merchant close to Tate Hill Pier,
U||   was found dead in the roadway opposite to its master’s yard. It had
U||   been fighting, and manifestly had had a savage opponent, for its throat
U||   was torn away, and its belly was slit open as if with a savage claw.
U||   Later.—By the kindness of the Board of Trade inspector, I have been
U||   permitted to look over the log-book of the Demeter, which was in order
U||   up to within three days, but contained nothing of special interest
U||   except as to facts of missing men. The greatest interest, however, is
U||   with regard to the paper found in the bottle, which was to-day produced
U||   at the inquest; and a more strange narrative than the two between them
U||   unfold it has not been my lot to come across. As there is no motive for
U||   concealment, I am permitted to use them, and accordingly send you a
U||   rescript, simply omitting technical details of seamanship and
U||   supercargo. It almost seems as though the captain had been seized with
U||   some kind of mania before he had got well into blue water, and that
U||   this had developed persistently throughout the voyage. Of course my
U||   statement must be taken cum grano, since I am writing from the
U||   dictation of a clerk of the Russian consul, who kindly translated for
U||   me, time being short.
U||   LOG OF THE “DEMETER.”
U||   Varna to Whitby.
U||   Written 18 July, things so strange happening, that I shall keep
U||   accurate note henceforth till we land.
U||   On 6 July we finished taking in cargo, silver sand and boxes of earth.
U||   At noon set sail. East wind, fresh. Crew, five hands ... two mates,
U||   cook, and myself (captain).
U||   On 11 July at dawn entered Bosphorus. Boarded by Turkish Customs
U||   officers. Backsheesh. All correct. Under way at 4 p. m.
U||   On 12 July through Dardanelles. More Customs officers and flagboat of
U||   guarding squadron. Backsheesh again. Work of officers thorough, but
U||   quick. Want us off soon. At dark passed into Archipelago.
U||   On 13 July passed Cape Matapan. Crew dissatisfied about something.
U||   Seemed scared, but would not speak out.
U||   On 14 July was somewhat anxious about crew. Men all steady fellows, who
U||   sailed with me before. Mate could not make out what was wrong; they
U||   only told him there was something, and crossed themselves. Mate lost
U||   temper with one of them that day and struck him. Expected fierce
U||   quarrel, but all was quiet.
U||   On 16 July mate reported in the morning that one of crew, Petrofsky,
U||   was missing. Could not account for it. Took larboard watch eight bells
U||   last night; was relieved by Abramoff, but did not go to bunk. Men more
U||   downcast than ever. All said they expected something of the kind, but
U||   would not say more than there was something aboard. Mate getting very
U||   impatient with them; feared some trouble ahead.
U||   On 17 July, yesterday, one of the men, Olgaren, came to my cabin, and
U||   in an awestruck way confided to me that he thought there was a strange
U||   man aboard the ship. He said that in his watch he had been sheltering
U||   behind the deck-house, as there was a rain-storm, when he saw a tall,
U||   thin man, who was not like any of the crew, come up the companion-way,
U||   and go along the deck forward, and disappear. He followed cautiously,
U||   but when he got to bows found no one, and the hatchways were all
U||   closed. He was in a panic of superstitious fear, and I am afraid the
U||   panic may spread. To allay it, I shall to-day search entire ship
U||   carefully from stem to stern.
U||   Later in the day I got together the whole crew, and told them, as they
U||   evidently thought there was some one in the ship, we would search from
U||   stem to stern. First mate angry; said it was folly, and to yield to
U||   such foolish ideas would demoralise the men; said he would engage to
U||   keep them out of trouble with a handspike. I let him take the helm,
U||   while the rest began thorough search, all keeping abreast, with
U||   lanterns: we left no corner unsearched. As there were only the big
U||   wooden boxes, there were no odd corners where a man could hide. Men
U||   much relieved when search over, and went back to work cheerfully. First
U||   mate scowled, but said nothing.
U||   22 July.—Rough weather last three days, and all hands busy with
U||   sails—no time to be frightened. Men seem to have forgotten their dread.
U||   Mate cheerful again, and all on good terms. Praised men for work in bad
U||   weather. Passed Gibralter and out through Straits. All well.
U||   24 July.—There seems some doom over this ship. Already a hand short,
U||   and entering on the Bay of Biscay with wild weather ahead, and yet last
U||   night another man lost—disappeared. Like the first, he came off his
U||   watch and was not seen again. Men all in a panic of fear; sent a round
U||   robin, asking to have double watch, as they fear to be alone. Mate
U||   angry. Fear there will be some trouble, as either he or the men will do
U||   some violence.
U||   28 July.—Four days in hell, knocking about in a sort of maelstrom, and
U||   the wind a tempest. No sleep for any one. Men all worn out. Hardly know
U||   how to set a watch, since no one fit to go on. Second mate volunteered
U||   to steer and watch, and let men snatch a few hours’ sleep. Wind
U||   abating; seas still terrific, but feel them less, as ship is steadier.
U||   29 July.—Another tragedy. Had single watch to-night, as crew too tired
U||   to double. When morning watch came on deck could find no one except
U||   steersman. Raised outcry, and all came on deck. Thorough search, but no
U||   one found. Are now without second mate, and crew in a panic. Mate and I
U||   agreed to go armed henceforth and wait for any sign of cause.
U||   30 July.—Last night. Rejoiced we are nearing England. Weather fine, all
U||   sails set. Retired worn out; slept soundly; awaked by mate telling me
U||   that both man of watch and steersman missing. Only self and mate and
U||   two hands left to work ship.
U||   1 August.—Two days of fog, and not a sail sighted. Had hoped when in
U||   the English Channel to be able to signal for help or get in somewhere.
U||   Not having power to work sails, have to run before wind. Dare not
U||   lower, as could not raise them again. We seem to be drifting to some
U||   terrible doom. Mate now more demoralised than either of men. His
U||   stronger nature seems to have worked inwardly against himself. Men are
U||   beyond fear, working stolidly and patiently, with minds made up to
U||   worst. They are Russian, he Roumanian.
U||   2 August, midnight.—Woke up from few minutes’ sleep by hearing a cry,
U||   seemingly outside my port. Could see nothing in fog. Rushed on deck,
U||   and ran against mate. Tells me heard cry and ran, but no sign of man on
U||   watch. One more gone. Lord, help us! Mate says we must be past Straits
U||   of Dover, as in a moment of fog lifting he saw North Foreland, just as
U||   he heard the man cry out. If so we are now off in the North Sea, and
U||   only God can guide us in the fog, which seems to move with us; and God
U||   seems to have deserted us.
U||   3 August.—At midnight I went to relieve the man at the wheel, and when
U||   I got to it found no one there. The wind was steady, and as we ran
U||   before it there was no yawing. I dared not leave it, so shouted for the
U||   mate. After a few seconds he rushed up on deck in his flannels. He
U||   looked wild-eyed and haggard, and I greatly fear his reason has given
U||   way. He came close to me and whispered hoarsely, with his mouth to my
U||   ear, as though fearing the very air might hear: “It is here; I know it,
U||   now. On the watch last night I saw It, like a man, tall and thin, and
U||   ghastly pale. It was in the bows, and looking out. I crept behind It,
U||   and gave It my knife; but the knife went through It, empty as the air.”
U||   And as he spoke he took his knife and drove it savagely into space.
U||   Then he went on: “But It is here, and I’ll find It. It is in the hold,
U||   perhaps in one of those boxes. I’ll unscrew them one by one and see.
U||   You work the helm.” And, with a warning look and his finger on his lip,
U||   he went below. There was springing up a choppy wind, and I could not
U||   leave the helm. I saw him come out on deck again with a tool-chest and
U||   a lantern, and go down the forward hatchway. He is mad, stark, raving
U||   mad, and it’s no use my trying to stop him. He can’t hurt those big
U||   boxes: they are invoiced as “clay,” and to pull them about is as
U||   harmless a thing as he can do. So here I stay, and mind the helm, and
U||   write these notes. I can only trust in God and wait till the fog
U||   clears. Then, if I can’t steer to any harbour with the wind that is, I
U||   shall cut down sails and lie by, and signal for help....
U||   It is nearly all over now. Just as I was beginning to hope that the
U||   mate would come out calmer—for I heard him knocking away at something
U||   in the hold, and work is good for him—there came up the hatchway a
U||   sudden, startled scream, which made my blood run cold, and up on the
U||   deck he came as if shot from a gun—a raging madman, with his eyes
U||   rolling and his face convulsed with fear. “Save me! save me!” he cried,
U||   and then looked round on the blanket of fog. His horror turned to
U||   despair, and in a steady voice he said: “You had better come too,
U||   captain, before it is too late. He is there. I know the secret now. The
U||   sea will save me from Him, and it is all that is left!” Before I could
U||   say a word, or move forward to seize him, he sprang on the bulwark and
U||   deliberately threw himself into the sea. I suppose I know the secret
U||   too, now. It was this madman who had got rid of the men one by one, and
U||   now he has followed them himself. God help me! How am I to account for
U||   all these horrors when I get to port? When I get to port! Will that
U||   ever be?
U||   4 August.—Still fog, which the sunrise cannot pierce. I know there is
U||   sunrise because I am a sailor, why else I know not. I dared not go
U||   below, I dared not leave the helm; so here all night I stayed, and in
U||   the dimness of the night I saw It—Him! God forgive me, but the mate was
U||   right to jump overboard. It was better to die like a man; to die like a
U||   sailor in blue water no man can object. But I am captain, and I must
U||   not leave my ship. But I shall baffle this fiend or monster, for I
U||   shall tie my hands to the wheel when my strength begins to fail, and
U||   along with them I shall tie that which He—It!—dare not touch; and then,
U||   come good wind or foul, I shall save my soul, and my honour as a
U||   captain. I am growing weaker, and the night is coming on. If He can
U||   look me in the face again, I may not have time to act.... If we are
U||   wrecked, mayhap this bottle may be found, and those who find it may
U||   understand; if not, ... well, then all men shall know that I have been
U||   true to my trust. God and the Blessed Virgin and the saints help a poor
U||   ignorant soul trying to do his duty....
U||   Of course the verdict was an open one. There is no evidence to adduce;
U||   and whether or not the man himself committed the murders there is now
U||   none to say. The folk here hold almost universally that the captain is
U||   simply a hero, and he is to be given a public funeral. Already it is
U||   arranged that his body is to be taken with a train of boats up the Esk
U||   for a piece and then brought back to Tate Hill Pier and up the abbey
U||   steps; for he is to be buried in the churchyard on the cliff. The
U||   owners of more than a hundred boats have already given in their names
U||   as wishing to follow him to the grave.
U||   No trace has ever been found of the great dog; at which there is much
U||   mourning, for, with public opinion in its present state, he would, I
U||   believe, be adopted by the town. To-morrow will see the funeral; and so
U||   will end this one more “mystery of the sea.”
U||   Mina Murray’s Journal.
U||   8 August.—Lucy was very restless all night, and I, too, could not
U||   sleep. The storm was fearful, and as it boomed loudly among the
U||   chimney-pots, it made me shudder. When a sharp puff came it seemed to
U||   be like a distant gun. Strangely enough, Lucy did not wake; but she got
U||   up twice and dressed herself. Fortunately, each time I awoke in time
U||   and managed to undress her without waking her, and got her back to bed.
U||   It is a very strange thing, this sleep-walking, for as soon as her will
U||   is thwarted in any physical way, her intention, if there be any,
U||   disappears, and she yields herself almost exactly to the routine of her
U||   life.
U||   Early in the morning we both got up and went down to the harbour to see
U||   if anything had happened in the night. There were very few people
U||   about, and though the sun was bright, and the air clear and fresh, the
U||   big, grim-looking waves, that seemed dark themselves because the foam
U||   that topped them was like snow, forced themselves in through the narrow
U||   mouth of the harbour—like a bullying man going through a crowd. Somehow
U||   I felt glad that Jonathan was not on the sea last night, but on land.
U||   But, oh, is he on land or sea? Where is he, and how? I am getting
U||   fearfully anxious about him. If I only knew what to do, and could do
U||   anything!
U||   10 August.—The funeral of the poor sea-captain to-day was most
U||   touching. Every boat in the harbour seemed to be there, and the coffin
U||   was carried by captains all the way from Tate Hill Pier up to the
U||   churchyard. Lucy came with me, and we went early to our old seat,
U||   whilst the cortège of boats went up the river to the Viaduct and came
U||   down again. We had a lovely view, and saw the procession nearly all the
U||   way. The poor fellow was laid to rest quite near our seat so that we
U||   stood on it when the time came and saw everything. Poor Lucy seemed
U||   much upset. She was restless and uneasy all the time, and I cannot but
U||   think that her dreaming at night is telling on her. She is quite odd in
U||   one thing: she will not admit to me that there is any cause for
U||   restlessness; or if there be, she does not understand it herself. There
U||   is an additional cause in that poor old Mr. Swales was found dead this
U||   morning on our seat, his neck being broken. He had evidently, as the
U||   doctor said, fallen back in the seat in some sort of fright, for there
U||   was a look of fear and horror on his face that the men said made them
U||   shudder. Poor dear old man! Perhaps he had seen Death with his dying
U||   eyes! Lucy is so sweet and sensitive that she feels influences more
U||   acutely than other people do. Just now she was quite upset by a little
U||   thing which I did not much heed, though I am myself very fond of
U||   animals. One of the men who came up here often to look for the boats
U||   was followed by his dog. The dog is always with him. They are both
U||   quiet persons, and I never saw the man angry, nor heard the dog bark.
U||   During the service the dog would not come to its master, who was on the
U||   seat with us, but kept a few yards off, barking and howling. Its master
U||   spoke to it gently, and then harshly, and then angrily; but it would
U||   neither come nor cease to make a noise. It was in a sort of fury, with
U||   its eyes savage, and all its hairs bristling out like a cat’s tail when
U||   puss is on the war-path. Finally the man, too, got angry, and jumped
U||   down and kicked the dog, and then took it by the scruff of the neck and
U||   half dragged and half threw it on the tombstone on which the seat is
U||   fixed. The moment it touched the stone the poor thing became quiet and
U||   fell all into a tremble. It did not try to get away, but crouched down,
U||   quivering and cowering, and was in such a pitiable state of terror that
U||   I tried, though without effect, to comfort it. Lucy was full of pity,
U||   too, but she did not attempt to touch the dog, but looked at it in an
U||   agonised sort of way. I greatly fear that she is of too super-sensitive
U||   a nature to go through the world without trouble. She will be dreaming
U||   of this to-night, I am sure. The whole agglomeration of things—the ship
U||   steered into port by a dead man; his attitude, tied to the wheel with a
U||   crucifix and beads; the touching funeral; the dog, now furious and now
U||   in terror—will all afford material for her dreams.
U||   I think it will be best for her to go to bed tired out physically, so I
U||   shall take her for a long walk by the cliffs to Robin Hood’s Bay and
U||   back. She ought not to have much inclination for sleep-walking then.
U||CHAPTER VIII
U||MINA MURRAY’S JOURNAL
U||   Same day, 11 o’clock p. m.—Oh, but I am tired! If it were not that I
U||   had made my diary a duty I should not open it to-night. We had a lovely
U||   walk. Lucy, after a while, was in gay spirits, owing, I think, to some
U||   dear cows who came nosing towards us in a field close to the
U||   lighthouse, and frightened the wits out of us. I believe we forgot
U||   everything except, of course, personal fear, and it seemed to wipe the
U||   slate clean and give us a fresh start. We had a capital “severe tea” at
U||   Robin Hood’s Bay in a sweet little old-fashioned inn, with a bow-window
U||   right over the seaweed-covered rocks of the strand. I believe we should
U||   have shocked the “New Woman” with our appetites. Men are more tolerant,
U||   bless them! Then we walked home with some, or rather many, stoppages to
U||   rest, and with our hearts full of a constant dread of wild bulls. Lucy
U||   was really tired, and we intended to creep off to bed as soon as we
U||   could. The young curate came in, however, and Mrs. Westenra asked him
U||   to stay for supper. Lucy and I had both a fight for it with the dusty
U||   miller; I know it was a hard fight on my part, and I am quite heroic. I
U||   think that some day the bishops must get together and see about
U||   breeding up a new class of curates, who don’t take supper, no matter
U||   how they may be pressed to, and who will know when girls are tired.
U||   Lucy is asleep and breathing softly. She has more colour in her cheeks
U||   than usual, and looks, oh, so sweet. If Mr. Holmwood fell in love with
U||   her seeing her only in the drawing-room, I wonder what he would say if
U||   he saw her now. Some of the “New Women” writers will some day start an
U||   idea that men and women should be allowed to see each other asleep
U||   before proposing or accepting. But I suppose the New Woman won’t
U||   condescend in future to accept; she will do the proposing herself. And
U||   a nice job she will make of it, too! There’s some consolation in that.
U||   I am so happy to-night, because dear Lucy seems better. I really
U||   believe she has turned the corner, and that we are over her troubles
U||   with dreaming. I should be quite happy if I only knew if Jonathan....
U||   God bless and keep him.
U||   11 August, 3 a. m.—Diary again. No sleep now, so I may as well write. I
U||   am too agitated to sleep. We have had such an adventure, such an
U||   agonising experience. I fell asleep as soon as I had closed my
U||   diary.... Suddenly I became broad awake, and sat up, with a horrible
U||   sense of fear upon me, and of some feeling of emptiness around me. The
U||   room was dark, so I could not see Lucy’s bed; I stole across and felt
U||   for her. The bed was empty. I lit a match and found that she was not in
U||   the room. The door was shut, but not locked, as I had left it. I feared
U||   to wake her mother, who has been more than usually ill lately, so threw
U||   on some clothes and got ready to look for her. As I was leaving the
U||   room it struck me that the clothes she wore might give me some clue to
U||   her dreaming intention. Dressing-gown would mean house; dress, outside.
U||   Dressing-gown and dress were both in their places. “Thank God,” I said
U||   to myself, “she cannot be far, as she is only in her nightdress.” I ran
U||   downstairs and looked in the sitting-room. Not there! Then I looked in
U||   all the other open rooms of the house, with an ever-growing fear
U||   chilling my heart. Finally I came to the hall door and found it open.
U||   It was not wide open, but the catch of the lock had not caught. The
U||   people of the house are careful to lock the door every night, so I
U||   feared that Lucy must have gone out as she was. There was no time to
U||   think of what might happen; a vague, overmastering fear obscured all
U||   details. I took a big, heavy shawl and ran out. The clock was striking
U||   one as I was in the Crescent, and there was not a soul in sight. I ran
U||   along the North Terrace, but could see no sign of the white figure
U||   which I expected. At the edge of the West Cliff above the pier I looked
U||   across the harbour to the East Cliff, in the hope or fear—I don’t know
U||   which—of seeing Lucy in our favourite seat. There was a bright full
U||   moon, with heavy black, driving clouds, which threw the whole scene
U||   into a fleeting diorama of light and shade as they sailed across. For a
U||   moment or two I could see nothing, as the shadow of a cloud obscured
U||   St. Mary’s Church and all around it. Then as the cloud passed I could
U||   see the ruins of the abbey coming into view; and as the edge of a
U||   narrow band of light as sharp as a sword-cut moved along, the church
U||   and the churchyard became gradually visible. Whatever my expectation
U||   was, it was not disappointed, for there, on our favourite seat, the
U||   silver light of the moon struck a half-reclining figure, snowy white.
U||   The coming of the cloud was too quick for me to see much, for shadow
U||   shut down on light almost immediately; but it seemed to me as though
U||   something dark stood behind the seat where the white figure shone, and
U||   bent over it. What it was, whether man or beast, I could not tell; I
U||   did not wait to catch another glance, but flew down the steep steps to
U||   the pier and along by the fish-market to the bridge, which was the only
U||   way to reach the East Cliff. The town seemed as dead, for not a soul
U||   did I see; I rejoiced that it was so, for I wanted no witness of poor
U||   Lucy’s condition. The time and distance seemed endless, and my knees
U||   trembled and my breath came laboured as I toiled up the endless steps
U||   to the abbey. I must have gone fast, and yet it seemed to me as if my
U||   feet were weighted with lead, and as though every joint in my body were
U||   rusty. When I got almost to the top I could see the seat and the white
U||   figure, for I was now close enough to distinguish it even through the
U||   spells of shadow. There was undoubtedly something, long and black,
U||   bending over the half-reclining white figure. I called in fright,
U||   “Lucy! Lucy!” and something raised a head, and from where I was I could
U||   see a white face and red, gleaming eyes. Lucy did not answer, and I ran
U||   on to the entrance of the churchyard. As I entered, the church was
U||   between me and the seat, and for a minute or so I lost sight of her.
U||   When I came in view again the cloud had passed, and the moonlight
U||   struck so brilliantly that I could see Lucy half reclining with her
U||   head lying over the back of the seat. She was quite alone, and there
U||   was not a sign of any living thing about.
U||   When I bent over her I could see that she was still asleep. Her lips
U||   were parted, and she was breathing—not softly as usual with her, but in
U||   long, heavy gasps, as though striving to get her lungs full at every
U||   breath. As I came close, she put up her hand in her sleep and pulled
U||   the collar of her nightdress close around her throat. Whilst she did so
U||   there came a little shudder through her, as though she felt the cold. I
U||   flung the warm shawl over her, and drew the edges tight round her neck,
U||   for I dreaded lest she should get some deadly chill from the night air,
U||   unclad as she was. I feared to wake her all at once, so, in order to
U||   have my hands free that I might help her, I fastened the shawl at her
U||   throat with a big safety-pin; but I must have been clumsy in my anxiety
U||   and pinched or pricked her with it, for by-and-by, when her breathing
U||   became quieter, she put her hand to her throat again and moaned. When I
U||   had her carefully wrapped up I put my shoes on her feet and then began
U||   very gently to wake her. At first she did not respond; but gradually
U||   she became more and more uneasy in her sleep, moaning and sighing
U||   occasionally. At last, as time was passing fast, and, for many other
U||   reasons, I wished to get her home at once, I shook her more forcibly,
U||   till finally she opened her eyes and awoke. She did not seem surprised
U||   to see me, as, of course, she did not realise all at once where she
U||   was. Lucy always wakes prettily, and even at such a time, when her body
U||   must have been chilled with cold, and her mind somewhat appalled at
U||   waking unclad in a churchyard at night, she did not lose her grace. She
U||   trembled a little, and clung to me; when I told her to come at once
U||   with me home she rose without a word, with the obedience of a child. As
U||   we passed along, the gravel hurt my feet, and Lucy noticed me wince.
U||   She stopped and wanted to insist upon my taking my shoes; but I would
U||   not. However, when we got to the pathway outside the churchyard, where
U||   there was a puddle of water, remaining from the storm, I daubed my feet
U||   with mud, using each foot in turn on the other, so that as we went
U||   home, no one, in case we should meet any one, should notice my bare
U||   feet.
U||   Fortune favoured us, and we got home without meeting a soul. Once we
U||   saw a man, who seemed not quite sober, passing along a street in front
U||   of us; but we hid in a door till he had disappeared up an opening such
U||   as there are here, steep little closes, or “wynds,” as they call them
U||   in Scotland. My heart beat so loud all the time that sometimes I
U||   thought I should faint. I was filled with anxiety about Lucy, not only
U||   for her health, lest she should suffer from the exposure, but for her
U||   reputation in case the story should get wind. When we got in, and had
U||   washed our feet, and had said a prayer of thankfulness together, I
U||   tucked her into bed. Before falling asleep she asked—even implored—me
U||   not to say a word to any one, even her mother, about her sleep-walking
U||   adventure. I hesitated at first to promise; but on thinking of the
U||   state of her mother’s health, and how the knowledge of such a thing
U||   would fret her, and thinking, too, of how such a story might become
U||   distorted—nay, infallibly would—in case it should leak out, I thought
U||   it wiser to do so. I hope I did right. I have locked the door, and the
U||   key is tied to my wrist, so perhaps I shall not be again disturbed.
U||   Lucy is sleeping soundly; the reflex of the dawn is high and far over
U||   the sea....
U||   Same day, noon.—All goes well. Lucy slept till I woke her and seemed
U||   not to have even changed her side. The adventure of the night does not
U||   seem to have harmed her; on the contrary, it has benefited her, for she
U||   looks better this morning than she has done for weeks. I was sorry to
U||   notice that my clumsiness with the safety-pin hurt her. Indeed, it
U||   might have been serious, for the skin of her throat was pierced. I must
U||   have pinched up a piece of loose skin and have transfixed it, for there
U||   are two little red points like pin-pricks, and on the band of her
U||   nightdress was a drop of blood. When I apologised and was concerned
U||   about it, she laughed and petted me, and said she did not even feel it.
U||   Fortunately it cannot leave a scar, as it is so tiny.
U||   Same day, night.—We passed a happy day. The air was clear, and the sun
U||   bright, and there was a cool breeze. We took our lunch to Mulgrave
U||   Woods, Mrs. Westenra driving by the road and Lucy and I walking by the
U||   cliff-path and joining her at the gate. I felt a little sad myself, for
U||   I could not but feel how absolutely happy it would have been had
U||   Jonathan been with me. But there! I must only be patient. In the
U||   evening we strolled in the Casino Terrace, and heard some good music by
U||   Spohr and Mackenzie, and went to bed early. Lucy seems more restful
U||   than she has been for some time, and fell asleep at once. I shall lock
U||   the door and secure the key the same as before, though I do not expect
U||   any trouble to-night.
U||   12 August.—My expectations were wrong, for twice during the night I was
U||   wakened by Lucy trying to get out. She seemed, even in her sleep, to be
U||   a little impatient at finding the door shut, and went back to bed under
U||   a sort of protest. I woke with the dawn, and heard the birds chirping
U||   outside of the window. Lucy woke, too, and, I was glad to see, was even
U||   better than on the previous morning. All her old gaiety of manner
U||   seemed to have come back, and she came and snuggled in beside me and
U||   told me all about Arthur. I told her how anxious I was about Jonathan,
U||   and then she tried to comfort me. Well, she succeeded somewhat, for,
U||   though sympathy can’t alter facts, it can help to make them more
U||   bearable.
U||   13 August.—Another quiet day, and to bed with the key on my wrist as
U||   before. Again I awoke in the night, and found Lucy sitting up in bed,
U||   still asleep, pointing to the window. I got up quietly, and pulling
U||   aside the blind, looked out. It was brilliant moonlight, and the soft
U||   effect of the light over the sea and sky—merged together in one great,
U||   silent mystery—was beautiful beyond words. Between me and the moonlight
U||   flitted a great bat, coming and going in great whirling circles. Once
U||   or twice it came quite close, but was, I suppose, frightened at seeing
U||   me, and flitted away across the harbour towards the abbey. When I came
U||   back from the window Lucy had lain down again, and was sleeping
U||   peacefully. She did not stir again all night.
U||   14 August.—On the East Cliff, reading and writing all day. Lucy seems
U||   to have become as much in love with the spot as I am, and it is hard to
U||   get her away from it when it is time to come home for lunch or tea or
U||   dinner. This afternoon she made a funny remark. We were coming home for
U||   dinner, and had come to the top of the steps up from the West Pier and
U||   stopped to look at the view, as we generally do. The setting sun, low
U||   down in the sky, was just dropping behind Kettleness; the red light was
U||   thrown over on the East Cliff and the old abbey, and seemed to bathe
U||   everything in a beautiful rosy glow. We were silent for a while, and
U||   suddenly Lucy murmured as if to herself:—
U||   “His red eyes again! They are just the same.” It was such an odd
U||   expression, coming apropos of nothing, that it quite startled me. I
U||   slewed round a little, so as to see Lucy well without seeming to stare
U||   at her, and saw that she was in a half-dreamy state, with an odd look
U||   on her face that I could not quite make out; so I said nothing, but
U||   followed her eyes. She appeared to be looking over at our own seat,
U||   whereon was a dark figure seated alone. I was a little startled myself,
U||   for it seemed for an instant as if the stranger had great eyes like
U||   burning flames; but a second look dispelled the illusion. The red
U||   sunlight was shining on the windows of St. Mary’s Church behind our
U||   seat, and as the sun dipped there was just sufficient change in the
U||   refraction and reflection to make it appear as if the light moved. I
U||   called Lucy’s attention to the peculiar effect, and she became herself
U||   with a start, but she looked sad all the same; it may have been that
U||   she was thinking of that terrible night up there. We never refer to it;
U||   so I said nothing, and we went home to dinner. Lucy had a headache and
U||   went early to bed. I saw her asleep, and went out for a little stroll
U||   myself; I walked along the cliffs to the westward, and was full of
U||   sweet sadness, for I was thinking of Jonathan. When coming home—it was
U||   then bright moonlight, so bright that, though the front of our part of
U||   the Crescent was in shadow, everything could be well seen—I threw a
U||   glance up at our window, and saw Lucy’s head leaning out. I thought
U||   that perhaps she was looking out for me, so I opened my handkerchief
U||   and waved it. She did not notice or make any movement whatever. Just
U||   then, the moonlight crept round an angle of the building, and the light
U||   fell on the window. There distinctly was Lucy with her head lying up
U||   against the side of the window-sill and her eyes shut. She was fast
U||   asleep, and by her, seated on the window-sill, was something that
U||   looked like a good-sized bird. I was afraid she might get a chill, so I
U||   ran upstairs, but as I came into the room she was moving back to her
U||   bed, fast asleep, and breathing heavily; she was holding her hand to
U||   her throat, as though to protect it from cold.
U||   I did not wake her, but tucked her up warmly; I have taken care that
U||   the door is locked and the window securely fastened.
U||   She looks so sweet as she sleeps; but she is paler than is her wont,
U||   and there is a drawn, haggard look under her eyes which I do not like.
U||   I fear she is fretting about something. I wish I could find out what it
U||   is.
U||   15 August.—Rose later than usual. Lucy was languid and tired, and slept
U||   on after we had been called. We had a happy surprise at breakfast.
U||   Arthur’s father is better, and wants the marriage to come off soon.
U||   Lucy is full of quiet joy, and her mother is glad and sorry at once.
U||   Later on in the day she told me the cause. She is grieved to lose Lucy
U||   as her very own, but she is rejoiced that she is soon to have some one
U||   to protect her. Poor dear, sweet lady! She confided to me that she has
U||   got her death-warrant. She has not told Lucy, and made me promise
U||   secrecy; her doctor told her that within a few months, at most, she
U||   must die, for her heart is weakening. At any time, even now, a sudden
U||   shock would be almost sure to kill her. Ah, we were wise to keep from
U||   her the affair of the dreadful night of Lucy’s sleep-walking.
U||   17 August.—No diary for two whole days. I have not had the heart to
U||   write. Some sort of shadowy pall seems to be coming over our happiness.
U||   No news from Jonathan, and Lucy seems to be growing weaker, whilst her
U||   mother’s hours are numbering to a close. I do not understand Lucy’s
U||   fading away as she is doing. She eats well and sleeps well, and enjoys
U||   the fresh air; but all the time the roses in her cheeks are fading, and
U||   she gets weaker and more languid day by day; at night I hear her
U||   gasping as if for air. I keep the key of our door always fastened to my
U||   wrist at night, but she gets up and walks about the room, and sits at
U||   the open window. Last night I found her leaning out when I woke up, and
U||   when I tried to wake her I could not; she was in a faint. When I
U||   managed to restore her she was as weak as water, and cried silently
U||   between long, painful struggles for breath. When I asked her how she
U||   came to be at the window she shook her head and turned away. I trust
U||   her feeling ill may not be from that unlucky prick of the safety-pin. I
U||   looked at her throat just now as she lay asleep, and the tiny wounds
U||   seem not to have healed. They are still open, and, if anything, larger
U||   than before, and the edges of them are faintly white. They are like
U||   little white dots with red centres. Unless they heal within a day or
U||   two, I shall insist on the doctor seeing about them.
