U||   18 August.—I am happy to-day, and write sitting on the seat in the
U||   churchyard. Lucy is ever so much better. Last night she slept well all
U||   night, and did not disturb me once. The roses seem coming back already
U||   to her cheeks, though she is still sadly pale and wan-looking. If she
U||   were in any way anæmic I could understand it, but she is not. She is in
U||   gay spirits and full of life and cheerfulness. All the morbid reticence
U||   seems to have passed from her, and she has just reminded me, as if I
U||   needed any reminding, of that night, and that it was here, on this very
U||   seat, I found her asleep. As she told me she tapped playfully with the
U||   heel of her boot on the stone slab and said:—
U||   “My poor little feet didn’t make much noise then! I daresay poor old
U||   Mr. Swales would have told me that it was because I didn’t want to wake
U||   up Geordie.” As she was in such a communicative humour, I asked her if
U||   she had dreamed at all that night. Before she answered, that sweet,
U||   puckered look came into her forehead, which Arthur—I call him Arthur
U||   from her habit—says he loves; and, indeed, I don’t wonder that he does.
U||   Then she went on in a half-dreaming kind of way, as if trying to recall
U||   it to herself:—
U||   “I didn’t quite dream; but it all seemed to be real. I only wanted to
U||   be here in this spot—I don’t know why, for I was afraid of something—I
U||   don’t know what. I remember, though I suppose I was asleep, passing
U||   through the streets and over the bridge. A fish leaped as I went by,
U||   and I leaned over to look at it, and I heard a lot of dogs howling—the
U||   whole town seemed as if it must be full of dogs all howling at once—as
U||   I went up the steps. Then I had a vague memory of something long and
U||   dark with red eyes, just as we saw in the sunset, and something very
U||   sweet and very bitter all around me at once; and then I seemed sinking
U||   into deep green water, and there was a singing in my ears, as I have
U||   heard there is to drowning men; and then everything seemed passing away
U||   from me; my soul seemed to go out from my body and float about the air.
U||   I seem to remember that once the West Lighthouse was right under me,
U||   and then there was a sort of agonising feeling, as if I were in an
U||   earthquake, and I came back and found you shaking my body. I saw you do
U||   it before I felt you.”
U||   Then she began to laugh. It seemed a little uncanny to me, and I
U||   listened to her breathlessly. I did not quite like it, and thought it
U||   better not to keep her mind on the subject, so we drifted on to other
U||   subjects, and Lucy was like her old self again. When we got home the
U||   fresh breeze had braced her up, and her pale cheeks were really more
U||   rosy. Her mother rejoiced when she saw her, and we all spent a very
U||   happy evening together.
U||   19 August.—Joy, joy, joy! although not all joy. At last, news of
U||   Jonathan. The dear fellow has been ill; that is why he did not write. I
U||   am not afraid to think it or say it, now that I know. Mr. Hawkins sent
U||   me on the letter, and wrote himself, oh, so kindly. I am to leave in
U||   the morning and go over to Jonathan, and to help to nurse him if
U||   necessary, and to bring him home. Mr. Hawkins says it would not be a
U||   bad thing if we were to be married out there. I have cried over the
U||   good Sister’s letter till I can feel it wet against my bosom, where it
U||   lies. It is of Jonathan, and must be next my heart, for he is in my
U||   heart. My journey is all mapped out, and my luggage ready. I am only
U||   taking one change of dress; Lucy will bring my trunk to London and keep
U||   it till I send for it, for it may be that ... I must write no more; I
U||   must keep it to say to Jonathan, my husband. The letter that he has
U||   seen and touched must comfort me till we meet.
