U||   Buda-Pesth, to Miss Wilhelmina Murray.
U||   “12 August.
U||   “Dear Madam,—
U||   “I write by desire of Mr. Jonathan Harker, who is himself not strong
U||   enough to write, though progressing well, thanks to God and St. Joseph
U||   and Ste. Mary. He has been under our care for nearly six weeks,
U||   suffering from a violent brain fever. He wishes me to convey his love,
U||   and to say that by this post I write for him to Mr. Peter Hawkins,
U||   Exeter, to say, with his dutiful respects, that he is sorry for his
U||   delay, and that all of his work is completed. He will require some few
U||   weeks’ rest in our sanatorium in the hills, but will then return. He
U||   wishes me to say that he has not sufficient money with him, and that he
U||   would like to pay for his staying here, so that others who need shall
U||   not be wanting for help.
U||   “Believe me,
U||   “Yours, with sympathy and all blessings,
U||   “Sister Agatha.
U||   “P. S.—My patient being asleep, I open this to let you know something
U||   more. He has told me all about you, and that you are shortly to be his
U||   wife. All blessings to you both! He has had some fearful shock—so says
U||   our doctor—and in his delirium his ravings have been dreadful; of
U||   wolves and poison and blood; of ghosts and demons; and I fear to say of
