U||   19 August.—Strange and sudden change in Renfield last night. About
U||   eight o’clock he began to get excited and sniff about as a dog does
U||   when setting. The attendant was struck by his manner, and knowing my
U||   interest in him, encouraged him to talk. He is usually respectful to
U||   the attendant and at times servile; but to-night, the man tells me, he
U||   was quite haughty. Would not condescend to talk with him at all. All he
U||   would say was:—
U||   “I don’t want to talk to you: you don’t count now; the Master is at
U||   hand.”
U||   The attendant thinks it is some sudden form of religious mania which
U||   has seized him. If so, we must look out for squalls, for a strong man
U||   with homicidal and religious mania at once might be dangerous. The
U||   combination is a dreadful one. At nine o’clock I visited him myself.
U||   His attitude to me was the same as that to the attendant; in his
U||   sublime self-feeling the difference between myself and attendant seemed
U||   to him as nothing. It looks like religious mania, and he will soon
U||   think that he himself is God. These infinitesimal distinctions between
U||   man and man are too paltry for an Omnipotent Being. How these madmen
U||   give themselves away! The real God taketh heed lest a sparrow fall; but
U||   the God created from human vanity sees no difference between an eagle
U||   and a sparrow. Oh, if men only knew!
U||   For half an hour or more Renfield kept getting excited in greater and
U||   greater degree. I did not pretend to be watching him, but I kept strict
U||   observation all the same. All at once that shifty look came into his
U||   eyes which we always see when a madman has seized an idea, and with it
U||   the shifty movement of the head and back which asylum attendants come
U||   to know so well. He became quite quiet, and went and sat on the edge of
U||   his bed resignedly, and looked into space with lack-lustre eyes. I
U||   thought I would find out if his apathy were real or only assumed, and
U||   tried to lead him to talk of his pets, a theme which had never failed
U||   to excite his attention. At first he made no reply, but at length said
U||   testily:—
U||   “Bother them all! I don’t care a pin about them.”
U||   “What?” I said. “You don’t mean to tell me you don’t care about
U||   spiders?” (Spiders at present are his hobby and the note-book is
U||   filling up with columns of small figures.) To this he answered
U||   enigmatically:—
U||   “The bride-maidens rejoice the eyes that wait the coming of the bride;
U||   but when the bride draweth nigh, then the maidens shine not to the eyes
U||   that are filled.”
U||   He would not explain himself, but remained obstinately seated on his
U||   bed all the time I remained with him.
U||   I am weary to-night and low in spirits. I cannot but think of Lucy, and
U||   how different things might have been. If I don’t sleep at once,
U||   chloral, the modern Morpheus—C[2]HCl[3]O. H[2]O! I must be careful not
U||   to let it grow into a habit. No, I shall take none to-night! I have
U||   thought of Lucy, and I shall not dishonour her by mixing the two. If
U||   need be, to-night shall be sleepless....
U||   Later.—Glad I made the resolution; gladder that I kept to it. I had
U||   lain tossing about, and had heard the clock strike only twice, when the
U||   night-watchman came to me, sent up from the ward, to say that Renfield
U||   had escaped. I threw on my clothes and ran down at once; my patient is
U||   too dangerous a person to be roaming about. Those ideas of his might
U||   work out dangerously with strangers. The attendant was waiting for me.
U||   He said he had seen him not ten minutes before, seemingly asleep in his
U||   bed, when he had looked through the observation-trap in the door. His
U||   attention was called by the sound of the window being wrenched out. He
U||   ran back and saw his feet disappear through the window, and had at once
U||   sent up for me. He was only in his night-gear, and cannot be far off.
U||   The attendant thought it would be more useful to watch where he should
U||   go than to follow him, as he might lose sight of him whilst getting out
U||   of the building by the door. He is a bulky man, and couldn’t get
U||   through the window. I am thin, so, with his aid, I got out, but feet
U||   foremost, and, as we were only a few feet above ground, landed unhurt.
U||   The attendant told me the patient had gone to the left, and had taken a
U||   straight line, so I ran as quickly as I could. As I got through the
U||   belt of trees I saw a white figure scale the high wall which separates
U||   our grounds from those of the deserted house.
U||   I ran back at once, told the watchman to get three or four men
U||   immediately and follow me into the grounds of Carfax, in case our
U||   friend might be dangerous. I got a ladder myself, and crossing the
U||   wall, dropped down on the other side. I could see Renfield’s figure
U||   just disappearing behind the angle of the house, so I ran after him. On
U||   the far side of the house I found him pressed close against the old
U||   ironbound oak door of the chapel. He was talking, apparently to some
U||   one, but I was afraid to go near enough to hear what he was saying,
U||   lest I might frighten him, and he should run off. Chasing an errant
U||   swarm of bees is nothing to following a naked lunatic, when the fit of
U||   escaping is upon him! After a few minutes, however, I could see that he
U||   did not take note of anything around him, and so ventured to draw
U||   nearer to him—the more so as my men had now crossed the wall and were
U||   closing him in. I heard him say:—
U||   “I am here to do Your bidding, Master. I am Your slave, and You will
U||   reward me, for I shall be faithful. I have worshipped You long and afar
U||   off. Now that You are near, I await Your commands, and You will not
U||   pass me by, will You, dear Master, in Your distribution of good
U||   things?”
U||   He is a selfish old beggar anyhow. He thinks of the loaves and fishes
U||   even when he believes he is in a Real Presence. His manias make a
U||   startling combination. When we closed in on him he fought like a tiger.
U||   He is immensely strong, for he was more like a wild beast than a man. I
U||   never saw a lunatic in such a paroxysm of rage before; and I hope I
U||   shall not again. It is a mercy that we have found out his strength and
U||   his danger in good time. With strength and determination like his, he
U||   might have done wild work before he was caged. He is safe now at any
U||   rate. Jack Sheppard himself couldn’t get free from the strait-waistcoat
U||   that keeps him restrained, and he’s chained to the wall in the padded
U||   room. His cries are at times awful, but the silences that follow are
U||   more deadly still, for he means murder in every turn and movement.
U||   Just now he spoke coherent words for the first time:—
U||   “I shall be patient, Master. It is coming—coming—coming!”
U||   So I took the hint, and came too. I was too excited to sleep, but this
U||   diary has quieted me, and I feel I shall get some sleep to-night.
U||CHAPTER IX
U||   Letter, Mina Harker to Lucy Westenra.
U||   “Buda-Pesth, 24 August.
U||   “My dearest Lucy,—
U||   “I know you will be anxious to hear all that has happened since we
U||   parted at the railway station at Whitby. Well, my dear, I got to Hull
U||   all right, and caught the boat to Hamburg, and then the train on here.
U||   I feel that I can hardly recall anything of the journey, except that I
U||   knew I was coming to Jonathan, and, that as I should have to do some
U||   nursing, I had better get all the sleep I could.... I found my dear
U||   one, oh, so thin and pale and weak-looking. All the resolution has gone
U||   out of his dear eyes, and that quiet dignity which I told you was in
U||   his face has vanished. He is only a wreck of himself, and he does not
U||   remember anything that has happened to him for a long time past. At
U||   least, he wants me to believe so, and I shall never ask. He has had
U||   some terrible shock, and I fear it might tax his poor brain if he were
U||   to try to recall it. Sister Agatha, who is a good creature and a born
U||   nurse, tells me that he raved of dreadful things whilst he was off his
U||   head. I wanted her to tell me what they were; but she would only cross
U||   herself, and say she would never tell; that the ravings of the sick
U||   were the secrets of God, and that if a nurse through her vocation
U||   should hear them, she should respect her trust. She is a sweet, good
U||   soul, and the next day, when she saw I was troubled, she opened up the
U||   subject again, and after saying that she could never mention what my
U||   poor dear raved about, added: ‘I can tell you this much, my dear: that
U||   it was not about anything which he has done wrong himself; and you, as
U||   his wife to be, have no cause to be concerned. He has not forgotten you
U||   or what he owes to you. His fear was of great and terrible things,
U||   which no mortal can treat of.’ I do believe the dear soul thought I
U||   might be jealous lest my poor dear should have fallen in love with any
U||   other girl. The idea of my being jealous about Jonathan! And yet, my
U||   dear, let me whisper, I felt a thrill of joy through me when I knew
U||   that no other woman was a cause of trouble. I am now sitting by his
U||   bedside, where I can see his face while he sleeps. He is waking!...
U||   “When he woke he asked me for his coat, as he wanted to get something
U||   from the pocket; I asked Sister Agatha, and she brought all his things.
U||   I saw that amongst them was his note-book, and was going to ask him to
U||   let me look at it—for I knew then that I might find some clue to his
U||   trouble—but I suppose he must have seen my wish in my eyes, for he sent
U||   me over to the window, saying he wanted to be quite alone for a moment.
U||   Then he called me back, and when I came he had his hand over the
U||   note-book, and he said to me very solemnly:—
U||   “‘Wilhelmina’—I knew then that he was in deadly earnest, for he has
U||   never called me by that name since he asked me to marry him—‘you know,
U||   dear, my ideas of the trust between husband and wife: there should be
U||   no secret, no concealment. I have had a great shock, and when I try to
U||   think of what it is I feel my head spin round, and I do not know if it
U||   was all real or the dreaming of a madman. You know I have had brain
U||   fever, and that is to be mad. The secret is here, and I do not want to
U||   know it. I want to take up my life here, with our marriage.’ For, my
U||   dear, we had decided to be married as soon as the formalities are
U||   complete. ‘Are you willing, Wilhelmina, to share my ignorance? Here is
U||   the book. Take it and keep it, read it if you will, but never let me
U||   know; unless, indeed, some solemn duty should come upon me to go back
U||   to the bitter hours, asleep or awake, sane or mad, recorded here.’ He
U||   fell back exhausted, and I put the book under his pillow, and kissed
U||   him. I have asked Sister Agatha to beg the Superior to let our wedding
U||   be this afternoon, and am waiting her reply....
U||   “She has come and told me that the chaplain of the English mission
U||   church has been sent for. We are to be married in an hour, or as soon
U||   after as Jonathan awakes....
U||   “Lucy, the time has come and gone. I feel very solemn, but very, very
U||   happy. Jonathan woke a little after the hour, and all was ready, and he
U||   sat up in bed, propped up with pillows. He answered his ‘I will’ firmly
U||   and strongly. I could hardly speak; my heart was so full that even
U||   those words seemed to choke me. The dear sisters were so kind. Please
U||   God, I shall never, never forget them, nor the grave and sweet
U||   responsibilities I have taken upon me. I must tell you of my wedding
U||   present. When the chaplain and the sisters had left me alone with my
U||   husband—oh, Lucy, it is the first time I have written the words ‘my
U||   husband’—left me alone with my husband, I took the book from under his
U||   pillow, and wrapped it up in white paper, and tied it with a little bit
U||   of pale blue ribbon which was round my neck, and sealed it over the
U||   knot with sealing-wax, and for my seal I used my wedding ring. Then I
U||   kissed it and showed it to my husband, and told him that I would keep
U||   it so, and then it would be an outward and visible sign for us all our
U||   lives that we trusted each other; that I would never open it unless it
U||   were for his own dear sake or for the sake of some stern duty. Then he
U||   took my hand in his, and oh, Lucy, it was the first time he took his
U||   wife’s hand, and said that it was the dearest thing in all the wide
U||   world, and that he would go through all the past again to win it, if
U||   need be. The poor dear meant to have said a part of the past, but he
U||   cannot think of time yet, and I shall not wonder if at first he mixes
U||   up not only the month, but the year.
U||   “Well, my dear, what could I say? I could only tell him that I was the
U||   happiest woman in all the wide world, and that I had nothing to give
U||   him except myself, my life, and my trust, and that with these went my
U||   love and duty for all the days of my life. And, my dear, when he kissed
U||   me, and drew me to him with his poor weak hands, it was like a very
U||   solemn pledge between us....
U||   “Lucy dear, do you know why I tell you all this? It is not only because
U||   it is all sweet to me, but because you have been, and are, very dear to
U||   me. It was my privilege to be your friend and guide when you came from
U||   the schoolroom to prepare for the world of life. I want you to see now,
U||   and with the eyes of a very happy wife, whither duty has led me; so
U||   that in your own married life you too may be all happy as I am. My
U||   dear, please Almighty God, your life may be all it promises: a long day
U||   of sunshine, with no harsh wind, no forgetting duty, no distrust. I
U||   must not wish you no pain, for that can never be; but I do hope you
U||   will be always as happy as I am now. Good-bye, my dear. I shall post
U||   this at once, and, perhaps, write you very soon again. I must stop, for
U||   Jonathan is waking—I must attend to my husband!
U||   “Your ever-loving
U||   “Mina Harker.”
U||   Letter, Lucy Westenra to Mina Harker.
U||   “Whitby, 30 August.
U||   “My dearest Mina,—
U||   “Oceans of love and millions of kisses, and may you soon be in your own
U||   home with your husband. I wish you could be coming home soon enough to
U||   stay with us here. The strong air would soon restore Jonathan; it has
U||   quite restored me. I have an appetite like a cormorant, am full of
U||   life, and sleep well. You will be glad to know that I have quite given
U||   up walking in my sleep. I think I have not stirred out of my bed for a
U||   week, that is when I once got into it at night. Arthur says I am
U||   getting fat. By the way, I forgot to tell you that Arthur is here. We
U||   have such walks and drives, and rides, and rowing, and tennis, and
U||   fishing together; and I love him more than ever. He tells me that he
U||   loves me more, but I doubt that, for at first he told me that he
U||   couldn’t love me more than he did then. But this is nonsense. There he
U||   is, calling to me. So no more just at present from your loving
U||   “Lucy.
U||   “P. S.—Mother sends her love. She seems better, poor dear.
U||   “P. P. S.—We are to be married on 28 September.”
U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   20 August.—The case of Renfield grows even more interesting. He has now
U||   so far quieted that there are spells of cessation from his passion. For
U||   the first week after his attack he was perpetually violent. Then one
U||   night, just as the moon rose, he grew quiet, and kept murmuring to
U||   himself: “Now I can wait; now I can wait.” The attendant came to tell
U||   me, so I ran down at once to have a look at him. He was still in the
U||   strait-waistcoat and in the padded room, but the suffused look had gone
U||   from his face, and his eyes had something of their old pleading—I might
U||   almost say, “cringing”—softness. I was satisfied with his present
U||   condition, and directed him to be relieved. The attendants hesitated,
U||   but finally carried out my wishes without protest. It was a strange
U||   thing that the patient had humour enough to see their distrust, for,
U||   coming close to me, he said in a whisper, all the while looking
U||   furtively at them:—
U||   “They think I could hurt you! Fancy me hurting you! The fools!”
U||   It was soothing, somehow, to the feelings to find myself dissociated
U||   even in the mind of this poor madman from the others; but all the same
U||   I do not follow his thought. Am I to take it that I have anything in
U||   common with him, so that we are, as it were, to stand together; or has
U||   he to gain from me some good so stupendous that my well-being is
U||   needful to him? I must find out later on. To-night he will not speak.
U||   Even the offer of a kitten or even a full-grown cat will not tempt him.
U||   He will only say: “I don’t take any stock in cats. I have more to think
U||   of now, and I can wait; I can wait.”
U||   After a while I left him. The attendant tells me that he was quiet
U||   until just before dawn, and that then he began to get uneasy, and at
U||   length violent, until at last he fell into a paroxysm which exhausted
U||   him so that he swooned into a sort of coma.
U||   ... Three nights has the same thing happened—violent all day then quiet
U||   from moonrise to sunrise. I wish I could get some clue to the cause. It
U||   would almost seem as if there was some influence which came and went.
U||   Happy thought! We shall to-night play sane wits against mad ones. He
U||   escaped before without our help; to-night he shall escape with it. We
U||   shall give him a chance, and have the men ready to follow in case they
U||   are required....
U||   23 August.—“The unexpected always happens.” How well Disraeli knew
U||   life. Our bird when he found the cage open would not fly, so all our
U||   subtle arrangements were for nought. At any rate, we have proved one
U||   thing; that the spells of quietness last a reasonable time. We shall in
U||   future be able to ease his bonds for a few hours each day. I have given
U||   orders to the night attendant merely to shut him in the padded room,
U||   when once he is quiet, until an hour before sunrise. The poor soul’s
U||   body will enjoy the relief even if his mind cannot appreciate it. Hark!
U||   The unexpected again! I am called; the patient has once more escaped.
U||   Later.—Another night adventure. Renfield artfully waited until the
U||   attendant was entering the room to inspect. Then he dashed out past him
U||   and flew down the passage. I sent word for the attendants to follow.
U||   Again he went into the grounds of the deserted house, and we found him
U||   in the same place, pressed against the old chapel door. When he saw me
U||   he became furious, and had not the attendants seized him in time, he
U||   would have tried to kill me. As we were holding him a strange thing
U||   happened. He suddenly redoubled his efforts, and then as suddenly grew
U||   calm. I looked round instinctively, but could see nothing. Then I
U||   caught the patient’s eye and followed it, but could trace nothing as it
U||   looked into the moonlit sky except a big bat, which was flapping its
U||   silent and ghostly way to the west. Bats usually wheel and flit about,
U||   but this one seemed to go straight on, as if it knew where it was bound
U||   for or had some intention of its own. The patient grew calmer every
U||   instant, and presently said:—
U||   “You needn’t tie me; I shall go quietly!” Without trouble we came back
U||   to the house. I feel there is something ominous in his calm, and shall
U||   not forget this night....
U||   Lucy Westenra’s Diary
U||   Hillingham, 24 August.—I must imitate Mina, and keep writing things
U||   down. Then we can have long talks when we do meet. I wonder when it
U||   will be. I wish she were with me again, for I feel so unhappy. Last
U||   night I seemed to be dreaming again just as I was at Whitby. Perhaps it
U||   is the change of air, or getting home again. It is all dark and horrid
U||   to me, for I can remember nothing; but I am full of vague fear, and I
U||   feel so weak and worn out. When Arthur came to lunch he looked quite
U||   grieved when he saw me, and I hadn’t the spirit to try to be cheerful.
U||   I wonder if I could sleep in mother’s room to-night. I shall make an
U||   excuse and try.
U||   25 August.—Another bad night. Mother did not seem to take to my
U||   proposal. She seems not too well herself, and doubtless she fears to
U||   worry me. I tried to keep awake, and succeeded for a while; but when
U||   the clock struck twelve it waked me from a doze, so I must have been
U||   falling asleep. There was a sort of scratching or flapping at the
U||   window, but I did not mind it, and as I remember no more, I suppose I
U||   must then have fallen asleep. More bad dreams. I wish I could remember
U||   them. This morning I am horribly weak. My face is ghastly pale, and my
U||   throat pains me. It must be something wrong with my lungs, for I don’t
U||   seem ever to get air enough. I shall try to cheer up when Arthur comes,
U||   or else I know he will be miserable to see me so.
U||   Letter, Arthur Holmwood to Dr. Seward.
U||   “Albemarle Hotel, 31 August.
U||   “My dear Jack,—
U||   “I want you to do me a favour. Lucy is ill; that is, she has no special
U||   disease, but she looks awful, and is getting worse every day. I have
U||   asked her if there is any cause; I do not dare to ask her mother, for
U||   to disturb the poor lady’s mind about her daughter in her present state
U||   of health would be fatal. Mrs. Westenra has confided to me that her
U||   doom is spoken—disease of the heart—though poor Lucy does not know it
U||   yet. I am sure that there is something preying on my dear girl’s mind.
U||   I am almost distracted when I think of her; to look at her gives me a
U||   pang. I told her I should ask you to see her, and though she demurred
U||   at first—I know why, old fellow—she finally consented. It will be a
U||   painful task for you, I know, old friend, but it is for her sake, and I
U||   must not hesitate to ask, or you to act. You are to come to lunch at
U||   Hillingham to-morrow, two o’clock, so as not to arouse any suspicion in
U||   Mrs. Westenra, and after lunch Lucy will take an opportunity of being
U||   alone with you. I shall come in for tea, and we can go away together; I
U||   am filled with anxiety, and want to consult with you alone as soon as I
U||   can after you have seen her. Do not fail!
U||   “Arthur.”
