U||   Letter from Dr. Seward to Arthur Holmwood.
U||   “2 September.
U||   “My dear old fellow,—
U||   “With regard to Miss Westenra’s health I hasten to let you know at once
U||   that in my opinion there is not any functional disturbance or any
U||   malady that I know of. At the same time, I am not by any means
U||   satisfied with her appearance; she is woefully different from what she
U||   was when I saw her last. Of course you must bear in mind that I did not
U||   have full opportunity of examination such as I should wish; our very
U||   friendship makes a little difficulty which not even medical science or
U||   custom can bridge over. I had better tell you exactly what happened,
U||   leaving you to draw, in a measure, your own conclusions. I shall then
U||   say what I have done and propose doing.
U||   “I found Miss Westenra in seemingly gay spirits. Her mother was
U||   present, and in a few seconds I made up my mind that she was trying all
U||   she knew to mislead her mother and prevent her from being anxious. I
U||   have no doubt she guesses, if she does not know, what need of caution
U||   there is. We lunched alone, and as we all exerted ourselves to be
U||   cheerful, we got, as some kind of reward for our labours, some real
U||   cheerfulness amongst us. Then Mrs. Westenra went to lie down, and Lucy
U||   was left with me. We went into her boudoir, and till we got there her
U||   gaiety remained, for the servants were coming and going. As soon as the
U||   door was closed, however, the mask fell from her face, and she sank
U||   down into a chair with a great sigh, and hid her eyes with her hand.
U||   When I saw that her high spirits had failed, I at once took advantage
U||   of her reaction to make a diagnosis. She said to me very sweetly:—
U||   “‘I cannot tell you how I loathe talking about myself.’ I reminded her
U||   that a doctor’s confidence was sacred, but that you were grievously
U||   anxious about her. She caught on to my meaning at once, and settled
U||   that matter in a word. ‘Tell Arthur everything you choose. I do not
U||   care for myself, but all for him!’ So I am quite free.
U||   “I could easily see that she is somewhat bloodless, but I could not see
U||   the usual anæmic signs, and by a chance I was actually able to test the
U||   quality of her blood, for in opening a window which was stiff a cord
U||   gave way, and she cut her hand slightly with broken glass. It was a
U||   slight matter in itself, but it gave me an evident chance, and I
U||   secured a few drops of the blood and have analysed them. The
U||   qualitative analysis gives a quite normal condition, and shows, I
U||   should infer, in itself a vigorous state of health. In other physical
U||   matters I was quite satisfied that there is no need for anxiety; but as
U||   there must be a cause somewhere, I have come to the conclusion that it
U||   must be something mental. She complains of difficulty in breathing
U||   satisfactorily at times, and of heavy, lethargic sleep, with dreams
U||   that frighten her, but regarding which she can remember nothing. She
U||   says that as a child she used to walk in her sleep, and that when in
U||   Whitby the habit came back, and that once she walked out in the night
U||   and went to East Cliff, where Miss Murray found her; but she assures me
U||   that of late the habit has not returned. I am in doubt, and so have
U||   done the best thing I know of; I have written to my old friend and
U||   master, Professor Van Helsing, of Amsterdam, who knows as much about
U||   obscure diseases as any one in the world. I have asked him to come
U||   over, and as you told me that all things were to be at your charge, I
U||   have mentioned to him who you are and your relations to Miss Westenra.
U||   This, my dear fellow, is in obedience to your wishes, for I am only too
U||   proud and happy to do anything I can for her. Van Helsing would, I
U||   know, do anything for me for a personal reason, so, no matter on what
U||   ground he comes, we must accept his wishes. He is a seemingly arbitrary
U||   man, but this is because he knows what he is talking about better than
U||   any one else. He is a philosopher and a metaphysician, and one of the
U||   most advanced scientists of his day; and he has, I believe, an
U||   absolutely open mind. This, with an iron nerve, a temper of the
U||   ice-brook, an indomitable resolution, self-command, and toleration
U||   exalted from virtues to blessings, and the kindliest and truest heart
U||   that beats—these form his equipment for the noble work that he is doing
U||   for mankind—work both in theory and practice, for his views are as wide
U||   as his all-embracing sympathy. I tell you these facts that you may know
U||   why I have such confidence in him. I have asked him to come at once. I
U||   shall see Miss Westenra to-morrow again. She is to meet me at the
U||   Stores, so that I may not alarm her mother by too early a repetition of
U||   my call.
U||   “Yours always,
U||   “John Seward.”
