U||   “3 September.
U||   “My dear Art,—
U||   “Van Helsing has come and gone. He came on with me to Hillingham, and
U||   found that, by Lucy’s discretion, her mother was lunching out, so that
U||   we were alone with her. Van Helsing made a very careful examination of
U||   the patient. He is to report to me, and I shall advise you, for of
U||   course I was not present all the time. He is, I fear, much concerned,
U||   but says he must think. When I told him of our friendship and how you
U||   trust to me in the matter, he said: ‘You must tell him all you think.
U||   Tell him what I think, if you can guess it, if you will. Nay, I am not
U||   jesting. This is no jest, but life and death, perhaps more.’ I asked
U||   what he meant by that, for he was very serious. This was when we had
