U||   I wrote him a letter simply telling him that you were coming, as Miss
U||   Westenra was not so well, and that I should let him know if need be.”
U||   “Right, my friend,” he said, “quite right! Better he not know as yet;
U||   perhaps he shall never know. I pray so; but if it be needed, then he
U||   shall know all. And, my good friend John, let me caution you. You deal
U||   with the madmen. All men are mad in some way or the other; and inasmuch
U||   as you deal discreetly with your madmen, so deal with God’s madmen,
U||   too—the rest of the world. You tell not your madmen what you do nor why
U||   you do it; you tell them not what you think. So you shall keep
U||   knowledge in its place, where it may rest—where it may gather its kind
U||   around it and breed. You and I shall keep as yet what we know here, and
U||   here.” He touched me on the heart and on the forehead, and then touched
U||   himself the same way. “I have for myself thoughts at the present. Later
U||   I shall unfold to you.”
U||   “Why not now?” I asked. “It may do some good; we may arrive at some
U||   decision.” He stopped and looked at me, and said:—
