U||   8 September.—I sat up all night with Lucy. The opiate worked itself off
U||   towards dusk, and she waked naturally; she looked a different being
U||   from what she had been before the operation. Her spirits even were
U||   good, and she was full of a happy vivacity, but I could see evidences
U||   of the absolute prostration which she had undergone. When I told Mrs.
U||   Westenra that Dr. Van Helsing had directed that I should sit up with
U||   her she almost pooh-poohed the idea, pointing out her daughter’s
U||   renewed strength and excellent spirits. I was firm, however, and made
U||   preparations for my long vigil. When her maid had prepared her for the
U||   night I came in, having in the meantime had supper, and took a seat by
U||   the bedside. She did not in any way make objection, but looked at me
U||   gratefully whenever I caught her eye. After a long spell she seemed
U||   sinking off to sleep, but with an effort seemed to pull herself
U||   together and shook it off. This was repeated several times, with
U||   greater effort and with shorter pauses as the time moved on. It was
U||   apparent that she did not want to sleep, so I tackled the subject at
U||   once:—
U||   “You do not want to go to sleep?”
U||   “No; I am afraid.”
U||   “Afraid to go to sleep! Why so? It is the boon we all crave for.”
U||   “Ah, not if you were like me—if sleep was to you a presage of horror!”
U||   “A presage of horror! What on earth do you mean?”
U||   “I don’t know; oh, I don’t know. And that is what is so terrible. All
U||   this weakness comes to me in sleep; until I dread the very thought.”
U||   “But, my dear girl, you may sleep to-night. I am here watching you, and
U||   I can promise that nothing will happen.”
U||   “Ah, I can trust you!” I seized the opportunity, and said: “I promise
U||   you that if I see any evidence of bad dreams I will wake you at once.”
