U||   to-night, as it might be well to be at hand, and stating that he was
U||   leaving by the night mail and would join me early in the morning.
U||   9 September.—I was pretty tired and worn out when I got to Hillingham.
U||   For two nights I had hardly had a wink of sleep, and my brain was
U||   beginning to feel that numbness which marks cerebral exhaustion. Lucy
U||   was up and in cheerful spirits. When she shook hands with me she looked
U||   sharply in my face and said:—
U||   “No sitting up to-night for you. You are worn out. I am quite well
U||   again; indeed, I am; and if there is to be any sitting up, it is I who
U||   will sit up with you.” I would not argue the point, but went and had my
U||   supper. Lucy came with me, and, enlivened by her charming presence, I
U||   made an excellent meal, and had a couple of glasses of the more than
U||   excellent port. Then Lucy took me upstairs, and showed me a room next
U||   her own, where a cozy fire was burning. “Now,” she said, “you must stay
U||   here. I shall leave this door open and my door too. You can lie on the
U||   sofa for I know that nothing would induce any of you doctors to go to
U||   bed whilst there is a patient above the horizon. If I want anything I
U||   shall call out, and you can come to me at once.” I could not but
U||   acquiesce, for I was “dog-tired,” and could not have sat up had I
U||   tried. So, on her renewing her promise to call me if she should want
U||   anything, I lay on the sofa, and forgot all about everything.
U||   Lucy Westenra’s Diary.
U||   9 September.—I feel so happy to-night. I have been so miserably weak,
U||   that to be able to think and move about is like feeling sunshine after
U||   a long spell of east wind out of a steel sky. Somehow Arthur feels
U||   very, very close to me. I seem to feel his presence warm about me. I
U||   suppose it is that sickness and weakness are selfish things and turn
U||   our inner eyes and sympathy on ourselves, whilst health and strength
U||   give Love rein, and in thought and feeling he can wander where he
U||   wills. I know where my thoughts are. If Arthur only knew! My dear, my
U||   dear, your ears must tingle as you sleep, as mine do waking. Oh, the
U||   blissful rest of last night! How I slept, with that dear, good Dr.
U||   Seward watching me. And to-night I shall not fear to sleep, since he is
U||   close at hand and within call. Thank everybody for being so good to me!
U||   Thank God! Good-night, Arthur.
U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   10 September.—I was conscious of the Professor’s hand on my head, and
U||   started awake all in a second. That is one of the things that we learn
U||   in an asylum, at any rate.
U||   “And how is our patient?”
U||   “Well, when I left her, or rather when she left me,” I answered.
U||   “Come, let us see,” he said. And together we went into the room.
U||   The blind was down, and I went over to raise it gently, whilst Van
U||   Helsing stepped, with his soft, cat-like tread, over to the bed.
U||   As I raised the blind, and the morning sunlight flooded the room, I
U||   heard the Professor’s low hiss of inspiration, and knowing its rarity,
U||   a deadly fear shot through my heart. As I passed over he moved back,
U||   and his exclamation of horror, “Gott in Himmel!” needed no enforcement
U||   from his agonised face. He raised his hand and pointed to the bed, and
U||   his iron face was drawn and ashen white. I felt my knees begin to
U||   tremble.
U||   There on the bed, seemingly in a swoon, lay poor Lucy, more horribly
U||   white and wan-looking than ever. Even the lips were white, and the gums
U||   seemed to have shrunken back from the teeth, as we sometimes see in a
U||   corpse after a prolonged illness. Van Helsing raised his foot to stamp
U||   in anger, but the instinct of his life and all the long years of habit
U||   stood to him, and he put it down again softly. “Quick!” he said. “Bring
U||   the brandy.” I flew to the dining-room, and returned with the decanter.
U||   He wetted the poor white lips with it, and together we rubbed palm and
U||   wrist and heart. He felt her heart, and after a few moments of
U||   agonising suspense said:—
U||   “It is not too late. It beats, though but feebly. All our work is
U||   undone; we must begin again. There is no young Arthur here now; I have
U||   to call on you yourself this time, friend John.” As he spoke, he was
U||   dipping into his bag and producing the instruments for transfusion; I
U||   had taken off my coat and rolled up my shirt-sleeve. There was no
U||   possibility of an opiate just at present, and no need of one; and so,
U||   without a moment’s delay, we began the operation. After a time—it did
U||   not seem a short time either, for the draining away of one’s blood, no
U||   matter how willingly it be given, is a terrible feeling—Van Helsing
U||   held up a warning finger. “Do not stir,” he said, “but I fear that with
U||   growing strength she may wake; and that would make danger, oh, so much
U||   danger. But I shall precaution take. I shall give hypodermic injection
U||   of morphia.” He proceeded then, swiftly and deftly, to carry out his
U||   intent. The effect on Lucy was not bad, for the faint seemed to merge
U||   subtly into the narcotic sleep. It was with a feeling of personal pride
U||   that I could see a faint tinge of colour steal back into the pallid
U||   cheeks and lips. No man knows, till he experiences it, what it is to
U||   feel his own life-blood drawn away into the veins of the woman he
U||   loves.
U||   The Professor watched me critically. “That will do,” he said.
U||   “Already?” I remonstrated. “You took a great deal more from Art.” To
U||   which he smiled a sad sort of smile as he replied:—
U||   “He is her lover, her fiancé. You have work, much work, to do for her
U||   and for others; and the present will suffice.”
U||   When we stopped the operation, he attended to Lucy, whilst I applied
U||   digital pressure to my own incision. I laid down, whilst I waited his
U||   leisure to attend to me, for I felt faint and a little sick. By-and-by
U||   he bound up my wound, and sent me downstairs to get a glass of wine for
U||   myself. As I was leaving the room, he came after me, and half
U||   whispered:—
U||   “Mind, nothing must be said of this. If our young lover should turn up
U||   unexpected, as before, no word to him. It would at once frighten him
U||   and enjealous him, too. There must be none. So!”
U||   When I came back he looked at me carefully, and then said:—
U||   “You are not much the worse. Go into the room, and lie on your sofa,
U||   and rest awhile; then have much breakfast, and come here to me.”
U||   I followed out his orders, for I knew how right and wise they were. I
U||   had done my part, and now my next duty was to keep up my strength. I
U||   felt very weak, and in the weakness lost something of the amazement at
U||   what had occurred. I fell asleep on the sofa, however, wondering over
U||   and over again how Lucy had made such a retrograde movement, and how
U||   she could have been drained of so much blood with no sign anywhere to
U||   show for it. I think I must have continued my wonder in my dreams, for,
U||   sleeping and waking, my thoughts always came back to the little
U||   punctures in her throat and the ragged, exhausted appearance of their
U||   edges—tiny though they were.
U||   Lucy slept well into the day, and when she woke she was fairly well and
U||   strong, though not nearly so much so as the day before. When Van
U||   Helsing had seen her, he went out for a walk, leaving me in charge,
U||   with strict injunctions that I was not to leave her for a moment. I
U||   could hear his voice in the hall, asking the way to the nearest
U||   telegraph office.
U||   Lucy chatted with me freely, and seemed quite unconscious that anything
U||   had happened. I tried to keep her amused and interested. When her
U||   mother came up to see her, she did not seem to notice any change
U||   whatever, but said to me gratefully:—
U||   “We owe you so much, Dr. Seward, for all you have done, but you really
U||   must now take care not to overwork yourself. You are looking pale
U||   yourself. You want a wife to nurse and look after you a bit; that you
U||   do!” As she spoke, Lucy turned crimson, though it was only momentarily,
U||   for her poor wasted veins could not stand for long such an unwonted
U||   drain to the head. The reaction came in excessive pallor as she turned
U||   imploring eyes on me. I smiled and nodded, and laid my finger on my
U||   lips; with a sigh, she sank back amid her pillows.
U||   Van Helsing returned in a couple of hours, and presently said to me:
U||   “Now you go home, and eat much and drink enough. Make yourself strong.
U||   I stay here to-night, and I shall sit up with little miss myself. You
U||   and I must watch the case, and we must have none other to know. I have
U||   grave reasons. No, do not ask them; think what you will. Do not fear to
U||   think even the most not-probable. Good-night.”
U||   In the hall two of the maids came to me, and asked if they or either of
U||   them might not sit up with Miss Lucy. They implored me to let them; and
U||   when I said it was Dr. Van Helsing’s wish that either he or I should
U||   sit up, they asked me quite piteously to intercede with the “foreign
U||   gentleman.” I was much touched by their kindness. Perhaps it is because
U||   I am weak at present, and perhaps because it was on Lucy’s account,
U||   that their devotion was manifested; for over and over again have I seen
U||   similar instances of woman’s kindness. I got back here in time for a
U||   late dinner; went my rounds—all well; and set this down whilst waiting
U||   for sleep. It is coming.
U||   11 September.—This afternoon I went over to Hillingham. Found Van
U||   Helsing in excellent spirits, and Lucy much better. Shortly after I had
U||   arrived, a big parcel from abroad came for the Professor. He opened it
U||   with much impressment—assumed, of course—and showed a great bundle of
U||   white flowers.
U||   “These are for you, Miss Lucy,” he said.
U||   “For me? Oh, Dr. Van Helsing!”
U||   “Yes, my dear, but not for you to play with. These are medicines.” Here
U||   Lucy made a wry face. “Nay, but they are not to take in a decoction or
U||   in nauseous form, so you need not snub that so charming nose, or I
U||   shall point out to my friend Arthur what woes he may have to endure in
U||   seeing so much beauty that he so loves so much distort. Aha, my pretty
U||   miss, that bring the so nice nose all straight again. This is
U||   medicinal, but you do not know how. I put him in your window, I make
U||   pretty wreath, and hang him round your neck, so that you sleep well. Oh
U||   yes! they, like the lotus flower, make your trouble forgotten. It smell
U||   so like the waters of Lethe, and of that fountain of youth that the
U||   Conquistadores sought for in the Floridas, and find him all too late.”
U||   Whilst he was speaking, Lucy had been examining the flowers and
U||   smelling them. Now she threw them down, saying, with half-laughter, and
U||   half-disgust:—
U||   “Oh, Professor, I believe you are only putting up a joke on me. Why,
U||   these flowers are only common garlic.”
U||   To my surprise, Van Helsing rose up and said with all his sternness,
U||   his iron jaw set and his bushy eyebrows meeting:—
U||   “No trifling with me! I never jest! There is grim purpose in all I do;
U||   and I warn you that you do not thwart me. Take care, for the sake of
U||   others if not for your own.” Then seeing poor Lucy scared, as she might
U||   well be, he went on more gently: “Oh, little miss, my dear, do not fear
U||   me. I only do for your good; but there is much virtue to you in those
U||   so common flowers. See, I place them myself in your room. I make myself
U||   the wreath that you are to wear. But hush! no telling to others that
U||   make so inquisitive questions. We must obey, and silence is a part of
U||   obedience; and obedience is to bring you strong and well into loving
U||   arms that wait for you. Now sit still awhile. Come with me, friend
U||   John, and you shall help me deck the room with my garlic, which is all
