U||CHAPTER XI
U||   Lucy Westenra’s Diary.
U||   12 September.—How good they all are to me. I quite love that dear Dr.
U||   Van Helsing. I wonder why he was so anxious about these flowers. He
U||   positively frightened me, he was so fierce. And yet he must have been
U||   right, for I feel comfort from them already. Somehow, I do not dread
U||   being alone to-night, and I can go to sleep without fear. I shall not
U||   mind any flapping outside the window. Oh, the terrible struggle that I
U||   have had against sleep so often of late; the pain of the sleeplessness,
U||   or the pain of the fear of sleep, with such unknown horrors as it has
U||   for me! How blessed are some people, whose lives have no fears, no
U||   dreads; to whom sleep is a blessing that comes nightly, and brings
U||   nothing but sweet dreams. Well, here I am to-night, hoping for sleep,
U||   and lying like Ophelia in the play, with “virgin crants and maiden
U||   strewments.” I never liked garlic before, but to-night it is
U||   delightful! There is peace in its smell; I feel sleep coming already.
U||   Good-night, everybody.
U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   13 September.—Called at the Berkeley and found Van Helsing, as usual,
U||   up to time. The carriage ordered from the hotel was waiting. The
U||   Professor took his bag, which he always brings with him now.
U||   Let all be put down exactly. Van Helsing and I arrived at Hillingham at
U||   eight o’clock. It was a lovely morning; the bright sunshine and all the
U||   fresh feeling of early autumn seemed like the completion of nature’s
U||   annual work. The leaves were turning to all kinds of beautiful colours,
U||   but had not yet begun to drop from the trees. When we entered we met
U||   Mrs. Westenra coming out of the morning room. She is always an early
U||   riser. She greeted us warmly and said:—
U||   “You will be glad to know that Lucy is better. The dear child is still
U||   asleep. I looked into her room and saw her, but did not go in, lest I
U||   should disturb her.” The Professor smiled, and looked quite jubilant.
U||   He rubbed his hands together, and said:—
U||   “Aha! I thought I had diagnosed the case. My treatment is working,” to
U||   which she answered:—
U||   “You must not take all the credit to yourself, doctor. Lucy’s state
U||   this morning is due in part to me.”
U||   “How you do mean, ma’am?” asked the Professor.
U||   “Well, I was anxious about the dear child in the night, and went into
U||   her room. She was sleeping soundly—so soundly that even my coming did
U||   not wake her. But the room was awfully stuffy. There were a lot of
U||   those horrible, strong-smelling flowers about everywhere, and she had
U||   actually a bunch of them round her neck. I feared that the heavy odour
U||   would be too much for the dear child in her weak state, so I took them
U||   all away and opened a bit of the window to let in a little fresh air.
U||   You will be pleased with her, I am sure.”
U||   She moved off into her boudoir, where she usually breakfasted early. As
U||   she had spoken, I watched the Professor’s face, and saw it turn ashen
U||   grey. He had been able to retain his self-command whilst the poor lady
U||   was present, for he knew her state and how mischievous a shock would
U||   be; he actually smiled on her as he held open the door for her to pass
U||   into her room. But the instant she had disappeared he pulled me,
U||   suddenly and forcibly, into the dining-room and closed the door.
U||   Then, for the first time in my life, I saw Van Helsing break down. He
U||   raised his hands over his head in a sort of mute despair, and then beat
U||   his palms together in a helpless way; finally he sat down on a chair,
U||   and putting his hands before his face, began to sob, with loud, dry
U||   sobs that seemed to come from the very racking of his heart. Then he
U||   raised his arms again, as though appealing to the whole universe. “God!
U||   God! God!” he said. “What have we done, what has this poor thing done,
U||   that we are so sore beset? Is there fate amongst us still, sent down
U||   from the pagan world of old, that such things must be, and in such way?
U||   This poor mother, all unknowing, and all for the best as she think,
U||   does such thing as lose her daughter body and soul; and we must not
U||   tell her, we must not even warn her, or she die, and then both die. Oh,
U||   how we are beset! How are all the powers of the devils against us!”
U||   Suddenly he jumped to his feet. “Come,” he said, “come, we must see and
U||   act. Devils or no devils, or all the devils at once, it matters not; we
U||   fight him all the same.” He went to the hall-door for his bag; and
U||   together we went up to Lucy’s room.
U||   Once again I drew up the blind, whilst Van Helsing went towards the
U||   bed. This time he did not start as he looked on the poor face with the
