U||   THE ESCAPED WOLF.
U||   PERILOUS ADVENTURE OF OUR INTERVIEWER.
U||   Interview with the Keeper in the Zoölogical Gardens.
U||   After many inquiries and almost as many refusals, and perpetually using
U||   the words “Pall Mall Gazette” as a sort of talisman, I managed to find
U||   the keeper of the section of the Zoölogical Gardens in which the wolf
U||   department is included. Thomas Bilder lives in one of the cottages in
U||   the enclosure behind the elephant-house, and was just sitting down to
U||   his tea when I found him. Thomas and his wife are hospitable folk,
U||   elderly, and without children, and if the specimen I enjoyed of their
U||   hospitality be of the average kind, their lives must be pretty
U||   comfortable. The keeper would not enter on what he called “business”
U||   until the supper was over, and we were all satisfied. Then when the
U||   table was cleared, and he had lit his pipe, he said:—
U||   “Now, sir, you can go on and arsk me what you want. You’ll excoose me
U||   refoosin’ to talk of perfeshunal subjects afore meals. I gives the
U||   wolves and the jackals and the hyenas in all our section their tea
U||   afore I begins to arsk them questions.”
U||   “How do you mean, ask them questions?” I queried, wishful to get him
U||   into a talkative humour.
U||   “’Ittin’ of them over the ’ead with a pole is one way; scratchin’ of
U||   their hears is another, when gents as is flush wants a bit of a
U||   show-orf to their gals. I don’t so much mind the fust—the ’ittin’ with
U||   a pole afore I chucks in their dinner; but I waits till they’ve ’ad
U||   their sherry and kawffee, so to speak, afore I tries on with the
U||   ear-scratchin’. Mind you,” he added philosophically, “there’s a deal of
U||   the same nature in us as in them theer animiles. Here’s you a-comin’
U||   and arskin’ of me questions about my business, and I that grumpy-like
U||   that only for your bloomin’ ’arf-quid I’d ’a’ seen you blowed fust
U||   ’fore I’d answer. Not even when you arsked me sarcastic-like if I’d
U||   like you to arsk the Superintendent if you might arsk me questions.
U||   Without offence did I tell yer to go to ’ell?”
U||   “You did.”
U||   “An’ when you said you’d report me for usin’ of obscene language that
U||   was ’ittin’ me over the ’ead; but the ’arf-quid made that all right. I
U||   weren’t a-goin’ to fight, so I waited for the food, and did with my
U||   ’owl as the wolves, and lions, and tigers does. But, Lor’ love yer
U||   ’art, now that the old ’ooman has stuck a chunk of her tea-cake in me,
U||   an’ rinsed me out with her bloomin’ old teapot, and I’ve lit hup, you
U||   may scratch my ears for all you’re worth, and won’t git even a growl
U||   out of me. Drive along with your questions. I know what yer a-comin’
U||   at, that ’ere escaped wolf.”
