U||   can; but I don’t know as ’ow you’d be satisfied with the theory.”
U||   “Certainly I shall. If a man like you, who knows the animals from
U||   experience, can’t hazard a good guess at any rate, who is even to try?”
U||   “Well then, sir, I accounts for it this way; it seems to me that ’ere
U||   wolf escaped—simply because he wanted to get out.”
U||   From the hearty way that both Thomas and his wife laughed at the joke I
U||   could see that it had done service before, and that the whole
U||   explanation was simply an elaborate sell. I couldn’t cope in badinage
U||   with the worthy Thomas, but I thought I knew a surer way to his heart,
U||   so I said:—
U||   “Now, Mr. Bilder, we’ll consider that first half-sovereign worked off,
U||   and this brother of his is waiting to be claimed when you’ve told me
U||   what you think will happen.”
U||   “Right y’are, sir,” he said briskly. “Ye’ll excoose me, I know, for
U||   a-chaffin’ of ye, but the old woman here winked at me, which was as
U||   much as telling me to go on.”
U||   “Well, I never!” said the old lady.
U||   “My opinion is this: that ’ere wolf is a-’idin’ of, somewheres. The
U||   gard’ner wot didn’t remember said he was a-gallopin’ northward faster
U||   than a horse could go; but I don’t believe him, for, yer see, sir,
U||   wolves don’t gallop no more nor dogs does, they not bein’ built that
U||   way. Wolves is fine things in a storybook, and I dessay when they gets
U||   in packs and does be chivyin’ somethin’ that’s more afeared than they
U||   is they can make a devil of a noise and chop it up, whatever it is.
U||   But, Lor’ bless you, in real life a wolf is only a low creature, not
U||   half so clever or bold as a good dog; and not half a quarter so much
U||   fight in ’im. This one ain’t been used to fightin’ or even to providin’
U||   for hisself, and more like he’s somewhere round the Park a-’idin’ an’
U||   a-shiverin’ of, and, if he thinks at all, wonderin’ where he is to get
U||   his breakfast from; or maybe he’s got down some area and is in a
U||   coal-cellar. My eye, won’t some cook get a rum start when she sees his
