U||   bound to look for it, and mayhap he may chance to light on a butcher’s
U||   shop in time. If he doesn’t, and some nursemaid goes a-walkin’ orf with
U||   a soldier, leavin’ of the hinfant in the perambulator—well, then I
U||   shouldn’t be surprised if the census is one babby the less. That’s
U||   all.”
U||   I was handing him the half-sovereign, when something came bobbing up
U||   against the window, and Mr. Bilder’s face doubled its natural length
U||   with surprise.
U||   “God bless me!” he said. “If there ain’t old Bersicker come back by
U||   ’isself!”
U||   He went to the door and opened it; a most unnecessary proceeding it
U||   seemed to me. I have always thought that a wild animal never looks so
U||   well as when some obstacle of pronounced durability is between us; a
U||   personal experience has intensified rather than diminished that idea.
U||   After all, however, there is nothing like custom, for neither Bilder
U||   nor his wife thought any more of the wolf than I should of a dog. The
U||   animal itself was as peaceful and well-behaved as that father of all
U||   picture-wolves—Red Riding Hood’s quondam friend, whilst moving her
U||   confidence in masquerade.
U||   The whole scene was an unutterable mixture of comedy and pathos. The
U||   wicked wolf that for half a day had paralysed London and set all the
U||   children in the town shivering in their shoes, was there in a sort of
U||   penitent mood, and was received and petted like a sort of vulpine
U||   prodigal son. Old Bilder examined him all over with most tender
U||   solicitude, and when he had finished with his penitent said:—
U||   “There, I knew the poor old chap would get into some kind of trouble;
U||   didn’t I say it all along? Here’s his head all cut and full of broken
U||   glass. ’E’s been a-gettin’ over some bloomin’ wall or other. It’s a
U||   shyme that people are allowed to top their walls with broken bottles.
U||   This ’ere’s what comes of it. Come along, Bersicker.”
U||   He took the wolf and locked him up in a cage, with a piece of meat that
U||   satisfied, in quantity at any rate, the elementary conditions of the
U||   fatted calf, and went off to report.
U||   I came off, too, to report the only exclusive information that is given
U||   to-day regarding the strange escapade at the Zoo.
U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   17 September.—I was engaged after dinner in my study posting up my
U||   books, which, through press of other work and the many visits to Lucy,
U||   had fallen sadly into arrear. Suddenly the door was burst open, and in
U||   rushed my patient, with his face distorted with passion. I was
U||   thunderstruck, for such a thing as a patient getting of his own accord
U||   into the Superintendent’s study is almost unknown. Without an instant’s
U||   pause he made straight at me. He had a dinner-knife in his hand, and,
U||   as I saw he was dangerous, I tried to keep the table between us. He was
U||   too quick and too strong for me, however; for before I could get my
U||   balance he had struck at me and cut my left wrist rather severely.
U||   Before he could strike again, however, I got in my right and he was
U||   sprawling on his back on the floor. My wrist bled freely, and quite a
U||   little pool trickled on to the carpet. I saw that my friend was not
U||   intent on further effort, and occupied myself binding up my wrist,
U||   keeping a wary eye on the prostrate figure all the time. When the
U||   attendants rushed in, and we turned our attention to him, his
U||   employment positively sickened me. He was lying on his belly on the
U||   floor licking up, like a dog, the blood which had fallen from my
U||   wounded wrist. He was easily secured, and, to my surprise, went with
U||   the attendants quite placidly, simply repeating over and over again:
U||   “The blood is the life! The blood is the life!”
U||   I cannot afford to lose blood just at present; I have lost too much of
U||   late for my physical good, and then the prolonged strain of Lucy’s
U||   illness and its horrible phases is telling on me. I am over-excited and
U||   weary, and I need rest, rest, rest. Happily Van Helsing has not
U||   summoned me, so I need not forego my sleep; to-night I could not well
U||   do without it.
U||   Telegram, Van Helsing, Antwerp, to Seward, Carfax.
U||   (Sent to Carfax, Sussex, as no county given; delivered late by
U||   twenty-two hours.)
U||   “17 September.—Do not fail to be at Hillingham to-night. If not
U||   watching all the time frequently, visit and see that flowers are as
