U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   18 September.—Just off for train to London. The arrival of Van
U||   Helsing’s telegram filled me with dismay. A whole night lost, and I
U||   know by bitter experience what may happen in a night. Of course it is
U||   possible that all may be well, but what may have happened? Surely there
U||   is some horrible doom hanging over us that every possible accident
U||   should thwart us in all we try to do. I shall take this cylinder with
U||   me, and then I can complete my entry on Lucy’s phonograph.
U||   Memorandum left by Lucy Westenra.
U||   17 September. Night.—I write this and leave it to be seen, so that no
U||   one may by any chance get into trouble through me. This is an exact
U||   record of what took place to-night. I feel I am dying of weakness, and
U||   have barely strength to write, but it must be done if I die in the
U||   doing.
U||   I went to bed as usual, taking care that the flowers were placed as Dr.
U||   Van Helsing directed, and soon fell asleep.
U||   I was waked by the flapping at the window, which had begun after that
U||   sleep-walking on the cliff at Whitby when Mina saved me, and which now
U||   I know so well. I was not afraid, but I did wish that Dr. Seward was in
U||   the next room—as Dr. Van Helsing said he would be—so that I might have
U||   called him. I tried to go to sleep, but could not. Then there came to
U||   me the old fear of sleep, and I determined to keep awake. Perversely
U||   sleep would try to come then when I did not want it; so, as I feared to
U||   be alone, I opened my door and called out: “Is there anybody there?”
U||   There was no answer. I was afraid to wake mother, and so closed my door
U||   again. Then outside in the shrubbery I heard a sort of howl like a
U||   dog’s, but more fierce and deeper. I went to the window and looked out,
U||   but could see nothing, except a big bat, which had evidently been
U||   buffeting its wings against the window. So I went back to bed again,
U||   but determined not to go to sleep. Presently the door opened, and
U||   mother looked in; seeing by my moving that I was not asleep, came in,
U||   and sat by me. She said to me even more sweetly and softly than her
U||   wont:—
U||   “I was uneasy about you, darling, and came in to see that you were all
U||   right.”
U||   I feared she might catch cold sitting there, and asked her to come in
U||   and sleep with me, so she came into bed, and lay down beside me; she
U||   did not take off her dressing gown, for she said she would only stay a
U||   while and then go back to her own bed. As she lay there in my arms, and
U||   I in hers, the flapping and buffeting came to the window again. She was
U||   startled and a little frightened, and cried out: “What is that?” I
U||   tried to pacify her, and at last succeeded, and she lay quiet; but I
U||   could hear her poor dear heart still beating terribly. After a while
U||   there was the low howl again out in the shrubbery, and shortly after
U||   there was a crash at the window, and a lot of broken glass was hurled
U||   on the floor. The window blind blew back with the wind that rushed in,
U||   and in the aperture of the broken panes there was the head of a great,
U||   gaunt grey wolf. Mother cried out in a fright, and struggled up into a
U||   sitting posture, and clutched wildly at anything that would help her.
U||   Amongst other things, she clutched the wreath of flowers that Dr. Van
U||   Helsing insisted on my wearing round my neck, and tore it away from me.
U||   For a second or two she sat up, pointing at the wolf, and there was a
U||   strange and horrible gurgling in her throat; then she fell over—as if
U||   struck with lightning, and her head hit my forehead and made me dizzy
U||   for a moment or two. The room and all round seemed to spin round. I
U||   kept my eyes fixed on the window, but the wolf drew his head back, and
U||   a whole myriad of little specks seemed to come blowing in through the
U||   broken window, and wheeling and circling round like the pillar of dust
U||   that travellers describe when there is a simoon in the desert. I tried
U||   to stir, but there was some spell upon me, and dear mother’s poor body,
U||   which seemed to grow cold already—for her dear heart had ceased to
U||   beat—weighed me down; and I remembered no more for a while.
U||   The time did not seem long, but very, very awful, till I recovered
U||   consciousness again. Somewhere near, a passing bell was tolling; the
U||   dogs all round the neighbourhood were howling; and in our shrubbery,
U||   seemingly just outside, a nightingale was singing. I was dazed and
U||   stupid with pain and terror and weakness, but the sound of the
U||   nightingale seemed like the voice of my dead mother come back to
U||   comfort me. The sounds seemed to have awakened the maids, too, for I
U||   could hear their bare feet pattering outside my door. I called to them,
U||   and they came in, and when they saw what had happened, and what it was
U||   that lay over me on the bed, they screamed out. The wind rushed in
U||   through the broken window, and the door slammed to. They lifted off the
U||   body of my dear mother, and laid her, covered up with a sheet, on the
U||   bed after I had got up. They were all so frightened and nervous that I
U||   directed them to go to the dining-room and have each a glass of wine.
U||   The door flew open for an instant and closed again. The maids shrieked,
U||   and then went in a body to the dining-room; and I laid what flowers I
U||   had on my dear mother’s breast. When they were there I remembered what
U||   Dr. Van Helsing had told me, but I didn’t like to remove them, and,
U||   besides, I would have some of the servants to sit up with me now. I was
U||   surprised that the maids did not come back. I called them, but got no
U||   answer, so I went to the dining-room to look for them.
U||   My heart sank when I saw what had happened. They all four lay helpless
U||   on the floor, breathing heavily. The decanter of sherry was on the
U||   table half full, but there was a queer, acrid smell about. I was
U||   suspicious, and examined the decanter. It smelt of laudanum, and
U||   looking on the sideboard, I found that the bottle which mother’s doctor
U||   uses for her—oh! did use—was empty. What am I to do? what am I to do? I
U||   am back in the room with mother. I cannot leave her, and I am alone,
U||   save for the sleeping servants, whom some one has drugged. Alone with
U||   the dead! I dare not go out, for I can hear the low howl of the wolf
U||   through the broken window.
U||   The air seems full of specks, floating and circling in the draught from
U||   the window, and the lights burn blue and dim. What am I to do? God
U||   shield me from harm this night! I shall hide this paper in my breast,
U||   where they shall find it when they come to lay me out. My dear mother
U||   gone! It is time that I go too. Good-bye, dear Arthur, if I should not
U||   survive this night. God keep you, dear, and God help me!
U||CHAPTER XII
U||DR. SEWARD’S DIARY
U||   18 September.—I drove at once to Hillingham and arrived early. Keeping
U||   my cab at the gate, I went up the avenue alone. I knocked gently and
U||   rang as quietly as possible, for I feared to disturb Lucy or her
U||   mother, and hoped to only bring a servant to the door. After a while,
U||   finding no response, I knocked and rang again; still no answer. I
U||   cursed the laziness of the servants that they should lie abed at such
U||   an hour—for it was now ten o’clock—and so rang and knocked again, but
U||   more impatiently, but still without response. Hitherto I had blamed
U||   only the servants, but now a terrible fear began to assail me. Was this
U||   desolation but another link in the chain of doom which seemed drawing
U||   tight around us? Was it indeed a house of death to which I had come,
U||   too late? I knew that minutes, even seconds of delay, might mean hours
U||   of danger to Lucy, if she had had again one of those frightful
U||   relapses; and I went round the house to try if I could find by chance
U||   an entry anywhere.
U||   I could find no means of ingress. Every window and door was fastened
U||   and locked, and I returned baffled to the porch. As I did so, I heard
U||   the rapid pit-pat of a swiftly driven horse’s feet. They stopped at the
U||   gate, and a few seconds later I met Van Helsing running up the avenue.
U||   When he saw me, he gasped out:—
U||   “Then it was you, and just arrived. How is she? Are we too late? Did
U||   you not get my telegram?”
U||   I answered as quickly and coherently as I could that I had only got his
U||   telegram early in the morning, and had not lost a minute in coming
U||   here, and that I could not make any one in the house hear me. He paused
U||   and raised his hat as he said solemnly:—
U||   “Then I fear we are too late. God’s will be done!” With his usual
U||   recuperative energy, he went on: “Come. If there be no way open to get
U||   in, we must make one. Time is all in all to us now.”
U||   We went round to the back of the house, where there was a kitchen
U||   window. The Professor took a small surgical saw from his case, and
U||   handing it to me, pointed to the iron bars which guarded the window. I
U||   attacked them at once and had very soon cut through three of them. Then
U||   with a long, thin knife we pushed back the fastening of the sashes and
U||   opened the window. I helped the Professor in, and followed him. There
U||   was no one in the kitchen or in the servants’ rooms, which were close
U||   at hand. We tried all the rooms as we went along, and in the
U||   dining-room, dimly lit by rays of light through the shutters, found
U||   four servant-women lying on the floor. There was no need to think them
U||   dead, for their stertorous breathing and the acrid smell of laudanum in
U||   the room left no doubt as to their condition. Van Helsing and I looked
U||   at each other, and as we moved away he said: “We can attend to them
U||   later.” Then we ascended to Lucy’s room. For an instant or two we
U||   paused at the door to listen, but there was no sound that we could
U||   hear. With white faces and trembling hands, we opened the door gently,
U||   and entered the room.
U||   How shall I describe what we saw? On the bed lay two women, Lucy and
U||   her mother. The latter lay farthest in, and she was covered with a
U||   white sheet, the edge of which had been blown back by the draught
U||   through the broken window, showing the drawn, white face, with a look
U||   of terror fixed upon it. By her side lay Lucy, with face white and
U||   still more drawn. The flowers which had been round her neck we found
U||   upon her mother’s bosom, and her throat was bare, showing the two
U||   little wounds which we had noticed before, but looking horribly white
U||   and mangled. Without a word the Professor bent over the bed, his head
U||   almost touching poor Lucy’s breast; then he gave a quick turn of his
U||   head, as of one who listens, and leaping to his feet, he cried out to
U||   me:—
U||   “It is not yet too late! Quick! quick! Bring the brandy!”
U||   I flew downstairs and returned with it, taking care to smell and taste
U||   it, lest it, too, were drugged like the decanter of sherry which I
U||   found on the table. The maids were still breathing, but more
U||   restlessly, and I fancied that the narcotic was wearing off. I did not
U||   stay to make sure, but returned to Van Helsing. He rubbed the brandy,
U||   as on another occasion, on her lips and gums and on her wrists and the
U||   palms of her hands. He said to me:—
U||   “I can do this, all that can be at the present. You go wake those
U||   maids. Flick them in the face with a wet towel, and flick them hard.
U||   Make them get heat and fire and a warm bath. This poor soul is nearly
U||   as cold as that beside her. She will need be heated before we can do
U||   anything more.”
U||   I went at once, and found little difficulty in waking three of the
U||   women. The fourth was only a young girl, and the drug had evidently
U||   affected her more strongly, so I lifted her on the sofa and let her
U||   sleep. The others were dazed at first, but as remembrance came back to
U||   them they cried and sobbed in a hysterical manner. I was stern with
U||   them, however, and would not let them talk. I told them that one life
U||   was bad enough to lose, and that if they delayed they would sacrifice
U||   Miss Lucy. So, sobbing and crying, they went about their way, half clad
U||   as they were, and prepared fire and water. Fortunately, the kitchen and
U||   boiler fires were still alive, and there was no lack of hot water. We
U||   got a bath and carried Lucy out as she was and placed her in it. Whilst
U||   we were busy chafing her limbs there was a knock at the hall door. One
U||   of the maids ran off, hurried on some more clothes, and opened it. Then
U||   she returned and whispered to us that there was a gentleman who had
U||   come with a message from Mr. Holmwood. I bade her simply tell him that
U||   he must wait, for we could see no one now. She went away with the
U||   message, and, engrossed with our work, I clean forgot all about him.
U||   I never saw in all my experience the Professor work in such deadly
U||   earnest. I knew—as he knew—that it was a stand-up fight with death, and
U||   in a pause told him so. He answered me in a way that I did not
U||   understand, but with the sternest look that his face could wear:—
U||   “If that were all, I would stop here where we are now, and let her fade
U||   away into peace, for I see no light in life over her horizon.” He went
U||   on with his work with, if possible, renewed and more frenzied vigour.
U||   Presently we both began to be conscious that the heat was beginning to
U||   be of some effect. Lucy’s heart beat a trifle more audibly to the
U||   stethoscope, and her lungs had a perceptible movement. Van Helsing’s
U||   face almost beamed, and as we lifted her from the bath and rolled her
U||   in a hot sheet to dry her he said to me:—
U||   “The first gain is ours! Check to the King!”
U||   We took Lucy into another room, which had by now been prepared, and
U||   laid her in bed and forced a few drops of brandy down her throat. I
U||   noticed that Van Helsing tied a soft silk handkerchief round her
U||   throat. She was still unconscious, and was quite as bad as, if not
U||   worse than, we had ever seen her.
U||   Van Helsing called in one of the women, and told her to stay with her
U||   and not to take her eyes off her till we returned, and then beckoned me
U||   out of the room.
U||   “We must consult as to what is to be done,” he said as we descended the
U||   stairs. In the hall he opened the dining-room door, and we passed in,
U||   he closing the door carefully behind him. The shutters had been opened,
U||   but the blinds were already down, with that obedience to the etiquette
U||   of death which the British woman of the lower classes always rigidly
U||   observes. The room was, therefore, dimly dark. It was, however, light
U||   enough for our purposes. Van Helsing’s sternness was somewhat relieved
U||   by a look of perplexity. He was evidently torturing his mind about
U||   something, so I waited for an instant, and he spoke:—
U||   “What are we to do now? Where are we to turn for help? We must have
U||   another transfusion of blood, and that soon, or that poor girl’s life
U||   won’t be worth an hour’s purchase. You are exhausted already; I am
U||   exhausted too. I fear to trust those women, even if they would have
U||   courage to submit. What are we to do for some one who will open his
U||   veins for her?”
U||   “What’s the matter with me, anyhow?”
U||   The voice came from the sofa across the room, and its tones brought
U||   relief and joy to my heart, for they were those of Quincey Morris. Van
U||   Helsing started angrily at the first sound, but his face softened and a
U||   glad look came into his eyes as I cried out: “Quincey Morris!” and
U||   rushed towards him with outstretched hands.
U||   “What brought you here?” I cried as our hands met.
U||   “I guess Art is the cause.”
U||   He handed me a telegram:—
U||   “Have not heard from Seward for three days, and am terribly anxious.
U||   Cannot leave. Father still in same condition. Send me word how Lucy is.
U||   Do not delay.—Holmwood.”
U||   “I think I came just in the nick of time. You know you have only to
U||   tell me what to do.”
U||   Van Helsing strode forward, and took his hand, looking him straight in
U||   the eyes as he said:—
U||   “A brave man’s blood is the best thing on this earth when a woman is in
U||   trouble. You’re a man and no mistake. Well, the devil may work against
U||   us for all he’s worth, but God sends us men when we want them.”
U||   Once again we went through that ghastly operation. I have not the heart
U||   to go through with the details. Lucy had got a terrible shock and it
U||   told on her more than before, for though plenty of blood went into her
U||   veins, her body did not respond to the treatment as well as on the
U||   other occasions. Her struggle back into life was something frightful to
U||   see and hear. However, the action of both heart and lungs improved, and
U||   Van Helsing made a subcutaneous injection of morphia, as before, and
U||   with good effect. Her faint became a profound slumber. The Professor
U||   watched whilst I went downstairs with Quincey Morris, and sent one of
U||   the maids to pay off one of the cabmen who were waiting. I left Quincey
U||   lying down after having a glass of wine, and told the cook to get ready
U||   a good breakfast. Then a thought struck me, and I went back to the room
U||   where Lucy now was. When I came softly in, I found Van Helsing with a
U||   sheet or two of note-paper in his hand. He had evidently read it, and
U||   was thinking it over as he sat with his hand to his brow. There was a
U||   look of grim satisfaction in his face, as of one who has had a doubt
U||   solved. He handed me the paper saying only: “It dropped from Lucy’s
U||   breast when we carried her to the bath.”
U||   When I had read it, I stood looking at the Professor, and after a pause
U||   asked him: “In God’s name, what does it all mean? Was she, or is she,
U||   mad; or what sort of horrible danger is it?” I was so bewildered that I
U||   did not know what to say more. Van Helsing put out his hand and took
U||   the paper, saying:—
U||   “Do not trouble about it now. Forget it for the present. You shall know
U||   and understand it all in good time; but it will be later. And now what
U||   is it that you came to me to say?” This brought me back to fact, and I
U||   was all myself again.
U||   “I came to speak about the certificate of death. If we do not act
U||   properly and wisely, there may be an inquest, and that paper would have
U||   to be produced. I am in hopes that we need have no inquest, for if we
U||   had it would surely kill poor Lucy, if nothing else did. I know, and
U||   you know, and the other doctor who attended her knows, that Mrs.
U||   Westenra had disease of the heart, and we can certify that she died of
U||   it. Let us fill up the certificate at once, and I shall take it myself
U||   to the registrar and go on to the undertaker.”
U||   “Good, oh my friend John! Well thought of! Truly Miss Lucy, if she be
U||   sad in the foes that beset her, is at least happy in the friends that
U||   love her. One, two, three, all open their veins for her, besides one
U||   old man. Ah yes, I know, friend John; I am not blind! I love you all
U||   the more for it! Now go.”
U||   In the hall I met Quincey Morris, with a telegram for Arthur telling
U||   him that Mrs. Westenra was dead; that Lucy also had been ill, but was
U||   now going on better; and that Van Helsing and I were with her. I told
U||   him where I was going, and he hurried me out, but as I was going said:—
U||   “When you come back, Jack, may I have two words with you all to
U||   ourselves?” I nodded in reply and went out. I found no difficulty about
U||   the registration, and arranged with the local undertaker to come up in
U||   the evening to measure for the coffin and to make arrangements.
U||   When I got back Quincey was waiting for me. I told him I would see him
U||   as soon as I knew about Lucy, and went up to her room. She was still
U||   sleeping, and the Professor seemingly had not moved from his seat at
U||   her side. From his putting his finger to his lips, I gathered that he
U||   expected her to wake before long and was afraid of forestalling nature.
U||   So I went down to Quincey and took him into the breakfast-room, where
U||   the blinds were not drawn down, and which was a little more cheerful,
U||   or rather less cheerless, than the other rooms. When we were alone, he
U||   said to me:—
U||   “Jack Seward, I don’t want to shove myself in anywhere where I’ve no
U||   right to be; but this is no ordinary case. You know I loved that girl
U||   and wanted to marry her; but, although that’s all past and gone, I
U||   can’t help feeling anxious about her all the same. What is it that’s
U||   wrong with her? The Dutchman—and a fine old fellow he is; I can see
U||   that—said, that time you two came into the room, that you must have
U||   another transfusion of blood, and that both you and he were exhausted.
U||   Now I know well that you medical men speak in camera, and that a man
U||   must not expect to know what they consult about in private. But this is
U||   no common matter, and, whatever it is, I have done my part. Is not that
U||   so?”
U||   “That’s so,” I said, and he went on:—
U||   “I take it that both you and Van Helsing had done already what I did
U||   to-day. Is not that so?”
U||   “That’s so.”
U||   “And I guess Art was in it too. When I saw him four days ago down at
U||   his own place he looked queer. I have not seen anything pulled down so
U||   quick since I was on the Pampas and had a mare that I was fond of go to
U||   grass all in a night. One of those big bats that they call vampires had
U||   got at her in the night, and what with his gorge and the vein left
U||   open, there wasn’t enough blood in her to let her stand up, and I had
U||   to put a bullet through her as she lay. Jack, if you may tell me
U||   without betraying confidence, Arthur was the first, is not that so?” As
U||   he spoke the poor fellow looked terribly anxious. He was in a torture
U||   of suspense regarding the woman he loved, and his utter ignorance of
U||   the terrible mystery which seemed to surround her intensified his pain.
U||   His very heart was bleeding, and it took all the manhood of him—and
U||   there was a royal lot of it, too—to keep him from breaking down. I
U||   paused before answering, for I felt that I must not betray anything
U||   which the Professor wished kept secret; but already he knew so much,
U||   and guessed so much, that there could be no reason for not answering,
U||   so I answered in the same phrase: “That’s so.”
U||   “And how long has this been going on?”
U||   “About ten days.”
U||   “Ten days! Then I guess, Jack Seward, that that poor pretty creature
U||   that we all love has had put into her veins within that time the blood
U||   of four strong men. Man alive, her whole body wouldn’t hold it.” Then,
U||   coming close to me, he spoke in a fierce half-whisper: “What took it
U||   out?”
U||   I shook my head. “That,” I said, “is the crux. Van Helsing is simply
U||   frantic about it, and I am at my wits’ end. I can’t even hazard a
U||   guess. There has been a series of little circumstances which have
U||   thrown out all our calculations as to Lucy being properly watched. But
U||   these shall not occur again. Here we stay until all be well—or ill.”
U||   Quincey held out his hand. “Count me in,” he said. “You and the
U||   Dutchman will tell me what to do, and I’ll do it.”
U||   When she woke late in the afternoon, Lucy’s first movement was to feel
U||   in her breast, and, to my surprise, produced the paper which Van
U||   Helsing had given me to read. The careful Professor had replaced it
U||   where it had come from, lest on waking she should be alarmed. Her eye
U||   then lit on Van Helsing and on me too, and gladdened. Then she looked
U||   around the room, and seeing where she was, shuddered; she gave a loud
U||   cry, and put her poor thin hands before her pale face. We both
U||   understood what that meant—that she had realised to the full her
U||   mother’s death; so we tried what we could to comfort her. Doubtless
U||   sympathy eased her somewhat, but she was very low in thought and
U||   spirit, and wept silently and weakly for a long time. We told her that
U||   either or both of us would now remain with her all the time, and that
U||   seemed to comfort her. Towards dusk she fell into a doze. Here a very
U||   odd thing occurred. Whilst still asleep she took the paper from her
U||   breast and tore it in two. Van Helsing stepped over and took the pieces
U||   from her. All the same, however, she went on with the action of
U||   tearing, as though the material were still in her hands; finally she
U||   lifted her hands and opened them as though scattering the fragments.
U||   Van Helsing seemed surprised, and his brows gathered as if in thought,
U||   but he said nothing.
U||   19 September.—All last night she slept fitfully, being always afraid to
U||   sleep, and something weaker when she woke from it. The Professor and I
U||   took it in turns to watch, and we never left her for a moment
U||   unattended. Quincey Morris said nothing about his intention, but I knew
U||   that all night long he patrolled round and round the house.
U||   When the day came, its searching light showed the ravages in poor
U||   Lucy’s strength. She was hardly able to turn her head, and the little
U||   nourishment which she could take seemed to do her no good. At times she
U||   slept, and both Van Helsing and I noticed the difference in her,
U||   between sleeping and waking. Whilst asleep she looked stronger,
U||   although more haggard, and her breathing was softer; her open mouth
U||   showed the pale gums drawn back from the teeth, which thus looked
U||   positively longer and sharper than usual; when she woke the softness of
U||   her eyes evidently changed the expression, for she looked her own self,
U||   although a dying one. In the afternoon she asked for Arthur, and we
U||   telegraphed for him. Quincey went off to meet him at the station.
U||   When he arrived it was nearly six o’clock, and the sun was setting full
U||   and warm, and the red light streamed in through the window and gave
U||   more colour to the pale cheeks. When he saw her, Arthur was simply
U||   choking with emotion, and none of us could speak. In the hours that had
U||   passed, the fits of sleep, or the comatose condition that passed for
U||   it, had grown more frequent, so that the pauses when conversation was
U||   possible were shortened. Arthur’s presence, however, seemed to act as a
U||   stimulant; she rallied a little, and spoke to him more brightly than
U||   she had done since we arrived. He too pulled himself together, and
U||   spoke as cheerily as he could, so that the best was made of everything.
U||   It was now nearly one o’clock, and he and Van Helsing are sitting with
U||   her. I am to relieve them in a quarter of an hour, and I am entering
U||   this on Lucy’s phonograph. Until six o’clock they are to try to rest. I
U||   fear that to-morrow will end our watching, for the shock has been too
U||   great; the poor child cannot rally. God help us all.
