U||   (Unopened by her.)
U||   “17 September.
U||   “My dearest Lucy,—
U||   “It seems an age since I heard from you, or indeed since I wrote. You
U||   will pardon me, I know, for all my faults when you have read all my
U||   budget of news. Well, I got my husband back all right; when we arrived
U||   at Exeter there was a carriage waiting for us, and in it, though he had
U||   an attack of gout, Mr. Hawkins. He took us to his house, where there
U||   were rooms for us all nice and comfortable, and we dined together.
U||   After dinner Mr. Hawkins said:—
U||   “‘My dears, I want to drink your health and prosperity; and may every
U||   blessing attend you both. I know you both from children, and have, with
U||   love and pride, seen you grow up. Now I want you to make your home here
U||   with me. I have left to me neither chick nor child; all are gone, and
U||   in my will I have left you everything.’ I cried, Lucy dear, as Jonathan
U||   and the old man clasped hands. Our evening was a very, very happy one.
U||   “So here we are, installed in this beautiful old house, and from both
U||   my bedroom and the drawing-room I can see the great elms of the
U||   cathedral close, with their great black stems standing out against the
U||   old yellow stone of the cathedral and I can hear the rooks overhead
U||   cawing and cawing and chattering and gossiping all day, after the
U||   manner of rooks—and humans. I am busy, I need not tell you, arranging
U||   things and housekeeping. Jonathan and Mr. Hawkins are busy all day;
U||   for, now that Jonathan is a partner, Mr. Hawkins wants to tell him all
U||   about the clients.
U||   “How is your dear mother getting on? I wish I could run up to town for
U||   a day or two to see you, dear, but I dare not go yet, with so much on
U||   my shoulders; and Jonathan wants looking after still. He is beginning
U||   to put some flesh on his bones again, but he was terribly weakened by
U||   the long illness; even now he sometimes starts out of his sleep in a
U||   sudden way and awakes all trembling until I can coax him back to his
U||   usual placidity. However, thank God, these occasions grow less frequent
U||   as the days go on, and they will in time pass away altogether, I trust.
U||   And now I have told you my news, let me ask yours. When are you to be
U||   married, and where, and who is to perform the ceremony, and what are
U||   you to wear, and is it to be a public or a private wedding? Tell me all
