U||   “20 September.
U||   “My dear Sir,—
U||   “In accordance with your wishes, I enclose report of the conditions of
U||   everything left in my charge.... With regard to patient, Renfield,
U||   there is more to say. He has had another outbreak, which might have had
U||   a dreadful ending, but which, as it fortunately happened, was
U||   unattended with any unhappy results. This afternoon a carrier’s cart
U||   with two men made a call at the empty house whose grounds abut on
U||   ours—the house to which, you will remember, the patient twice ran away.
U||   The men stopped at our gate to ask the porter their way, as they were
U||   strangers. I was myself looking out of the study window, having a smoke
U||   after dinner, and saw one of them come up to the house. As he passed
U||   the window of Renfield’s room, the patient began to rate him from
U||   within, and called him all the foul names he could lay his tongue to.
U||   The man, who seemed a decent fellow enough, contented himself by
U||   telling him to “shut up for a foul-mouthed beggar,” whereon our man
U||   accused him of robbing him and wanting to murder him and said that he
U||   would hinder him if he were to swing for it. I opened the window and
U||   signed to the man not to notice, so he contented himself after looking
U||   the place over and making up his mind as to what kind of a place he had
U||   got to by saying: ‘Lor’ bless yer, sir, I wouldn’t mind what was said
U||   to me in a bloomin’ madhouse. I pity ye and the guv’nor for havin’ to
U||   live in the house with a wild beast like that.’ Then he asked his way
U||   civilly enough, and I told him where the gate of the empty house was;
U||   he went away, followed by threats and curses and revilings from our
U||   man. I went down to see if I could make out any cause for his anger,
U||   since he is usually such a well-behaved man, and except his violent
U||   fits nothing of the kind had ever occurred. I found him, to my
U||   astonishment, quite composed and most genial in his manner. I tried to
U||   get him to talk of the incident, but he blandly asked me questions as
U||   to what I meant, and led me to believe that he was completely oblivious
U||   of the affair. It was, I am sorry to say, however, only another
U||   instance of his cunning, for within half an hour I heard of him again.
U||   This time he had broken out through the window of his room, and was
U||   running down the avenue. I called to the attendants to follow me, and
U||   ran after him, for I feared he was intent on some mischief. My fear was
U||   justified when I saw the same cart which had passed before coming down
U||   the road, having on it some great wooden boxes. The men were wiping
U||   their foreheads, and were flushed in the face, as if with violent
U||   exercise. Before I could get up to him the patient rushed at them, and
U||   pulling one of them off the cart, began to knock his head against the
