U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   20 September.—Only resolution and habit can let me make an entry
U||   to-night. I am too miserable, too low-spirited, too sick of the world
U||   and all in it, including life itself, that I would not care if I heard
U||   this moment the flapping of the wings of the angel of death. And he has
U||   been flapping those grim wings to some purpose of late—Lucy’s mother
U||   and Arthur’s father, and now.... Let me get on with my work.
U||   I duly relieved Van Helsing in his watch over Lucy. We wanted Arthur to
U||   go to rest also, but he refused at first. It was only when I told him
U||   that we should want him to help us during the day, and that we must not
U||   all break down for want of rest, lest Lucy should suffer, that he
U||   agreed to go. Van Helsing was very kind to him. “Come, my child,” he
U||   said; “come with me. You are sick and weak, and have had much sorrow
U||   and much mental pain, as well as that tax on your strength that we know
U||   of. You must not be alone; for to be alone is to be full of fears and
U||   alarms. Come to the drawing-room, where there is a big fire, and there
U||   are two sofas. You shall lie on one, and I on the other, and our
U||   sympathy will be comfort to each other, even though we do not speak,
U||   and even if we sleep.” Arthur went off with him, casting back a longing
U||   look on Lucy’s face, which lay in her pillow, almost whiter than the
U||   lawn. She lay quite still, and I looked round the room to see that all
U||   was as it should be. I could see that the Professor had carried out in
U||   this room, as in the other, his purpose of using the garlic; the whole
U||   of the window-sashes reeked with it, and round Lucy’s neck, over the
U||   silk handkerchief which Van Helsing made her keep on, was a rough
U||   chaplet of the same odorous flowers. Lucy was breathing somewhat
U||   stertorously, and her face was at its worst, for the open mouth showed
U||   the pale gums. Her teeth, in the dim, uncertain light, seemed longer
U||   and sharper than they had been in the morning. In particular, by some
U||   trick of the light, the canine teeth looked longer and sharper than the
U||   rest. I sat down by her, and presently she moved uneasily. At the same
U||   moment there came a sort of dull flapping or buffeting at the window. I
U||   went over to it softly, and peeped out by the corner of the blind.
U||   There was a full moonlight, and I could see that the noise was made by
U||   a great bat, which wheeled round—doubtless attracted by the light,
U||   although so dim—and every now and again struck the window with its
U||   wings. When I came back to my seat, I found that Lucy had moved
U||   slightly, and had torn away the garlic flowers from her throat. I
U||   replaced them as well as I could, and sat watching her.
U||   Presently she woke, and I gave her food, as Van Helsing had prescribed.
U||   She took but a little, and that languidly. There did not seem to be
U||   with her now the unconscious struggle for life and strength that had
U||   hitherto so marked her illness. It struck me as curious that the moment
U||   she became conscious she pressed the garlic flowers close to her. It
U||   was certainly odd that whenever she got into that lethargic state, with
U||   the stertorous breathing, she put the flowers from her; but that when
U||   she waked she clutched them close. There was no possibility of making
U||   any mistake about this, for in the long hours that followed, she had
U||   many spells of sleeping and waking and repeated both actions many
U||   times.
U||   At six o’clock Van Helsing came to relieve me. Arthur had then fallen
U||   into a doze, and he mercifully let him sleep on. When he saw Lucy’s
U||   face I could hear the sissing indraw of his breath, and he said to me
U||   in a sharp whisper: “Draw up the blind; I want light!” Then he bent
U||   down, and, with his face almost touching Lucy’s, examined her
U||   carefully. He removed the flowers and lifted the silk handkerchief from
U||   her throat. As he did so he started back, and I could hear his
U||   ejaculation, “Mein Gott!” as it was smothered in his throat. I bent
U||   over and looked, too, and as I noticed some queer chill came over me.
U||   The wounds on the throat had absolutely disappeared.
U||   For fully five minutes Van Helsing stood looking at her, with his face
U||   at its sternest. Then he turned to me and said calmly:—
U||   “She is dying. It will not be long now. It will be much difference,
U||   mark me, whether she dies conscious or in her sleep. Wake that poor
U||   boy, and let him come and see the last; he trusts us, and we have
U||   promised him.”
U||   I went to the dining-room and waked him. He was dazed for a moment, but
U||   when he saw the sunlight streaming in through the edges of the shutters
U||   he thought he was late, and expressed his fear. I assured him that Lucy
U||   was still asleep, but told him as gently as I could that both Van
U||   Helsing and I feared that the end was near. He covered his face with
U||   his hands, and slid down on his knees by the sofa, where he remained,
U||   perhaps a minute, with his head buried, praying, whilst his shoulders
U||   shook with grief. I took him by the hand and raised him up. “Come,” I
U||   said, “my dear old fellow, summon all your fortitude: it will be best
U||   and easiest for her.”
U||   When we came into Lucy’s room I could see that Van Helsing had, with
U||   his usual forethought, been putting matters straight and making
U||   everything look as pleasing as possible. He had even brushed Lucy’s
U||   hair, so that it lay on the pillow in its usual sunny ripples. When we
U||   came into the room she opened her eyes, and seeing him, whispered
U||   softly:—
U||   “Arthur! Oh, my love, I am so glad you have come!” He was stooping to
U||   kiss her, when Van Helsing motioned him back. “No,” he whispered, “not
U||   yet! Hold her hand; it will comfort her more.”
U||   So Arthur took her hand and knelt beside her, and she looked her best,
U||   with all the soft lines matching the angelic beauty of her eyes. Then
U||   gradually her eyes closed, and she sank to sleep. For a little bit her
U||   breast heaved softly, and her breath came and went like a tired
U||   child’s.
U||   And then insensibly there came the strange change which I had noticed
U||   in the night. Her breathing grew stertorous, the mouth opened, and the
U||   pale gums, drawn back, made the teeth look longer and sharper than
U||   ever. In a sort of sleep-waking, vague, unconscious way she opened her
U||   eyes, which were now dull and hard at once, and said in a soft,
U||   voluptuous voice, such as I had never heard from her lips:—
U||   “Arthur! Oh, my love, I am so glad you have come! Kiss me!” Arthur bent
U||   eagerly over to kiss her; but at that instant Van Helsing, who, like
U||   me, had been startled by her voice, swooped upon him, and catching him
U||   by the neck with both hands, dragged him back with a fury of strength
U||   which I never thought he could have possessed, and actually hurled him
U||   almost across the room.
U||   “Not for your life!” he said; “not for your living soul and hers!” And
U||   he stood between them like a lion at bay.
U||   Arthur was so taken aback that he did not for a moment know what to do
U||   or say; and before any impulse of violence could seize him he realised
U||   the place and the occasion, and stood silent, waiting.
U||   I kept my eyes fixed on Lucy, as did Van Helsing, and we saw a spasm as
U||   of rage flit like a shadow over her face; the sharp teeth champed
U||   together. Then her eyes closed, and she breathed heavily.
U||   Very shortly after she opened her eyes in all their softness, and
U||   putting out her poor, pale, thin hand, took Van Helsing’s great brown
U||   one; drawing it to her, she kissed it. “My true friend,” she said, in a
U||   faint voice, but with untellable pathos, “My true friend, and his! Oh,
U||   guard him, and give me peace!”
U||   “I swear it!” he said solemnly, kneeling beside her and holding up his
U||   hand, as one who registers an oath. Then he turned to Arthur, and said
U||   to him: “Come, my child, take her hand in yours, and kiss her on the
U||   forehead, and only once.”
U||   Their eyes met instead of their lips; and so they parted.
U||   Lucy’s eyes closed; and Van Helsing, who had been watching closely,
U||   took Arthur’s arm, and drew him away.
U||   And then Lucy’s breathing became stertorous again, and all at once it
U||   ceased.
U||   “It is all over,” said Van Helsing. “She is dead!”
U||   I took Arthur by the arm, and led him away to the drawing-room, where
U||   he sat down, and covered his face with his hands, sobbing in a way that
U||   nearly broke me down to see.
U||   I went back to the room, and found Van Helsing looking at poor Lucy,
U||   and his face was sterner than ever. Some change had come over her body.
U||   Death had given back part of her beauty, for her brow and cheeks had
U||   recovered some of their flowing lines; even the lips had lost their
U||   deadly pallor. It was as if the blood, no longer needed for the working
U||   of the heart, had gone to make the harshness of death as little rude as
U||   might be.
U||   “We thought her dying whilst she slept,
U||   And sleeping when she died.”
U||   I stood beside Van Helsing, and said:—
U||   “Ah, well, poor girl, there is peace for her at last. It is the end!”
U||   He turned to me, and said with grave solemnity:—
U||   “Not so; alas! not so. It is only the beginning!”
U||   When I asked him what he meant, he only shook his head and answered:—
U||   “We can do nothing as yet. Wait and see.”
U||CHAPTER XIII
U||DR. SEWARD’S DIARY—continued.
U||   THE funeral was arranged for the next succeeding day, so that Lucy and
U||   her mother might be buried together. I attended to all the ghastly
U||   formalities, and the urbane undertaker proved that his staff were
U||   afflicted—or blessed—with something of his own obsequious suavity. Even
U||   the woman who performed the last offices for the dead remarked to me,
U||   in a confidential, brother-professional way, when she had come out from
U||   the death-chamber:—
U||   “She makes a very beautiful corpse, sir. It’s quite a privilege to
U||   attend on her. It’s not too much to say that she will do credit to our
U||   establishment!”
U||   I noticed that Van Helsing never kept far away. This was possible from
U||   the disordered state of things in the household. There were no
U||   relatives at hand; and as Arthur had to be back the next day to attend
U||   at his father’s funeral, we were unable to notify any one who should
U||   have been bidden. Under the circumstances, Van Helsing and I took it
U||   upon ourselves to examine papers, etc. He insisted upon looking over
U||   Lucy’s papers himself. I asked him why, for I feared that he, being a
U||   foreigner, might not be quite aware of English legal requirements, and
U||   so might in ignorance make some unnecessary trouble. He answered me:—
U||   “I know; I know. You forget that I am a lawyer as well as a doctor. But
U||   this is not altogether for the law. You knew that, when you avoided the
U||   coroner. I have more than him to avoid. There may be papers more—such
U||   as this.”
U||   As he spoke he took from his pocket-book the memorandum which had been
U||   in Lucy’s breast, and which she had torn in her sleep.
U||   “When you find anything of the solicitor who is for the late Mrs.
U||   Westenra, seal all her papers, and write him to-night. For me, I watch
U||   here in the room and in Miss Lucy’s old room all night, and I myself
U||   search for what may be. It is not well that her very thoughts go into
U||   the hands of strangers.”
U||   I went on with my part of the work, and in another half hour had found
U||   the name and address of Mrs. Westenra’s solicitor and had written to
U||   him. All the poor lady’s papers were in order; explicit directions
U||   regarding the place of burial were given. I had hardly sealed the
U||   letter, when, to my surprise, Van Helsing walked into the room,
U||   saying:—
U||   “Can I help you, friend John? I am free, and if I may, my service is to
U||   you.”
U||   “Have you got what you looked for?” I asked, to which he replied:—
U||   “I did not look for any specific thing. I only hoped to find, and find
U||   I have, all that there was—only some letters and a few memoranda, and a
U||   diary new begun. But I have them here, and we shall for the present say
U||   nothing of them. I shall see that poor lad to-morrow evening, and, with
U||   his sanction, I shall use some.”
U||   When we had finished the work in hand, he said to me:—
U||   “And now, friend John, I think we may to bed. We want sleep, both you
U||   and I, and rest to recuperate. To-morrow we shall have much to do, but
U||   for the to-night there is no need of us. Alas!”
U||   Before turning in we went to look at poor Lucy. The undertaker had
U||   certainly done his work well, for the room was turned into a small
U||   chapelle ardente. There was a wilderness of beautiful white flowers,
U||   and death was made as little repulsive as might be. The end of the
U||   winding-sheet was laid over the face; when the Professor bent over and
U||   turned it gently back, we both started at the beauty before us, the
U||   tall wax candles showing a sufficient light to note it well. All Lucy’s
U||   loveliness had come back to her in death, and the hours that had
U||   passed, instead of leaving traces of “decay’s effacing fingers,” had
U||   but restored the beauty of life, till positively I could not believe my
U||   eyes that I was looking at a corpse.
U||   The Professor looked sternly grave. He had not loved her as I had, and
U||   there was no need for tears in his eyes. He said to me: “Remain till I
U||   return,” and left the room. He came back with a handful of wild garlic
U||   from the box waiting in the hall, but which had not been opened, and
U||   placed the flowers amongst the others on and around the bed. Then he
U||   took from his neck, inside his collar, a little gold crucifix, and
U||   placed it over the mouth. He restored the sheet to its place, and we
U||   came away.
U||   I was undressing in my own room, when, with a premonitory tap at the
U||   door, he entered, and at once began to speak:—
U||   “To-morrow I want you to bring me, before night, a set of post-mortem
U||   knives.”
U||   “Must we make an autopsy?” I asked.
U||   “Yes and no. I want to operate, but not as you think. Let me tell you
U||   now, but not a word to another. I want to cut off her head and take out
U||   her heart. Ah! you a surgeon, and so shocked! You, whom I have seen
U||   with no tremble of hand or heart, do operations of life and death that
U||   make the rest shudder. Oh, but I must not forget, my dear friend John,
U||   that you loved her; and I have not forgotten it, for it is I that shall
U||   operate, and you must only help. I would like to do it to-night, but
U||   for Arthur I must not; he will be free after his father’s funeral
U||   to-morrow, and he will want to see her—to see it. Then, when she is
U||   coffined ready for the next day, you and I shall come when all sleep.
U||   We shall unscrew the coffin-lid, and shall do our operation: and then
U||   replace all, so that none know, save we alone.”
U||   “But why do it at all? The girl is dead. Why mutilate her poor body
U||   without need? And if there is no necessity for a post-mortem and
U||   nothing to gain by it—no good to her, to us, to science, to human
U||   knowledge—why do it? Without such it is monstrous.”
U||   For answer he put his hand on my shoulder, and said, with infinite
U||   tenderness:—
U||   “Friend John, I pity your poor bleeding heart; and I love you the more
U||   because it does so bleed. If I could, I would take on myself the burden
U||   that you do bear. But there are things that you know not, but that you
U||   shall know, and bless me for knowing, though they are not pleasant
U||   things. John, my child, you have been my friend now many years, and yet
U||   did you ever know me to do any without good cause? I may err—I am but
U||   man; but I believe in all I do. Was it not for these causes that you
U||   send for me when the great trouble came? Yes! Were you not amazed, nay
U||   horrified, when I would not let Arthur kiss his love—though she was
U||   dying—and snatched him away by all my strength? Yes! And yet you saw
U||   how she thanked me, with her so beautiful dying eyes, her voice, too,
U||   so weak, and she kiss my rough old hand and bless me? Yes! And did you
U||   not hear me swear promise to her, that so she closed her eyes grateful?
U||   Yes!
U||   “Well, I have good reason now for all I want to do. You have for many
U||   years trust me; you have believe me weeks past, when there be things so
U||   strange that you might have well doubt. Believe me yet a little, friend
U||   John. If you trust me not, then I must tell what I think; and that is
U||   not perhaps well. And if I work—as work I shall, no matter trust or no
U||   trust—without my friend trust in me, I work with heavy heart and feel,
U||   oh! so lonely when I want all help and courage that may be!” He paused
U||   a moment and went on solemnly: “Friend John, there are strange and
U||   terrible days before us. Let us not be two, but one, that so we work to
U||   a good end. Will you not have faith in me?”
U||   I took his hand, and promised him. I held my door open as he went away,
U||   and watched him go into his room and close the door. As I stood without
U||   moving, I saw one of the maids pass silently along the passage—she had
U||   her back towards me, so did not see me—and go into the room where Lucy
U||   lay. The sight touched me. Devotion is so rare, and we are so grateful
U||   to those who show it unasked to those we love. Here was a poor girl
U||   putting aside the terrors which she naturally had of death to go watch
U||   alone by the bier of the mistress whom she loved, so that the poor clay
U||   might not be lonely till laid to eternal rest....
U||   I must have slept long and soundly, for it was broad daylight when Van
U||   Helsing waked me by coming into my room. He came over to my bedside and
U||   said:—
U||   “You need not trouble about the knives; we shall not do it.”
U||   “Why not?” I asked. For his solemnity of the night before had greatly
U||   impressed me.
U||   “Because,” he said sternly, “it is too late—or too early. See!” Here he
U||   held up the little golden crucifix. “This was stolen in the night.”
U||   “How, stolen,” I asked in wonder, “since you have it now?”
U||   “Because I get it back from the worthless wretch who stole it, from the
U||   woman who robbed the dead and the living. Her punishment will surely
U||   come, but not through me; she knew not altogether what she did and thus
U||   unknowing, she only stole. Now we must wait.”
U||   He went away on the word, leaving me with a new mystery to think of, a
U||   new puzzle to grapple with.
U||   The forenoon was a dreary time, but at noon the solicitor came: Mr.
U||   Marquand, of Wholeman, Sons, Marquand & Lidderdale. He was very genial
U||   and very appreciative of what we had done, and took off our hands all
U||   cares as to details. During lunch he told us that Mrs. Westenra had for
U||   some time expected sudden death from her heart, and had put her affairs
U||   in absolute order; he informed us that, with the exception of a certain
U||   entailed property of Lucy’s father’s which now, in default of direct
U||   issue, went back to a distant branch of the family, the whole estate,
U||   real and personal, was left absolutely to Arthur Holmwood. When he had
U||   told us so much he went on:—
U||   “Frankly we did our best to prevent such a testamentary disposition,
U||   and pointed out certain contingencies that might leave her daughter
U||   either penniless or not so free as she should be to act regarding a
U||   matrimonial alliance. Indeed, we pressed the matter so far that we
U||   almost came into collision, for she asked us if we were or were not
U||   prepared to carry out her wishes. Of course, we had then no alternative
U||   but to accept. We were right in principle, and ninety-nine times out of
U||   a hundred we should have proved, by the logic of events, the accuracy
U||   of our judgment. Frankly, however, I must admit that in this case any
U||   other form of disposition would have rendered impossible the carrying
U||   out of her wishes. For by her predeceasing her daughter the latter
U||   would have come into possession of the property, and, even had she only
U||   survived her mother by five minutes, her property would, in case there
U||   were no will—and a will was a practical impossibility in such a
U||   case—have been treated at her decease as under intestacy. In which case
U||   Lord Godalming, though so dear a friend, would have had no claim in the
U||   world; and the inheritors, being remote, would not be likely to abandon
U||   their just rights, for sentimental reasons regarding an entire
U||   stranger. I assure you, my dear sirs, I am rejoiced at the result,
U||   perfectly rejoiced.”
U||   He was a good fellow, but his rejoicing at the one little part—in which
U||   he was officially interested—of so great a tragedy, was an
U||   object-lesson in the limitations of sympathetic understanding.
U||   He did not remain long, but said he would look in later in the day and
U||   see Lord Godalming. His coming, however, had been a certain comfort to
U||   us, since it assured us that we should not have to dread hostile
U||   criticism as to any of our acts. Arthur was expected at five o’clock,
U||   so a little before that time we visited the death-chamber. It was so in
U||   very truth, for now both mother and daughter lay in it. The undertaker,
U||   true to his craft, had made the best display he could of his goods, and
U||   there was a mortuary air about the place that lowered our spirits at
U||   once. Van Helsing ordered the former arrangement to be adhered to,
U||   explaining that, as Lord Godalming was coming very soon, it would be
U||   less harrowing to his feelings to see all that was left of his fiancée
U||   quite alone. The undertaker seemed shocked at his own stupidity and
U||   exerted himself to restore things to the condition in which we left
U||   them the night before, so that when Arthur came such shocks to his
U||   feelings as we could avoid were saved.
U||   Poor fellow! He looked desperately sad and broken; even his stalwart
U||   manhood seemed to have shrunk somewhat under the strain of his
U||   much-tried emotions. He had, I knew, been very genuinely and devotedly
U||   attached to his father; and to lose him, and at such a time, was a
U||   bitter blow to him. With me he was warm as ever, and to Van Helsing he
U||   was sweetly courteous; but I could not help seeing that there was some
U||   constraint with him. The Professor noticed it, too, and motioned me to
U||   bring him upstairs. I did so, and left him at the door of the room, as
U||   I felt he would like to be quite alone with her, but he took my arm and
U||   led me in, saying huskily:—
U||   “You loved her too, old fellow; she told me all about it, and there was
U||   no friend had a closer place in her heart than you. I don’t know how to
U||   thank you for all you have done for her. I can’t think yet....”
U||   Here he suddenly broke down, and threw his arms round my shoulders and
U||   laid his head on my breast, crying:—
U||   “Oh, Jack! Jack! What shall I do! The whole of life seems gone from me
U||   all at once, and there is nothing in the wide world for me to live
U||   for.”
U||   I comforted him as well as I could. In such cases men do not need much
U||   expression. A grip of the hand, the tightening of an arm over the
U||   shoulder, a sob in unison, are expressions of sympathy dear to a man’s
U||   heart. I stood still and silent till his sobs died away, and then I
U||   said softly to him:—
U||   “Come and look at her.”
U||   Together we moved over to the bed, and I lifted the lawn from her face.
U||   God! how beautiful she was. Every hour seemed to be enhancing her
U||   loveliness. It frightened and amazed me somewhat; and as for Arthur, he
U||   fell a-trembling, and finally was shaken with doubt as with an ague. At
U||   last, after a long pause, he said to me in a faint whisper:—
U||   “Jack, is she really dead?”
U||   I assured him sadly that it was so, and went on to suggest—for I felt
U||   that such a horrible doubt should not have life for a moment longer
U||   than I could help—that it often happened that after death faces became
U||   softened and even resolved into their youthful beauty; that this was
U||   especially so when death had been preceded by any acute or prolonged
U||   suffering. It seemed to quite do away with any doubt, and, after
U||   kneeling beside the couch for a while and looking at her lovingly and
U||   long, he turned aside. I told him that that must be good-bye, as the
U||   coffin had to be prepared; so he went back and took her dead hand in
U||   his and kissed it, and bent over and kissed her forehead. He came away,
U||   fondly looking back over his shoulder at her as he came.
U||   I left him in the drawing-room, and told Van Helsing that he had said
