U||   replied:—
U||   “I am not surprised. Just now I doubted for a moment myself!”
U||   We all dined together, and I could see that poor Art was trying to make
U||   the best of things. Van Helsing had been silent all dinner-time; but
U||   when we had lit our cigars he said—
U||   “Lord——”; but Arthur interrupted him:—
U||   “No, no, not that, for God’s sake! not yet at any rate. Forgive me,
U||   sir: I did not mean to speak offensively; it is only because my loss is
U||   so recent.”
U||   The Professor answered very sweetly:—
U||   “I only used that name because I was in doubt. I must not call you
U||   ‘Mr.,’ and I have grown to love you—yes, my dear boy, to love you—as
U||   Arthur.”
U||   Arthur held out his hand, and took the old man’s warmly.
U||   “Call me what you will,” he said. “I hope I may always have the title
U||   of a friend. And let me say that I am at a loss for words to thank you
U||   for your goodness to my poor dear.” He paused a moment, and went on: “I
U||   know that she understood your goodness even better than I do; and if I
U||   was rude or in any way wanting at that time you acted so—you
U||   remember”—the Professor nodded—“you must forgive me.”
U||   He answered with a grave kindness:—
U||   “I know it was hard for you to quite trust me then, for to trust such
U||   violence needs to understand; and I take it that you do not—that you
U||   cannot—trust me now, for you do not yet understand. And there may be
U||   more times when I shall want you to trust when you cannot—and may
U||   not—and must not yet understand. But the time will come when your trust
