U||   though the sunlight himself shone through. Then you shall bless me from
U||   first to last for your own sake, and for the sake of others and for her
U||   dear sake to whom I swore to protect.”
U||   “And, indeed, indeed, sir,” said Arthur warmly, “I shall in all ways
U||   trust you. I know and believe you have a very noble heart, and you are
U||   Jack’s friend, and you were hers. You shall do what you like.”
U||   The Professor cleared his throat a couple of times, as though about to
U||   speak, and finally said:—
U||   “May I ask you something now?”
U||   “Certainly.”
U||   “You know that Mrs. Westenra left you all her property?”
U||   “No, poor dear; I never thought of it.”
U||   “And as it is all yours, you have a right to deal with it as you will.
U||   I want you to give me permission to read all Miss Lucy’s papers and
U||   letters. Believe me, it is no idle curiosity. I have a motive of which,
U||   be sure, she would have approved. I have them all here. I took them
U||   before we knew that all was yours, so that no strange hand might touch
U||   them—no strange eye look through words into her soul. I shall keep
U||   them, if I may; even you may not see them yet, but I shall keep them
U||   safe. No word shall be lost; and in the good time I shall give them
U||   back to you. It’s a hard thing I ask, but you will do it, will you not,
U||   for Lucy’s sake?”
U||   Arthur spoke out heartily, like his old self:—
U||   “Dr. Van Helsing, you may do what you will. I feel that in saying this
U||   I am doing what my dear one would have approved. I shall not trouble
U||   you with questions till the time comes.”
U||   The old Professor stood up as he said solemnly:—
U||   “And you are right. There will be pain for us all; but it will not be
U||   all pain, nor will this pain be the last. We and you too—you most of
U||   all, my dear boy—will have to pass through the bitter water before we
U||   reach the sweet. But we must be brave of heart and unselfish, and do
U||   our duty, and all will be well!”
U||   I slept on a sofa in Arthur’s room that night. Van Helsing did not go
U||   to bed at all. He went to and fro, as if patrolling the house, and was
U||   never out of sight of the room where Lucy lay in her coffin, strewn
U||   with the wild garlic flowers, which sent, through the odour of lily and
U||   rose, a heavy, overpowering smell into the night.
U||   Mina Harker’s Journal.
U||   22 September.—In the train to Exeter. Jonathan sleeping.
U||   It seems only yesterday that the last entry was made, and yet how much
U||   between then, in Whitby and all the world before me, Jonathan away and
U||   no news of him; and now, married to Jonathan, Jonathan a solicitor, a
U||   partner, rich, master of his business, Mr. Hawkins dead and buried, and
U||   Jonathan with another attack that may harm him. Some day he may ask me
U||   about it. Down it all goes. I am rusty in my shorthand—see what
U||   unexpected prosperity does for us—so it may be as well to freshen it up
U||   again with an exercise anyhow....
U||   The service was very simple and very solemn. There were only ourselves
U||   and the servants there, one or two old friends of his from Exeter, his
U||   London agent, and a gentleman representing Sir John Paxton, the
U||   President of the Incorporated Law Society. Jonathan and I stood hand in
U||   hand, and we felt that our best and dearest friend was gone from us....
U||   We came back to town quietly, taking a ’bus to Hyde Park Corner.
U||   Jonathan thought it would interest me to go into the Row for a while,
U||   so we sat down; but there were very few people there, and it was
U||   sad-looking and desolate to see so many empty chairs. It made us think
U||   of the empty chair at home; so we got up and walked down Piccadilly.
U||   Jonathan was holding me by the arm, the way he used to in old days
U||   before I went to school. I felt it very improper, for you can’t go on
U||   for some years teaching etiquette and decorum to other girls without
U||   the pedantry of it biting into yourself a bit; but it was Jonathan, and
U||   he was my husband, and we didn’t know anybody who saw us—and we didn’t
U||   care if they did—so on we walked. I was looking at a very beautiful
U||   girl, in a big cart-wheel hat, sitting in a victoria outside
U||   Guiliano’s, when I felt Jonathan clutch my arm so tight that he hurt
U||   me, and he said under his breath: “My God!” I am always anxious about
U||   Jonathan, for I fear that some nervous fit may upset him again; so I
U||   turned to him quickly, and asked him what it was that disturbed him.
U||   He was very pale, and his eyes seemed bulging out as, half in terror
U||   and half in amazement, he gazed at a tall, thin man, with a beaky nose
U||   and black moustache and pointed beard, who was also observing the
U||   pretty girl. He was looking at her so hard that he did not see either
U||   of us, and so I had a good view of him. His face was not a good face;
U||   it was hard, and cruel, and sensual, and his big white teeth, that
U||   looked all the whiter because his lips were so red, were pointed like
U||   an animal’s. Jonathan kept staring at him, till I was afraid he would
U||   notice. I feared he might take it ill, he looked so fierce and nasty. I
U||   asked Jonathan why he was disturbed, and he answered, evidently
U||   thinking that I knew as much about it as he did: “Do you see who it
U||   is?”
U||   “No, dear,” I said; “I don’t know him; who is it?” His answer seemed to
U||   shock and thrill me, for it was said as if he did not know that it was
U||   to me, Mina, to whom he was speaking:—
U||   “It is the man himself!”
U||   The poor dear was evidently terrified at something—very greatly
U||   terrified; I do believe that if he had not had me to lean on and to
U||   support him he would have sunk down. He kept staring; a man came out of
U||   the shop with a small parcel, and gave it to the lady, who then drove
U||   off. The dark man kept his eyes fixed on her, and when the carriage
U||   moved up Piccadilly he followed in the same direction, and hailed a
U||   hansom. Jonathan kept looking after him, and said, as if to himself:—
U||   “I believe it is the Count, but he has grown young. My God, if this be
U||   so! Oh, my God! my God! If I only knew! if I only knew!” He was
U||   distressing himself so much that I feared to keep his mind on the
U||   subject by asking him any questions, so I remained silent. I drew him
U||   away quietly, and he, holding my arm, came easily. We walked a little
U||   further, and then went in and sat for a while in the Green Park. It was
U||   a hot day for autumn, and there was a comfortable seat in a shady
U||   place. After a few minutes’ staring at nothing, Jonathan’s eyes closed,
U||   and he went quietly into a sleep, with his head on my shoulder. I
U||   thought it was the best thing for him, so did not disturb him. In about
U||   twenty minutes he woke up, and said to me quite cheerfully:—
U||   “Why, Mina, have I been asleep! Oh, do forgive me for being so rude.
