U||   that Lucy died the day before yesterday. They were both buried to-day.”
U||   Oh, what a wealth of sorrow in a few words! Poor Mrs. Westenra! poor
U||   Lucy! Gone, gone, never to return to us! And poor, poor Arthur, to have
U||   lost such sweetness out of his life! God help us all to bear our
U||   troubles.
U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   22 September.—It is all over. Arthur has gone back to Ring, and has
U||   taken Quincey Morris with him. What a fine fellow is Quincey! I believe
U||   in my heart of hearts that he suffered as much about Lucy’s death as
U||   any of us; but he bore himself through it like a moral Viking. If
U||   America can go on breeding men like that, she will be a power in the
U||   world indeed. Van Helsing is lying down, having a rest preparatory to
U||   his journey. He goes over to Amsterdam to-night, but says he returns
U||   to-morrow night; that he only wants to make some arrangements which can
U||   only be made personally. He is to stop with me then, if he can; he says
U||   he has work to do in London which may take him some time. Poor old
U||   fellow! I fear that the strain of the past week has broken down even
U||   his iron strength. All the time of the burial he was, I could see,
U||   putting some terrible restraint on himself. When it was all over, we
U||   were standing beside Arthur, who, poor fellow, was speaking of his part
U||   in the operation where his blood had been transfused to his Lucy’s
U||   veins; I could see Van Helsing’s face grow white and purple by turns.
U||   Arthur was saying that he felt since then as if they two had been
U||   really married and that she was his wife in the sight of God. None of
U||   us said a word of the other operations, and none of us ever shall.
U||   Arthur and Quincey went away together to the station, and Van Helsing
