U||   characteristic of him, for it was logical and forceful and mysterious.
U||   He said:—
U||   “Ah, you don’t comprehend, friend John. Do not think that I am not sad,
U||   though I laugh. See, I have cried even when the laugh did choke me. But
U||   no more think that I am all sorry when I cry, for the laugh he come
U||   just the same. Keep it always with you that laughter who knock at your
U||   door and say, ‘May I come in?’ is not the true laughter. No! he is a
U||   king, and he come when and how he like. He ask no person; he choose no
U||   time of suitability. He say, ‘I am here.’ Behold, in example I grieve
U||   my heart out for that so sweet young girl; I give my blood for her,
U||   though I am old and worn; I give my time, my skill, my sleep; I let my
U||   other sufferers want that so she may have all. And yet I can laugh at
U||   her very grave—laugh when the clay from the spade of the sexton drop
U||   upon her coffin and say ‘Thud! thud!’ to my heart, till it send back
U||   the blood from my cheek. My heart bleed for that poor boy—that dear
U||   boy, so of the age of mine own boy had I been so blessed that he live,
U||   and with his hair and eyes the same. There, you know now why I love him
U||   so. And yet when he say things that touch my husband-heart to the
U||   quick, and make my father-heart yearn to him as to no other man—not
U||   even to you, friend John, for we are more level in experiences than
U||   father and son—yet even at such moment King Laugh he come to me and
U||   shout and bellow in my ear, ‘Here I am! here I am!’ till the blood come
U||   dance back and bring some of the sunshine that he carry with him to my
U||   cheek. Oh, friend John, it is a strange world, a sad world, a world
U||   full of miseries, and woes, and troubles; and yet when King Laugh come
