U||   bones of the churchyard, and tears that burn as they fall—all dance
U||   together to the music that he make with that smileless mouth of him.
U||   And believe me, friend John, that he is good to come, and kind. Ah, we
U||   men and women are like ropes drawn tight with strain that pull us
U||   different ways. Then tears come; and, like the rain on the ropes, they
U||   brace us up, until perhaps the strain become too great, and we break.
U||   But King Laugh he come like the sunshine, and he ease off the strain
U||   again; and we bear to go on with our labour, what it may be.”
U||   I did not like to wound him by pretending not to see his idea; but, as
U||   I did not yet understand the cause of his laughter, I asked him. As he
U||   answered me his face grew stern, and he said in quite a different
U||   tone:—
