U||   A HAMPSTEAD MYSTERY.
U||   The neighbourhood of Hampstead is just at present exercised with a
U||   series of events which seem to run on lines parallel to those of what
U||   was known to the writers of headlines as “The Kensington Horror,” or
U||   “The Stabbing Woman,” or “The Woman in Black.” During the past two or
U||   three days several cases have occurred of young children straying from
U||   home or neglecting to return from their playing on the Heath. In all
U||   these cases the children were too young to give any properly
U||   intelligible account of themselves, but the consensus of their excuses
U||   is that they had been with a “bloofer lady.” It has always been late in
U||   the evening when they have been missed, and on two occasions the
U||   children have not been found until early in the following morning. It
U||   is generally supposed in the neighbourhood that, as the first child
U||   missed gave as his reason for being away that a “bloofer lady” had
U||   asked him to come for a walk, the others had picked up the phrase and
U||   used it as occasion served. This is the more natural as the favourite
U||   game of the little ones at present is luring each other away by wiles.
U||   A correspondent writes us that to see some of the tiny tots pretending
U||   to be the “bloofer lady” is supremely funny. Some of our caricaturists
U||   might, he says, take a lesson in the irony of grotesque by comparing
U||   the reality and the picture. It is only in accordance with general
U||   principles of human nature that the “bloofer lady” should be the
U||   popular rôle at these al fresco performances. Our correspondent naïvely
U||   says that even Ellen Terry could not be so winningly attractive as some
U||   of these grubby-faced little children pretend—and even imagine
U||   themselves—to be.
U||   There is, however, possibly a serious side to the question, for some of
U||   the children, indeed all who have been missed at night, have been
U||   slightly torn or wounded in the throat. The wounds seem such as might
U||   be made by a rat or a small dog, and although of not much importance
U||   individually, would tend to show that whatever animal inflicts them has
U||   a system or method of its own. The police of the division have been
U||   instructed to keep a sharp look-out for straying children, especially
U||   when very young, in and around Hampstead Heath, and for any stray dog
U||   which may be about.
