U||   MINA HARKER’S JOURNAL.
U||   25 September.—I cannot help feeling terribly excited as the time draws
U||   near for the visit of Dr. Van Helsing, for somehow I expect that it
U||   will throw some light upon Jonathan’s sad experience; and as he
U||   attended poor dear Lucy in her last illness, he can tell me all about
U||   her. That is the reason of his coming; it is concerning Lucy and her
U||   sleep-walking, and not about Jonathan. Then I shall never know the real
U||   truth now! How silly I am. That awful journal gets hold of my
U||   imagination and tinges everything with something of its own colour. Of
U||   course it is about Lucy. That habit came back to the poor dear, and
U||   that awful night on the cliff must have made her ill. I had almost
U||   forgotten in my own affairs how ill she was afterwards. She must have
U||   told him of her sleep-walking adventure on the cliff, and that I knew
U||   all about it; and now he wants me to tell him what she knows, so that
U||   he may understand. I hope I did right in not saying anything of it to
U||   Mrs. Westenra; I should never forgive myself if any act of mine, were
U||   it even a negative one, brought harm on poor dear Lucy. I hope, too,
U||   Dr. Van Helsing will not blame me; I have had so much trouble and
U||   anxiety of late that I feel I cannot bear more just at present.
U||   I suppose a cry does us all good at times—clears the air as other rain
U||   does. Perhaps it was reading the journal yesterday that upset me, and
U||   then Jonathan went away this morning to stay away from me a whole day
U||   and night, the first time we have been parted since our marriage. I do
U||   hope the dear fellow will take care of himself, and that nothing will
U||   occur to upset him. It is two o’clock, and the doctor will be here soon
