U||   Jonathan Harker’s Journal.
U||   26 September.—I thought never to write in this diary again, but the
U||   time has come. When I got home last night Mina had supper ready, and
U||   when we had supped she told me of Van Helsing’s visit, and of her
U||   having given him the two diaries copied out, and of how anxious she has
U||   been about me. She showed me in the doctor’s letter that all I wrote
U||   down was true. It seems to have made a new man of me. It was the doubt
U||   as to the reality of the whole thing that knocked me over. I felt
U||   impotent, and in the dark, and distrustful. But, now that I know, I am
U||   not afraid, even of the Count. He has succeeded after all, then, in his
U||   design in getting to London, and it was he I saw. He has got younger,
U||   and how? Van Helsing is the man to unmask him and hunt him out, if he
U||   is anything like what Mina says. We sat late, and talked it all over.
U||   Mina is dressing, and I shall call at the hotel in a few minutes and
U||   bring him over....
U||   He was, I think, surprised to see me. When I came into the room where
U||   he was, and introduced myself, he took me by the shoulder, and turned
U||   my face round to the light, and said, after a sharp scrutiny:—
U||   “But Madam Mina told me you were ill, that you had had a shock.” It was
U||   so funny to hear my wife called “Madam Mina” by this kindly,
U||   strong-faced old man. I smiled, and said:—
U||   “I was ill, I have had a shock; but you have cured me already.”
U||   “And how?”
U||   “By your letter to Mina last night. I was in doubt, and then everything
U||   took a hue of unreality, and I did not know what to trust, even the
U||   evidence of my own senses. Not knowing what to trust, I did not know
U||   what to do; and so had only to keep on working in what had hitherto
U||   been the groove of my life. The groove ceased to avail me, and I
U||   mistrusted myself. Doctor, you don’t know what it is to doubt
U||   everything, even yourself. No, you don’t; you couldn’t with eyebrows
U||   like yours.” He seemed pleased, and laughed as he said:—
