U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   26 September.—Truly there is no such thing as finality. Not a week
U||   since I said “Finis,” and yet here I am starting fresh again, or rather
U||   going on with the same record. Until this afternoon I had no cause to
U||   think of what is done. Renfield had become, to all intents, as sane as
U||   he ever was. He was already well ahead with his fly business; and he
U||   had just started in the spider line also; so he had not been of any
U||   trouble to me. I had a letter from Arthur, written on Sunday, and from
U||   it I gather that he is bearing up wonderfully well. Quincey Morris is
U||   with him, and that is much of a help, for he himself is a bubbling well
U||   of good spirits. Quincey wrote me a line too, and from him I hear that
U||   Arthur is beginning to recover something of his old buoyancy; so as to
U||   them all my mind is at rest. As for myself, I was settling down to my
U||   work with the enthusiasm which I used to have for it, so that I might
U||   fairly have said that the wound which poor Lucy left on me was becoming
U||   cicatrised. Everything is, however, now reopened; and what is to be the
U||   end God only knows. I have an idea that Van Helsing thinks he knows,
U||   too, but he will only let out enough at a time to whet curiosity. He
U||   went to Exeter yesterday, and stayed there all night. To-day he came
U||   back, and almost bounded into the room at about half-past five o’clock,
U||   and thrust last night’s “Westminster Gazette” into my hand.
U||   “What do you think of that?” he asked as he stood back and folded his
U||   arms.
U||   I looked over the paper, for I really did not know what he meant; but
U||   he took it from me and pointed out a paragraph about children being
U||   decoyed away at Hampstead. It did not convey much to me, until I
U||   reached a passage where it described small punctured wounds on their
U||   throats. An idea struck me, and I looked up. “Well?” he said.
U||   “It is like poor Lucy’s.”
U||   “And what do you make of it?”
U||   “Simply that there is some cause in common. Whatever it was that
U||   injured her has injured them.” I did not quite understand his answer:—
U||   “That is true indirectly, but not directly.”
U||   “How do you mean, Professor?” I asked. I was a little inclined to take
