U||   despair about poor Lucy, had he looked more stern.
U||   “Tell me!” I said. “I can hazard no opinion. I do not know what to
U||   think, and I have no data on which to found a conjecture.”
U||   “Do you mean to tell me, friend John, that you have no suspicion as to
U||   what poor Lucy died of; not after all the hints given, not only by
U||   events, but by me?”
U||   “Of nervous prostration following on great loss or waste of blood.”
U||   “And how the blood lost or waste?” I shook my head. He stepped over and
U||   sat down beside me, and went on:—
U||   “You are clever man, friend John; you reason well, and your wit is
U||   bold; but you are too prejudiced. You do not let your eyes see nor your
U||   ears hear, and that which is outside your daily life is not of account
U||   to you. Do you not think that there are things which you cannot
U||   understand, and yet which are; that some people see things that others
U||   cannot? But there are things old and new which must not be contemplate
U||   by men’s eyes, because they know—or think they know—some things which
U||   other men have told them. Ah, it is the fault of our science that it
U||   wants to explain all; and if it explain not, then it says there is
