U||CHAPTER XV
U||DR. SEWARD’S DIARY—continued.
U||   FOR a while sheer anger mastered me; it was as if he had during her
U||   life struck Lucy on the face. I smote the table hard and rose up as I
U||   said to him:—
U||   “Dr. Van Helsing, are you mad?” He raised his head and looked at me,
U||   and somehow the tenderness of his face calmed me at once. “Would I
U||   were!” he said. “Madness were easy to bear compared with truth like
U||   this. Oh, my friend, why, think you, did I go so far round, why take so
U||   long to tell you so simple a thing? Was it because I hate you and have
U||   hated you all my life? Was it because I wished to give you pain? Was it
U||   that I wanted, now so late, revenge for that time when you saved my
U||   life, and from a fearful death? Ah no!”
U||   “Forgive me,” said I. He went on:—
U||   “My friend, it was because I wished to be gentle in the breaking to
U||   you, for I know you have loved that so sweet lady. But even yet I do
U||   not expect you to believe. It is so hard to accept at once any abstract
U||   truth, that we may doubt such to be possible when we have always
U||   believed the ‘no’ of it; it is more hard still to accept so sad a
U||   concrete truth, and of such a one as Miss Lucy. To-night I go to prove
U||   it. Dare you come with me?”
U||   This staggered me. A man does not like to prove such a truth; Byron
U||   excepted from the category, jealousy.
U||   “And prove the very truth he most abhorred.”
U||   He saw my hesitation, and spoke:—
U||   “The logic is simple, no madman’s logic this time, jumping from tussock
U||   to tussock in a misty bog. If it be not true, then proof will be
U||   relief; at worst it will not harm. If it be true! Ah, there is the
U||   dread; yet very dread should help my cause, for in it is some need of
U||   belief. Come, I tell you what I propose: first, that we go off now and
U||   see that child in the hospital. Dr. Vincent, of the North Hospital,
U||   where the papers say the child is, is friend of mine, and I think of
U||   yours since you were in class at Amsterdam. He will let two scientists
U||   see his case, if he will not let two friends. We shall tell him
U||   nothing, but only that we wish to learn. And then——”
U||   “And then?” He took a key from his pocket and held it up. “And then we
U||   spend the night, you and I, in the churchyard where Lucy lies. This is
U||   the key that lock the tomb. I had it from the coffin-man to give to
U||   Arthur.” My heart sank within me, for I felt that there was some
U||   fearful ordeal before us. I could do nothing, however, so I plucked up
U||   what heart I could and said that we had better hasten, as the afternoon
U||   was passing....
U||   We found the child awake. It had had a sleep and taken some food, and
U||   altogether was going on well. Dr. Vincent took the bandage from its
U||   throat, and showed us the punctures. There was no mistaking the
U||   similarity to those which had been on Lucy’s throat. They were smaller,
U||   and the edges looked fresher; that was all. We asked Vincent to what he
U||   attributed them, and he replied that it must have been a bite of some
U||   animal, perhaps a rat; but, for his own part, he was inclined to think
U||   that it was one of the bats which are so numerous on the northern
U||   heights of London. “Out of so many harmless ones,” he said, “there may
U||   be some wild specimen from the South of a more malignant species. Some
U||   sailor may have brought one home, and it managed to escape; or even
U||   from the Zoölogical Gardens a young one may have got loose, or one be
U||   bred there from a vampire. These things do occur, you know. Only ten
U||   days ago a wolf got out, and was, I believe, traced up in this
U||   direction. For a week after, the children were playing nothing but Red
U||   Riding Hood on the Heath and in every alley in the place until this
U||   ‘bloofer lady’ scare came along, since when it has been quite a
U||   gala-time with them. Even this poor little mite, when he woke up
U||   to-day, asked the nurse if he might go away. When she asked him why he
U||   wanted to go, he said he wanted to play with the ‘bloofer lady.’”
U||   “I hope,” said Van Helsing, “that when you are sending the child home
U||   you will caution its parents to keep strict watch over it. These
U||   fancies to stray are most dangerous; and if the child were to remain
U||   out another night, it would probably be fatal. But in any case I
U||   suppose you will not let it away for some days?”
U||   “Certainly not, not for a week at least; longer if the wound is not
U||   healed.”
U||   Our visit to the hospital took more time than we had reckoned on, and
U||   the sun had dipped before we came out. When Van Helsing saw how dark it
U||   was, he said:—
U||   “There is no hurry. It is more late than I thought. Come, let us seek
U||   somewhere that we may eat, and then we shall go on our way.”
U||   We dined at “Jack Straw’s Castle” along with a little crowd of
U||   bicyclists and others who were genially noisy. About ten o’clock we
U||   started from the inn. It was then very dark, and the scattered lamps
U||   made the darkness greater when we were once outside their individual
U||   radius. The Professor had evidently noted the road we were to go, for
U||   he went on unhesitatingly; but, as for me, I was in quite a mixup as to
U||   locality. As we went further, we met fewer and fewer people, till at
U||   last we were somewhat surprised when we met even the patrol of horse
U||   police going their usual suburban round. At last we reached the wall of
U||   the churchyard, which we climbed over. With some little difficulty—for
U||   it was very dark, and the whole place seemed so strange to us—we found
U||   the Westenra tomb. The Professor took the key, opened the creaky door,
U||   and standing back, politely, but quite unconsciously, motioned me to
U||   precede him. There was a delicious irony in the offer, in the
U||   courtliness of giving preference on such a ghastly occasion. My
U||   companion followed me quickly, and cautiously drew the door to, after
U||   carefully ascertaining that the lock was a falling, and not a spring,
U||   one. In the latter case we should have been in a bad plight. Then he
U||   fumbled in his bag, and taking out a matchbox and a piece of candle,
U||   proceeded to make a light. The tomb in the day-time, and when wreathed
U||   with fresh flowers, had looked grim and gruesome enough; but now, some
U||   days afterwards, when the flowers hung lank and dead, their whites
U||   turning to rust and their greens to browns; when the spider and the
U||   beetle had resumed their accustomed dominance; when time-discoloured
U||   stone, and dust-encrusted mortar, and rusty, dank iron, and tarnished
U||   brass, and clouded silver-plating gave back the feeble glimmer of a
U||   candle, the effect was more miserable and sordid than could have been
U||   imagined. It conveyed irresistibly the idea that life—animal life—was
U||   not the only thing which could pass away.
U||   Van Helsing went about his work systematically. Holding his candle so
U||   that he could read the coffin plates, and so holding it that the sperm
U||   dropped in white patches which congealed as they touched the metal, he
U||   made assurance of Lucy’s coffin. Another search in his bag, and he took
U||   out a turnscrew.
U||   “What are you going to do?” I asked.
U||   “To open the coffin. You shall yet be convinced.” Straightway he began
U||   taking out the screws, and finally lifted off the lid, showing the
U||   casing of lead beneath. The sight was almost too much for me. It seemed
U||   to be as much an affront to the dead as it would have been to have
U||   stripped off her clothing in her sleep whilst living; I actually took
U||   hold of his hand to stop him. He only said: “You shall see,” and again
U||   fumbling in his bag, took out a tiny fret-saw. Striking the turnscrew
U||   through the lead with a swift downward stab, which made me wince, he
U||   made a small hole, which was, however, big enough to admit the point of
U||   the saw. I had expected a rush of gas from the week-old corpse. We
U||   doctors, who have had to study our dangers, have to become accustomed
U||   to such things, and I drew back towards the door. But the Professor
U||   never stopped for a moment; he sawed down a couple of feet along one
U||   side of the lead coffin, and then across, and down the other side.
U||   Taking the edge of the loose flange, he bent it back towards the foot
U||   of the coffin, and holding up the candle into the aperture, motioned to
U||   me to look.
U||   I drew near and looked. The coffin was empty.
U||   It was certainly a surprise to me, and gave me a considerable shock,
U||   but Van Helsing was unmoved. He was now more sure than ever of his
U||   ground, and so emboldened to proceed in his task. “Are you satisfied
U||   now, friend John?” he asked.
U||   I felt all the dogged argumentativeness of my nature awake within me as
U||   I answered him:—
U||   “I am satisfied that Lucy’s body is not in that coffin; but that only
U||   proves one thing.”
U||   “And what is that, friend John?”
U||   “That it is not there.”
U||   “That is good logic,” he said, “so far as it goes. But how do you—how
U||   can you—account for it not being there?”
U||   “Perhaps a body-snatcher,” I suggested. “Some of the undertaker’s
U||   people may have stolen it.” I felt that I was speaking folly, and yet
U||   it was the only real cause which I could suggest. The Professor sighed.
U||   “Ah well!” he said, “we must have more proof. Come with me.”
U||   He put on the coffin-lid again, gathered up all his things and placed
U||   them in the bag, blew out the light, and placed the candle also in the
U||   bag. We opened the door, and went out. Behind us he closed the door and
U||   locked it. He handed me the key, saying: “Will you keep it? You had
U||   better be assured.” I laughed—it was not a very cheerful laugh, I am
U||   bound to say—as I motioned him to keep it. “A key is nothing,” I said;
U||   “there may be duplicates; and anyhow it is not difficult to pick a lock
U||   of that kind.” He said nothing, but put the key in his pocket. Then he
U||   told me to watch at one side of the churchyard whilst he would watch at
U||   the other. I took up my place behind a yew-tree, and I saw his dark
U||   figure move until the intervening headstones and trees hid it from my
U||   sight.
U||   It was a lonely vigil. Just after I had taken my place I heard a
U||   distant clock strike twelve, and in time came one and two. I was
U||   chilled and unnerved, and angry with the Professor for taking me on
U||   such an errand and with myself for coming. I was too cold and too
U||   sleepy to be keenly observant, and not sleepy enough to betray my trust
U||   so altogether I had a dreary, miserable time.
U||   Suddenly, as I turned round, I thought I saw something like a white
U||   streak, moving between two dark yew-trees at the side of the churchyard
U||   farthest from the tomb; at the same time a dark mass moved from the
U||   Professor’s side of the ground, and hurriedly went towards it. Then I
U||   too moved; but I had to go round headstones and railed-off tombs, and I
U||   stumbled over graves. The sky was overcast, and somewhere far off an
U||   early cock crew. A little way off, beyond a line of scattered
U||   juniper-trees, which marked the pathway to the church, a white, dim
U||   figure flitted in the direction of the tomb. The tomb itself was hidden
U||   by trees, and I could not see where the figure disappeared. I heard the
U||   rustle of actual movement where I had first seen the white figure, and
U||   coming over, found the Professor holding in his arms a tiny child. When
U||   he saw me he held it out to me, and said:—
U||   “Are you satisfied now?”
U||   “No,” I said, in a way that I felt was aggressive.
U||   “Do you not see the child?”
U||   “Yes, it is a child, but who brought it here? And is it wounded?” I
U||   asked.
U||   “We shall see,” said the Professor, and with one impulse we took our
U||   way out of the churchyard, he carrying the sleeping child.
U||   When we had got some little distance away, we went into a clump of
U||   trees, and struck a match, and looked at the child’s throat. It was
U||   without a scratch or scar of any kind.
U||   “Was I right?” I asked triumphantly.
U||   “We were just in time,” said the Professor thankfully.
U||   We had now to decide what we were to do with the child, and so
U||   consulted about it. If we were to take it to a police-station we should
U||   have to give some account of our movements during the night; at least,
U||   we should have had to make some statement as to how we had come to find
U||   the child. So finally we decided that we would take it to the Heath,
U||   and when we heard a policeman coming, would leave it where he could not
U||   fail to find it; we would then seek our way home as quickly as we
U||   could. All fell out well. At the edge of Hampstead Heath we heard a
U||   policeman’s heavy tramp, and laying the child on the pathway, we waited
U||   and watched until he saw it as he flashed his lantern to and fro. We
U||   heard his exclamation of astonishment, and then we went away silently.
U||   By good chance we got a cab near the “Spaniards,” and drove to town.
U||   I cannot sleep, so I make this entry. But I must try to get a few
U||   hours’ sleep, as Van Helsing is to call for me at noon. He insists that
U||   I shall go with him on another expedition.
U||   27 September.—It was two o’clock before we found a suitable opportunity
U||   for our attempt. The funeral held at noon was all completed, and the
U||   last stragglers of the mourners had taken themselves lazily away, when,
U||   looking carefully from behind a clump of alder-trees, we saw the sexton
U||   lock the gate after him. We knew then that we were safe till morning
U||   did we desire it; but the Professor told me that we should not want
U||   more than an hour at most. Again I felt that horrid sense of the
U||   reality of things, in which any effort of imagination seemed out of
U||   place; and I realised distinctly the perils of the law which we were
U||   incurring in our unhallowed work. Besides, I felt it was all so
U||   useless. Outrageous as it was to open a leaden coffin, to see if a
U||   woman dead nearly a week were really dead, it now seemed the height of
U||   folly to open the tomb again, when we knew, from the evidence of our
U||   own eyesight, that the coffin was empty. I shrugged my shoulders,
U||   however, and rested silent, for Van Helsing had a way of going on his
U||   own road, no matter who remonstrated. He took the key, opened the
U||   vault, and again courteously motioned me to precede. The place was not
U||   so gruesome as last night, but oh, how unutterably mean-looking when
U||   the sunshine streamed in. Van Helsing walked over to Lucy’s coffin, and
U||   I followed. He bent over and again forced back the leaden flange; and
U||   then a shock of surprise and dismay shot through me.
U||   There lay Lucy, seemingly just as we had seen her the night before her
U||   funeral. She was, if possible, more radiantly beautiful than ever; and
U||   I could not believe that she was dead. The lips were red, nay redder
U||   than before; and on the cheeks was a delicate bloom.
U||   “Is this a juggle?” I said to him.
U||   “Are you convinced now?” said the Professor in response, and as he
U||   spoke he put over his hand, and in a way that made me shudder, pulled
U||   back the dead lips and showed the white teeth.
U||   “See,” he went on, “see, they are even sharper than before. With this
U||   and this”—and he touched one of the canine teeth and that below it—“the
U||   little children can be bitten. Are you of belief now, friend John?”
U||   Once more, argumentative hostility woke within me. I could not accept
U||   such an overwhelming idea as he suggested; so, with an attempt to argue
U||   of which I was even at the moment ashamed, I said:—
U||   “She may have been placed here since last night.”
U||   “Indeed? That is so, and by whom?”
U||   “I do not know. Some one has done it.”
U||   “And yet she has been dead one week. Most peoples in that time would
U||   not look so.” I had no answer for this, so was silent. Van Helsing did
U||   not seem to notice my silence; at any rate, he showed neither chagrin
U||   nor triumph. He was looking intently at the face of the dead woman,
U||   raising the eyelids and looking at the eyes, and once more opening the
U||   lips and examining the teeth. Then he turned to me and said:—
U||   “Here, there is one thing which is different from all recorded; here is
U||   some dual life that is not as the common. She was bitten by the vampire
U||   when she was in a trance, sleep-walking—oh, you start; you do not know
U||   that, friend John, but you shall know it all later—and in trance could
U||   he best come to take more blood. In trance she died, and in trance she
U||   is Un-Dead, too. So it is that she differ from all other. Usually when
U||   the Un-Dead sleep at home”—as he spoke he made a comprehensive sweep of
U||   his arm to designate what to a vampire was “home”—“their face show what
U||   they are, but this so sweet that was when she not Un-Dead she go back
U||   to the nothings of the common dead. There is no malign there, see, and
U||   so it make hard that I must kill her in her sleep.” This turned my
U||   blood cold, and it began to dawn upon me that I was accepting Van
U||   Helsing’s theories; but if she were really dead, what was there of
U||   terror in the idea of killing her? He looked up at me, and evidently
U||   saw the change in my face, for he said almost joyously:—
U||   “Ah, you believe now?”
U||   I answered: “Do not press me too hard all at once. I am willing to
U||   accept. How will you do this bloody work?”
U||   “I shall cut off her head and fill her mouth with garlic, and I shall
U||   drive a stake through her body.” It made me shudder to think of so
U||   mutilating the body of the woman whom I had loved. And yet the feeling
U||   was not so strong as I had expected. I was, in fact, beginning to
U||   shudder at the presence of this being, this Un-Dead, as Van Helsing
U||   called it, and to loathe it. Is it possible that love is all
U||   subjective, or all objective?
U||   I waited a considerable time for Van Helsing to begin, but he stood as
U||   if wrapped in thought. Presently he closed the catch of his bag with a
U||   snap, and said:—
U||   “I have been thinking, and have made up my mind as to what is best. If
U||   I did simply follow my inclining I would do now, at this moment, what
U||   is to be done; but there are other things to follow, and things that
U||   are thousand times more difficult in that them we do not know. This is
U||   simple. She have yet no life taken, though that is of time; and to act
U||   now would be to take danger from her for ever. But then we may have to
U||   want Arthur, and how shall we tell him of this? If you, who saw the
U||   wounds on Lucy’s throat, and saw the wounds so similar on the child’s
U||   at the hospital; if you, who saw the coffin empty last night and full
U||   to-day with a woman who have not change only to be more rose and more
U||   beautiful in a whole week, after she die—if you know of this and know
U||   of the white figure last night that brought the child to the
U||   churchyard, and yet of your own senses you did not believe, how, then,
U||   can I expect Arthur, who know none of those things, to believe? He
U||   doubted me when I took him from her kiss when she was dying. I know he
U||   has forgiven me because in some mistaken idea I have done things that
U||   prevent him say good-bye as he ought; and he may think that in some
U||   more mistaken idea this woman was buried alive; and that in most
U||   mistake of all we have killed her. He will then argue back that it is
U||   we, mistaken ones, that have killed her by our ideas; and so he will be
U||   much unhappy always. Yet he never can be sure; and that is the worst of
U||   all. And he will sometimes think that she he loved was buried alive,
U||   and that will paint his dreams with horrors of what she must have
U||   suffered; and again, he will think that we may be right, and that his
U||   so beloved was, after all, an Un-Dead. No! I told him once, and since
U||   then I learn much. Now, since I know it is all true, a hundred thousand
U||   times more do I know that he must pass through the bitter waters to
U||   reach the sweet. He, poor fellow, must have one hour that will make the
U||   very face of heaven grow black to him; then we can act for good all
U||   round and send him peace. My mind is made up. Let us go. You return
U||   home for to-night to your asylum, and see that all be well. As for me,
U||   I shall spend the night here in this churchyard in my own way.
U||   To-morrow night you will come to me to the Berkeley Hotel at ten of the
U||   clock. I shall send for Arthur to come too, and also that so fine young
U||   man of America that gave his blood. Later we shall all have work to do.
U||   I come with you so far as Piccadilly and there dine, for I must be back
U||   here before the sun set.”
U||   So we locked the tomb and came away, and got over the wall of the
U||   churchyard, which was not much of a task, and drove back to Piccadilly.
