U||   “I write this in case anything should happen. I go alone to watch in
U||   that churchyard. It pleases me that the Un-Dead, Miss Lucy, shall not
U||   leave to-night, that so on the morrow night she may be more eager.
U||   Therefore I shall fix some things she like not—garlic and a
U||   crucifix—and so seal up the door of the tomb. She is young as Un-Dead,
U||   and will heed. Moreover, these are only to prevent her coming out; they
U||   may not prevail on her wanting to get in; for then the Un-Dead is
U||   desperate, and must find the line of least resistance, whatsoever it
U||   may be. I shall be at hand all the night from sunset till after the
U||   sunrise, and if there be aught that may be learned I shall learn it.
U||   For Miss Lucy or from her, I have no fear; but that other to whom is
U||   there that she is Un-Dead, he have now the power to seek her tomb and
U||   find shelter. He is cunning, as I know from Mr. Jonathan and from the
U||   way that all along he have fooled us when he played with us for Miss
