U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   28 September.—It is wonderful what a good night’s sleep will do for
U||   one. Yesterday I was almost willing to accept Van Helsing’s monstrous
U||   ideas; but now they seem to start out lurid before me as outrages on
U||   common sense. I have no doubt that he believes it all. I wonder if his
U||   mind can have become in any way unhinged. Surely there must be some
U||   rational explanation of all these mysterious things. Is it possible
U||   that the Professor can have done it himself? He is so abnormally clever
U||   that if he went off his head he would carry out his intent with regard
U||   to some fixed idea in a wonderful way. I am loath to think it, and
U||   indeed it would be almost as great a marvel as the other to find that
U||   Van Helsing was mad; but anyhow I shall watch him carefully. I may get
U||   some light on the mystery.
U||   29 September, morning..... Last night, at a little before ten o’clock,
U||   Arthur and Quincey came into Van Helsing’s room; he told us all that he
U||   wanted us to do, but especially addressing himself to Arthur, as if all
U||   our wills were centred in his. He began by saying that he hoped we
U||   would all come with him too, “for,” he said, “there is a grave duty to
U||   be done there. You were doubtless surprised at my letter?” This query
U||   was directly addressed to Lord Godalming.
U||   “I was. It rather upset me for a bit. There has been so much trouble
U||   around my house of late that I could do without any more. I have been
U||   curious, too, as to what you mean. Quincey and I talked it over; but
U||   the more we talked, the more puzzled we got, till now I can say for
U||   myself that I’m about up a tree as to any meaning about anything.”
U||   “Me too,” said Quincey Morris laconically.
U||   “Oh,” said the Professor, “then you are nearer the beginning, both of
U||   you, than friend John here, who has to go a long way back before he can
U||   even get so far as to begin.”
U||   It was evident that he recognised my return to my old doubting frame of
U||   mind without my saying a word. Then, turning to the other two, he said
U||   with intense gravity:—
U||   “I want your permission to do what I think good this night. It is, I
U||   know, much to ask; and when you know what it is I propose to do you
U||   will know, and only then, how much. Therefore may I ask that you
U||   promise me in the dark, so that afterwards, though you may be angry
U||   with me for a time—I must not disguise from myself the possibility that
U||   such may be—you shall not blame yourselves for anything.”
U||   “That’s frank anyhow,” broke in Quincey. “I’ll answer for the
U||   Professor. I don’t quite see his drift, but I swear he’s honest; and
U||   that’s good enough for me.”
U||   “I thank you, sir,” said Van Helsing proudly. “I have done myself the
U||   honour of counting you one trusting friend, and such endorsement is
U||   dear to me.” He held out a hand, which Quincey took.
U||   Then Arthur spoke out:—
U||   “Dr. Van Helsing, I don’t quite like to ‘buy a pig in a poke,’ as they
U||   say in Scotland, and if it be anything in which my honour as a
U||   gentleman or my faith as a Christian is concerned, I cannot make such a
U||   promise. If you can assure me that what you intend does not violate
U||   either of these two, then I give my consent at once; though for the
U||   life of me, I cannot understand what you are driving at.”
U||   “I accept your limitation,” said Van Helsing, “and all I ask of you is
U||   that if you feel it necessary to condemn any act of mine, you will
U||   first consider it well and be satisfied that it does not violate your
U||   reservations.”
U||   “Agreed!” said Arthur; “that is only fair. And now that the pourparlers
U||   are over, may I ask what it is we are to do?”
U||   “I want you to come with me, and to come in secret, to the churchyard
U||   at Kingstead.”
U||   Arthur’s face fell as he said in an amazed sort of way:—
U||   “Where poor Lucy is buried?” The Professor bowed. Arthur went on: “And
U||   when there?”
U||   “To enter the tomb!” Arthur stood up.
U||   “Professor, are you in earnest; or it is some monstrous joke? Pardon
U||   me, I see that you are in earnest.” He sat down again, but I could see
U||   that he sat firmly and proudly, as one who is on his dignity. There was
U||   silence until he asked again:—
U||   “And when in the tomb?”
U||   “To open the coffin.”
U||   “This is too much!” he said, angrily rising again. “I am willing to be
U||   patient in all things that are reasonable; but in this—this desecration
U||   of the grave—of one who——” He fairly choked with indignation. The
U||   Professor looked pityingly at him.
U||   “If I could spare you one pang, my poor friend,” he said, “God knows I
U||   would. But this night our feet must tread in thorny paths; or later,
U||   and for ever, the feet you love must walk in paths of flame!”
U||   Arthur looked up with set white face and said:—
U||   “Take care, sir, take care!”
U||   “Would it not be well to hear what I have to say?” said Van Helsing.
U||   “And then you will at least know the limit of my purpose. Shall I go
U||   on?”
U||   “That’s fair enough,” broke in Morris.
U||   After a pause Van Helsing went on, evidently with an effort:—
U||   “Miss Lucy is dead; is it not so? Yes! Then there can be no wrong to
U||   her. But if she be not dead——”
U||   Arthur jumped to his feet.
U||   “Good God!” he cried. “What do you mean? Has there been any mistake;
U||   has she been buried alive?” He groaned in anguish that not even hope
U||   could soften.
U||   “I did not say she was alive, my child; I did not think it. I go no
U||   further than to say that she might be Un-Dead.”
U||   “Un-Dead! Not alive! What do you mean? Is this all a nightmare, or what
U||   is it?”
U||   “There are mysteries which men can only guess at, which age by age they
U||   may solve only in part. Believe me, we are now on the verge of one. But
U||   I have not done. May I cut off the head of dead Miss Lucy?”
U||   “Heavens and earth, no!” cried Arthur in a storm of passion. “Not for
U||   the wide world will I consent to any mutilation of her dead body. Dr.
U||   Van Helsing, you try me too far. What have I done to you that you
U||   should torture me so? What did that poor, sweet girl do that you should
U||   want to cast such dishonour on her grave? Are you mad to speak such
