U||   from you will wipe away all this so sad hour, for I would do what a man
U||   can to save you from sorrow. Just think. For why should I give myself
U||   so much of labour and so much of sorrow? I have come here from my own
U||   land to do what I can of good; at the first to please my friend John,
U||   and then to help a sweet young lady, whom, too, I came to love. For
U||   her—I am ashamed to say so much, but I say it in kindness—I gave what
U||   you gave; the blood of my veins; I gave it, I, who was not, like you,
U||   her lover, but only her physician and her friend. I gave to her my
U||   nights and days—before death, after death; and if my death can do her
U||   good even now, when she is the dead Un-Dead, she shall have it freely.”
U||   He said this with a very grave, sweet pride, and Arthur was much
U||   affected by it. He took the old man’s hand and said in a broken voice:—
U||   “Oh, it is hard to think of it, and I cannot understand; but at least I
U||   shall go with you and wait.”
U||CHAPTER XVI
U||DR. SEWARD’S DIARY—continued
U||   IT was just a quarter before twelve o’clock when we got into the
U||   churchyard over the low wall. The night was dark with occasional gleams
U||   of moonlight between the rents of the heavy clouds that scudded across
U||   the sky. We all kept somehow close together, with Van Helsing slightly
U||   in front as he led the way. When we had come close to the tomb I looked
U||   well at Arthur, for I feared that the proximity to a place laden with
U||   so sorrowful a memory would upset him; but he bore himself well. I took
U||   it that the very mystery of the proceeding was in some way a
U||   counteractant to his grief. The Professor unlocked the door, and seeing
U||   a natural hesitation amongst us for various reasons, solved the
U||   difficulty by entering first himself. The rest of us followed, and he
U||   closed the door. He then lit a dark lantern and pointed to the coffin.
U||   Arthur stepped forward hesitatingly; Van Helsing said to me:—
U||   “You were with me here yesterday. Was the body of Miss Lucy in that
U||   coffin?”
U||   “It was.” The Professor turned to the rest saying:—
U||   “You hear; and yet there is no one who does not believe with me.” He
U||   took his screwdriver and again took off the lid of the coffin. Arthur
U||   looked on, very pale but silent; when the lid was removed he stepped
U||   forward. He evidently did not know that there was a leaden coffin, or,
U||   at any rate, had not thought of it. When he saw the rent in the lead,
U||   the blood rushed to his face for an instant, but as quickly fell away
U||   again, so that he remained of a ghastly whiteness; he was still silent.
U||   Van Helsing forced back the leaden flange, and we all looked in and
U||   recoiled.
U||   The coffin was empty!
U||   For several minutes no one spoke a word. The silence was broken by
U||   Quincey Morris:—
U||   “Professor, I answered for you. Your word is all I want. I wouldn’t ask
U||   such a thing ordinarily—I wouldn’t so dishonour you as to imply a
U||   doubt; but this is a mystery that goes beyond any honour or dishonour.
U||   Is this your doing?”
U||   “I swear to you by all that I hold sacred that I have not removed nor
U||   touched her. What happened was this: Two nights ago my friend Seward
U||   and I came here—with good purpose, believe me. I opened that coffin,
U||   which was then sealed up, and we found it, as now, empty. We then
U||   waited, and saw something white come through the trees. The next day we
U||   came here in day-time, and she lay there. Did she not, friend John?”
U||   “Yes.”
U||   “That night we were just in time. One more so small child was missing,
U||   and we find it, thank God, unharmed amongst the graves. Yesterday I
U||   came here before sundown, for at sundown the Un-Dead can move. I waited
U||   here all the night till the sun rose, but I saw nothing. It was most
U||   probable that it was because I had laid over the clamps of those doors
U||   garlic, which the Un-Dead cannot bear, and other things which they
U||   shun. Last night there was no exodus, so to-night before the sundown I
U||   took away my garlic and other things. And so it is we find this coffin
U||   empty. But bear with me. So far there is much that is strange. Wait you
U||   with me outside, unseen and unheard, and things much stranger are yet
U||   to be. So”—here he shut the dark slide of his lantern—“now to the
U||   outside.” He opened the door, and we filed out, he coming last and
U||   locking the door behind him.
U||   Oh! but it seemed fresh and pure in the night air after the terror of
U||   that vault. How sweet it was to see the clouds race by, and the passing
U||   gleams of the moonlight between the scudding clouds crossing and
U||   passing—like the gladness and sorrow of a man’s life; how sweet it was
U||   to breathe the fresh air, that had no taint of death and decay; how
U||   humanising to see the red lighting of the sky beyond the hill, and to
U||   hear far away the muffled roar that marks the life of a great city.
U||   Each in his own way was solemn and overcome. Arthur was silent, and
U||   was, I could see, striving to grasp the purpose and the inner meaning
U||   of the mystery. I was myself tolerably patient, and half inclined again
U||   to throw aside doubt and to accept Van Helsing’s conclusions. Quincey
U||   Morris was phlegmatic in the way of a man who accepts all things, and
U||   accepts them in the spirit of cool bravery, with hazard of all he has
U||   to stake. Not being able to smoke, he cut himself a good-sized plug of
U||   tobacco and began to chew. As to Van Helsing, he was employed in a
U||   definite way. First he took from his bag a mass of what looked like
U||   thin, wafer-like biscuit, which was carefully rolled up in a white
U||   napkin; next he took out a double-handful of some whitish stuff, like
U||   dough or putty. He crumbled the wafer up fine and worked it into the
U||   mass between his hands. This he then took, and rolling it into thin
U||   strips, began to lay them into the crevices between the door and its
U||   setting in the tomb. I was somewhat puzzled at this, and being close,
U||   asked him what it was that he was doing. Arthur and Quincey drew near
U||   also, as they too were curious. He answered:—
U||   “I am closing the tomb, so that the Un-Dead may not enter.”
U||   “And is that stuff you have put there going to do it?” asked Quincey.
U||   “Great Scott! Is this a game?”
U||   “It is.”
U||   “What is that which you are using?” This time the question was by
U||   Arthur. Van Helsing reverently lifted his hat as he answered:—
U||   “The Host. I brought it from Amsterdam. I have an Indulgence.” It was
U||   an answer that appalled the most sceptical of us, and we felt
U||   individually that in the presence of such earnest purpose as the
U||   Professor’s, a purpose which could thus use the to him most sacred of
U||   things, it was impossible to distrust. In respectful silence we took
U||   the places assigned to us close round the tomb, but hidden from the
U||   sight of any one approaching. I pitied the others, especially Arthur. I
U||   had myself been apprenticed by my former visits to this watching
U||   horror; and yet I, who had up to an hour ago repudiated the proofs,
U||   felt my heart sink within me. Never did tombs look so ghastly white;
U||   never did cypress, or yew, or juniper so seem the embodiment of
U||   funereal gloom; never did tree or grass wave or rustle so ominously;
U||   never did bough creak so mysteriously; and never did the far-away
U||   howling of dogs send such a woeful presage through the night.
U||   There was a long spell of silence, a big, aching void, and then from
U||   the Professor a keen “S-s-s-s!” He pointed; and far down the avenue of
U||   yews we saw a white figure advance—a dim white figure, which held
U||   something dark at its breast. The figure stopped, and at the moment a
U||   ray of moonlight fell upon the masses of driving clouds and showed in
U||   startling prominence a dark-haired woman, dressed in the cerements of
U||   the grave. We could not see the face, for it was bent down over what we
U||   saw to be a fair-haired child. There was a pause and a sharp little
U||   cry, such as a child gives in sleep, or a dog as it lies before the
U||   fire and dreams. We were starting forward, but the Professor’s warning
U||   hand, seen by us as he stood behind a yew-tree, kept us back; and then
U||   as we looked the white figure moved forwards again. It was now near
U||   enough for us to see clearly, and the moonlight still held. My own
U||   heart grew cold as ice, and I could hear the gasp of Arthur, as we
U||   recognised the features of Lucy Westenra. Lucy Westenra, but yet how
U||   changed. The sweetness was turned to adamantine, heartless cruelty, and
U||   the purity to voluptuous wantonness. Van Helsing stepped out, and,
U||   obedient to his gesture, we all advanced too; the four of us ranged in
U||   a line before the door of the tomb. Van Helsing raised his lantern and
U||   drew the slide; by the concentrated light that fell on Lucy’s face we
U||   could see that the lips were crimson with fresh blood, and that the
U||   stream had trickled over her chin and stained the purity of her lawn
U||   death-robe.
U||   We shuddered with horror. I could see by the tremulous light that even
U||   Van Helsing’s iron nerve had failed. Arthur was next to me, and if I
U||   had not seized his arm and held him up, he would have fallen.
U||   When Lucy—I call the thing that was before us Lucy because it bore her
U||   shape—saw us she drew back with an angry snarl, such as a cat gives
U||   when taken unawares; then her eyes ranged over us. Lucy’s eyes in form
U||   and colour; but Lucy’s eyes unclean and full of hell-fire, instead of
U||   the pure, gentle orbs we knew. At that moment the remnant of my love
U||   passed into hate and loathing; had she then to be killed, I could have
U||   done it with savage delight. As she looked, her eyes blazed with unholy
