U||   how it made me shudder to see it! With a careless motion, she flung to
U||   the ground, callous as a devil, the child that up to now she had
U||   clutched strenuously to her breast, growling over it as a dog growls
U||   over a bone. The child gave a sharp cry, and lay there moaning. There
U||   was a cold-bloodedness in the act which wrung a groan from Arthur; when
U||   she advanced to him with outstretched arms and a wanton smile he fell
U||   back and hid his face in his hands.
U||   She still advanced, however, and with a languorous, voluptuous grace,
U||   said:—
U||   “Come to me, Arthur. Leave these others and come to me. My arms are
U||   hungry for you. Come, and we can rest together. Come, my husband,
U||   come!”
U||   There was something diabolically sweet in her tones—something of the
U||   tingling of glass when struck—which rang through the brains even of us
U||   who heard the words addressed to another. As for Arthur, he seemed
U||   under a spell; moving his hands from his face, he opened wide his arms.
U||   She was leaping for them, when Van Helsing sprang forward and held
U||   between them his little golden crucifix. She recoiled from it, and,
U||   with a suddenly distorted face, full of rage, dashed past him as if to
U||   enter the tomb.
U||   When within a foot or two of the door, however, she stopped, as if
U||   arrested by some irresistible force. Then she turned, and her face was
U||   shown in the clear burst of moonlight and by the lamp, which had now no
U||   quiver from Van Helsing’s iron nerves. Never did I see such baffled
U||   malice on a face; and never, I trust, shall such ever be seen again by
U||   mortal eyes. The beautiful colour became livid, the eyes seemed to
U||   throw out sparks of hell-fire, the brows were wrinkled as though the
