U||   entry. Van Helsing broke the silence by asking Arthur:—
U||   “Answer me, oh my friend! Am I to proceed in my work?”
U||   Arthur threw himself on his knees, and hid his face in his hands, as he
U||   answered:—
U||   “Do as you will, friend; do as you will. There can be no horror like
U||   this ever any more;” and he groaned in spirit. Quincey and I
U||   simultaneously moved towards him, and took his arms. We could hear the
U||   click of the closing lantern as Van Helsing held it down; coming close
U||   to the tomb, he began to remove from the chinks some of the sacred
U||   emblem which he had placed there. We all looked on in horrified
U||   amazement as we saw, when he stood back, the woman, with a corporeal
U||   body as real at that moment as our own, pass in through the interstice
