U||   Arthur and Quincey came home with me, and we tried to cheer each other
U||   on the way. We had left the child in safety, and were tired; so we all
U||   slept with more or less reality of sleep.
U||   29 September, night.—A little before twelve o’clock we three—Arthur,
U||   Quincey Morris, and myself—called for the Professor. It was odd to
U||   notice that by common consent we had all put on black clothes. Of
U||   course, Arthur wore black, for he was in deep mourning, but the rest of
U||   us wore it by instinct. We got to the churchyard by half-past one, and
U||   strolled about, keeping out of official observation, so that when the
U||   gravediggers had completed their task and the sexton under the belief
U||   that every one had gone, had locked the gate, we had the place all to
U||   ourselves. Van Helsing, instead of his little black bag, had with him a
U||   long leather one, something like a cricketing bag; it was manifestly of
U||   fair weight.
U||   When we were alone and had heard the last of the footsteps die out up
U||   the road, we silently, and as if by ordered intention, followed the
U||   Professor to the tomb. He unlocked the door, and we entered, closing it
U||   behind us. Then he took from his bag the lantern, which he lit, and
U||   also two wax candles, which, when lighted, he stuck, by melting their
U||   own ends, on other coffins, so that they might give light sufficient to
U||   work by. When he again lifted the lid off Lucy’s coffin we all
U||   looked—Arthur trembling like an aspen—and saw that the body lay there
U||   in all its death-beauty. But there was no love in my own heart, nothing
U||   but loathing for the foul Thing which had taken Lucy’s shape without
U||   her soul. I could see even Arthur’s face grow hard as he looked.
U||   Presently he said to Van Helsing:—
U||   “Is this really Lucy’s body, or only a demon in her shape?”
U||   “It is her body, and yet not it. But wait a while, and you all see her
U||   as she was, and is.”
U||   She seemed like a nightmare of Lucy as she lay there; the pointed
U||   teeth, the bloodstained, voluptuous mouth—which it made one shudder to
U||   see—the whole carnal and unspiritual appearance, seeming like a
U||   devilish mockery of Lucy’s sweet purity. Van Helsing, with his usual
U||   methodicalness, began taking the various contents from his bag and
U||   placing them ready for use. First he took out a soldering iron and some
U||   plumbing solder, and then a small oil-lamp, which gave out, when lit in
U||   a corner of the tomb, gas which burned at fierce heat with a blue
U||   flame; then his operating knives, which he placed to hand; and last a
U||   round wooden stake, some two and a half or three inches thick and about
U||   three feet long. One end of it was hardened by charring in the fire,
