U||CHAPTER XVII
U||DR. SEWARD’S DIARY—continued
U||   WHEN we arrived at the Berkeley Hotel, Van Helsing found a telegram
U||   waiting for him:—
U||   “Am coming up by train. Jonathan at Whitby. Important news.—Mina
U||   Harker.”
U||   The Professor was delighted. “Ah, that wonderful Madam Mina,” he said,
U||   “pearl among women! She arrive, but I cannot stay. She must go to your
U||   house, friend John. You must meet her at the station. Telegraph her en
U||   route, so that she may be prepared.”
U||   When the wire was despatched he had a cup of tea; over it he told me of
U||   a diary kept by Jonathan Harker when abroad, and gave me a typewritten
U||   copy of it, as also of Mrs. Harker’s diary at Whitby. “Take these,” he
U||   said, “and study them well. When I have returned you will be master of
U||   all the facts, and we can then better enter on our inquisition. Keep
U||   them safe, for there is in them much of treasure. You will need all
U||   your faith, even you who have had such an experience as that of to-day.
U||   What is here told,” he laid his hand heavily and gravely on the packet
U||   of papers as he spoke, “may be the beginning of the end to you and me
U||   and many another; or it may sound the knell of the Un-Dead who walk the
U||   earth. Read all, I pray you, with the open mind; and if you can add in
U||   any way to the story here told do so, for it is all-important. You have
U||   kept diary of all these so strange things; is it not so? Yes! Then we
U||   shall go through all these together when we meet.” He then made ready
U||   for his departure, and shortly after drove off to Liverpool Street. I
U||   took my way to Paddington, where I arrived about fifteen minutes before
U||   the train came in.
U||   The crowd melted away, after the bustling fashion common to arrival
U||   platforms; and I was beginning to feel uneasy, lest I might miss my
U||   guest, when a sweet-faced, dainty-looking girl stepped up to me, and,
U||   after a quick glance, said: “Dr. Seward, is it not?”
U||   “And you are Mrs. Harker!” I answered at once; whereupon she held out
U||   her hand.
U||   “I knew you from the description of poor dear Lucy; but——” She stopped
U||   suddenly, and a quick blush overspread her face.
U||   The blush that rose to my own cheeks somehow set us both at ease, for
U||   it was a tacit answer to her own. I got her luggage, which included a
U||   typewriter, and we took the Underground to Fenchurch Street, after I
U||   had sent a wire to my housekeeper to have a sitting-room and bedroom
U||   prepared at once for Mrs. Harker.
U||   In due time we arrived. She knew, of course, that the place was a
U||   lunatic asylum, but I could see that she was unable to repress a
U||   shudder when we entered.
U||   She told me that, if she might, she would come presently to my study,
U||   as she had much to say. So here I am finishing my entry in my
U||   phonograph diary whilst I await her. As yet I have not had the chance
U||   of looking at the papers which Van Helsing left with me, though they
U||   lie open before me. I must get her interested in something, so that I
U||   may have an opportunity of reading them. She does not know how precious
U||   time is, or what a task we have in hand. I must be careful not to
U||   frighten her. Here she is!
U||   Mina Harker’s Journal.
U||   29 September.—After I had tidied myself, I went down to Dr. Seward’s
U||   study. At the door I paused a moment, for I thought I heard him talking
U||   with some one. As, however, he had pressed me to be quick, I knocked at
U||   the door, and on his calling out, “Come in,” I entered.
U||   To my intense surprise, there was no one with him. He was quite alone,
U||   and on the table opposite him was what I knew at once from the
U||   description to be a phonograph. I had never seen one, and was much
U||   interested.
U||   “I hope I did not keep you waiting,” I said; “but I stayed at the door
U||   as I heard you talking, and thought there was some one with you.”
U||   “Oh,” he replied with a smile, “I was only entering my diary.”
U||   “Your diary?” I asked him in surprise.
U||   “Yes,” he answered. “I keep it in this.” As he spoke he laid his hand
U||   on the phonograph. I felt quite excited over it, and blurted out:—
U||   “Why, this beats even shorthand! May I hear it say something?”
U||   “Certainly,” he replied with alacrity, and stood up to put it in train
U||   for speaking. Then he paused, and a troubled look overspread his face.
U||   “The fact is,” he began awkwardly, “I only keep my diary in it; and as
U||   it is entirely—almost entirely—about my cases, it may be awkward—that
U||   is, I mean——” He stopped, and I tried to help him out of his
U||   embarrassment:—
U||   “You helped to attend dear Lucy at the end. Let me hear how she died;
U||   for all that I know of her, I shall be very grateful. She was very,
U||   very dear to me.”
U||   To my surprise, he answered, with a horrorstruck look in his face:—
U||   “Tell you of her death? Not for the wide world!”
U||   “Why not?” I asked, for some grave, terrible feeling was coming over
U||   me. Again he paused, and I could see that he was trying to invent an
U||   excuse. At length he stammered out:—
U||   “You see, I do not know how to pick out any particular part of the
U||   diary.” Even while he was speaking an idea dawned upon him, and he said
U||   with unconscious simplicity, in a different voice, and with the naïveté
U||   of a child: “That’s quite true, upon my honour. Honest Indian!” I could
U||   not but smile, at which he grimaced. “I gave myself away that time!” he
U||   said. “But do you know that, although I have kept the diary for months
U||   past, it never once struck me how I was going to find any particular
U||   part of it in case I wanted to look it up?” By this time my mind was
U||   made up that the diary of a doctor who attended Lucy might have
U||   something to add to the sum of our knowledge of that terrible Being,
U||   and I said boldly:—
U||   “Then, Dr. Seward, you had better let me copy it out for you on my
U||   typewriter.” He grew to a positively deathly pallor as he said:—
U||   “No! no! no! For all the world, I wouldn’t let you know that terrible
U||   story!”
U||   Then it was terrible; my intuition was right! For a moment I thought,
U||   and as my eyes ranged the room, unconsciously looking for something or
U||   some opportunity to aid me, they lit on a great batch of typewriting on
U||   the table. His eyes caught the look in mine, and, without his thinking,
U||   followed their direction. As they saw the parcel he realised my
U||   meaning.
U||   “You do not know me,” I said. “When you have read those papers—my own
U||   diary and my husband’s also, which I have typed—you will know me
U||   better. I have not faltered in giving every thought of my own heart in
U||   this cause; but, of course, you do not know me—yet; and I must not
U||   expect you to trust me so far.”
U||   He is certainly a man of noble nature; poor dear Lucy was right about
U||   him. He stood up and opened a large drawer, in which were arranged in
U||   order a number of hollow cylinders of metal covered with dark wax, and
U||   said:—
U||   “You are quite right. I did not trust you because I did not know you.
U||   But I know you now; and let me say that I should have known you long
U||   ago. I know that Lucy told you of me; she told me of you too. May I
U||   make the only atonement in my power? Take the cylinders and hear
U||   them—the first half-dozen of them are personal to me, and they will not
U||   horrify you; then you will know me better. Dinner will by then be
U||   ready. In the meantime I shall read over some of these documents, and
U||   shall be better able to understand certain things.” He carried the
U||   phonograph himself up to my sitting-room and adjusted it for me. Now I
U||   shall learn something pleasant, I am sure; for it will tell me the
U||   other side of a true love episode of which I know one side already....
U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   29 September.—I was so absorbed in that wonderful diary of Jonathan
U||   Harker and that other of his wife that I let the time run on without
U||   thinking. Mrs. Harker was not down when the maid came to announce
U||   dinner, so I said: “She is possibly tired; let dinner wait an hour,”
U||   and I went on with my work. I had just finished Mrs. Harker’s diary,
U||   when she came in. She looked sweetly pretty, but very sad, and her eyes
U||   were flushed with crying. This somehow moved me much. Of late I have
U||   had cause for tears, God knows! but the relief of them was denied me;
U||   and now the sight of those sweet eyes, brightened with recent tears,
U||   went straight to my heart. So I said as gently as I could:—
U||   “I greatly fear I have distressed you.”
U||   “Oh, no, not distressed me,” she replied, “but I have been more touched
U||   than I can say by your grief. That is a wonderful machine, but it is
U||   cruelly true. It told me, in its very tones, the anguish of your heart.
U||   It was like a soul crying out to Almighty God. No one must hear them
U||   spoken ever again! See, I have tried to be useful. I have copied out
U||   the words on my typewriter, and none other need now hear your heart
U||   beat, as I did.”
U||   “No one need ever know, shall ever know,” I said in a low voice. She
U||   laid her hand on mine and said very gravely:—
U||   “Ah, but they must!”
U||   “Must! But why?” I asked.
U||   “Because it is a part of the terrible story, a part of poor dear Lucy’s
U||   death and all that led to it; because in the struggle which we have
U||   before us to rid the earth of this terrible monster we must have all
U||   the knowledge and all the help which we can get. I think that the
U||   cylinders which you gave me contained more than you intended me to
U||   know; but I can see that there are in your record many lights to this
U||   dark mystery. You will let me help, will you not? I know all up to a
U||   certain point; and I see already, though your diary only took me to 7
U||   September, how poor Lucy was beset, and how her terrible doom was being
U||   wrought out. Jonathan and I have been working day and night since
U||   Professor Van Helsing saw us. He is gone to Whitby to get more
U||   information, and he will be here to-morrow to help us. We need have no
U||   secrets amongst us; working together and with absolute trust, we can
U||   surely be stronger than if some of us were in the dark.” She looked at
U||   me so appealingly, and at the same time manifested such courage and
U||   resolution in her bearing, that I gave in at once to her wishes. “You
U||   shall,” I said, “do as you like in the matter. God forgive me if I do
U||   wrong! There are terrible things yet to learn of; but if you have so
U||   far travelled on the road to poor Lucy’s death, you will not be
U||   content, I know, to remain in the dark. Nay, the end—the very end—may
U||   give you a gleam of peace. Come, there is dinner. We must keep one
U||   another strong for what is before us; we have a cruel and dreadful
U||   task. When you have eaten you shall learn the rest, and I shall answer
U||   any questions you ask—if there be anything which you do not understand,
U||   though it was apparent to us who were present.”
U||   Mina Harker’s Journal.
U||   29 September.—After dinner I came with Dr. Seward to his study. He
U||   brought back the phonograph from my room, and I took my typewriter. He
U||   placed me in a comfortable chair, and arranged the phonograph so that I
U||   could touch it without getting up, and showed me how to stop it in case
U||   I should want to pause. Then he very thoughtfully took a chair, with
U||   his back to me, so that I might be as free as possible, and began to
U||   read. I put the forked metal to my ears and listened.
U||   When the terrible story of Lucy’s death, and—and all that followed, was
U||   done, I lay back in my chair powerless. Fortunately I am not of a
U||   fainting disposition. When Dr. Seward saw me he jumped up with a
U||   horrified exclamation, and hurriedly taking a case-bottle from a
U||   cupboard, gave me some brandy, which in a few minutes somewhat restored
U||   me. My brain was all in a whirl, and only that there came through all
U||   the multitude of horrors, the holy ray of light that my dear, dear Lucy
U||   was at last at peace, I do not think I could have borne it without
U||   making a scene. It is all so wild, and mysterious, and strange that if
U||   I had not known Jonathan’s experience in Transylvania I could not have
U||   believed. As it was, I didn’t know what to believe, and so got out of
U||   my difficulty by attending to something else. I took the cover off my
U||   typewriter, and said to Dr. Seward:—
U||   “Let me write this all out now. We must be ready for Dr. Van Helsing
U||   when he comes. I have sent a telegram to Jonathan to come on here when
U||   he arrives in London from Whitby. In this matter dates are everything,
U||   and I think that if we get all our material ready, and have every item
U||   put in chronological order, we shall have done much. You tell me that
U||   Lord Godalming and Mr. Morris are coming too. Let us be able to tell
U||   him when they come.” He accordingly set the phonograph at a slow pace,
U||   and I began to typewrite from the beginning of the seventh cylinder. I
U||   used manifold, and so took three copies of the diary, just as I had
U||   done with all the rest. It was late when I got through, but Dr. Seward
U||   went about his work of going his round of the patients; when he had
U||   finished he came back and sat near me, reading, so that I did not feel
U||   too lonely whilst I worked. How good and thoughtful he is; the world
U||   seems full of good men—even if there are monsters in it. Before I left
U||   him I remembered what Jonathan put in his diary of the Professor’s
U||   perturbation at reading something in an evening paper at the station at
U||   Exeter; so, seeing that Dr. Seward keeps his newspapers, I borrowed the
U||   files of “The Westminster Gazette” and “The Pall Mall Gazette,” and
U||   took them to my room. I remember how much “The Dailygraph” and “The
U||   Whitby Gazette,” of which I had made cuttings, helped us to understand
U||   the terrible events at Whitby when Count Dracula landed, so I shall
U||   look through the evening papers since then, and perhaps I shall get
U||   some new light. I am not sleepy, and the work will help to keep me
U||   quiet.
U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   30 September.—Mr. Harker arrived at nine o’clock. He had got his wife’s
U||   wire just before starting. He is uncommonly clever, if one can judge
U||   from his face, and full of energy. If this journal be true—and judging
U||   by one’s own wonderful experiences, it must be—he is also a man of
U||   great nerve. That going down to the vault a second time was a
U||   remarkable piece of daring. After reading his account of it I was
U||   prepared to meet a good specimen of manhood, but hardly the quiet,
U||   business-like gentleman who came here to-day.
U||   Later.—After lunch Harker and his wife went back to their own room, and
U||   as I passed a while ago I heard the click of the typewriter. They are
U||   hard at it. Mrs. Harker says that they are knitting together in
U||   chronological order every scrap of evidence they have. Harker has got
U||   the letters between the consignee of the boxes at Whitby and the
U||   carriers in London who took charge of them. He is now reading his
U||   wife’s typescript of my diary. I wonder what they make out of it. Here
U||   it is....
U||   Strange that it never struck me that the very next house might be the
U||   Count’s hiding-place! Goodness knows that we had enough clues from the
U||   conduct of the patient Renfield! The bundle of letters relating to the
U||   purchase of the house were with the typescript. Oh, if we had only had
U||   them earlier we might have saved poor Lucy! Stop; that way madness
U||   lies! Harker has gone back, and is again collating his material. He
U||   says that by dinner-time they will be able to show a whole connected
U||   narrative. He thinks that in the meantime I should see Renfield, as
U||   hitherto he has been a sort of index to the coming and going of the
U||   Count. I hardly see this yet, but when I get at the dates I suppose I
U||   shall. What a good thing that Mrs. Harker put my cylinders into type!
U||   We never could have found the dates otherwise....
U||   I found Renfield sitting placidly in his room with his hands folded,
U||   smiling benignly. At the moment he seemed as sane as any one I ever
U||   saw. I sat down and talked with him on a lot of subjects, all of which
U||   he treated naturally. He then, of his own accord, spoke of going home,
U||   a subject he has never mentioned to my knowledge during his sojourn
U||   here. In fact, he spoke quite confidently of getting his discharge at
U||   once. I believe that, had I not had the chat with Harker and read the
U||   letters and the dates of his outbursts, I should have been prepared to
U||   sign for him after a brief time of observation. As it is, I am darkly
U||   suspicious. All those outbreaks were in some way linked with the
U||   proximity of the Count. What then does this absolute content mean? Can
U||   it be that his instinct is satisfied as to the vampire’s ultimate
U||   triumph? Stay; he is himself zoöphagous, and in his wild ravings
U||   outside the chapel door of the deserted house he always spoke of
U||   “master.” This all seems confirmation of our idea. However, after a
U||   while I came away; my friend is just a little too sane at present to
U||   make it safe to probe him too deep with questions. He might begin to
U||   think, and then—! So I came away. I mistrust these quiet moods of his;
U||   so I have given the attendant a hint to look closely after him, and to
U||   have a strait-waistcoat ready in case of need.
U||   Jonathan Harker’s Journal.
U||   29 September, in train to London.—When I received Mr. Billington’s
U||   courteous message that he would give me any information in his power I
U||   thought it best to go down to Whitby and make, on the spot, such
U||   inquiries as I wanted. It was now my object to trace that horrid cargo
U||   of the Count’s to its place in London. Later, we may be able to deal
U||   with it. Billington junior, a nice lad, met me at the station, and
U||   brought me to his father’s house, where they had decided that I must
U||   stay the night. They are hospitable, with true Yorkshire hospitality:
U||   give a guest everything, and leave him free to do as he likes. They all
U||   knew that I was busy, and that my stay was short, and Mr. Billington
U||   had ready in his office all the papers concerning the consignment of
U||   boxes. It gave me almost a turn to see again one of the letters which I
U||   had seen on the Count’s table before I knew of his diabolical plans.
U||   Everything had been carefully thought out, and done systematically and
U||   with precision. He seemed to have been prepared for every obstacle
U||   which might be placed by accident in the way of his intentions being
U||   carried out. To use an Americanism, he had “taken no chances,” and the
U||   absolute accuracy with which his instructions were fulfilled, was
U||   simply the logical result of his care. I saw the invoice, and took note
U||   of it: “Fifty cases of common earth, to be used for experimental
U||   purposes.” Also the copy of letter to Carter Paterson, and their reply;
U||   of both of these I got copies. This was all the information Mr.
U||   Billington could give me, so I went down to the port and saw the
U||   coastguards, the Customs officers and the harbour-master. They had all
U||   something to say of the strange entry of the ship, which is already
U||   taking its place in local tradition; but no one could add to the simple
U||   description “Fifty cases of common earth.” I then saw the
U||   station-master, who kindly put me in communication with the men who had
U||   actually received the boxes. Their tally was exact with the list, and
U||   they had nothing to add except that the boxes were “main and mortal
U||   heavy,” and that shifting them was dry work. One of them added that it
U||   was hard lines that there wasn’t any gentleman “such-like as yourself,
U||   squire,” to show some sort of appreciation of their efforts in a liquid
U||   form; another put in a rider that the thirst then generated was such
U||   that even the time which had elapsed had not completely allayed it.
U||   Needless to add, I took care before leaving to lift, for ever and
U||   adequately, this source of reproach.
U||   30 September.—The station-master was good enough to give me a line to
U||   his old companion the station-master at King’s Cross, so that when I
U||   arrived there in the morning I was able to ask him about the arrival of
U||   the boxes. He, too, put me at once in communication with the proper
U||   officials, and I saw that their tally was correct with the original
U||   invoice. The opportunities of acquiring an abnormal thirst had been
U||   here limited; a noble use of them had, however, been made, and again I
U||   was compelled to deal with the result in an ex post facto manner.
U||   From thence I went on to Carter Paterson’s central office, where I met
U||   with the utmost courtesy. They looked up the transaction in their
U||   day-book and letter-book, and at once telephoned to their King’s Cross
U||   office for more details. By good fortune, the men who did the teaming
U||   were waiting for work, and the official at once sent them over, sending
U||   also by one of them the way-bill and all the papers connected with the
U||   delivery of the boxes at Carfax. Here again I found the tally agreeing
U||   exactly; the carriers’ men were able to supplement the paucity of the
U||   written words with a few details. These were, I shortly found,
U||   connected almost solely with the dusty nature of the job, and of the
U||   consequent thirst engendered in the operators. On my affording an
U||   opportunity, through the medium of the currency of the realm, of the
U||   allaying, at a later period, this beneficial evil, one of the men
U||   remarked:—
U||   “That ’ere ’ouse, guv’nor, is the rummiest I ever was in. Blyme! but it
U||   ain’t been touched sence a hundred years. There was dust that thick in
U||   the place that you might have slep’ on it without ’urtin’ of yer bones;
U||   an’ the place was that neglected that yer might ’ave smelled ole
U||   Jerusalem in it. But the ole chapel—that took the cike, that did! Me
U||   and my mate, we thort we wouldn’t never git out quick enough. Lor’, I
U||   wouldn’t take less nor a quid a moment to stay there arter dark.”
U||   Having been in the house, I could well believe him; but if he knew what
U||   I know, he would, I think, have raised his terms.
U||   Of one thing I am now satisfied: that all the boxes which arrived at
U||   Whitby from Varna in the Demeter were safely deposited in the old
U||   chapel at Carfax. There should be fifty of them there, unless any have
U||   since been removed—as from Dr. Seward’s diary I fear.
U||   I shall try to see the carter who took away the boxes from Carfax when
U||   Renfield attacked them. By following up this clue we may learn a good
U||   deal.
U||   Later.—Mina and I have worked all day, and we have put all the papers
U||   into order.
U||   Mina Harker’s Journal
U||   30 September.—I am so glad that I hardly know how to contain myself. It
U||   is, I suppose, the reaction from the haunting fear which I have had:
U||   that this terrible affair and the reopening of his old wound might act
U||   detrimentally on Jonathan. I saw him leave for Whitby with as brave a
U||   face as I could, but I was sick with apprehension. The effort has,
U||   however, done him good. He was never so resolute, never so strong,
U||   never so full of volcanic energy, as at present. It is just as that
U||   dear, good Professor Van Helsing said: he is true grit, and he improves
U||   under strain that would kill a weaker nature. He came back full of life
U||   and hope and determination; we have got everything in order for
U||   to-night. I feel myself quite wild with excitement. I suppose one ought
U||   to pity any thing so hunted as is the Count. That is just it: this
U||   Thing is not human—not even beast. To read Dr. Seward’s account of poor
U||   Lucy’s death, and what followed, is enough to dry up the springs of
U||   pity in one’s heart.
U||   Later.—Lord Godalming and Mr. Morris arrived earlier than we expected.
U||   Dr. Seward was out on business, and had taken Jonathan with him, so I
U||   had to see them. It was to me a painful meeting, for it brought back
U||   all poor dear Lucy’s hopes of only a few months ago. Of course they had
U||   heard Lucy speak of me, and it seemed that Dr. Van Helsing, too, has
U||   been quite “blowing my trumpet,” as Mr. Morris expressed it. Poor
U||   fellows, neither of them is aware that I know all about the proposals
U||   they made to Lucy. They did not quite know what to say or do, as they
U||   were ignorant of the amount of my knowledge; so they had to keep on
U||   neutral subjects. However, I thought the matter over, and came to the
U||   conclusion that the best thing I could do would be to post them in
U||   affairs right up to date. I knew from Dr. Seward’s diary that they had
U||   been at Lucy’s death—her real death—and that I need not fear to betray
U||   any secret before the time. So I told them, as well as I could, that I
U||   had read all the papers and diaries, and that my husband and I, having
U||   typewritten them, had just finished putting them in order. I gave them
U||   each a copy to read in the library. When Lord Godalming got his and
U||   turned it over—it does make a pretty good pile—he said:—
U||   “Did you write all this, Mrs. Harker?”
U||   I nodded, and he went on:—
U||   “I don’t quite see the drift of it; but you people are all so good and
U||   kind, and have been working so earnestly and so energetically, that all
U||   I can do is to accept your ideas blindfold and try to help you. I have
U||   had one lesson already in accepting facts that should make a man humble
U||   to the last hour of his life. Besides, I know you loved my poor Lucy—”
U||   Here he turned away and covered his face with his hands. I could hear
U||   the tears in his voice. Mr. Morris, with instinctive delicacy, just
U||   laid a hand for a moment on his shoulder, and then walked quietly out
U||   of the room. I suppose there is something in woman’s nature that makes
U||   a man free to break down before her and express his feelings on the
U||   tender or emotional side without feeling it derogatory to his manhood;
U||   for when Lord Godalming found himself alone with me he sat down on the
U||   sofa and gave way utterly and openly. I sat down beside him and took
U||   his hand. I hope he didn’t think it forward of me, and that if he ever
U||   thinks of it afterwards he never will have such a thought. There I
U||   wrong him; I know he never will—he is too true a gentleman. I said to
U||   him, for I could see that his heart was breaking:—
U||   “I loved dear Lucy, and I know what she was to you, and what you were
U||   to her. She and I were like sisters; and now she is gone, will you not
U||   let me be like a sister to you in your trouble? I know what sorrows you
U||   have had, though I cannot measure the depth of them. If sympathy and
U||   pity can help in your affliction, won’t you let me be of some little
U||   service—for Lucy’s sake?”
U||   In an instant the poor dear fellow was overwhelmed with grief. It
U||   seemed to me that all that he had of late been suffering in silence
U||   found a vent at once. He grew quite hysterical, and raising his open
U||   hands, beat his palms together in a perfect agony of grief. He stood up
U||   and then sat down again, and the tears rained down his cheeks. I felt
U||   an infinite pity for him, and opened my arms unthinkingly. With a sob
U||   he laid his head on my shoulder and cried like a wearied child, whilst
U||   he shook with emotion.
U||   We women have something of the mother in us that makes us rise above
U||   smaller matters when the mother-spirit is invoked; I felt this big
U||   sorrowing man’s head resting on me, as though it were that of the baby
U||   that some day may lie on my bosom, and I stroked his hair as though he
U||   were my own child. I never thought at the time how strange it all was.
U||   After a little bit his sobs ceased, and he raised himself with an
U||   apology, though he made no disguise of his emotion. He told me that for
U||   days and nights past—weary days and sleepless nights—he had been unable
U||   to speak with any one, as a man must speak in his time of sorrow. There
U||   was no woman whose sympathy could be given to him, or with whom, owing
U||   to the terrible circumstance with which his sorrow was surrounded, he
U||   could speak freely. “I know now how I suffered,” he said, as he dried
U||   his eyes, “but I do not know even yet—and none other can ever know—how
U||   much your sweet sympathy has been to me to-day. I shall know better in
U||   time; and believe me that, though I am not ungrateful now, my gratitude
U||   will grow with my understanding. You will let me be like a brother,
U||   will you not, for all our lives—for dear Lucy’s sake?”
U||   “For dear Lucy’s sake,” I said as we clasped hands. “Ay, and for your
U||   own sake,” he added, “for if a man’s esteem and gratitude are ever
U||   worth the winning, you have won mine to-day. If ever the future should
U||   bring to you a time when you need a man’s help, believe me, you will
U||   not call in vain. God grant that no such time may ever come to you to
U||   break the sunshine of your life; but if it should ever come, promise me
U||   that you will let me know.” He was so earnest, and his sorrow was so
U||   fresh, that I felt it would comfort him, so I said:—
U||   “I promise.”
U||   As I came along the corridor I saw Mr. Morris looking out of a window.
U||   He turned as he heard my footsteps. “How is Art?” he said. Then
U||   noticing my red eyes, he went on: “Ah, I see you have been comforting
U||   him. Poor old fellow! he needs it. No one but a woman can help a man
U||   when he is in trouble of the heart; and he had no one to comfort him.”
U||   He bore his own trouble so bravely that my heart bled for him. I saw
U||   the manuscript in his hand, and I knew that when he read it he would
U||   realise how much I knew; so I said to him:—
U||   “I wish I could comfort all who suffer from the heart. Will you let me
U||   be your friend, and will you come to me for comfort if you need it? You
U||   will know, later on, why I speak.” He saw that I was in earnest, and
U||   stooping, took my hand, and raising it to his lips, kissed it. It
U||   seemed but poor comfort to so brave and unselfish a soul, and
U||   impulsively I bent over and kissed him. The tears rose in his eyes, and
U||   there was a momentary choking in his throat; he said quite calmly:—
U||   “Little girl, you will never regret that true-hearted kindness, so long
U||   as ever you live!” Then he went into the study to his friend.
U||   “Little girl!”—the very words he had used to Lucy, and oh, but he
U||   proved himself a friend!
U||CHAPTER XVIII
U||DR. SEWARD’S DIARY
U||   30 September.—I got home at five o’clock, and found that Godalming and
U||   Morris had not only arrived, but had already studied the transcript of
U||   the various diaries and letters which Harker and his wonderful wife had
U||   made and arranged. Harker had not yet returned from his visit to the
U||   carriers’ men, of whom Dr. Hennessey had written to me. Mrs. Harker
U||   gave us a cup of tea, and I can honestly say that, for the first time
U||   since I have lived in it, this old house seemed like home. When we had
U||   finished, Mrs. Harker said:—
U||   “Dr. Seward, may I ask a favour? I want to see your patient, Mr.
U||   Renfield. Do let me see him. What you have said of him in your diary
U||   interests me so much!” She looked so appealing and so pretty that I
U||   could not refuse her, and there was no possible reason why I should; so
U||   I took her with me. When I went into the room, I told the man that a
U||   lady would like to see him; to which he simply answered: “Why?”
U||   “She is going through the house, and wants to see every one in it,” I
U||   answered. “Oh, very well,” he said; “let her come in, by all means; but
U||   just wait a minute till I tidy up the place.” His method of tidying was
U||   peculiar: he simply swallowed all the flies and spiders in the boxes
U||   before I could stop him. It was quite evident that he feared, or was
U||   jealous of, some interference. When he had got through his disgusting
U||   task, he said cheerfully: “Let the lady come in,” and sat down on the
U||   edge of his bed with his head down, but with his eyelids raised so that
U||   he could see her as she entered. For a moment I thought that he might
U||   have some homicidal intent; I remembered how quiet he had been just
U||   before he attacked me in my own study, and I took care to stand where I
U||   could seize him at once if he attempted to make a spring at her. She
U||   came into the room with an easy gracefulness which would at once
U||   command the respect of any lunatic—for easiness is one of the qualities
U||   mad people most respect. She walked over to him, smiling pleasantly,
U||   and held out her hand.
U||   “Good-evening, Mr. Renfield,” said she. “You see, I know you, for Dr.
U||   Seward has told me of you.” He made no immediate reply, but eyed her
U||   all over intently with a set frown on his face. This look gave way to
U||   one of wonder, which merged in doubt; then, to my intense astonishment,
U||   he said:—
U||   “You’re not the girl the doctor wanted to marry, are you? You can’t be,
U||   you know, for she’s dead.” Mrs. Harker smiled sweetly as she replied:—
U||   “Oh no! I have a husband of my own, to whom I was married before I ever
U||   saw Dr. Seward, or he me. I am Mrs. Harker.”
U||   “Then what are you doing here?”
U||   “My husband and I are staying on a visit with Dr. Seward.”
U||   “Then don’t stay.”
U||   “But why not?” I thought that this style of conversation might not be
U||   pleasant to Mrs. Harker, any more than it was to me, so I joined in:—
U||   “How did you know I wanted to marry any one?” His reply was simply
U||   contemptuous, given in a pause in which he turned his eyes from Mrs.
U||   Harker to me, instantly turning them back again:—
U||   “What an asinine question!”
U||   “I don’t see that at all, Mr. Renfield,” said Mrs. Harker, at once
U||   championing me. He replied to her with as much courtesy and respect as
U||   he had shown contempt to me:—
U||   “You will, of course, understand, Mrs. Harker, that when a man is so
U||   loved and honoured as our host is, everything regarding him is of
U||   interest in our little community. Dr. Seward is loved not only by his
U||   household and his friends, but even by his patients, who, being some of
U||   them hardly in mental equilibrium, are apt to distort causes and
U||   effects. Since I myself have been an inmate of a lunatic asylum, I
U||   cannot but notice that the sophistic tendencies of some of its inmates
U||   lean towards the errors of non causa and ignoratio elenchi.” I
U||   positively opened my eyes at this new development. Here was my own pet
U||   lunatic—the most pronounced of his type that I had ever met
U||   with—talking elemental philosophy, and with the manner of a polished
U||   gentleman. I wonder if it was Mrs. Harker’s presence which had touched
U||   some chord in his memory. If this new phase was spontaneous, or in any
U||   way due to her unconscious influence, she must have some rare gift or
U||   power.
U||   We continued to talk for some time; and, seeing that he was seemingly
U||   quite reasonable, she ventured, looking at me questioningly as she
U||   began, to lead him to his favourite topic. I was again astonished, for
U||   he addressed himself to the question with the impartiality of the
U||   completest sanity; he even took himself as an example when he mentioned
U||   certain things.
U||   “Why, I myself am an instance of a man who had a strange belief.
U||   Indeed, it was no wonder that my friends were alarmed, and insisted on
U||   my being put under control. I used to fancy that life was a positive
U||   and perpetual entity, and that by consuming a multitude of live things,
U||   no matter how low in the scale of creation, one might indefinitely
U||   prolong life. At times I held the belief so strongly that I actually
U||   tried to take human life. The doctor here will bear me out that on one
U||   occasion I tried to kill him for the purpose of strengthening my vital
U||   powers by the assimilation with my own body of his life through the
U||   medium of his blood—relying, of course, upon the Scriptural phrase,
U||   ‘For the blood is the life.’ Though, indeed, the vendor of a certain
U||   nostrum has vulgarised the truism to the very point of contempt. Isn’t
U||   that true, doctor?” I nodded assent, for I was so amazed that I hardly
U||   knew what to either think or say; it was hard to imagine that I had
U||   seen him eat up his spiders and flies not five minutes before. Looking
U||   at my watch, I saw that I should go to the station to meet Van Helsing,
U||   so I told Mrs. Harker that it was time to leave. She came at once,
U||   after saying pleasantly to Mr. Renfield: “Good-bye, and I hope I may
U||   see you often, under auspices pleasanter to yourself,” to which, to my
U||   astonishment, he replied:—
U||   “Good-bye, my dear. I pray God I may never see your sweet face again.
U||   May He bless and keep you!”
U||   When I went to the station to meet Van Helsing I left the boys behind
U||   me. Poor Art seemed more cheerful than he has been since Lucy first
U||   took ill, and Quincey is more like his own bright self than he has been
U||   for many a long day.
U||   Van Helsing stepped from the carriage with the eager nimbleness of a
U||   boy. He saw me at once, and rushed up to me, saying:—
U||   “Ah, friend John, how goes all? Well? So! I have been busy, for I come
U||   here to stay if need be. All affairs are settled with me, and I have
U||   much to tell. Madam Mina is with you? Yes. And her so fine husband? And
U||   Arthur and my friend Quincey, they are with you, too? Good!”
U||   As I drove to the house I told him of what had passed, and of how my
U||   own diary had come to be of some use through Mrs. Harker’s suggestion;
U||   at which the Professor interrupted me:—
U||   “Ah, that wonderful Madam Mina! She has man’s brain—a brain that a man
U||   should have were he much gifted—and a woman’s heart. The good God
U||   fashioned her for a purpose, believe me, when He made that so good
U||   combination. Friend John, up to now fortune has made that woman of help
U||   to us; after to-night she must not have to do with this so terrible
U||   affair. It is not good that she run a risk so great. We men are
U||   determined—nay, are we not pledged?—to destroy this monster; but it is
U||   no part for a woman. Even if she be not harmed, her heart may fail her
U||   in so much and so many horrors; and hereafter she may suffer—both in
U||   waking, from her nerves, and in sleep, from her dreams. And, besides,
U||   she is young woman and not so long married; there may be other things
U||   to think of some time, if not now. You tell me she has wrote all, then
U||   she must consult with us; but to-morrow she say good-bye to this work,
U||   and we go alone.” I agreed heartily with him, and then I told him what
U||   we had found in his absence: that the house which Dracula had bought
U||   was the very next one to my own. He was amazed, and a great concern
U||   seemed to come on him. “Oh that we had known it before!” he said, “for
U||   then we might have reached him in time to save poor Lucy. However, ‘the
U||   milk that is spilt cries not out afterwards,’ as you say. We shall not
U||   think of that, but go on our way to the end.” Then he fell into a
U||   silence that lasted till we entered my own gateway. Before we went to
U||   prepare for dinner he said to Mrs. Harker:—
U||   “I am told, Madam Mina, by my friend John that you and your husband
U||   have put up in exact order all things that have been, up to this
U||   moment.”
U||   “Not up to this moment, Professor,” she said impulsively, “but up to
U||   this morning.”
U||   “But why not up to now? We have seen hitherto how good light all the
U||   little things have made. We have told our secrets, and yet no one who
U||   has told is the worse for it.”
U||   Mrs. Harker began to blush, and taking a paper from her pockets, she
U||   said:—
U||   “Dr. Van Helsing, will you read this, and tell me if it must go in. It
U||   is my record of to-day. I too have seen the need of putting down at
U||   present everything, however trivial; but there is little in this except
U||   what is personal. Must it go in?” The Professor read it over gravely,
U||   and handed it back, saying:—
U||   “It need not go in if you do not wish it; but I pray that it may. It
U||   can but make your husband love you the more, and all us, your friends,
U||   more honour you—as well as more esteem and love.” She took it back with
U||   another blush and a bright smile.
U||   And so now, up to this very hour, all the records we have are complete
U||   and in order. The Professor took away one copy to study after dinner,
U||   and before our meeting, which is fixed for nine o’clock. The rest of us
U||   have already read everything; so when we meet in the study we shall all
U||   be informed as to facts, and can arrange our plan of battle with this
U||   terrible and mysterious enemy.
U||   Mina Harker’s Journal.
U||   30 September.—When we met in Dr. Seward’s study two hours after dinner,
U||   which had been at six o’clock, we unconsciously formed a sort of board
U||   or committee. Professor Van Helsing took the head of the table, to
U||   which Dr. Seward motioned him as he came into the room. He made me sit
U||   next to him on his right, and asked me to act as secretary; Jonathan
U||   sat next to me. Opposite us were Lord Godalming, Dr. Seward, and Mr.
U||   Morris—Lord Godalming being next the Professor, and Dr. Seward in the
U||   centre. The Professor said:—
U||   “I may, I suppose, take it that we are all acquainted with the facts
U||   that are in these papers.” We all expressed assent, and he went on:—
U||   “Then it were, I think good that I tell you something of the kind of
U||   enemy with which we have to deal. I shall then make known to you
U||   something of the history of this man, which has been ascertained for
U||   me. So we then can discuss how we shall act, and can take our measure
U||   according.
U||   “There are such beings as vampires; some of us have evidence that they
U||   exist. Even had we not the proof of our own unhappy experience, the
U||   teachings and the records of the past give proof enough for sane
U||   peoples. I admit that at the first I was sceptic. Were it not that
U||   through long years I have train myself to keep an open mind, I could
U||   not have believe until such time as that fact thunder on my ear. ‘See!
U||   see! I prove; I prove.’ Alas! Had I known at the first what now I
U||   know—nay, had I even guess at him—one so precious life had been spared
U||   to many of us who did love her. But that is gone; and we must so work,
U||   that other poor souls perish not, whilst we can save. The nosferatu do
U||   not die like the bee when he sting once. He is only stronger; and being
U||   stronger, have yet more power to work evil. This vampire which is
U||   amongst us is of himself so strong in person as twenty men; he is of
U||   cunning more than mortal, for his cunning be the growth of ages; he
U||   have still the aids of necromancy, which is, as his etymology imply,
U||   the divination by the dead, and all the dead that he can come nigh to
U||   are for him at command; he is brute, and more than brute; he is devil
U||   in callous, and the heart of him is not; he can, within limitations,
U||   appear at will when, and where, and in any of the forms that are to
U||   him; he can, within his range, direct the elements; the storm, the fog,
U||   the thunder; he can command all the meaner things: the rat, and the
U||   owl, and the bat—the moth, and the fox, and the wolf; he can grow and
U||   become small; and he can at times vanish and come unknown. How then are
U||   we to begin our strike to destroy him? How shall we find his where; and
U||   having found it, how can we destroy? My friends, this is much; it is a
U||   terrible task that we undertake, and there may be consequence to make
U||   the brave shudder. For if we fail in this our fight he must surely win;
U||   and then where end we? Life is nothings; I heed him not. But to fail
U||   here, is not mere life or death. It is that we become as him; that we
U||   henceforward become foul things of the night like him—without heart or
U||   conscience, preying on the bodies and the souls of those we love best.
U||   To us for ever are the gates of heaven shut; for who shall open them to
U||   us again? We go on for all time abhorred by all; a blot on the face of
U||   God’s sunshine; an arrow in the side of Him who died for man. But we
U||   are face to face with duty; and in such case must we shrink? For me, I
U||   say, no; but then I am old, and life, with his sunshine, his fair
U||   places, his song of birds, his music and his love, lie far behind. You
U||   others are young. Some have seen sorrow; but there are fair days yet in
U||   store. What say you?”
U||   Whilst he was speaking, Jonathan had taken my hand. I feared, oh so
U||   much, that the appalling nature of our danger was overcoming him when I
U||   saw his hand stretch out; but it was life to me to feel its touch—so
U||   strong, so self-reliant, so resolute. A brave man’s hand can speak for
U||   itself; it does not even need a woman’s love to hear its music.
U||   When the Professor had done speaking my husband looked in my eyes, and
U||   I in his; there was no need for speaking between us.
U||   “I answer for Mina and myself,” he said.
U||   “Count me in, Professor,” said Mr. Quincey Morris, laconically as
U||   usual.
U||   “I am with you,” said Lord Godalming, “for Lucy’s sake, if for no other
U||   reason.”
U||   Dr. Seward simply nodded. The Professor stood up and, after laying his
U||   golden crucifix on the table, held out his hand on either side. I took
U||   his right hand, and Lord Godalming his left; Jonathan held my right
U||   with his left and stretched across to Mr. Morris. So as we all took
U||   hands our solemn compact was made. I felt my heart icy cold, but it did
U||   not even occur to me to draw back. We resumed our places, and Dr. Van
U||   Helsing went on with a sort of cheerfulness which showed that the
U||   serious work had begun. It was to be taken as gravely, and in as
U||   businesslike a way, as any other transaction of life:—
U||   “Well, you know what we have to contend against; but we, too, are not
U||   without strength. We have on our side power of combination—a power
U||   denied to the vampire kind; we have sources of science; we are free to
U||   act and think; and the hours of the day and the night are ours equally.
U||   In fact, so far as our powers extend, they are unfettered, and we are
U||   free to use them. We have self-devotion in a cause, and an end to
U||   achieve which is not a selfish one. These things are much.
U||   “Now let us see how far the general powers arrayed against us are
U||   restrict, and how the individual cannot. In fine, let us consider the
U||   limitations of the vampire in general, and of this one in particular.
U||   “All we have to go upon are traditions and superstitions. These do not
U||   at the first appear much, when the matter is one of life and death—nay
U||   of more than either life or death. Yet must we be satisfied; in the
U||   first place because we have to be—no other means is at our control—and
U||   secondly, because, after all, these things—tradition and
U||   superstition—are everything. Does not the belief in vampires rest for
U||   others—though not, alas! for us—on them? A year ago which of us would
U||   have received such a possibility, in the midst of our scientific,
U||   sceptical, matter-of-fact nineteenth century? We even scouted a belief
U||   that we saw justified under our very eyes. Take it, then, that the
U||   vampire, and the belief in his limitations and his cure, rest for the
