U||   far from us in all ways, there even is he, and the peoples fear him at
U||   this day. He have follow the wake of the berserker Icelander, the
U||   devil-begotten Hun, the Slav, the Saxon, the Magyar. So far, then, we
U||   have all we may act upon; and let me tell you that very much of the
U||   beliefs are justified by what we have seen in our own so unhappy
U||   experience. The vampire live on, and cannot die by mere passing of the
U||   time; he can flourish when that he can fatten on the blood of the
U||   living. Even more, we have seen amongst us that he can even grow
U||   younger; that his vital faculties grow strenuous, and seem as though
U||   they refresh themselves when his special pabulum is plenty. But he
U||   cannot flourish without this diet; he eat not as others. Even friend
U||   Jonathan, who lived with him for weeks, did never see him to eat,
U||   never! He throws no shadow; he make in the mirror no reflect, as again
U||   Jonathan observe. He has the strength of many of his hand—witness again
U||   Jonathan when he shut the door against the wolfs, and when he help him
U||   from the diligence too. He can transform himself to wolf, as we gather
U||   from the ship arrival in Whitby, when he tear open the dog; he can be
U||   as bat, as Madam Mina saw him on the window at Whitby, and as friend
U||   John saw him fly from this so near house, and as my friend Quincey saw
U||   him at the window of Miss Lucy. He can come in mist which he
U||   create—that noble ship’s captain proved him of this; but, from what we
U||   know, the distance he can make this mist is limited, and it can only be
U||   round himself. He come on moonlight rays as elemental dust—as again
U||   Jonathan saw those sisters in the castle of Dracula. He become so
U||   small—we ourselves saw Miss Lucy, ere she was at peace, slip through a
U||   hairbreadth space at the tomb door. He can, when once he find his way,
U||   come out from anything or into anything, no matter how close it be
