U||   been from the loins of this very one great men and good women, and
U||   their graves make sacred the earth where alone this foulness can dwell.
U||   For it is not the least of its terrors that this evil thing is rooted
U||   deep in all good; in soil barren of holy memories it cannot rest.”
U||   Whilst they were talking Mr. Morris was looking steadily at the window,
U||   and he now got up quietly, and went out of the room. There was a little
U||   pause, and then the Professor went on:—
U||   “And now we must settle what we do. We have here much data, and we must
U||   proceed to lay out our campaign. We know from the inquiry of Jonathan
U||   that from the castle to Whitby came fifty boxes of earth, all of which
U||   were delivered at Carfax; we also know that at least some of these
U||   boxes have been removed. It seems to me, that our first step should be
U||   to ascertain whether all the rest remain in the house beyond that wall
U||   where we look to-day; or whether any more have been removed. If the
U||   latter, we must trace——”
U||   Here we were interrupted in a very startling way. Outside the house
U||   came the sound of a pistol-shot; the glass of the window was shattered
U||   with a bullet, which, ricochetting from the top of the embrasure,
U||   struck the far wall of the room. I am afraid I am at heart a coward,
U||   for I shrieked out. The men all jumped to their feet; Lord Godalming
U||   flew over to the window and threw up the sash. As he did so we heard
U||   Mr. Morris’s voice without:—
U||   “Sorry! I fear I have alarmed you. I shall come in and tell you about
U||   it.” A minute later he came in and said:—
U||   “It was an idiotic thing of me to do, and I ask your pardon, Mrs.
U||   Harker, most sincerely; I fear I must have frightened you terribly. But
U||   the fact is that whilst the Professor was talking there came a big bat
U||   and sat on the window-sill. I have got such a horror of the damned
U||   brutes from recent events that I cannot stand them, and I went out to
U||   have a shot, as I have been doing of late of evenings, whenever I have
U||   seen one. You used to laugh at me for it then, Art.”
U||   “Did you hit it?” asked Dr. Van Helsing.
U||   “I don’t know; I fancy not, for it flew away into the wood.” Without
U||   saying any more he took his seat, and the Professor began to resume his
U||   statement:—
U||   “We must trace each of these boxes; and when we are ready, we must
U||   either capture or kill this monster in his lair; or we must, so to
U||   speak, sterilise the earth, so that no more he can seek safety in it.
U||   Thus in the end we may find him in his form of man between the hours of
U||   noon and sunset, and so engage with him when he is at his most weak.
U||   “And now for you, Madam Mina, this night is the end until all be well.
U||   You are too precious to us to have such risk. When we part to-night,
U||   you no more must question. We shall tell you all in good time. We are
U||   men and are able to bear; but you must be our star and our hope, and we
U||   shall act all the more free that you are not in the danger, such as we
U||   are.”
U||   All the men, even Jonathan, seemed relieved; but it did not seem to me
U||   good that they should brave danger and, perhaps, lessen their
U||   safety—strength being the best safety—through care of me; but their
U||   minds were made up, and, though it was a bitter pill for me to swallow,
U||   I could say nothing, save to accept their chivalrous care of me.
U||   Mr. Morris resumed the discussion:—
U||   “As there is no time to lose, I vote we have a look at his house right
U||   now. Time is everything with him; and swift action on our part may save
U||   another victim.”
U||   I own that my heart began to fail me when the time for action came so
U||   close, but I did not say anything, for I had a greater fear that if I
U||   appeared as a drag or a hindrance to their work, they might even leave
U||   me out of their counsels altogether. They have now gone off to Carfax,
U||   with means to get into the house.
U||   Manlike, they had told me to go to bed and sleep; as if a woman can
U||   sleep when those she loves are in danger! I shall lie down and pretend
U||   to sleep, lest Jonathan have added anxiety about me when he returns.
U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   1 October, 4 a. m.—Just as we were about to leave the house, an urgent
U||   message was brought to me from Renfield to know if I would see him at
U||   once, as he had something of the utmost importance to say to me. I told
U||   the messenger to say that I would attend to his wishes in the morning;
U||   I was busy just at the moment. The attendant added:—
U||   “He seems very importunate, sir. I have never seen him so eager. I
U||   don’t know but what, if you don’t see him soon, he will have one of his
U||   violent fits.” I knew the man would not have said this without some
U||   cause, so I said: “All right; I’ll go now”; and I asked the others to
U||   wait a few minutes for me, as I had to go and see my “patient.”
U||   “Take me with you, friend John,” said the Professor. “His case in your
U||   diary interest me much, and it had bearing, too, now and again on our
U||   case. I should much like to see him, and especial when his mind is
U||   disturbed.”
U||   “May I come also?” asked Lord Godalming.
U||   “Me too?” said Quincey Morris. “May I come?” said Harker. I nodded, and
U||   we all went down the passage together.
U||   We found him in a state of considerable excitement, but far more
U||   rational in his speech and manner than I had ever seen him. There was
U||   an unusual understanding of himself, which was unlike anything I had
U||   ever met with in a lunatic; and he took it for granted that his reasons
U||   would prevail with others entirely sane. We all four went into the
U||   room, but none of the others at first said anything. His request was
U||   that I would at once release him from the asylum and send him home.
U||   This he backed up with arguments regarding his complete recovery, and
U||   adduced his own existing sanity. “I appeal to your friends,” he said,
U||   “they will, perhaps, not mind sitting in judgment on my case. By the
U||   way, you have not introduced me.” I was so much astonished, that the
U||   oddness of introducing a madman in an asylum did not strike me at the
U||   moment; and, besides, there was a certain dignity in the man’s manner,
U||   so much of the habit of equality, that I at once made the introduction:
U||   “Lord Godalming; Professor Van Helsing; Mr. Quincey Morris, of Texas;
U||   Mr. Renfield.” He shook hands with each of them, saying in turn:—
U||   “Lord Godalming, I had the honour of seconding your father at the
U||   Windham; I grieve to know, by your holding the title, that he is no
U||   more. He was a man loved and honoured by all who knew him; and in his
U||   youth was, I have heard, the inventor of a burnt rum punch, much
U||   patronised on Derby night. Mr. Morris, you should be proud of your
U||   great state. Its reception into the Union was a precedent which may
U||   have far-reaching effects hereafter, when the Pole and the Tropics may
U||   hold alliance to the Stars and Stripes. The power of Treaty may yet
U||   prove a vast engine of enlargement, when the Monroe doctrine takes its
U||   true place as a political fable. What shall any man say of his pleasure
U||   at meeting Van Helsing? Sir, I make no apology for dropping all forms
U||   of conventional prefix. When an individual has revolutionised
U||   therapeutics by his discovery of the continuous evolution of
U||   brain-matter, conventional forms are unfitting, since they would seem
U||   to limit him to one of a class. You, gentlemen, who by nationality, by
U||   heredity, or by the possession of natural gifts, are fitted to hold
U||   your respective places in the moving world, I take to witness that I am
U||   as sane as at least the majority of men who are in full possession of
U||   their liberties. And I am sure that you, Dr. Seward, humanitarian and
U||   medico-jurist as well as scientist, will deem it a moral duty to deal
U||   with me as one to be considered as under exceptional circumstances.” He
U||   made this last appeal with a courtly air of conviction which was not
U||   without its own charm.
U||   I think we were all staggered. For my own part, I was under the
U||   conviction, despite my knowledge of the man’s character and history,
U||   that his reason had been restored; and I felt under a strong impulse to
U||   tell him that I was satisfied as to his sanity, and would see about the
U||   necessary formalities for his release in the morning. I thought it
U||   better to wait, however, before making so grave a statement, for of old
U||   I knew the sudden changes to which this particular patient was liable.
U||   So I contented myself with making a general statement that he appeared
U||   to be improving very rapidly; that I would have a longer chat with him
U||   in the morning, and would then see what I could do in the direction of
U||   meeting his wishes. This did not at all satisfy him, for he said
U||   quickly:—
U||   “But I fear, Dr. Seward, that you hardly apprehend my wish. I desire to
U||   go at once—here—now—this very hour—this very moment, if I may. Time
U||   presses, and in our implied agreement with the old scytheman it is of
U||   the essence of the contract. I am sure it is only necessary to put
U||   before so admirable a practitioner as Dr. Seward so simple, yet so
U||   momentous a wish, to ensure its fulfilment.” He looked at me keenly,
U||   and seeing the negative in my face, turned to the others, and
U||   scrutinised them closely. Not meeting any sufficient response, he went
U||   on:—
U||   “Is it possible that I have erred in my supposition?”
U||   “You have,” I said frankly, but at the same time, as I felt, brutally.
U||   There was a considerable pause, and then he said slowly:—
U||   “Then I suppose I must only shift my ground of request. Let me ask for
U||   this concession—boon, privilege, what you will. I am content to implore
U||   in such a case, not on personal grounds, but for the sake of others. I
U||   am not at liberty to give you the whole of my reasons; but you may, I
U||   assure you, take it from me that they are good ones, sound and
U||   unselfish, and spring from the highest sense of duty. Could you look,
U||   sir, into my heart, you would approve to the full the sentiments which
U||   animate me. Nay, more, you would count me amongst the best and truest
U||   of your friends.” Again he looked at us all keenly. I had a growing
U||   conviction that this sudden change of his entire intellectual method
U||   was but yet another form or phase of his madness, and so determined to
U||   let him go on a little longer, knowing from experience that he would,
U||   like all lunatics, give himself away in the end. Van Helsing was gazing
U||   at him with a look of utmost intensity, his bushy eyebrows almost
U||   meeting with the fixed concentration of his look. He said to Renfield
U||   in a tone which did not surprise me at the time, but only when I
U||   thought of it afterwards—for it was as of one addressing an equal:—
U||   “Can you not tell frankly your real reason for wishing to be free
U||   to-night? I will undertake that if you will satisfy even me—a stranger,
U||   without prejudice, and with the habit of keeping an open mind—Dr.
U||   Seward will give you, at his own risk and on his own responsibility,
