U||   poignant regret on his face. The Professor went on:—
U||   “Come, sir, bethink yourself. You claim the privilege of reason in the
U||   highest degree, since you seek to impress us with your complete
U||   reasonableness. You do this, whose sanity we have reason to doubt,
U||   since you are not yet released from medical treatment for this very
U||   defect. If you will not help us in our effort to choose the wisest
U||   course, how can we perform the duty which you yourself put upon us? Be
U||   wise, and help us; and if we can we shall aid you to achieve your
U||   wish.” He still shook his head as he said:—
U||   “Dr. Van Helsing, I have nothing to say. Your argument is complete, and
U||   if I were free to speak I should not hesitate a moment; but I am not my
U||   own master in the matter. I can only ask you to trust me. If I am
U||   refused, the responsibility does not rest with me.” I thought it was
U||   now time to end the scene, which was becoming too comically grave, so I
U||   went towards the door, simply saying:—
U||   “Come, my friends, we have work to do. Good-night.”
U||   As, however, I got near the door, a new change came over the patient.
U||   He moved towards me so quickly that for the moment I feared that he was
U||   about to make another homicidal attack. My fears, however, were
U||   groundless, for he held up his two hands imploringly, and made his
U||   petition in a moving manner. As he saw that the very excess of his
U||   emotion was militating against him, by restoring us more to our old
U||   relations, he became still more demonstrative. I glanced at Van
U||   Helsing, and saw my conviction reflected in his eyes; so I became a
U||   little more fixed in my manner, if not more stern, and motioned to him
U||   that his efforts were unavailing. I had previously seen something of
U||   the same constantly growing excitement in him when he had to make some
U||   request of which at the time he had thought much, such, for instance,
U||   as when he wanted a cat; and I was prepared to see the collapse into
U||   the same sullen acquiescence on this occasion. My expectation was not
U||   realised, for, when he found that his appeal would not be successful,
U||   he got into quite a frantic condition. He threw himself on his knees,
U||   and held up his hands, wringing them in plaintive supplication, and
U||   poured forth a torrent of entreaty, with the tears rolling down his
U||   cheeks, and his whole face and form expressive of the deepest emotion:—
