U||CHAPTER XIX
U||JONATHAN HARKER’S JOURNAL
U||   1 October, 5 a. m.—I went with the party to the search with an easy
U||   mind, for I think I never saw Mina so absolutely strong and well. I am
U||   so glad that she consented to hold back and let us men do the work.
U||   Somehow, it was a dread to me that she was in this fearful business at
U||   all; but now that her work is done, and that it is due to her energy
U||   and brains and foresight that the whole story is put together in such a
U||   way that every point tells, she may well feel that her part is
U||   finished, and that she can henceforth leave the rest to us. We were, I
U||   think, all a little upset by the scene with Mr. Renfield. When we came
U||   away from his room we were silent till we got back to the study. Then
U||   Mr. Morris said to Dr. Seward:—
U||   “Say, Jack, if that man wasn’t attempting a bluff, he is about the
U||   sanest lunatic I ever saw. I’m not sure, but I believe that he had some
U||   serious purpose, and if he had, it was pretty rough on him not to get a
U||   chance.” Lord Godalming and I were silent, but Dr. Van Helsing added:—
U||   “Friend John, you know more of lunatics than I do, and I’m glad of it,
U||   for I fear that if it had been to me to decide I would before that last
U||   hysterical outburst have given him free. But we live and learn, and in
U||   our present task we must take no chance, as my friend Quincey would
U||   say. All is best as they are.” Dr. Seward seemed to answer them both in
U||   a dreamy kind of way:—
U||   “I don’t know but that I agree with you. If that man had been an
U||   ordinary lunatic I would have taken my chance of trusting him; but he
U||   seems so mixed up with the Count in an indexy kind of way that I am
U||   afraid of doing anything wrong by helping his fads. I can’t forget how
U||   he prayed with almost equal fervour for a cat, and then tried to tear
U||   my throat out with his teeth. Besides, he called the Count ‘lord and
U||   master,’ and he may want to get out to help him in some diabolical way.
U||   That horrid thing has the wolves and the rats and his own kind to help
U||   him, so I suppose he isn’t above trying to use a respectable lunatic.
U||   He certainly did seem earnest, though. I only hope we have done what is
U||   best. These things, in conjunction with the wild work we have in hand,
U||   help to unnerve a man.” The Professor stepped over, and laying his hand
U||   on his shoulder, said in his grave, kindly way:—
U||   “Friend John, have no fear. We are trying to do our duty in a very sad
U||   and terrible case; we can only do as we deem best. What else have we to
U||   hope for, except the pity of the good God?” Lord Godalming had slipped
U||   away for a few minutes, but now he returned. He held up a little silver
U||   whistle, as he remarked:—
U||   “That old place may be full of rats, and if so, I’ve got an antidote on
U||   call.” Having passed the wall, we took our way to the house, taking
U||   care to keep in the shadows of the trees on the lawn when the moonlight
U||   shone out. When we got to the porch the Professor opened his bag and
U||   took out a lot of things, which he laid on the step, sorting them into
U||   four little groups, evidently one for each. Then he spoke:—
U||   “My friends, we are going into a terrible danger, and we need arms of
U||   many kinds. Our enemy is not merely spiritual. Remember that he has the
U||   strength of twenty men, and that, though our necks or our windpipes are
U||   of the common kind—and therefore breakable or crushable—his are not
U||   amenable to mere strength. A stronger man, or a body of men more strong
U||   in all than him, can at certain times hold him; but they cannot hurt
U||   him as we can be hurt by him. We must, therefore, guard ourselves from
U||   his touch. Keep this near your heart”—as he spoke he lifted a little
U||   silver crucifix and held it out to me, I being nearest to him—“put
U||   these flowers round your neck”—here he handed to me a wreath of
U||   withered garlic blossoms—“for other enemies more mundane, this revolver
U||   and this knife; and for aid in all, these so small electric lamps,
U||   which you can fasten to your breast; and for all, and above all at the
U||   last, this, which we must not desecrate needless.” This was a portion
U||   of Sacred Wafer, which he put in an envelope and handed to me. Each of
U||   the others was similarly equipped. “Now,” he said, “friend John, where
U||   are the skeleton keys? If so that we can open the door, we need not
U||   break house by the window, as before at Miss Lucy’s.”
U||   Dr. Seward tried one or two skeleton keys, his mechanical dexterity as
U||   a surgeon standing him in good stead. Presently he got one to suit;
U||   after a little play back and forward the bolt yielded, and, with a
U||   rusty clang, shot back. We pressed on the door, the rusty hinges
U||   creaked, and it slowly opened. It was startlingly like the image
U||   conveyed to me in Dr. Seward’s diary of the opening of Miss Westenra’s
U||   tomb; I fancy that the same idea seemed to strike the others, for with
U||   one accord they shrank back. The Professor was the first to move
U||   forward, and stepped into the open door.
U||   “In manus tuas, Domine!” he said, crossing himself as he passed over
U||   the threshold. We closed the door behind us, lest when we should have
U||   lit our lamps we should possibly attract attention from the road. The
U||   Professor carefully tried the lock, lest we might not be able to open
U||   it from within should we be in a hurry making our exit. Then we all lit
U||   our lamps and proceeded on our search.
U||   The light from the tiny lamps fell in all sorts of odd forms, as the
U||   rays crossed each other, or the opacity of our bodies threw great
U||   shadows. I could not for my life get away from the feeling that there
U||   was some one else amongst us. I suppose it was the recollection, so
U||   powerfully brought home to me by the grim surroundings, of that
U||   terrible experience in Transylvania. I think the feeling was common to
U||   us all, for I noticed that the others kept looking over their shoulders
U||   at every sound and every new shadow, just as I felt myself doing.
U||   The whole place was thick with dust. The floor was seemingly inches
U||   deep, except where there were recent footsteps, in which on holding
U||   down my lamp I could see marks of hobnails where the dust was cracked.
U||   The walls were fluffy and heavy with dust, and in the corners were
U||   masses of spider’s webs, whereon the dust had gathered till they looked
U||   like old tattered rags as the weight had torn them partly down. On a
U||   table in the hall was a great bunch of keys, with a time-yellowed label
U||   on each. They had been used several times, for on the table were
U||   several similar rents in the blanket of dust, similar to that exposed
U||   when the Professor lifted them. He turned to me and said:—
U||   “You know this place, Jonathan. You have copied maps of it, and you
U||   know it at least more than we do. Which is the way to the chapel?” I
U||   had an idea of its direction, though on my former visit I had not been
U||   able to get admission to it; so I led the way, and after a few wrong
U||   turnings found myself opposite a low, arched oaken door, ribbed with
U||   iron bands. “This is the spot,” said the Professor as he turned his
U||   lamp on a small map of the house, copied from the file of my original
U||   correspondence regarding the purchase. With a little trouble we found
U||   the key on the bunch and opened the door. We were prepared for some
U||   unpleasantness, for as we were opening the door a faint, malodorous air
U||   seemed to exhale through the gaps, but none of us ever expected such an
U||   odour as we encountered. None of the others had met the Count at all at
U||   close quarters, and when I had seen him he was either in the fasting
U||   stage of his existence in his rooms or, when he was gloated with fresh
U||   blood, in a ruined building open to the air; but here the place was
U||   small and close, and the long disuse had made the air stagnant and
U||   foul. There was an earthy smell, as of some dry miasma, which came
U||   through the fouler air. But as to the odour itself, how shall I
U||   describe it? It was not alone that it was composed of all the ills of
U||   mortality and with the pungent, acrid smell of blood, but it seemed as
U||   though corruption had become itself corrupt. Faugh! it sickens me to
U||   think of it. Every breath exhaled by that monster seemed to have clung
U||   to the place and intensified its loathsomeness.
U||   Under ordinary circumstances such a stench would have brought our
U||   enterprise to an end; but this was no ordinary case, and the high and
U||   terrible purpose in which we were involved gave us a strength which
U||   rose above merely physical considerations. After the involuntary
U||   shrinking consequent on the first nauseous whiff, we one and all set
U||   about our work as though that loathsome place were a garden of roses.
U||   We made an accurate examination of the place, the Professor saying as
U||   we began:—
U||   “The first thing is to see how many of the boxes are left; we must then
U||   examine every hole and corner and cranny and see if we cannot get some
U||   clue as to what has become of the rest.” A glance was sufficient to
U||   show how many remained, for the great earth chests were bulky, and
U||   there was no mistaking them.
U||   There were only twenty-nine left out of the fifty! Once I got a fright,
U||   for, seeing Lord Godalming suddenly turn and look out of the vaulted
U||   door into the dark passage beyond, I looked too, and for an instant my
U||   heart stood still. Somewhere, looking out from the shadow, I seemed to
U||   see the high lights of the Count’s evil face, the ridge of the nose,
U||   the red eyes, the red lips, the awful pallor. It was only for a moment,
U||   for, as Lord Godalming said, “I thought I saw a face, but it was only
U||   the shadows,” and resumed his inquiry, I turned my lamp in the
U||   direction, and stepped into the passage. There was no sign of any one;
U||   and as there were no corners, no doors, no aperture of any kind, but
U||   only the solid walls of the passage, there could be no hiding-place
U||   even for him. I took it that fear had helped imagination, and said
U||   nothing.
U||   A few minutes later I saw Morris step suddenly back from a corner,
U||   which he was examining. We all followed his movements with our eyes,
U||   for undoubtedly some nervousness was growing on us, and we saw a whole
U||   mass of phosphorescence, which twinkled like stars. We all
U||   instinctively drew back. The whole place was becoming alive with rats.
U||   For a moment or two we stood appalled, all save Lord Godalming, who was
U||   seemingly prepared for such an emergency. Rushing over to the great
U||   iron-bound oaken door, which Dr. Seward had described from the outside,
U||   and which I had seen myself, he turned the key in the lock, drew the
U||   huge bolts, and swung the door open. Then, taking his little silver
U||   whistle from his pocket, he blew a low, shrill call. It was answered
U||   from behind Dr. Seward’s house by the yelping of dogs, and after about
U||   a minute three terriers came dashing round the corner of the house.
U||   Unconsciously we had all moved towards the door, and as we moved I
U||   noticed that the dust had been much disturbed: the boxes which had been
U||   taken out had been brought this way. But even in the minute that had
U||   elapsed the number of the rats had vastly increased. They seemed to
U||   swarm over the place all at once, till the lamplight, shining on their
U||   moving dark bodies and glittering, baleful eyes, made the place look
U||   like a bank of earth set with fireflies. The dogs dashed on, but at the
U||   threshold suddenly stopped and snarled, and then, simultaneously
U||   lifting their noses, began to howl in most lugubrious fashion. The rats
U||   were multiplying in thousands, and we moved out.
U||   Lord Godalming lifted one of the dogs, and carrying him in, placed him
U||   on the floor. The instant his feet touched the ground he seemed to
U||   recover his courage, and rushed at his natural enemies. They fled
U||   before him so fast that before he had shaken the life out of a score,
U||   the other dogs, who had by now been lifted in the same manner, had but
U||   small prey ere the whole mass had vanished.
U||   With their going it seemed as if some evil presence had departed, for
U||   the dogs frisked about and barked merrily as they made sudden darts at
U||   their prostrate foes, and turned them over and over and tossed them in
U||   the air with vicious shakes. We all seemed to find our spirits rise.
U||   Whether it was the purifying of the deadly atmosphere by the opening of
U||   the chapel door, or the relief which we experienced by finding
U||   ourselves in the open I know not; but most certainly the shadow of
U||   dread seemed to slip from us like a robe, and the occasion of our
U||   coming lost something of its grim significance, though we did not
U||   slacken a whit in our resolution. We closed the outer door and barred
U||   and locked it, and bringing the dogs with us, began our search of the
U||   house. We found nothing throughout except dust in extraordinary
U||   proportions, and all untouched save for my own footsteps when I had
U||   made my first visit. Never once did the dogs exhibit any symptom of
U||   uneasiness, and even when we returned to the chapel they frisked about
U||   as though they had been rabbit-hunting in a summer wood.
U||   The morning was quickening in the east when we emerged from the front.
U||   Dr. Van Helsing had taken the key of the hall-door from the bunch, and
U||   locked the door in orthodox fashion, putting the key into his pocket
U||   when he had done.
U||   “So far,” he said, “our night has been eminently successful. No harm
U||   has come to us such as I feared might be and yet we have ascertained
U||   how many boxes are missing. More than all do I rejoice that this, our
U||   first—and perhaps our most difficult and dangerous—step has been
U||   accomplished without the bringing thereinto our most sweet Madam Mina
U||   or troubling her waking or sleeping thoughts with sights and sounds and
U||   smells of horror which she might never forget. One lesson, too, we have
U||   learned, if it be allowable to argue a particulari: that the brute
U||   beasts which are to the Count’s command are yet themselves not amenable
U||   to his spiritual power; for look, these rats that would come to his
U||   call, just as from his castle top he summon the wolves to your going
U||   and to that poor mother’s cry, though they come to him, they run
U||   pell-mell from the so little dogs of my friend Arthur. We have other
U||   matters before us, other dangers, other fears; and that monster—he has
U||   not used his power over the brute world for the only or the last time
U||   to-night. So be it that he has gone elsewhere. Good! It has given us
U||   opportunity to cry ‘check’ in some ways in this chess game, which we
U||   play for the stake of human souls. And now let us go home. The dawn is
U||   close at hand, and we have reason to be content with our first night’s
U||   work. It may be ordained that we have many nights and days to follow,
U||   if full of peril; but we must go on, and from no danger shall we
U||   shrink.”
U||   The house was silent when we got back, save for some poor creature who
U||   was screaming away in one of the distant wards, and a low, moaning
U||   sound from Renfield’s room. The poor wretch was doubtless torturing
U||   himself, after the manner of the insane, with needless thoughts of
U||   pain.
U||   I came tiptoe into our own room, and found Mina asleep, breathing so
U||   softly that I had to put my ear down to hear it. She looks paler than
U||   usual. I hope the meeting to-night has not upset her. I am truly
U||   thankful that she is to be left out of our future work, and even of our
U||   deliberations. It is too great a strain for a woman to bear. I did not
U||   think so at first, but I know better now. Therefore I am glad that it
U||   is settled. There may be things which would frighten her to hear; and
U||   yet to conceal them from her might be worse than to tell her if once
U||   she suspected that there was any concealment. Henceforth our work is to
U||   be a sealed book to her, till at least such time as we can tell her
U||   that all is finished, and the earth free from a monster of the nether
U||   world. I daresay it will be difficult to begin to keep silence after
U||   such confidence as ours; but I must be resolute, and to-morrow I shall
U||   keep dark over to-night’s doings, and shall refuse to speak of anything
U||   that has happened. I rest on the sofa, so as not to disturb her.
U||   1 October, later.—I suppose it was natural that we should have all
U||   overslept ourselves, for the day was a busy one, and the night had no
U||   rest at all. Even Mina must have felt its exhaustion, for though I
U||   slept till the sun was high, I was awake before her, and had to call
U||   two or three times before she awoke. Indeed, she was so sound asleep
U||   that for a few seconds she did not recognize me, but looked at me with
U||   a sort of blank terror, as one looks who has been waked out of a bad
U||   dream. She complained a little of being tired, and I let her rest till
U||   later in the day. We now know of twenty-one boxes having been removed,
U||   and if it be that several were taken in any of these removals we may be
U||   able to trace them all. Such will, of course, immensely simplify our
U||   labour, and the sooner the matter is attended to the better. I shall
U||   look up Thomas Snelling to-day.
U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   1 October.—It was towards noon when I was awakened by the Professor
U||   walking into my room. He was more jolly and cheerful than usual, and it
U||   is quite evident that last night’s work has helped to take some of the
U||   brooding weight off his mind. After going over the adventure of the
U||   night he suddenly said:—
U||   “Your patient interests me much. May it be that with you I visit him
U||   this morning? Or if that you are too occupy, I can go alone if it may
U||   be. It is a new experience to me to find a lunatic who talk philosophy,
U||   and reason so sound.” I had some work to do which pressed, so I told
U||   him that if he would go alone I would be glad, as then I should not
U||   have to keep him waiting; so I called an attendant and gave him the
U||   necessary instructions. Before the Professor left the room I cautioned
U||   him against getting any false impression from my patient. “But,” he
U||   answered, “I want him to talk of himself and of his delusion as to
U||   consuming live things. He said to Madam Mina, as I see in your diary of
U||   yesterday, that he had once had such a belief. Why do you smile, friend
U||   John?”
U||   “Excuse me,” I said, “but the answer is here.” I laid my hand on the
U||   type-written matter. “When our sane and learned lunatic made that very
U||   statement of how he used to consume life, his mouth was actually
U||   nauseous with the flies and spiders which he had eaten just before Mrs.
U||   Harker entered the room.” Van Helsing smiled in turn. “Good!” he said.
U||   “Your memory is true, friend John. I should have remembered. And yet it
U||   is this very obliquity of thought and memory which makes mental disease
U||   such a fascinating study. Perhaps I may gain more knowledge out of the
U||   folly of this madman than I shall from the teaching of the most wise.
U||   Who knows?” I went on with my work, and before long was through that in
U||   hand. It seemed that the time had been very short indeed, but there was
U||   Van Helsing back in the study. “Do I interrupt?” he asked politely as
U||   he stood at the door.
U||   “Not at all,” I answered. “Come in. My work is finished, and I am free.
U||   I can go with you now, if you like.
U||   “It is needless; I have seen him!”
U||   “Well?”
U||   “I fear that he does not appraise me at much. Our interview was short.
U||   When I entered his room he was sitting on a stool in the centre, with
U||   his elbows on his knees, and his face was the picture of sullen
U||   discontent. I spoke to him as cheerfully as I could, and with such a
U||   measure of respect as I could assume. He made no reply whatever. “Don’t
U||   you know me?” I asked. His answer was not reassuring: “I know you well
U||   enough; you are the old fool Van Helsing. I wish you would take
U||   yourself and your idiotic brain theories somewhere else. Damn all
U||   thick-headed Dutchmen!” Not a word more would he say, but sat in his
U||   implacable sullenness as indifferent to me as though I had not been in
U||   the room at all. Thus departed for this time my chance of much learning
U||   from this so clever lunatic; so I shall go, if I may, and cheer myself
U||   with a few happy words with that sweet soul Madam Mina. Friend John, it
U||   does rejoice me unspeakable that she is no more to be pained, no more
U||   to be worried with our terrible things. Though we shall much miss her
U||   help, it is better so.”
U||   “I agree with you with all my heart,” I answered earnestly, for I did
U||   not want him to weaken in this matter. “Mrs. Harker is better out of
U||   it. Things are quite bad enough for us, all men of the world, and who
U||   have been in many tight places in our time; but it is no place for a
U||   woman, and if she had remained in touch with the affair, it would in
U||   time infallibly have wrecked her.”
U||   So Van Helsing has gone to confer with Mrs. Harker and Harker; Quincey
U||   and Art are all out following up the clues as to the earth-boxes. I
U||   shall finish my round of work and we shall meet to-night.
U||   Mina Harker’s Journal.
U||   1 October.—It is strange to me to be kept in the dark as I am to-day;
U||   after Jonathan’s full confidence for so many years, to see him
U||   manifestly avoid certain matters, and those the most vital of all. This
U||   morning I slept late after the fatigues of yesterday, and though
U||   Jonathan was late too, he was the earlier. He spoke to me before he
U||   went out, never more sweetly or tenderly, but he never mentioned a word
U||   of what had happened in the visit to the Count’s house. And yet he must
U||   have known how terribly anxious I was. Poor dear fellow! I suppose it
U||   must have distressed him even more than it did me. They all agreed that
U||   it was best that I should not be drawn further into this awful work,
U||   and I acquiesced. But to think that he keeps anything from me! And now
U||   I am crying like a silly fool, when I know it comes from my husband’s
U||   great love and from the good, good wishes of those other strong men.
U||   That has done me good. Well, some day Jonathan will tell me all; and
U||   lest it should ever be that he should think for a moment that I kept
U||   anything from him, I still keep my journal as usual. Then if he has
U||   feared of my trust I shall show it to him, with every thought of my
U||   heart put down for his dear eyes to read. I feel strangely sad and
U||   low-spirited to-day. I suppose it is the reaction from the terrible
U||   excitement.
U||   Last night I went to bed when the men had gone, simply because they
U||   told me to. I didn’t feel sleepy, and I did feel full of devouring
U||   anxiety. I kept thinking over everything that has been ever since
U||   Jonathan came to see me in London, and it all seems like a horrible
U||   tragedy, with fate pressing on relentlessly to some destined end.
U||   Everything that one does seems, no matter how right it may be, to bring
U||   on the very thing which is most to be deplored. If I hadn’t gone to
U||   Whitby, perhaps poor dear Lucy would be with us now. She hadn’t taken
U||   to visiting the churchyard till I came, and if she hadn’t come there in
U||   the day-time with me she wouldn’t have walked there in her sleep; and
U||   if she hadn’t gone there at night and asleep, that monster couldn’t
U||   have destroyed her as he did. Oh, why did I ever go to Whitby? There
U||   now, crying again! I wonder what has come over me to-day. I must hide
U||   it from Jonathan, for if he knew that I had been crying twice in one
U||   morning—I, who never cried on my own account, and whom he has never
U||   caused to shed a tear—the dear fellow would fret his heart out. I shall
U||   put a bold face on, and if I do feel weepy, he shall never see it. I
U||   suppose it is one of the lessons that we poor women have to learn....
U||   I can’t quite remember how I fell asleep last night. I remember hearing
U||   the sudden barking of the dogs and a lot of queer sounds, like praying
U||   on a very tumultuous scale, from Mr. Renfield’s room, which is
U||   somewhere under this. And then there was silence over everything,
U||   silence so profound that it startled me, and I got up and looked out of
U||   the window. All was dark and silent, the black shadows thrown by the
U||   moonlight seeming full of a silent mystery of their own. Not a thing
U||   seemed to be stirring, but all to be grim and fixed as death or fate;
U||   so that a thin streak of white mist, that crept with almost
U||   imperceptible slowness across the grass towards the house, seemed to
U||   have a sentience and a vitality of its own. I think that the digression
U||   of my thoughts must have done me good, for when I got back to bed I
U||   found a lethargy creeping over me. I lay a while, but could not quite
U||   sleep, so I got out and looked out of the window again. The mist was
U||   spreading, and was now close up to the house, so that I could see it
U||   lying thick against the wall, as though it were stealing up to the
U||   windows. The poor man was more loud than ever, and though I could not
U||   distinguish a word he said, I could in some way recognise in his tones
U||   some passionate entreaty on his part. Then there was the sound of a
U||   struggle, and I knew that the attendants were dealing with him. I was
U||   so frightened that I crept into bed, and pulled the clothes over my
U||   head, putting my fingers in my ears. I was not then a bit sleepy, at
U||   least so I thought; but I must have fallen asleep, for, except dreams,
U||   I do not remember anything until the morning, when Jonathan woke me. I
U||   think that it took me an effort and a little time to realise where I
U||   was, and that it was Jonathan who was bending over me. My dream was
U||   very peculiar, and was almost typical of the way that waking thoughts
U||   become merged in, or continued in, dreams.
U||   I thought that I was asleep, and waiting for Jonathan to come back. I
U||   was very anxious about him, and I was powerless to act; my feet, and my
U||   hands, and my brain were weighted, so that nothing could proceed at the
U||   usual pace. And so I slept uneasily and thought. Then it began to dawn
U||   upon me that the air was heavy, and dank, and cold. I put back the
U||   clothes from my face, and found, to my surprise, that all was dim
U||   around. The gaslight which I had left lit for Jonathan, but turned
U||   down, came only like a tiny red spark through the fog, which had
U||   evidently grown thicker and poured into the room. Then it occurred to
U||   me that I had shut the window before I had come to bed. I would have
U||   got out to make certain on the point, but some leaden lethargy seemed
U||   to chain my limbs and even my will. I lay still and endured; that was
U||   all. I closed my eyes, but could still see through my eyelids. (It is
U||   wonderful what tricks our dreams play us, and how conveniently we can
U||   imagine.) The mist grew thicker and thicker and I could see now how it
U||   came in, for I could see it like smoke—or with the white energy of
U||   boiling water—pouring in, not through the window, but through the
U||   joinings of the door. It got thicker and thicker, till it seemed as if
U||   it became concentrated into a sort of pillar of cloud in the room,
U||   through the top of which I could see the light of the gas shining like
U||   a red eye. Things began to whirl through my brain just as the cloudy
U||   column was now whirling in the room, and through it all came the
U||   scriptural words “a pillar of cloud by day and of fire by night.” Was
U||   it indeed some such spiritual guidance that was coming to me in my
U||   sleep? But the pillar was composed of both the day and the
U||   night-guiding, for the fire was in the red eye, which at the thought
U||   got a new fascination for me; till, as I looked, the fire divided, and
U||   seemed to shine on me through the fog like two red eyes, such as Lucy
U||   told me of in her momentary mental wandering when, on the cliff, the
U||   dying sunlight struck the windows of St. Mary’s Church. Suddenly the
U||   horror burst upon me that it was thus that Jonathan had seen those
U||   awful women growing into reality through the whirling mist in the
U||   moonlight, and in my dream I must have fainted, for all became black
U||   darkness. The last conscious effort which imagination made was to show
U||   me a livid white face bending over me out of the mist. I must be
U||   careful of such dreams, for they would unseat one’s reason if there
U||   were too much of them. I would get Dr. Van Helsing or Dr. Seward to
U||   prescribe something for me which would make me sleep, only that I fear
U||   to alarm them. Such a dream at the present time would become woven into
U||   their fears for me. To-night I shall strive hard to sleep naturally. If
U||   I do not, I shall to-morrow night get them to give me a dose of
U||   chloral; that cannot hurt me for once, and it will give me a good
U||   night’s sleep. Last night tired me more than if I had not slept at all.
U||   2 October 10 p. m.—Last night I slept, but did not dream. I must have
U||   slept soundly, for I was not waked by Jonathan coming to bed; but the
U||   sleep has not refreshed me, for to-day I feel terribly weak and
U||   spiritless. I spent all yesterday trying to read, or lying down dozing.
U||   In the afternoon Mr. Renfield asked if he might see me. Poor man, he
U||   was very gentle, and when I came away he kissed my hand and bade God
U||   bless me. Some way it affected me much; I am crying when I think of
U||   him. This is a new weakness, of which I must be careful. Jonathan would
U||   be miserable if he knew I had been crying. He and the others were out
U||   till dinner-time, and they all came in tired. I did what I could to
U||   brighten them up, and I suppose that the effort did me good, for I
U||   forgot how tired I was. After dinner they sent me to bed, and all went
U||   off to smoke together, as they said, but I knew that they wanted to
U||   tell each other of what had occurred to each during the day; I could
U||   see from Jonathan’s manner that he had something important to
U||   communicate. I was not so sleepy as I should have been; so before they
U||   went I asked Dr. Seward to give me a little opiate of some kind, as I
U||   had not slept well the night before. He very kindly made me up a
U||   sleeping draught, which he gave to me, telling me that it would do me
U||   no harm, as it was very mild.... I have taken it, and am waiting for
U||   sleep, which still keeps aloof. I hope I have not done wrong, for as
U||   sleep begins to flirt with me, a new fear comes: that I may have been
U||   foolish in thus depriving myself of the power of waking. I might want
U||   it. Here comes sleep. Good-night.
U||CHAPTER XX
U||JONATHAN HARKER’S JOURNAL
U||   1 October, evening.—I found Thomas Snelling in his house at Bethnal
U||   Green, but unhappily he was not in a condition to remember anything.
U||   The very prospect of beer which my expected coming had opened to him
U||   had proved too much, and he had begun too early on his expected
U||   debauch. I learned, however, from his wife, who seemed a decent, poor
U||   soul, that he was only the assistant to Smollet, who of the two mates
U||   was the responsible person. So off I drove to Walworth, and found Mr.
U||   Joseph Smollet at home and in his shirtsleeves, taking a late tea out
U||   of a saucer. He is a decent, intelligent fellow, distinctly a good,
U||   reliable type of workman, and with a headpiece of his own. He
U||   remembered all about the incident of the boxes, and from a wonderful
U||   dog’s-eared notebook, which he produced from some mysterious receptacle
U||   about the seat of his trousers, and which had hieroglyphical entries in
U||   thick, half-obliterated pencil, he gave me the destinations of the
U||   boxes. There were, he said, six in the cartload which he took from
U||   Carfax and left at 197, Chicksand Street, Mile End New Town, and
U||   another six which he deposited at Jamaica Lane, Bermondsey. If then the
U||   Count meant to scatter these ghastly refuges of his over London, these
U||   places were chosen as the first of delivery, so that later he might
U||   distribute more fully. The systematic manner in which this was done
U||   made me think that he could not mean to confine himself to two sides of
U||   London. He was now fixed on the far east of the northern shore, on the
U||   east of the southern shore, and on the south. The north and west were
U||   surely never meant to be left out of his diabolical scheme—let alone
U||   the City itself and the very heart of fashionable London in the
U||   south-west and west. I went back to Smollet, and asked him if he could
U||   tell us if any other boxes had been taken from Carfax.
U||   He replied:—
U||   “Well, guv’nor, you’ve treated me wery ’an’some”—I had given him half a
U||   sovereign—“an’ I’ll tell yer all I know. I heard a man by the name of
U||   Bloxam say four nights ago in the ’Are an’ ’Ounds, in Pincher’s Alley,
U||   as ’ow he an’ his mate ’ad ’ad a rare dusty job in a old ’ouse at
U||   Purfect. There ain’t a-many such jobs as this ’ere, an’ I’m thinkin’
U||   that maybe Sam Bloxam could tell ye summut.” I asked if he could tell
U||   me where to find him. I told him that if he could get me the address it
U||   would be worth another half-sovereign to him. So he gulped down the
U||   rest of his tea and stood up, saying that he was going to begin the
U||   search then and there. At the door he stopped, and said:—
U||   “Look ’ere, guv’nor, there ain’t no sense in me a-keepin’ you ’ere. I
U||   may find Sam soon, or I mayn’t; but anyhow he ain’t like to be in a way
U||   to tell ye much to-night. Sam is a rare one when he starts on the
U||   booze. If you can give me a envelope with a stamp on it, and put yer
U||   address on it, I’ll find out where Sam is to be found and post it ye
U||   to-night. But ye’d better be up arter ’im soon in the mornin’, or maybe
U||   ye won’t ketch ’im; for Sam gets off main early, never mind the booze
U||   the night afore.”
U||   This was all practical, so one of the children went off with a penny to
U||   buy an envelope and a sheet of paper, and to keep the change. When she
U||   came back, I addressed the envelope and stamped it, and when Smollet
U||   had again faithfully promised to post the address when found, I took my
U||   way to home. We’re on the track anyhow. I am tired to-night, and want
U||   sleep. Mina is fast asleep, and looks a little too pale; her eyes look
U||   as though she had been crying. Poor dear, I’ve no doubt it frets her to
U||   be kept in the dark, and it may make her doubly anxious about me and
U||   the others. But it is best as it is. It is better to be disappointed
U||   and worried in such a way now than to have her nerve broken. The
U||   doctors were quite right to insist on her being kept out of this
U||   dreadful business. I must be firm, for on me this particular burden of
U||   silence must rest. I shall not ever enter on the subject with her under
U||   any circumstances. Indeed, it may not be a hard task, after all, for
U||   she herself has become reticent on the subject, and has not spoken of
U||   the Count or his doings ever since we told her of our decision.
U||   2 October, evening.—A long and trying and exciting day. By the first
U||   post I got my directed envelope with a dirty scrap of paper enclosed,
U||   on which was written with a carpenter’s pencil in a sprawling hand:—
U||   “Sam Bloxam, Korkrans, 4, Poters Cort, Bartel Street, Walworth. Arsk
U||   for the depite.”
U||   I got the letter in bed, and rose without waking Mina. She looked heavy
U||   and sleepy and pale, and far from well. I determined not to wake her,
U||   but that, when I should return from this new search, I would arrange
U||   for her going back to Exeter. I think she would be happier in our own
U||   home, with her daily tasks to interest her, than in being here amongst
U||   us and in ignorance. I only saw Dr. Seward for a moment, and told him
U||   where I was off to, promising to come back and tell the rest so soon as
U||   I should have found out anything. I drove to Walworth and found, with
U||   some difficulty, Potter’s Court. Mr. Smollet’s spelling misled me, as I
U||   asked for Poter’s Court instead of Potter’s Court. However, when I had
U||   found the court, I had no difficulty in discovering Corcoran’s
U||   lodging-house. When I asked the man who came to the door for the
U||   “depite,” he shook his head, and said: “I dunno ’im. There ain’t no
U||   such a person ’ere; I never ’eard of ’im in all my bloomin’ days. Don’t
U||   believe there ain’t nobody of that kind livin’ ere or anywheres.” I
U||   took out Smollet’s letter, and as I read it it seemed to me that the
U||   lesson of the spelling of the name of the court might guide me. “What
U||   are you?” I asked.
U||   “I’m the depity,” he answered. I saw at once that I was on the right
U||   track; phonetic spelling had again misled me. A half-crown tip put the
U||   deputy’s knowledge at my disposal, and I learned that Mr. Bloxam, who
U||   had slept off the remains of his beer on the previous night at
U||   Corcoran’s, had left for his work at Poplar at five o’clock that
U||   morning. He could not tell me where the place of work was situated, but
U||   he had a vague idea that it was some kind of a “new-fangled ware’us”;
U||   and with this slender clue I had to start for Poplar. It was twelve
U||   o’clock before I got any satisfactory hint of such a building, and this
U||   I got at a coffee-shop, where some workmen were having their dinner.
U||   One of these suggested that there was being erected at Cross Angel
U||   Street a new “cold storage” building; and as this suited the condition
U||   of a “new-fangled ware’us,” I at once drove to it. An interview with a
U||   surly gatekeeper and a surlier foreman, both of whom were appeased with
U||   the coin of the realm, put me on the track of Bloxam; he was sent for
U||   on my suggesting that I was willing to pay his day’s wages to his
U||   foreman for the privilege of asking him a few questions on a private
U||   matter. He was a smart enough fellow, though rough of speech and
U||   bearing. When I had promised to pay for his information and given him
U||   an earnest, he told me that he had made two journeys between Carfax and
U||   a house in Piccadilly, and had taken from this house to the latter nine
U||   great boxes—“main heavy ones”—with a horse and cart hired by him for
U||   this purpose. I asked him if he could tell me the number of the house
U||   in Piccadilly, to which he replied:—
U||   “Well, guv’nor, I forgits the number, but it was only a few doors from
U||   a big white church or somethink of the kind, not long built. It was a
U||   dusty old ’ouse, too, though nothin’ to the dustiness of the ’ouse we
U||   tooked the bloomin’ boxes from.”
U||   “How did you get into the houses if they were both empty?”
U||   “There was the old party what engaged me a-waitin’ in the ’ouse at
U||   Purfleet. He ’elped me to lift the boxes and put them in the dray.
U||   Curse me, but he was the strongest chap I ever struck, an’ him a old
U||   feller, with a white moustache, one that thin you would think he
U||   couldn’t throw a shadder.”
U||   How this phrase thrilled through me!
U||   “Why, ’e took up ’is end o’ the boxes like they was pounds of tea, and
U||   me a-puffin’ an’ a-blowin’ afore I could up-end mine anyhow—an’ I’m no
U||   chicken, neither.”
U||   “How did you get into the house in Piccadilly?” I asked.
U||   “He was there too. He must ’a’ started off and got there afore me, for
U||   when I rung of the bell he kem an’ opened the door ’isself an’ ’elped
U||   me to carry the boxes into the ’all.”
U||   “The whole nine?” I asked.
U||   “Yus; there was five in the first load an’ four in the second. It was
U||   main dry work, an’ I don’t so well remember ’ow I got ’ome.” I
U||   interrupted him:—
U||   “Were the boxes left in the hall?”
U||   “Yus; it was a big ’all, an’ there was nothin’ else in it.” I made one
U||   more attempt to further matters:—
U||   “You didn’t have any key?”
U||   “Never used no key nor nothink. The old gent, he opened the door
U||   ’isself an’ shut it again when I druv off. I don’t remember the last
U||   time—but that was the beer.”
