U||   closing in, so I did not lose any time. Having learned the address of
U||   Mitchell, Sons, & Candy from a directory at the Berkeley, I was soon at
U||   their office in Sackville Street.
U||   The gentleman who saw me was particularly suave in manner, but
U||   uncommunicative in equal proportion. Having once told me that the
U||   Piccadilly house—which throughout our interview he called a
U||   “mansion”—was sold, he considered my business as concluded. When I
U||   asked who had purchased it, he opened his eyes a thought wider, and
U||   paused a few seconds before replying:—
U||   “It is sold, sir.”
U||   “Pardon me,” I said, with equal politeness, “but I have a special
U||   reason for wishing to know who purchased it.”
U||   Again he paused longer, and raised his eyebrows still more. “It is
U||   sold, sir,” was again his laconic reply.
U||   “Surely,” I said, “you do not mind letting me know so much.”
