U||   I wanted to secure a friend, and not to make an enemy, so I thanked
U||   him, gave the address at Dr. Seward’s and came away. It was now dark,
U||   and I was tired and hungry. I got a cup of tea at the Aërated Bread
U||   Company and came down to Purfleet by the next train.
U||   I found all the others at home. Mina was looking tired and pale, but
U||   she made a gallant effort to be bright and cheerful, it wrung my heart
U||   to think that I had had to keep anything from her and so caused her
U||   inquietude. Thank God, this will be the last night of her looking on at
U||   our conferences, and feeling the sting of our not showing our
U||   confidence. It took all my courage to hold to the wise resolution of
U||   keeping her out of our grim task. She seems somehow more reconciled; or
U||   else the very subject seems to have become repugnant to her, for when
U||   any accidental allusion is made she actually shudders. I am glad we
U||   made our resolution in time, as with such a feeling as this, our
U||   growing knowledge would be torture to her.
U||   I could not tell the others of the day’s discovery till we were alone;
U||   so after dinner—followed by a little music to save appearances even
U||   amongst ourselves—I took Mina to her room and left her to go to bed.
U||   The dear girl was more affectionate with me than ever, and clung to me
U||   as though she would detain me; but there was much to be talked of and I
U||   came away. Thank God, the ceasing of telling things has made no
U||   difference between us.
U||   When I came down again I found the others all gathered round the fire
U||   in the study. In the train I had written my diary so far, and simply
U||   read it off to them as the best means of letting them get abreast of my
U||   own information; when I had finished Van Helsing said:—
U||   “This has been a great day’s work, friend Jonathan. Doubtless we are on
U||   the track of the missing boxes. If we find them all in that house, then
U||   our work is near the end. But if there be some missing, we must search
U||   until we find them. Then shall we make our final coup, and hunt the
U||   wretch to his real death.” We all sat silent awhile and all at once Mr.
U||   Morris spoke:—
U||   “Say! how are we going to get into that house?”
U||   “We got into the other,” answered Lord Godalming quickly.
U||   “But, Art, this is different. We broke house at Carfax, but we had
U||   night and a walled park to protect us. It will be a mighty different
U||   thing to commit burglary in Piccadilly, either by day or night. I
U||   confess I don’t see how we are going to get in unless that agency duck
U||   can find us a key of some sort; perhaps we shall know when you get his
U||   letter in the morning.” Lord Godalming’s brows contracted, and he stood
U||   up and walked about the room. By-and-by he stopped and said, turning
U||   from one to another of us:—
U||   “Quincey’s head is level. This burglary business is getting serious; we
U||   got off once all right; but we have now a rare job on hand—unless we
U||   can find the Count’s key basket.”
