U||   various lights and bearings; I took the opportunity of bringing this
U||   diary right up to the moment. I am very sleepy and shall go to bed....
U||   Just a line. Mina sleeps soundly and her breathing is regular. Her
U||   forehead is puckered up into little wrinkles, as though she thinks even
U||   in her sleep. She is still too pale, but does not look so haggard as
U||   she did this morning. To-morrow will, I hope, mend all this; she will
U||   be herself at home in Exeter. Oh, but I am sleepy!
U||   Dr. Seward’s Diary.
U||   1 October.—I am puzzled afresh about Renfield. His moods change so
U||   rapidly that I find it difficult to keep touch of them, and as they
U||   always mean something more than his own well-being, they form a more
U||   than interesting study. This morning, when I went to see him after his
U||   repulse of Van Helsing, his manner was that of a man commanding
U||   destiny. He was, in fact, commanding destiny—subjectively. He did not
U||   really care for any of the things of mere earth; he was in the clouds
U||   and looked down on all the weaknesses and wants of us poor mortals. I
U||   thought I would improve the occasion and learn something, so I asked
U||   him:—
U||   “What about the flies these times?” He smiled on me in quite a superior
U||   sort of way—such a smile as would have become the face of Malvolio—as
U||   he answered me:—
U||   “The fly, my dear sir, has one striking feature; its wings are typical
U||   of the aërial powers of the psychic faculties. The ancients did well
U||   when they typified the soul as a butterfly!”
U||   I thought I would push his analogy to its utmost logically, so I said
U||   quickly:—
U||   “Oh, it is a soul you are after now, is it?” His madness foiled his
U||   reason, and a puzzled look spread over his face as, shaking his head
U||   with a decision which I had but seldom seen in him, he said:—
U||   “Oh, no, oh no! I want no souls. Life is all I want.” Here he
U||   brightened up; “I am pretty indifferent about it at present. Life is
U||   all right; I have all I want. You must get a new patient, doctor, if
U||   you wish to study zoöphagy!”
U||   This puzzled me a little, so I drew him on:—
U||   “Then you command life; you are a god, I suppose?” He smiled with an
U||   ineffably benign superiority.
U||   “Oh no! Far be it from me to arrogate to myself the attributes of the
U||   Deity. I am not even concerned in His especially spiritual doings. If I
U||   may state my intellectual position I am, so far as concerns things
U||   purely terrestrial, somewhat in the position which Enoch occupied
U||   spiritually!” This was a poser to me. I could not at the moment recall
U||   Enoch’s appositeness; so I had to ask a simple question, though I felt
U||   that by so doing I was lowering myself in the eyes of the lunatic:—
U||   “And why with Enoch?”
U||   “Because he walked with God.” I could not see the analogy, but did not
U||   like to admit it; so I harked back to what he had denied:—
U||   “So you don’t care about life and you don’t want souls. Why not?” I put
U||   my question quickly and somewhat sternly, on purpose to disconcert him.
U||   The effort succeeded; for an instant he unconsciously relapsed into his
U||   old servile manner, bent low before me, and actually fawned upon me as
U||   he replied:—
U||   “I don’t want any souls, indeed, indeed! I don’t. I couldn’t use them
U||   if I had them; they would be no manner of use to me. I couldn’t eat
U||   them or——” He suddenly stopped and the old cunning look spread over his
U||   face, like a wind-sweep on the surface of the water. “And doctor, as to
U||   life, what is it after all? When you’ve got all you require, and you
U||   know that you will never want, that is all. I have friends—good
U||   friends—like you, Dr. Seward”; this was said with a leer of
U||   inexpressible cunning. “I know that I shall never lack the means of
U||   life!”
U||   I think that through the cloudiness of his insanity he saw some
U||   antagonism in me, for he at once fell back on the last refuge of such
U||   as he—a dogged silence. After a short time I saw that for the present
U||   it was useless to speak to him. He was sulky, and so I came away.
U||   Later in the day he sent for me. Ordinarily I would not have come
U||   without special reason, but just at present I am so interested in him
U||   that I would gladly make an effort. Besides, I am glad to have anything
U||   to help to pass the time. Harker is out, following up clues; and so are
U||   Lord Godalming and Quincey. Van Helsing sits in my study poring over
U||   the record prepared by the Harkers; he seems to think that by accurate
U||   knowledge of all details he will light upon some clue. He does not wish
U||   to be disturbed in the work, without cause. I would have taken him with
U||   me to see the patient, only I thought that after his last repulse he
U||   might not care to go again. There was also another reason: Renfield
U||   might not speak so freely before a third person as when he and I were
U||   alone.
U||   I found him sitting out in the middle of the floor on his stool, a pose
U||   which is generally indicative of some mental energy on his part. When I
U||   came in, he said at once, as though the question had been waiting on
U||   his lips:—
U||   “What about souls?” It was evident then that my surmise had been
U||   correct. Unconscious cerebration was doing its work, even with the
U||   lunatic. I determined to have the matter out. “What about them
U||   yourself?” I asked. He did not reply for a moment but looked all round
U||   him, and up and down, as though he expected to find some inspiration
U||   for an answer.
U||   “I don’t want any souls!” he said in a feeble, apologetic way. The
U||   matter seemed preying on his mind, and so I determined to use it—to “be
U||   cruel only to be kind.” So I said:—
U||   “You like life, and you want life?”
U||   “Oh yes! but that is all right; you needn’t worry about that!”
U||   “But,” I asked, “how are we to get the life without getting the soul
U||   also?” This seemed to puzzle him, so I followed it up:—
U||   “A nice time you’ll have some time when you’re flying out there, with
U||   the souls of thousands of flies and spiders and birds and cats buzzing
U||   and twittering and miauing all round you. You’ve got their lives, you
U||   know, and you must put up with their souls!” Something seemed to affect
U||   his imagination, for he put his fingers to his ears and shut his eyes,
U||   screwing them up tightly just as a small boy does when his face is
U||   being soaped. There was something pathetic in it that touched me; it
U||   also gave me a lesson, for it seemed that before me was a child—only a
U||   child, though the features were worn, and the stubble on the jaws was
U||   white. It was evident that he was undergoing some process of mental
U||   disturbance, and, knowing how his past moods had interpreted things
U||   seemingly foreign to himself, I thought I would enter into his mind as
U||   well as I could and go with him. The first step was to restore
U||   confidence, so I asked him, speaking pretty loud so that he would hear
U||   me through his closed ears:—
U||   “Would you like some sugar to get your flies round again?” He seemed to
U||   wake up all at once, and shook his head. With a laugh he replied:—
U||   “Not much! flies are poor things, after all!” After a pause he added,
U||   “But I don’t want their souls buzzing round me, all the same.”
U||   “Or spiders?” I went on.
U||   “Blow spiders! What’s the use of spiders? There isn’t anything in them
U||   to eat or”—he stopped suddenly, as though reminded of a forbidden
U||   topic.
U||   “So, so!” I thought to myself, “this is the second time he has suddenly
U||   stopped at the word ‘drink’; what does it mean?” Renfield seemed
U||   himself aware of having made a lapse, for he hurried on, as though to
U||   distract my attention from it:—
U||   “I don’t take any stock at all in such matters. ‘Rats and mice and such
U||   small deer,’ as Shakespeare has it, ‘chicken-feed of the larder’ they
U||   might be called. I’m past all that sort of nonsense. You might as well
U||   ask a man to eat molecules with a pair of chop-sticks, as to try to
U||   interest me about the lesser carnivora, when I know of what is before
U||   me.”
U||   “I see,” I said. “You want big things that you can make your teeth meet
U||   in? How would you like to breakfast on elephant?”
U||   “What ridiculous nonsense you are talking!” He was getting too wide
U||   awake, so I thought I would press him hard. “I wonder,” I said
U||   reflectively, “what an elephant’s soul is like!”
U||   The effect I desired was obtained, for he at once fell from his
U||   high-horse and became a child again.
U||   “I don’t want an elephant’s soul, or any soul at all!” he said. For a
U||   few moments he sat despondently. Suddenly he jumped to his feet, with
U||   his eyes blazing and all the signs of intense cerebral excitement. “To
U||   hell with you and your souls!” he shouted. “Why do you plague me about
U||   souls? Haven’t I got enough to worry, and pain, and distract me
U||   already, without thinking of souls!” He looked so hostile that I
U||   thought he was in for another homicidal fit, so I blew my whistle. The
U||   instant, however, that I did so he became calm, and said
U||   apologetically:—
U||   “Forgive me, Doctor; I forgot myself. You do not need any help. I am so
U||   worried in my mind that I am apt to be irritable. If you only knew the
U||   problem I have to face, and that I am working out, you would pity, and
