U||   interviewer calls “a story,” if one could only get them in proper
U||   order. Here they are:—
U||   Will not mention “drinking.”
U||   Fears the thought of being burdened with the “soul” of anything.
U||   Has no dread of wanting “life” in the future.
U||   Despises the meaner forms of life altogether, though he dreads being
U||   haunted by their souls.
U||   Logically all these things point one way! he has assurance of some kind
U||   that he will acquire some higher life. He dreads the consequence—the
U||   burden of a soul. Then it is a human life he looks to!
U||   And the assurance—?
U||   Merciful God! the Count has been to him, and there is some new scheme
U||   of terror afoot!
U||   Later.—I went after my round to Van Helsing and told him my suspicion.
U||   He grew very grave; and, after thinking the matter over for a while
U||   asked me to take him to Renfield. I did so. As we came to the door we
U||   heard the lunatic within singing gaily, as he used to do in the time
U||   which now seems so long ago. When we entered we saw with amazement that
U||   he had spread out his sugar as of old; the flies, lethargic with the
U||   autumn, were beginning to buzz into the room. We tried to make him talk
U||   of the subject of our previous conversation, but he would not attend.
U||   He went on with his singing, just as though we had not been present. He
U||   had got a scrap of paper and was folding it into a note-book. We had to
U||   come away as ignorant as we went in.
U||   His is a curious case indeed; we must watch him to-night.
