U||   2 October.—I placed a man in the corridor last night, and told him to
U||   make an accurate note of any sound he might hear from Renfield’s room,
U||   and gave him instructions that if there should be anything strange he
U||   was to call me. After dinner, when we had all gathered round the fire
U||   in the study—Mrs. Harker having gone to bed—we discussed the attempts
U||   and discoveries of the day. Harker was the only one who had any result,
U||   and we are in great hopes that his clue may be an important one.
U||   Before going to bed I went round to the patient’s room and looked in
U||   through the observation trap. He was sleeping soundly, and his heart
U||   rose and fell with regular respiration.
U||   This morning the man on duty reported to me that a little after
U||   midnight he was restless and kept saying his prayers somewhat loudly. I
U||   asked him if that was all; he replied that it was all he heard. There
U||   was something about his manner so suspicious that I asked him point
U||   blank if he had been asleep. He denied sleep, but admitted to having
U||   “dozed” for a while. It is too bad that men cannot be trusted unless
U||   they are watched.
U||   To-day Harker is out following up his clue, and Art and Quincey are
U||   looking after horses. Godalming thinks that it will be well to have
U||   horses always in readiness, for when we get the information which we
U||   seek there will be no time to lose. We must sterilise all the imported
U||   earth between sunrise and sunset; we shall thus catch the Count at his
U||   weakest, and without a refuge to fly to. Van Helsing is off to the
U||   British Museum looking up some authorities on ancient medicine. The old
U||   physicians took account of things which their followers do not accept,
U||   and the Professor is searching for witch and demon cures which may be
